<SLUG> BC-OLY-WATERPOLO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SQUAD HAS WAITED A LONG TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The years of service of the 13 women on the U.S. National water
polo team varies from a lifetime served by Maureen O'Toole to nine
years put in by Julie Swail and Kathy ``Gubba'' Sheehy to the seven
months that Ericka Lorenz and Heather Petrie have been a part of
the squad.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, no matter how long it took to get here, the primary goal of
earning a medal - preferably gold - is the same for each and every
member of the team which will represent the country in the Sydney
Olympics in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have friends who have been to the Olympics who tell me that
when you look back it is the process of getting there that you
remember most,'' said goalkeeper Nicolle Payne, a graduate of UCLA
and former All-American at UCLA. ``You remember the relationships
and what it meant to be a team. But right now, the most important
thing is getting a medal.''
</P>
<P>
   There won't be any Olympic medals handed out until Sept. 23, but
there will be a good opportunity for a preview this week when the
six entrants participate in the Holiday Cup at the U.S. National
Aquatics Center on the Armed Forces Reserve Center in Los Alamitos.
</P>
<P>
   The men had control of the pool last week during the UPS
International Cup with Yugoslavia beating the U.S., 4-3, in
Sunday's championship game. The women's turn in the water begins
today with Kazakhstan playing Netherlands at 4:30 p.m., Australia
squaring off with Russia at 5:45 p.m. and the U.S. taking on Canada
at 7 p.m. and culminates with the championship game on Sunday night
at 7.
</P>
<P>
   According to U.S. coach Guy Baker said there will also be some
fireworks in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the women's game is exciting,'' said Baker. ``The
women are playing with movement, finesse and excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   What the women's game doesn't have, however, is the Olympic
tradition. The sport has been played for 100 years but the women's
first shot at winning Olympic gold will come in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance of being the first Olympic team can't be
overestimated,'' said United States water polo executive director
Bruce Wigo.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of women on the American squad who have waited
for a long time for this day. The 39-year-old O'Toole was 17 years
old when she first joined the national team in 1978 and has come
out of retirement twice. Swail and Sheehy each joined the national
team in 1991 and have been members since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us, to some degree, have put our life on
hold,'' said Payne, a member of the national team since 1996 and
three-time NCAA champion at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Which is one reason the celebration included plenty of tears
when the U.S. qualified for the Olympic Games with a 6-5 semifinal
victory of Hungary during the World Olympic Qualification
Tournament in April in Palermo, Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans lost to Russia, 6-5, in the championship game of
the tournament but that didn't take the luster of Olympic
qualification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget it,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, the focus is on getting ready to challenge
for an Olympic medal. Baker's system calls for a a pressing defense
and the speed to create counterattack opportunities for the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Leading scorers in the Olympic qualification tournament were
Coralie Simmons (12 goals), Bell Gardens High graduate Brenda Villa
(10 goals), Robin Beauregard (seven goals) and Lorenz (six goals).
Beauregard won't be in the pool during the Holiday Cup as she
continues to rehab an injured knee that isn't expected to keep her
out of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. also has the luxury of featuring two top-notch
goalkeepers in starter Bernie Orwig and Payne. Orwig, who made a
spectacular save in the final seconds of the qualifying victory
over Hungary, was the collegiate water polo player of the year in
1999 after she led USC to the national title.
</P>
<P>
   Baker is anxious to see his group take on the world's best this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last chance all the teams will be together before
the Olympics,'' Baker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
