<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTSTEPS STILL FRESH FROM ROAD TRIPS WITH DAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is the Fourth of July. America's birthday. Just as
important to me, my father's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his career as a journalist, my father has written
about sports.
</P>
<P>
   For years, his birthday would come and he would have to call me
from wherever he was on the road so I could wish him a happy
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   A few times, the birthday calls came from Italy or France during
the World Cup. He would be rhapsodizing on the virtues of Roberto
Baggio or Zinedine Zidane and even Diego Maradona, the madman
artist of the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Once, all I wanted to know was whether I could borrow $5,000
because I had just found a house I couldn't afford.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was soccer's intoxicating effects on him, but my father
said OK, the check's in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Many times, the birthday call came from London, where Wimbledon
was nearing the end of its grassy fortnight. Through the crackle of
long distance, my father would tell me how he was writing fast so
he could meet my mother at the theater that night.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all I wanted to know was why Jana Novotna choked
again, what the tabloids were saying about Andre Agassi and Brooke
Shields or how Fergie looked in the royal box.
</P>
<P>
   Well before there was any kind of national ``Take Your Daughter
To Work'' day, my father used to take me to work. And that meant
road trips. Spring training. The barns at the race track. Football
training camps.
</P>
<P>
   I loved going. It was a blast, hanging out, watching practice or
games, stopping at diners to eat BLT sandwiches while my father did
his ``work.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, he took me to Chicago, where he interviewed Joe Frazier
the day before Frazier's son, Marvis, made his pro boxing debut. I
accompanied my father to Frazier's hotel suite. When Smokin' Joe
asked me where I went to school, for some reason I blanked out. He
shook his head and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least she's pretty,'' Frazier rasped to my father, dissing
my memory lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Then Frazier added: ``She must have gotten her good looks from
her mother,'' essentially dissing my father.
</P>
<P>
   My father rolled his eyes and smiled. If you're going to be
insulted, it may as well be by Joe Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   The whole ``On The Road'' sports thing started when I was 1{
years old. The Mets had finished their second season and were
moving to Shea Stadium, so my father did what any New York National
League fan would have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the '63 season, I took you to the Polo Grounds
just so you could say you were there before they tore it down,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   I think, more to the point, it was so he could say he had taken
me there. But that's cool. We still secretly root for the Mets. And
the designated hitter ... well, I understand where he's coming
from.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest memory I have of being ``on the road'' with my
father was during spring training in 1965 or '66. We drove from New
York to Florida, where he was covering the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   One night, we were in the lobby of the Colonial Inn in St.
Petersburg. I was 3 or 4, and my father told me to sit and wait
while he talked with some ballplayers. When he turned around to
check on me, he saw I had been taken to the hotel lobby bar by an
animated, white-haired old man.
</P>
<P>
   The fellow was holding court, telling wild stories to a small
crowd gathered at the bar, making plenty sure I was supplied with
glass after glass of bubbly ginger ale.
</P>
<P>
   Later, my father told me that man was Casey Stengel. The manager
of the Mets, former manager of the Yankees, was one of sports'
all-time classic characters.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I tried to understand the intricacies of Stengel's
legend, but all I knew was that Casey had made my night, flooding
me with soda and putting me smack in the middle of a good time.
</P>
<P>
   I might have decided right there, ``This isn't a bad life.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, when I was about 8, I had another encounter
with a big-name baseball player. While my father was in the
clubhouse, me and some other kids were waiting outside, trying to
get autographs. A burly guy with a handlebar mustache came out and
I shoved my pen and paper at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, little girl,'' the man said. ``But come back and see me in
10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when my father and I were driving back to the hotel, I
told him what Thurman Munson had said. What did he mean, come back
and see him in 10 years?
</P>
<P>
   Amused by Munson's ridiculously lecherous humor, my father
delicately explained to me that the Yankees catcher would probably
be a little more interested in visiting with young women of legal
age. It was an insight into ballplayers that has served well
through the years.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Munson did not make it 10 years, dying in 1979 when he
crashed his own plane.
</P>
<P>
   For me and my Pops, though, that story gets better with age.
</P>
<P>
   So does my father and so do the times we share in this world of
sports, which is what I'll tell him Tuesday on his birthday.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey is the daughter of New York Times
columnist
</P>
<P>
   George Vecsey. She can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
