<HEADLINE>
MEXICO, VOTING IN NEW LEADER, BEGINS POLITICAL SEA CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert new 6th and 7th grafs; rewrites 10th graf for
accuracy; inserts `PRD' in 17th and 19th grafs; inserts quote from
Morales as new 23rd graf.)  
(See also MEXICO-FOX, MEXICO-ASSESS and related stories.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Swept to power by younger, better-educated voters
fed up with corruption and one-party rule, President-elect Vicente
Fox on Monday began the transition of Mexico from a republic headed
for decades by an autocratic president to one in which political
power suddenly seemed up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   As Fox fielded congratulatory phone calls Monday from world
leaders, including President Clinton, and met with President
Ernesto Zedillo, election returns showed that Mexican voters on
Sunday had handed him a substantially more decisive victory over
the governing party than any poll had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   With 93 percent of the ballots tabulated, the Mexican electoral
agency reported that Fox had won 43 percent of the votes, while
Francisco Labastida, the candidate of the ruling party, won 36
percent and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a leftist candidate, won 17
percent. Fox will take office on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   For many Mexicans, it was still sinking in Monday that after 71
years, the Institutional Revolutionary Party, which evolved from a
alliance of revolutionary generals into a model nationalist party
imitated across Latin America before degenerating into a clique of
corrupt insiders, had finally been deposed from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But when the dust settles on the first democratic transition of
power in this country's history, for the first time none of the
major parties _ the deposed one, Fox's center-right party, or the
largest leftist grouping _ will be in control of either house of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday night, Fox said he had assured
Zedillo that he did not intend to carry out a purge of the
government bureaucracy, at least in the first stage of his new
administration. The two leaders agreed to meet frequently between
now and December to plan next year's budget and to discuss the
transition, Fox added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team will take office with creative ideas and new
philosophies, but there'll be no change in federal work rhythms,''
Fox said. ``Mexico will be a country on the move, headed by a
government that keeps its commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox will preside over a government unused to coalition politics
but one in which all major business will require the consent of one
or the other of his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the parties are going to have to relearn the art of making
politics,'' said Carlos Elizondo, a political scientist who is
rector of the Center for Research and Teaching in Mexico City.
``The fundamental pillars of Mexico's political system have
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   These unsettled results were reflected around the country. Fox's
National Action Party won the two governor's seats up for grabs on
Sunday and will now govern in seven of Mexico's 31 states. In
Mexico City, the leftist Party of the Democratic Revolution, or
PRD, retained control of the mayor's office, but the
president-elect's party took control of the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Fox will face the ticklish task of meeting the
hopes for quick and sweeping change of the diverse voters who
backed him. He has promised, simultaneously, to modernize the
economy and spur 7 percent growth, carry out sweeping political
reforms, and initiate an ``educational revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   He has pledged to better the lot not only of the largely young,
middle-class professionals in his own center-right party, but also
of millions of poor urban workers and farmers who have in the past
supported the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all got to get to work right away,'' Fox said in an
interview early Monday, after his triumph. ``I want to be certain
to deliver good results to the people of Mexico, to govern and to
govern well.''
</P>
<P>
   The election results provoked a debate over how successfully
Zedillo's party would navigate its journey from its powerhouse
position into the ranks of the opposition. Some said that the party
had already proved its adaptability and resilience in states where
Fox's party had already won control of the governor's chair.
</P>
<P>
   But others, comparing the position of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, to some communist parties in
Eastern Europe, argued that without presidential support and
control over federal patronage, the party would crumble.
</P>
<P>
   The party's president during the presidential campaign quickly
announced her resignation, and some party officials said they
feared that a sweeping exodus could follow.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the elections to fill all 128 seats in the Senate
and all 500 in the Chamber of Deputies indicated that Fox's party
would finish with its powers significantly enhanced, mainly at the
expense of the leftist PRD, with which it shared opposition powers
during the last Legislature; but that it would not control a
majority of votes.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI lost the Senate majority it had enjoyed since the
party's creation and without the power of the president to
coordinate its efforts, the PRI's entire legislative delegation
will wield considerably less clout.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's party was receiving 38 percent of the votes for Congress,
the returns showed. The PRI was receiving 36 percent and the PRD,
18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As the ballot-counting continued, Zedillo met privately in the
presidential compound with the top PRI leaders, whose power now
rests almost entirely in the provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that Zedillo outlined his views of the unprecedented
survival challenges facing the party, which had gone undefeated in
presidential voting _ often through the simple exercise of its vast
powers of patronage and pork and sometimes through outright ballot
fraud _ for 71 years, longer than any other party in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In a second encounter, Zedillo addressed the 21 of Mexico's 31
state governors who belong to his party, urging them to cooperate
fully with Fox's government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is like the phoenix,'' Melquiades Morales, the PRI
governor of Puebla, told reporters as he entered the meeting. ``It
will rise again from its own ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to work with the new president in a relation of
respect and collaboration,'' Fernando Silva, the PRI governor of
the north central state of San Luis Potosi, told reporters after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   If Mexico was entering absolutely new political terrain with the
PRI's defeat, neither foreign nor domestic investors appeared
concerned. The Mexican stock market surged 6.1 percent on news of
Fox's victory, and the peso, which had been battered in recent
weeks as nervous Mexicans converted savings to dollars,
strengthened 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are very enthusiastic,'' said Rogelio Ramirez,
president of Ecanal, a Mexico City consulting firm. ``The market is
seeing Fox as a man who can bring important changes, in the sense
of modernizing the economy and the system.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview early Monday, hours after his triumph became
apparent, Fox outlined his hopes to forge tighter relations with
the United States, where he attended high school in Wisconsin and
has traveled extensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, I know well the philosophy of the American
people, because I've worked all my life there both in business and
in politics,'' he said. ``I know that we are going to be able to
accomplish many things together. We can develop our great
potential, which still stretches before us. I want to work
intensely with the United States because it is the world's largest
market, it's our neighbor, it's our partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox offered words of conciliation to Labastida and to Cardenas,
with both of whom he had traded extraordinarily harsh criticisms
during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I send him my regards, I recognize his participation and his
passion in defending his ideas,'' Fox said of Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   In a victory speech, Fox said he would withdraw the libel suit
he filed last week against his rivals, who had accused him, without
providing documentation, of accepting illegal campaign donations
from a Belgian company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours is going to be a government of national concord, a
government of unity, a government with its eyes fixed on the
future, a government that we're going to build with the help of all
Mexicans,'' Fox said in the speech. ``I think that's the way to
build the great nation that we all dream about.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Fox spent several hours at the downtown Mexico City
hotel that had been his residence for a year, greeting
well-wishers, speaking to reporters, and speaking to foreign
leaders by phone.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called Fox Monday morning, said Jorge
Castaneda, an adviser to Fox. ``Clinton was very cordial, very
supportive, in general and in particular,'' Castaneda said that Fox
told him. ``Fox committed himself to a meeting with Clinton before
Clinton leaves office. They had a very pleasant conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Several delegations of international observers on Monday praised
the elections as well-organized and fraud-free.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter called the elections ``a turning point of great
significance for all those who love freedom and democracy.'' He
said reforms implemented by an autonomous federal electoral agency
since the 1994 presidential balloting ``turned out to be almost
perfect''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, analysts were scratching their head about why Fox's
victory was far more sweeping than most public opinion surveys had
predicted. Several polls had shown Fox and Labastida to be running
neck and neck, but preliminary results show that Fox won by a
9-point margin.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Reforma wrote Monday that the nearly 20 percent of
Mexican voters who said they were undecided before the vote, had in
reality been planning to vote for Fox, but had been disguising
their anti-government sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Greenberg, the American pollster who worked on contract
to the PRI during the campaign, said that Labastida's candidacy was
doomed when he failed to compete with Fox among the young, urban
middle-class voters whose portion of the Mexican electorate is
growing fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the country's changing demographics, given the
globalization of its economy, all the changes in Mexico, Labastida
and the PRI simply had to attract votes beyond their longtime base
in the rural areas,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas not only went down to his worst defeat in three
presidential bids, but also saw his leftist party's power in
Congress reduced considerably, the returns show. The party's only
bright spot was the election of Andres Manuel Lopez to a six-year
term at the head of the Mexico City government, which will remain
the party's stronghold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
