<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-FOX-2NDLD-WRIT     07-04 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICENTE FOX: MEXICO'S PRESIDENT-ELECT NOT ONE TO HIDE HIS
AMBITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert new 4th-to-last graf re Fox's marriage.)  
(With MEXICO-ELECTION and related stories) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The confirmation of his election as president of
Mexico was still hours away, the victory real only in the computers
of his pollsters, but Vicente Fox was already three steps down the
road. There would be a quick sip of champagne, a victory speech and
then he would get to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right tomorrow I want to be working,'' Fox told an American
journalist in between nonstop interviews handled over his
ever-present cell phone. ``My hobby is work. It enchants me. I
thoroughly enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who turned 58 on the day that Mexicans elected him the
first president in the nation's modern history from an opposition
party, is nothing if not a man of considerable ambition and energy.
He is a politician who once told his political marketing strategist
to ``sell me'' like any other product.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a prosperous rancher, his career has traversed
business and politics. A manufacturer of cowboy boots and a former
Coca-Cola executive, Fox entered politics by being elected a
congressman and later was a governor.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more than anything else, Fox is a maverick. In
Congress half of his votes followed the line of his conservative,
pro-business party. The other half were leftist positions, many of
which were backed by the long-governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, which he vanquished on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Even before his campaign began, he was careful to manage
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ending 70 years of dictatorship will be a great heroic exploit
for Mexico,'' he said, ``something like when you Americans put a
man on the moon. Reaching the moon took a decade of work, and
defeating the ruling party will also require lots of time, talent
and money.''
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Fox sought to allay fears that turmoil
might result were he to prevail by pledging to form what he has
called a government of transition. After his victory, he reiterated
those promises, extending friendly messages to his rivals and
calling for unity.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as governor of Guanajuato state in central Mexico from
1995 until he resigned to campaign for president, Fox appointed a
woman with ties to the PRI as his state auditor and enlisted the
help of a member of the largest leftist party to devise programs to
benefit rural women.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly the government he will lead will contrast sharply
with those of the 13 consecutive PRI presidents before him, partly
because he is likely to bring his business instincts to the job.
</P>
<P>
   When he formed his campaign team last fall, Fox asked a
headhunting firm to locate superstar executives to act as his top
aides. He is unabashed at using marketing techniques for political
communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at me as a product, and figure out how to sell me,'' Fox
said to Francisco Ortiz, the former Procter &AMP; Gamble marketing
wizard he hired to direct his broadcast campaign, Ortiz recalled in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Although he ran as the candidate of the center-right National
Action Party, Fox reached out to leftist intellectuals from across
Latin America, and in discussion groups, he demonstrated
considerable political flexibility, according to Jorge Castaneda,
the liberal New York University professor and author who lives here
part time.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people were from a different world, ideologically and
socially, and he was learning how to get along,'' Castaneda said.
``These were establishment and leftist intellectuals. They dressed
differently, they liked different things. To put it mildly, he was
not in his element. But he'd sit down and he'd manage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vicente Fox is a phenomenon,'' said Dick Morris, the American
political consultant, who worked for Fox. ``This has not been a
situation where the consultant runs the campaign. Fox has a
chemistry with the people of Mexico that is beyond belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Born on July 2, 1942, in Mexico City, Fox spent his childhood on
an 1,100-acre ranch in San Francisco del Rincon, Guanajuato,
purchased during the Mexican revolution by his paternal
grandfather, an immigrant to Mexico of Irish descent.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Mercedes Quesada, was born in Spain, a legal
impediment for Fox's eventual political ambitions until a clause
barring the children of immigrants from serving as president was
eliminated from the Mexican constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has eight siblings. His father was a prosperous landholder,
although not vastly wealthy in Mexican terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something I'm proud of is that I became good friends with the
children of the smallholders and peasants; with them I shared my
infancy, my playthings, my house and my food,'' he wrote in a
campaign autobiography. ``From that time I began to understand our
country's painful inequalities.''
</P>
<P>
   He was educated by Jesuits, and spent a year at an academy in
Prairie du Chien, Wis., learning among other things how to speak
fluent but accented English.
</P>
<P>
   A devout Catholic, he could be the most unapologetically
religious of Mexico's modern presidents. The governing party that
coalesced after Mexico's 1917 Revolution had a strong anticlerical
bias, and the armies of the revolutionary governments that ruled
during the 1920s carried out a bloody counterinsurgency against
Catholic rebels in the west-central region that surrounds Fox's
birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has expressed historical fascination with the legacy of the
Catholic insurgents, known as Cristeros, and during his campaign
often ended rallies with a Cristero war cry: ``If I advance, follow
me! If I stop, push me! If I retreat, kill me!''
</P>
<P>
   If his predecessors have learned the country's local
idiosyncracies as military men or as government bureaucrats, Fox's
sense for the texture of grassroots life came as a route supervisor
for Coca Cola, where he worked in six cities in seven years. After
his transfer to Mexico City in 1971, he climbed to the top of
Coke's corporate hierarchy, serving as chief executive from 1975 to
1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hated most about those years at Coca-Cola was the time
I had to spend dithering with the government,'' he said recently,
recalling how the president would convene Fox and hundreds of other
business executives to the presidential palace ``so we could listen
to a lot of foolishness.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Coke offered to make Fox the head of its Latin American
operations, which would have required that he move to Miami.
Instead, he quit and returned to Guanajuato to work with his
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   While at Coke, Fox married his secretary, Lillian de la Concha,
and the couple adopted four children. They were divorced in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The early 1980s saw many peso devaluations, and Fox has said
that the harrowing experience of running a small business with a
chaotic economy helped persuade him of the need for political
change.
</P>
<P>
   During that economic turmoil, Mexico's opposition forces were
achieving their first major victories in local elections in the
north, and in 1988, dozens of entrepreneurs ran for Congress
representing the National Action Party, including Fox.
</P>
<P>
   He won, served one term in the Chamber of Deputies, and ran for
governor in 1991, losing an election marred by fraud. Four years
later he won. Three years into his governorship, he launched his
quest for the presidency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
