<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DEATH PENALTY UPHELD FOR TAHOE MAN  &HT;     By BILL WALLACE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a 5-to-2 decision, the California Supreme
Court upheld the death penalty Monday for a South Lake Tahoe man
who murdered two women and raped two others during a crime spree in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   At his trial, prosecutors presented evidence that Herbert James
Coddington had falsely represented himself as a model talent scout
in order to lure two teenage girls and their chaperones _ Mabs
Martin, 69, and Dorothy Walsh, 73 _ to his trailer house in South
Lake Tahoe.
</P>
<P>
   Coddington then murdered the two adults and sexually assaulted
the teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Coddington's defense attorneys argued that their client was
insane at the time, saying he believed he was being ordered to
perform do  &LR; the murders by God, who communicated with him
indirectly through such instruments as traffic signals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, an El Dorado County Superior Court jury rejected the
insanity defense and convicted Coddington of the murders and sex
crimes. He was later sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   Coddington's attorneys appealed the death sentence, claiming
that a variety of errors had hampered his opportunity to have a
fair trial, including moving his trial to Placerville from South
Lake Tahoe; allowing evidence from a search of his trailer, even
though investigators did not have a warrant; and excluding some
evidence of his longtime mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's 155-page ruling, five members of the state Supreme
Court upheld the death sentence. While acknowledging that some of
Coddington's arguments are true, the majority _ Justices Marvin
Baxter, Ronald George, Kathryn Werdegar, Ming Chin and Janice Brown
_ found that any errors that may have occurred during the trial did
not harm Coddington's right to a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   A dissenting opinion by Justices Stanley Mosk and Joyce Kennard
drew the opposite conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That the Superior Court committed error, and the prosecutor
engaged in misconduct bearing on the issue, is undoubted,'' Mosk
wrote in the dissent. ``Whether such error and misconduct caused
prejudice is the question. The majority give a negative answer.
After reviewing the record on appeal, I would give a positive
one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
