<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-REACT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO ELECTION BRINGS FEELING OF EMPOWERMENT TO THE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite lede and adds dateline.)  
(With MEXICO-ELECTION) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For three generations, Juan Quiroz's family has
run a fruit-and-vegetable stand in the market that sits in the
shadow of the presidential mansion, Los Pinos. But Mexican politics
seemed so impenetrable, he said, that he has never felt close to
it.
</P>
<P>
   But several hours after he cast his vote on Sunday, Quiroz said
he realized he had touched power for the first time. His choice for
president, Vicente Fox, would be the first man in 70 years to oust
the ruling Revolutionary Institutional Party, known as the PRI,
from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought that Fox would win, even if all the votes were
for him because the PRI was so powerful,'' Quiroz said. ``The
people finally showed that we are more powerful than any political
party _ even a dictatorship like the PRI. Now the people are in
control.''
</P>
<P>
   That euphoric feeling of empowerment echoed across Mexico on
Monday, among people of various backgrounds, professions and
political stripes, in newspaper columns and radio commentary, in
bookstores and cafes. A day after the most historic election in
recent memory, the nation seemed stunned and excited by Fox's
decisive triumph over one of the longest ruling political machines
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, people said, marked more than a challenge for
Mexico's president-elect. In words full of optimism, people
expressed pride in the peaceful way their votes were cast and
counted, in the way they overcame their fear of change and embraced
it. And almost everyone interviewed, no matter which candidate they
had supported, emerged with some personal feeling of triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new day for me,'' said Francisco Rosales, 50, while
browsing through classics at a popular bookstore called Ghandi.
``The PRI has been defeated and once they are going everything else
in our lives will be easier. There will be less corruption, less
manipulation, less fear and more participation.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at the market near los Pinos, people like Luis Manuel
Dominguez said that they did not expect all of Mexico's troubles to
vanish quickly and that they would be happy with slow, steady steps
toward progress.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans took the first step on Election Day, Dominguez, 38, a
telephone repairman, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time,'' he added as he ate stewed chicken at a
lunch counter, ``we are entering a government that was really
created by the people. This is not a cosmetic victory. It is
real.''
</P>
<P>
   Along a commercial strip in the working-class town of
Nezahuacoyotl, just east of the capital, the celebration of Fox's
victory stretched into the late afternoon Monday. Students waved at
passing cars, holding up their first two fingers, now a well-known
gesture from Fox's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents used to say it was better to vote for someone who
is bad but familiar rather than someone who is good but unknown,''
said Alejandro Robles, a student of veterinary medicine at the
National Autonomous University of Mexico who stood smiling among a
group of Fox supporters even though he had voted for Cardenas. ``I
think young people are ready to try something new.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager of a clothing store showed off the ink that was
rubbed on his thumb at the polls to indicate that he had voted. He
said he had voted for Fox, but he saw the election as a victory for
many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox became president,'' the manager said, ``but the people of
Mexico became a democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
