<SLUG> BC-BIG-BROTHER-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SHOW PROMISES REAL LIFE DRAMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Moving in the ``a'' national news file, the ``e'' entertainment
news file and in the ``n'' California news file.) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tonight, 10 strangers will enter a two-bedroom,
one-bathroom house to begin an 89-day living experiment, cut off
from the outside world but in plain sight of millions of TV viewers
thanks to 28 cameras and 60 microphones.
</P>
<P>
   Now what everybody really wants to know, on the eve Wednesday's
premiere of the much-talked-about KCBS-TV (Channel 2) reality show
``Big Brother,'' are the particulars -- such as what will be
recorded in the bathroom, what will the contestants be forbidden to
bring into the house and how will they eliminate housemates. We're
here to help.
</P>
<P>
   What's the house look like?
</P>
<P>
   It is part of a prefabricated structure assembled in a parking
lot deep inside the CBS Studio Center lot on Radford Drive in
Studio City. The interior living space covers 1,800 square feet,
with two cramped bedrooms sleeping five each; a bathroom with a
pedestal sink, a shower stall and a more private toilet chamber; a
kitchen with a double sink, refrigerator and electric stove; a
dining room table for 10; a living room with three couches and a
coffee table; a storage room; and the Red Room with a single chair.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the building is dedicated to the making of the show,
with camera bays, control rooms and other crew work spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Where do they go for fresh air?
</P>
<P>
   The living room and kitchen have windows and a door to a
courtyard measuring about 49 by 68 feet. It has a patio, new sod, a
vegetable patch, free weights, an umbrella table with four chairs
and a very small pool with the ``Big Brother'' logo painted on the
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Where will they get their food?
</P>
<P>
   The vegetable garden, already thriving, includes corn, tomatoes,
zucchini, radishes, lettuce, peppers, herbs and a very dainty lemon
tree (from which not much should be expected). There is a coop
housing seven Rhode Island red hens, each expected to lay five eggs
per week for a ration of 3.5 eggs per person while the household
remains full.
</P>
<P>
   Other provisions will be ordered weekly from a budget of $5 per
day per head to be spent as they decide collectively. Beer and wine
are for sale in Big Brother's grocery, but, the producers note,
with money that tight, no one will be getting drunk.
</P>
<P>
   The allowance pool drops each time a resident is voted out of
the house, but the garden produce and the eggs will be stable
supplies, so look for the biggest eaters to be among the first to
go. And don't fear for the chickens -- there's to be no
neck-wringing or feather-plucking.
</P>
<P>
   What can they bring with them?
</P>
<P>
   Each houseguest is provided two suitcases, one for clothes,
shoes and toiletries and the other for other personal items: family
photos, books, wine, cigarettes, even condoms, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Each person is allowed only one container each of toothpaste,
face cream, shaving cream, shampoo, soap and hair spray or gel.
They are allowed to bring instruments, which could make for some
charming after-dinner musicales -- or a karaoke twilight zone for
those who don't like to sing along.
</P>
<P>
   What CAN'T they bring with them?
</P>
<P>
   Electronic devices, cellular phones, pens, paper, diaries,
calendars, narcotics, hard liquor, weapons and pencil-shaped
makeup. The idea is not to prevent residents from preparing books
about their experiences, but to ensure they keep interacting with
the others as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   All those cameras and microphones -- does that mean nudity and
profanity on network television?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is no, to the relief of many and the disappointment
of some. CBS and its Internet partner, America Online, insist the
``Big Brother'' telecasts will meet the same standards as other
programming.
</P>
<P>
   True, there are cameras and microphones positioned to cover
every angle of the space, but producers say they are there for the
protection of the residents and to prevent secret meetings from
taking place.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
