r f BC-PAYLESS-CASHWAYS-KAN &LR;      07-04 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYLESS-CASHWAYS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYLESS CASHWAYS CHANGES THE WAY IT SELLS TO PROFESSIONALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JENNIFER MANN, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Mo. After two years of cleaning up the mess left
to him at Payless Cashways Inc., Millard Barron is ready to trade
his push broom and repair tools for some building materials and
blueprints for growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City home improvements company has made several
Internet e-commerce alliances and, more importantly, is creating a
division to capture a chunk of new business from professional home
builders.
</P>
<P>
   When Barron took the reins two years ago, Payless had undergone
Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization _ but only its debt had really
been restructured. His new team still needed a year to stabilize
the company and another year to really reorganize it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been eliminating impaired assets, changing the team,
developing a mission statement, remerchandising the stores,
changing the marketing _ those are all things that should have been
done under the umbrella of Chapter 11,'' Barron said.
</P>
<P>
   With that work done, Barron is looking forward to Payless' new
initiatives, especially the wholesale operation called Builder's
Resource.
</P>
<P>
   Payless currently owns a little less than 1 percent of the $200
billion home improvement market _ a market where it's sandwiched by
giants Home Depot and Lowe's on one side and thousands of
mom-and-pop stores on the other. But with Builder's Resource, the
company hopes to tap into the separate $130 billion home-builder
market. Payless' goal for just 2001 is an additional $200 million
in sales from the new initiative.
</P>
<P>
   And the ``neat'' thing about it, as Barron says, is that Payless
is spending a small amount of money to launch the initiative, a
total of $5 million to open what will basically be five sales
offices for a newly hired sales force _ many lured away from
Payless' competition in the professional dealer market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gist of this story is that we're leveraging our existing
assets,'' Barron said. ``We're not adding new inventory. We're not
building new stores. The biggest expense really is the people we've
hired.''
</P>
<P>
   The current Payless management had always planned to capture
part of the professional market, and it has. Those on the
professional side of the business who patronize Payless are home
remodelers and repairmen and maintenance contractors.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of that market was attracted to Payless by another
initiative started by Barron more than a year ago, which was to
have separate entrances and sales counters for the repair and
remodeling contractors at the company's 150 stores.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company addressed the do-it-yourself market by
giving the stores a cleaner sight line, reconfiguring the
merchandise mix and widening the aisles. To date, about a fourth of
Payless' 150 stores have been redone.
</P>
<P>
   What was missing were the lucrative pure professional builders,
who put up the thousands of new homes that make up the sprawling
suburbs surrounding Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, that's one of the interesting things I've learned in
my time here,'' Barron said. ``If we ever hoped to get part of the
builder market we had to get a different set of people to sell to
them, a different model.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was the failure of dual-path _ (previous management)
was trying to serve everybody from the same store, and it didn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dual-path'' may not ring any bells with most people, but those
involved with Payless will probably never forget the term. The
idea, under Barron's predecessor, David Stanley, was to serve the
entire do-it-yourself consumer market and the professional builder
from the same type of store.
</P>
<P>
   But the all-encompassing spectrum Payless was going after simply
doesn't shop at the same places _ not even at the stores of Orange
and Blue, as Home Depot and Lowe's are nicknamed in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Dual-path left everyone _ from customers to industry analysts _
scratching their heads. The idea failed along with the company, and
Payless' bankers forced the company to reorganize.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Barron hopes he can make up for some of the damage done by
Stanley and his team. If he can build the plan the way it's laid
out on the blueprint, sales will increase, margins will widen and,
most importantly, Payless will once again be a solidly profitable
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if all those things happen, hopefully Wall Street will
notice,'' Barron said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the ideal builder's world as Barron sees it:
</P>
<P>
   A contractor on the job site pulls out his Palm Pilot. He orders
what he needs to build an entire home and sends the order to a
Builder's Resource center.
</P>
<P>
   Over the ensuing weeks and months, virtually everything needed
to build a house _ from concrete fasteners, plumbing and electrical
packages to wallboard, light fixtures, doors, windows and roofing _
is delivered by Payless trucks to the job site in the sequence the
materials are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Builder's Resource center connects with the
builder's banker, who draws on his credit as needed, sends invoices
and pays bills.
</P>
<P>
   To attract and serve this demanding and sometimes disorganized
customer, Payless has lured away from other pro dealers a slew of
salespeople, people who already know this business, people ready to
bring their books of business to Payless.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Duggan of Duggan Securities, a longtime follower of
Payless, is impressed with Barron and his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millard has stabilized this company, has redone the debt in a
way that is much, much more favorable to Payless, and put it on
solid footing,'' Duggan said. ``Now, people in the business are
convinced of Payless' survivability. They're leaving good companies
where they've put in 10, 15, 20 years and uprooting their families.
You don't do that lightly, and I think that's a testament to
Millard.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of the five Builder's Resource centers will open
within the next 30 to 45 days. Barron declined to say where, but he
did say they would open on real estate already owned by Payless,
including distribution centers and manufacturing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like this, you only get one chance to do it right,''
Barron said. ``The worst thing you can do is screw it up, so we're
gonna crawl before we start running with this.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of Payless' spectrum, for the serious
do-it-yourselfer, Payless has signed several e-commerce agreements,
including one with ImproveNet, a Web-based home improvement
contractor referral program.
</P>
<P>
   And just Friday, the company announced a new alliance with
DIYonline.com, a site designed for customers interested in
designing their own products and which will allow users to order
goods from Payless.
</P>
<P>
   Other initiatives include one whereby Payless is digitizing the
catalog images of its top special order vendors. About 10 percent
of Payless' existing business comes from special orders.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, a customer wanting to place a special order goes into
a Payless store and thumbs through thousands of pages in a number
of catalogs. Once the new system is in place, the customer can come
in, type in what he's looking for on a computer terminal and get
real-time pricing and delivery schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another new agreement is with CornerHardware.com, another
site for do-it-yourselfers.
</P>
<P>
   All these initiatives, Payless hopes, will strengthen its brand
name and shore up sales, which are slipping at an alarming rate,
including a 12.2 percent drop in same-store sales for the most
recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Barron said he abhors declining sales, but some of the drop was
expected. For instance, the company culled 7,000 items from its
inventory, reducing offerings from 30,000 to 23,000. The items it
dumped garnered sales, but not profits.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the company has cut the number of advertising circulars
inserted in 10 million newspapers each Sunday. Those circulars have
a typical response rate of 2 percent, meaning that on weeks when
Payless doesn't have circulars there are typically 200,000 fewer
customers walking into its stores.
</P>
<P>
   But those marketing dollars have migrated elsewhere. For
instance, over the last year the company has built a detailed
database of its 1.5 million most loyal customers. And it's adding
new ones at the rate of 100,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   That database allows Payless to target and tailor its marketing
to its best customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
