<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2592 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BEES-REVIVAL-KAN &LR;      07-04 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEES-REVIVAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BEES ABUZZ IS A BOOST FOR FARMERS AND GARDENERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY BILL GRAHAM, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a honeybee revival going on this summer, and that's
sweet news to farmers and gardeners.
</P>
<P>
   Parasitic mites decimated America's wild honeybees during the
past decade and damaged hive populations maintained by beekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   That was a hit on an insect that contributes $10 billion in crop
pollination value annually in the United States and creates a $150
million honey harvest, said Ray Nabors, state apiculture
(beekeeping) specialist for the University of Missouri system.
</P>
<P>
   But bees in the Kansas City region _ with help from beekeepers
and mild weather _ are making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've actually seen more swarms of bees in Missouri this year
than we saw during the entire decade in the '90s,'' Nabors said.
</P>
<P>
   A bee swarm occurs when a hive gets crowded. The queen bee,
which can lay an egg a minute around the clock, leaves the hive and
some bees follow. When the queen alights on a limb, thousands of
bees swarm over her in a hanging mass while scout bees search for a
new home.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial beekeepers try to avoid swarms with hive management.
</P>
<P>
   But wild bees or bees from untended hobby hives will swarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did see an increase in swarms in our area,'' said Kenny
Bunting, owner of Osage Honey Farm near Sibley in Jackson County.
``I'm hoping we're finally starting to bounce back from the
mites.''
</P>
<P>
   Swarming bees are unlikely to sting unless provoked, Nabors
said. They're so full of honey it's painful for them to bend their
abdomen to use the stinger.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Burgess, a Kansas City area entomologist for the Missouri
Department of Agriculture, said he has received many calls asking
how to handle swarms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just good news that the bees are back. I've seen lots of
bees working the nectar plants like white clover. It helps our
orchards and gardens. It's definitely a good sign,'' Burgess said.
</P>
<P>
   Many farm crops such as soybeans can self-pollinate, Nabors
said. But honeybees can boost pollination in crop fields, raising
yields and thus profits.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains whether the bee boost is temporary or the
start of a long-range rebound.
</P>
<P>
   A warm winter and mild spring helped bee colonies build
populations early, Nabors said. Less rain and more sunny days gave
them more time to make honey and propagate.
</P>
<P>
   The long-range future depends on how the bees and beekeepers
battle the parasitic mites. One is microscopic and an internal
parasite, while the other is pinhead size and attaches externally.
</P>
<P>
   Honeybees were brought to America from Europe beginning in the
1600s. Pioneers kept bees for honey and some escaped to form wild
honeybee colonies.
</P>
<P>
   But the European bees were not adapted to fend off the two
bee-killing mites that arrived from Asia. Those mites were on bees
introduced to South America in the 1950s and they migrated to North
America, Nabors said.
</P>
<P>
   Wild honeybee colonies in Missouri were eliminated by the mites
in the 1990s, he said. Beekeepers suffered losses, and only those
who treated hives with mite control pesticides kept domestic
colonies going.
</P>
<P>
   The hives are only treated during winter months when honey is
not produced, so no mite control agents are present in commercial
honey.
</P>
<P>
   Many of this year's swarms probably came from well-tended
domestic hives with some help from the weather, said Roger Nichols
of Raytown, president of the Midwestern Beekeepers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because of the work beekeepers have been doing,''
Nichols said. ``Beekeepers are not losing their bees to the
mites.''
</P>
<P>
   Both wild and tame bees are needed, and Nabors is working on
mite controls that can help both.
</P>
<P>
   He helped design a screen and pollen trap for tended hives that
keeps external mites off bees. Apiculture experts also are
experimenting with organic mite control chemicals such as formic
acid, which is naturally produced by bees and wasps. A chemical
by-product from chrysanthemum flowers that kills mites shows
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Apiculturists also are breeding bee strains resistant to mites.
Some strains have been developed with healthy habits; the bees will
groom mites off their bodies and remove infected larvae from the
colony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically good housekeeping,'' Nabors said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to keep domestic beekeeping productive and restore
beneficial wild honeybee populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we begin to control mites, we'll have more swarms out and
begin to replace all the feral bees we lost in the last 20 years,''
Nabors said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
