r a BC-OIL-KAN &LR;      07-04 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER OIL PRICES LEAD TO MORE DRILLING IN KANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY STEVE EVERLY, KNIGHT RIDDER NEWSPAPERS   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time in years, drilling for oil in Kansas is on
the upswing, and credit is being given to higher oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Geological Survey said that 19 oil rigs were drilling
for oil in the state, compared with three rigs when oil prices
reached their lows in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Drilling in the state practically disappeared as oil prices
dropped below $10 per barrel in early 1999. Generally, $15 is
considered a break-even price in the state. And now with oil prices
hovering above $30, the incentives are back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Higher crude prices have led to more exploration activity, and
that's a positive thing,'' said Tim Carr, a geologist for the
Kansas Geological Survey, which is part of the University of Kansas
in Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Higher oil prices are a politically sensitive issue, with some
consumers complaining that oil companies are price-gouging. But
what's happening in Kansas is an example of another side to the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Carr said the below-$15 oil prices had hurt exploration for oil
in the state. One problem now with the renewed interest in drilling
is finding experienced crews to do the drilling.
</P>
<P>
   The low prices ``decimated the infrastructure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Williams, a geologist for the Kansas Corporation
Commission, agreed that there was a shortage of crews.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas produces more energy _ oil and gas _ than it uses. But
depending on older oil and gas fields without new drilling had put
that position at risk. Kansas oil production, much of which occurs
in the western part of the state, totaled 34 million barrels in
1999, down 8 percent from the previous year, according to the
Geological Survey.
</P>
<P>
   Carr said higher prices made it easier to keep open wells that
produced less than five barrels a day _ the production of most
Kansas wells.
</P>
<P>
   It also makes it easier to get the financing to drill wells and
to try new technologies that can boost production.
</P>
<P>
   For example, horizontal drilling allows a rig to drill sideways
once it hits a formation containing oil. The process produces
additional oil, but it costs twice as much as traditional wells.
</P>
<P>
   Another technique is injecting carbon dioxide to force out
additional oil. There's now a pilot project in Russell County to
test the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``With prices at these levels, alternatives like carbon dioxide
flooding become much more attractive,'' Carr said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
