<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-IMPACT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., MEXICO COULD BENEFIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILLBURG  
 and CHRIS SIEROTY  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After Sunday's historic change south of the
border, both Mexico and California could experience monumental
economic changes, a majority of economists and politicians
forecasted Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is one more step in Mexico's maturing as a
vibrant democracy,'' said Rep. Howard Berman, D-Mission Hills.
``It's great news, not because of who won or who lost, but because
the election was held without substantial reports of irregularities
or fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman, a member of the House International Relations Committee,
credited the leadership of outgoing Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo. He noted that Zedillo ordered open primary elections to
choose his successor and also allowed international observers,
including former U.S. President Jimmy Carter, to monitor Mexico's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   John Isaacson, a managing principal with the Los Angeles-based
international investment firm of Payden and Rygel, said the
election of National Action Party (PAN) nominee Vicente Fox was a
``historic'' event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very significant change that approaches the
significance of the falling of the Berlin Wall,'' said Isaacson,
who traveled to Mexico just before the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's victory was the first presidential defeat for the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, in 71 years. The former
Coca-Cola executive will take office in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is surprising is the margin of victory,'' said Isaacson.
``If the contest had been closer, there would have been anxiety on
the world markets that the race would have been contested, sending
the Mexican economy downward.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said that with such a large margin of victory, the Mexican
economy should avert a repeat of the declines that have frequently
occurred after a change in administration, even though the ruling
party, the PRI, has not changed in seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that Zedillo as well as both candidates have done a
good job at getting the word out to foreign investors that the
process of change will be smooth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has the second-largest economy in Latin America behind
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a new administration and a stable economy, hopefully they
will be able to move to a more free market-style economy,'' said
Jack Kyser, chief economist with the Los Angeles Economic
Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   A prosperous economy will mean continued good news for
California exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
   California exports to Mexico continue to be driven by shipments
of electronics and electrical equipment and industrial machinery
and computer equipment. In the first quarter of this year, exports
in these two sectors totaled $2.2 billion, or 52 percent, of total
state exports to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released by the California Trade and
Commerce Agency in Sacramento, California exports to Mexico in the
first six years of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)
have increased nearly 129 percent or $8.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Today, California exports to Mexico directly and indirectly
support approximately 179,000 jobs in California, with more than
100,000 of these jobs resulting from export growth under NAFTA, the
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question NAFTA has meant a tremendous amount for
Mexico,'' said Isaacson. ``However, Fox has made it very clear that
they'll have to spread the wealth of NAFTA throughout the society
for continued economic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyser said NAFTA has also helped increase exports in agriculture
and transportation equipment to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can have true economic reform that would allow the
benefits of growth to be felt by everyone, major problems,
including immigration, tax reform and education, would begin to be
solved,'' said Isaacson.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser, however, warned that since the new administration doesn't
take office until December, it will be at least five years before
any major changes are seen in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican government has to eliminate the problems of
corruption and crime,'' he said. ``If they can develop a middle
class in Mexico, it will have an impact on illegal immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there are those who remain skeptical that a new
political party and president will bring about significant change
south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see a big difference between the two parties in
Mexico,'' said Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Woodland Hills. ``But getting
some new blood into Mexico City could reduce corruption and the
drug trade. These may be the most significant elections this year,
other than our own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a strong interest in the prosperity of Mexico,'' added
Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proof that Mexico needs a new government is evidenced by
the thousands of Mexicans who are leaving their country for the
U.S.,'' he said. ``Our economy values their skills and they can
earn $8 to $10 an hour. In Mexico, the system pays those people $2
a day for the same work.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
