r i BC-MEXICO-ASSESS-SFCHRON     07-04 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ASSESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO CONFRONTS SHOCK WAVE OF CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  MEXICO CITY _ The nation awoke to a new era Monday as Mexicans
of all political persuasions tried to make sense of the changes in
store after the historic defeat of Mexico's ruling party.
<P>
   Although President-elect Vicente Fox reached out to the defeated
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), repeating earlier pledges
that the end of its 71-year rule does not mark oblivion for its
members, many wondered whether the PRI would survive.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat of the PRI will mean wrenching changes throughout
Mexican society as the regime that has exercised enormous control
enters its final months before Fox's inauguration on December 1.
</P>
<P>
   In a portent of the PRI's impending dire straits _ the end of
its generous under-the-table federal government subsidies _ the
party began making layoffs Monday in the central bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unclear how the PRI will survive in the future,'' said
political analyst Sergio Sarmiento. ``The PRI is not organized
around an ideology but around the capacity of maintaining itself in
power. Without power, it will lose its coherence on a national
level.''
</P>
<P>
   For many millions of Mexicans, the PRI is not just a party _ it
is their sustenance.
</P>
<P>
   After Fox takes office December 1, farmers will no longer go to
the PRI to solve their problems, and an army of bureaucrats will no
longer migrate between the PRI's massive headquarters in Mexico
City and federal and state bureaucracies around the country.
</P>
<P>
   PRI-controlled labor unions that for 65 years have been
subservient to the government must suddenly fend for themselves.
Leonardo Rodriguez Alcaine, a conservative, old-guard labor leader
who leads the Confederation of Mexican Workers, a 2 million-member
PRI union that is widely viewed as corrupt, quickly backtracked
Monday from his campaign threats to call a nationwide strike if Fox
won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I merely meant to draw a line in the sand,'' he said. ``I just
want Fox to take into consideration the interests of the workers.''
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Fox never made clear exactly what would
replace the PRI machine. His stands on the issues were generally
middle-of-the-road, avoiding the conservative ideology of his
National Action Party (PAN). Many of his policy proposals were
hardly different from those of Francisco Labastida, the PRI
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   If Monday's developments failed to give a clear indication of
Mexico's future, they at least gave Mexicans a better idea about
what had just happened:
</P>
<P>
   -- READING THE POLLS _ As election results and detailed
exit-poll information became available Monday, it was clear that
millions of young voters had swung toward Fox out of a vague desire
to simply get rid of the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of Fox voters said their main reason for supporting
him was the desire for change, while 28 percent primarily were
drawn to the candidate and his policies.
</P>
<P>
   According to an exit survey conducted at voting stations by the
Reforma newspaper chain, Fox's voters were overwhelmingly young and
well-educated, either private-sector workers or students.
Labastida's voters, on the other hand, were concentrated among the
elderly, those with little schooling, housewives and those who
voted out of mere loyalty to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Fox even seems to have dented the PRI's traditional stronghold
in rural Mexico, where the ruling party's support fell below 50
percent for the first time in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's voting results proved that public opinion polls carried
out before the election had lied _ or perhaps the people who
participated had. Most of the polls conducted in the weeks before
Sunday's vote indicated that Labastida would win by a margin of
several points. Fox's 7-point margin of victory led many analysts
to conclude that some poll participants felt afraid to tell their
questioners their real opinions. Only in the curtained voting
booth, the analysts surmised, did people feel protected enough from
the PRI's coercive party machinery to vent their anti-PRI feelings.
</P>
<P>
   -- PRI'S DIGNITY _ The ruling party came out defeated but with
its head held high. Labastida and President Ernesto Zedillo earned
the surprised respect of many Mexicans and foreign observers by
immediately admitting the PRI's defeat as soon as initial results
were released Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, Fox lauded Zedillo _ whom he had never praised
before, to anyone's memory _ for his ``honor and democratic
maturity.'' Fox himself made a gracious victory speech, pledging to
name members of the PRI and the leftist Party of the Democratic
Revolution (PRD) to his Cabinet. At his victory rally, when
supporters broke into spontaneous chants of ``The PRI is going to
hell,'' Fox scolded them: ``We agreed to bid it farewell with
happiness, without rancor.''
</P>
<P>
   The party's newfound respect may not save it from internal
divisions and witch hunts, however. Some party officials bitterly
criticized Zedillo and Labastida, saying that the leadership's
democratic reforms should be reversed and the PRI should return to
its old-fashioned, populist ways.
</P>
<P>
   -- DEMOCRACY AT LAST _ International observers heaped praise on
all sides in the elections and said that with reforms instituted in
recent years _ a freer press, fairer campaign rules and a new
voting system to combat fraud _ Mexico now can be considered a
full-fledged member of the democratic community of nations.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. President Jimmy Carter, who led an observer
delegation, was especially effusive, calling the election ``a
historic turning point of the most profound significance for all
who love freedom and democracy in Mexico and throughout this
hemisphere and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The smoothness and fairness of Sunday's election was a welcome
development for the Clinton administration, which had worried that
post-election cries of fraud would create instability in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   American politicians and officials fell over themselves Monday
with compliments for Mexico's new leader. President Clinton phoned
Fox to congratulate him, and Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush offered their congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCaffrey, director of the White House drug control
office, called Fox ``enormously determined'' to stop narcotics
trafficking and ``extremely smart, dedicated and bold,'' and added
that Fox is ``determined not to turn Mexico over to the
narcotraffickers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
