r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     07-04 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAM DOESN'T LOOK A DAY OVER 224
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I love birthdays, but what the heck do you get a
country that has everything?
</P>
<P>
   Botox treatments for Uncle Sam, to make those worry furrows
disappear? A Paul Revere and the Raiders Greatest Hits CD? A
stripped and star-spangled baseball cap that Uncle can wear
backwards for an updated look?
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, Unc Sam, blow out those 224 candles. Be careful not to
spit your dentures into the cake, it makes the frosting taste like
Polygrip.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, you blew 'em all out, Unc! Did you remember to make a wish?
Wait, there's a news bulletin on TV.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; We have just received word that presidential candidates &LR; 
 &UR; George W. Bush and Al Gore have been marooned on a desert &LR; 
 &UR; island, with no hope of rescue for at least a year. There is &LR; 
 &UR; little danger that they will starve to death, because the island &LR; 
 &UR; is teeming with rats and the two men have an unlimited supply of &LR; 
 &UR; campfire material, since hundreds of bales of `soft' money have &LR; 
 &UR; washed ashore. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THOMAS JEFFERSON penned the first draft of the Declaration of
Independence in two weeks. Imagine what he could have cranked out
on a laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Lear, the famed TV sitcom producer, recently purchased
one of the few remaining copies of the Declaration from the limited
first printing.
</P>
<P>
   Lear will probably send the document out to his writers, ask 'em
to punch it up a little. King George III will be referred to as
``Meathead.''
</P>
<P>
   THE DECLARATION of Independence is the greatest pink slip in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Yo, Wig Boy: You are so fired as our king, effective
immediately, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Your severance check is in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Should you wish to appeal your severence to the union grievance
committee, please do so immediately, because we could use a good
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   We've got your grievance committee right here.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON and the boys get all the credit for the Declaration,
but they couldn't have done it without George III.
</P>
<P>
   Had the king been merely heavy-handed and tyrannical, the
colonists probably would have endured British rule forever,
bitching and moaning about stamp taxes but going along with the
program.
</P>
<P>
   But no, George squeezed and squeezed until the founding fathers
cried out, ``R-e-s-p-e-c-t, find out what it means to we.''
</P>
<P>
   George III wrote the handbook on how to lose colonies. It is
believed that he was the inspiration for the term ``royal pain in
the butt.'' John Malkovich would make a great George III.
</P>
<P>
   NOT THAT any of the Georges were a bargain. George I was
obstinate and lazy. George II was stubborn and stupid. George W was
a below-average student and a party boy. ... No, wait, George W. is
from a different royal family of Georges.
</P>
<P>
   George III, in keeping with the family tradition, was a few
raisins short of a scone. He suffered from a mental disease that
made him emotionally unbalanced.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God for that.
</P>
<P>
   The colonists needed a big push to take the huge leap they took.
This was no bungee jump.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody but a world-class control freak and power tripper like
George III could have provided the inspiration for these gentlemen
to pledge ``our Lives, our Fortunes and our sacred Honor, not that
you would know diddly about sacred Honor, That last part was added
by Norman Lear's writers.
</P>
<P>
   HAD WE HUNG in there under British rule, this would have been a
duller country.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth of July, instead of being a day for fireworks and
wonderful parades and barbecued chicken, would simply be the date
when our British income taxes are due.
</P>
<P>
   If we were still attached to Britain like a swollen polyp, our
judges, instead of Marv Albert and Sam Donaldson, would wear funny
wigs. Our cars would break down every week, whether we drove 'em or
not.
</P>
<P>
   INSTEAD OF getting excited about the baseball pennant races,
right now we would be checking out ESPN for the highlights of the
American and National cricket leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Cricket is like baseball, but without baseball's dizzying pace.
In cricket, both teams wear the same uniform, which kills the
merchandising industry. If a kid wants to show support for his
beloved Tottenham Teaslurpers, he wears a plain white shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Cricket players don't even have numbers on their shirts. They
probably don't even have agents or shoe contracts or groupies.
</P>
<P>
   Our kids would be playing Little League polo, and we parents
would be on the sidelines exhorting junior to ``Swing the damn
mallet!'' And the kid would be whining, how can we expect him to
make the big leagues riding this sway-backed pony?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hundreds of crazed Laker fans rampaging through the
streets, we'd have thousands of soccer hooligans rampaging through
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT A colossal mismatch: Jefferson and Ben Franklin and the
Boys vs. George III.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson invented the french fry. Jefferson, bless his heart,
said if he had to choose between a government without newspapers
and newspapers without a government, he'd go with ``B,'' and that
was before Doonesbury.
</P>
<P>
   Go to a parade today, eat watermelon and apple pie and chicken,
even though Jefferson said, ``We never repent of having eaten too
little.''
</P>
<P>
   Wave a flag. Happy birthday to us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
