<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2602 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKW-COOPER-TO-RETIRE-     07-04 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COOPER-TO-RETIRE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Comets' Cooper to retire at season's end
<TEXT>
<P>
   By W.H. STICKNEY JR.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Less than happy with her diminished role in the
Comets' offense, three-time WNBA Finals Most Valuable Player
Cynthia Cooper said Monday night that she will retire at the end of
the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my last year in the league,'' Cooper said. ``I will
retire after this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With different things that have happened this year, and
obviously last year, just the things that are going on now, I think
it's time for me to move on. I know it's going to make a lot of
people happy that I'm, to use a cliche, passing the torch. It's
just time for me to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the WNBA's two oldest players, Cooper, 37, has reigned as
the league's scoring champion in each of its previous three seasons
and was the regular-season Most Valuable Player in 1997 and '98. In
this year's season opener, she became the first player in the
league to reach 2,000 career points.
</P>
<P>
   But the past 21 months have been among the toughest for Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1999, her mother died after a long fight with breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   During the four months prior to that, Cooper was involved in a
late-night auto accident that caused nearly $30,000 in damages to
her Mercedes-Benz convertible, and one of her two homes in Sugar
Land burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   And while coping with those traumas, Cooper learned that her
best friend and Comets teammate, Kim Perrot, had lung and brain
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Last Aug. 19, Perrot died at M.D. Anderson Cancer Center with
her mother, several family members and Cooper at her bedside. Two
weeks later, the Comets won their third WNBA championship, a
tribute Cooper had hoped she and the team could give Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   Once the season was over, Cooper dropped out of the spotlight.
Although invited to be on the United States women's national
basketball team competing in the Summer Olympic Games in Sydney,
Australia, she chose to use the offseason as a time to get her life
in order.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper reported for Comets training camp in early May bearing a
temperament closer to the one she brought along over the WNBA's
first two years. But in camp, she became increasingly disgruntled.
</P>
<P>
   With the emergence of Sheryl Swoopes, Tina Thompson and Janeth
Arcain as more potent weapons than ever before, Cooper felt her
role with the Comets was beginning to get altered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I've thought about (retirement) since preseason,''
Cooper said. ``I made the decision after we went to Seattle (for
the third game of the regular season).
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who is close to me told me to think about it, think
about it, think about it before I made an announcement. So I've
thought about it, and I've made the decision. Now, I'm making the
announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Cooper makes good on the retirement vow, it will bring
to an end a 15-year professional career that began shortly after
she came out of Southern Cal as an unheralded member of a two-time
NCAA championship team featuring Hall of Famer Cheryl Miller.
</P>
<P>
   During 11 years of pro ball overseas, primarily in Italy, Cooper
established herself as one of the world's premier offensive players
and one who Comets coach Van Chancellor says has talents unique to
the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind,'' Chancellor has said,
``Cynthia is the greatest player in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But news of Cooper's intentions caught Chancellor by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty much a shocker,'' he said. ``If this is true,
it will be a loss for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to see us lose one of the top five people who have
ever played this game. She's a player _ there's just nobody who's
played this game that makes plays any better than Cynthia Cooper.
She can create for herself, but she's better than anyone else at
creating for her teammates, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor said he hasn't considered how Cooper's announcement
will affect the Comets, now and in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has really caught me off-guard. I'd really have to think
about that,'' he said. ``I don't know what it will do to us right
now. I haven't thought about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always in the future, any time you lose a great player, I
think it's a tremendous loss. It's a compensation we'll have to
find some way to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper heads up a number of companies and organizations that are
involved with activities ranging from providing literary enrichment
for the underprivileged to building structures in impoverished
areas of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she'll do after entering retirement, Cooper said,
``I'll always be around basketball. I really want to get into (TV)
broadcasting, begin a career in broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also want to coach,'' she said. ``I want to start coaching
in the NBA, as an assistant, get my feet wet, get some experience
there and then move on, try something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper discounted the possibility of being traded, or after
entering retirement, returning to play for another WNBA team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a lot more basketball in me, but I'm not
happy,'' she said. ``And I'm not going to play for another team.
Houston is where I started. This is where I want to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love (Comets/Rockets owner) Les Alexander and (his wife)
Nanci, everything they've done for the Comets and the WNBA. They've
been wonderful, even with Kim's family. They've just been awesome.
The Lord couldn't have blessed me with a better organization to
play for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 115,000 percent happy that I fell in Houston and started
playing for the Comets,'' added Cooper, who was born in Chicago and
raised in Los Angeles. ``Obviously, this is bittersweet. The bitter
part is I have a lot of basketball left in me; I'm still on top of
my game. But the sweet part is this is something new I'm getting
ready to embark on. It's special, and I'm excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
