<HEADER>
A2608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-UTICA-MAYOR-NYT &LR;      07-04 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UTICA-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR OF UTICA, N.Y., RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The colorful mayor of the chronically depressed upstate city of
Utica, N.Y., Edward A. Hanna, resigned Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hanna, 78, has been fending off allegations of sexual
harassment by four male city employees, he said in a statement that
the move was ``strictly a health decision,'' prompted by ``my
serious heart condition along with my age, the execution of and
stress in the regular routine as mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna, whose efforts to rebuild Utica were often overshadowed by
the publicity he got for actions like calling the city ``a lousy
place to live,'' bolstered the contention that his decision to
resign was health-related by including a list of his daily
medications in his news release.
</P>
<P>
   He also stated that he had been having increasingly frequent
chest pains in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also attached a 1992 note from his cardiologist
stating that he had blocked arteries.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna, a Democrat-turned-Republican who made a fortune off a
photo developer he perfected, governed Utica, an old factory town
of 64,000 along the Mohawk River 240 miles north of New York City,
from 1975 to 1977 and again from January 1996 until 11:59 Monday
night. He also served as city comptroller in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Under Utica's charter, the City Council president, Tim Julian,
now becomes mayor and a special election for mayor will be held in
November, The Utica Observer-Dispatch reported.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual harassment accusations against Hanna, who has been
married for more than 50 years, came June 14 in notices of intent
to sue him and the city, according to the Observer-Dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   The men contend that the mayor threatened their jobs if they
refused his sexual advances, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were filed by Hanna's former executive assistant,
23; a 24-year-old Parks Department employee; a 22-year-old former
development administrator; and a 35-year-old former executive
assistant with the city, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
   In a fax to the Observer-Dispatch, Hanna called the accusations
``a scam, loaded with outrageous lies.'' The men's lawyer, Joseph
Policelli, countered by telling the Observer-Dispatch, ``People
don't blackmail people by claiming that they had homosexual
activities with somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna's statements and actions included the brash and the
mysterious. On one hand, he proposed closing down the city
government. On the other, he built a Tower of Hope next to City
Hall to honor Bob Hope, who has no particular connection to Utica.
</P>
<P>
   But he nurtured a reputation as a watchdog against fiscal
incompetence and corruption, and his many supporters credited him
with forcing Utica to confront its difficult situation. When the
city's bonds received the poorest rating of any city in the country
in 1996, the mayor opined, ``We got just what we deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna's resignation statement ended with an epitaph-like
sentiment: ``I would hope to be remembered as a mayor who had eyes
that could see what needed to be done and a heart that cared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
