u k BC-HINESCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-04 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUTINE &HT;    
 &HT;    CONTACT: VERONICA BUCIO 713-220-7733
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CAUSE FOR REALISTIC REJOICING IN MEXICO
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news out of Mexico is almost unbelievable. For Mexicans and
for anyone else who has watched our problematic neighbor with an
uneasy mix of hope and horror, a different day has finally dawned.
</P>
<P>
   Que pasa, indeed?
</P>
<P>
   The world's longest ruling party has been driven out of power by
disgusted voters with long memories. In truth, the voters had
probably intended to do this at least twice before, in the
elections of 1988 and 1994, but electoral fraud most likely
postponed the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Sunday, in what may have been the first fair national
vote in years, Mexicans rejected the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, and its lackluster presidential contender, Francisco
Labastida. They turned to the longtime opposition National Action
Party, or PAN, and its more magnetic candidate, Vicente Fox.
</P>
<P>
   What was supposed to be a squeaker, judging by the final public
opinion polls, turned into a landslide. Smashing, crushing,
seismic. Pick your adjective and rejoice.
</P>
<P>
   As always, however, celebration must be tempered with reality.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be easy for Fox to translate his victory into an
effective national government and to address Mexico's difficulties
and divisions. The biggest is economic disparity _ the issue that
the PRI swore for seven decades it would address but which it
quickly grew to exploit cynically to cement its hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has pledged to attempt to spread around the relatively good
times. Like much of his program, details were left vague. But to
make good on the promise, whatever it means, he will have to
carefully meld his innate belief in the free market with a program
that seeks to ensure that the prosperity that has come to many in
northern and central Mexico flows south and to the rural poor all
over the nation. Decades of PRI's economic mismanagement will not
make this any easier.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's problem will be complicated by cross-cutting political
pressures. Fox's constituency is the urban and northern middle
class who rightfully equated PRI with a government that did not
respond to their needs. These voters will want an even lighter hand
from the central government. The neediest are from PRI fiefdoms in
the south and the countryside and in the slums of Mexico City where
the Party of the Democratic Revolution and its also-ran
presidential contender Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the former mayor, are
popular.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had a dog in this fight. It was Fox _ and,
more broadly, the chance for fundamental change in Mexico that he
represents. Bureaucratic calcification in Mexico City and in many
of the state capitals, not to mention outright corruption, that has
grown up under the PRI made a charade of many cross-border
dealings, including the key issues of pollution, immigration, drugs
and crime.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether the Clinton administration fully grasped
the importance of this Mexican election to our country. But at any
rate the White House and State Department thankfully kept quiet.
Ditto the Republicans on Capitol Hill who have been more vociferous
over the years in their denunciations of PRI shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and his successor should move quickly to make
clear that the United States supports the basic outlines of a
reform agenda that Fox has put forward. We should assist as
requested in helping him flesh out those proposals and do nothing
to complicate his fulfilling them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the last time that Mexico and the United States briefly
had presidents-elect at the same time, then-Vice President George
Bush arranged an informal meeting with the incoming Mexican leader,
Carlos Salinas. That could be a useful model for the victor in the
U.S. election on Nov. 7 as Fox will not be sworn in until Dec. 1,
and it wouldn't hurt for the new leaders to accent the importance
of the two nations' relationship.
</P>
<P>
   With Fox, that cross-border tie could become steadier and even
more productive after seven decades of PRI regimes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1899, as President Porfirio Diaz continued his despotic rule,
a touring guide to Mexico quoted ``a patriotic Mexican writer'' as
saying: ``With the restless, inconstant character of our race, the
long tenure of office by one man is one of the greatest dangers of
the peace of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   After 71 years, one party proved to be just as bad. Goodbye and
good riddance.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY
</P>
