<SLUG> BC-ELY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUTINE &HT;    
 &HT;    CONTACT: VERONICA BUCIO 713-220-7733
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WHERE DID SENSE OF RESPONSIBILITY GO?
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course it's distressing American college students, as a
recent survey proves, have little knowledge of American history.
</P>
<P>
   Distressing, but far from surprising.
</P>
<P>
   As an abundance of news leading up to this country's
Independence Day all-too-easily demonstrated, a huge majority of
U.S. citizens have not just forgotten their history, they have
little or no concept of the fantastic willingness of our historic
leaders to assume responsibility for themselves, their actions and
the nation which their beliefs led them to conceive and fight for.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most brutally obvious denial of responsibility came
Friday from President Clinton. He didn't even deign to respond
personally to the recommendation of an Arkansas Supreme Court
committee's suit contending Clinton should be stripped of his law
license for lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only reaction that came to the case against Clinton
came from his attorney, who announced, ``We ... will defend
vigorously against it.'' Remember, this is the president who, in
giving a deposition in another sexual misconduct case, said he had
not had sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky, only to tell a
federal grand jury eight months later he had, in fact, had an
inappropriate intimate relationship with the young woman.
</P>
<P>
   What is especially stomach-wrenching is less that the president,
by his own word, lied, than that the majority of the American
public has never comprehended it is the willful lie under oath _
not the sex _ that betrayed the founding of this country. It seems
few see the true horror of a president unprepared to take
responsibility for his blatant lie and his inability to grasp he
broke faith with the risk those who formed our union accepted for
their cause.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the president is not alone. Less and less do we see
Americans willing to accept the responsibility for their own
actions. More and more, we see a wild and weird inclination on the
part of many to insist that any who disagree with them are evil,
most likely part of a dangerous, un-American conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a columnist, an editorial writer, a newspaper publisher. We
are inundated daily with often-filthy sentiments denouncing us for
crimes we have not committed. We must take responsibility for what
we write and publish, but so must our critics take responsibility
for being able to comprehend what is written.
</P>
<P>
   You want to hate me for what I write, fine. But understand what
I write before slandering me with ignorant declarations I am
un-American.
</P>
<P>
   Un-American. Ha.
</P>
<P>
   What is un-American are those who know only how to hate, who can
only denounce for, too often, the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   What is un-American are crowds running amok and then arguing it
is unfair to prosecute them for destroying property, endangering
lives and resisting, sometimes with violence, agents of the law.
</P>
<P>
   What is un-American is the absurd organization of protests _
demonstrations performed on a schedule in a designated area. If
there are those who are determined to insult the beliefs of a major
political party, let them take responsibility for their dissension.
What value is a belief you're only willing to express with police
protection?
</P>
<P>
   Why should millions of dollars in public funds be used to
provide protection and control for those who come to protest?
Shouldn't the protesters be responsible for their own ways of
demonstrating _ responsible for choosing between a peaceful and
self-confined protest and a destructive, uncontained attack on
those attending political conventions _ or any other legal activity
in this country, such as a licensed family-planning facility?
</P>
<P>
   And if they select the latter form, should they not be deemed
responsible for their foul actions and held accountable for them?
</P>
<P>
   What is un-American? It is a gang of heavily armed men who march
about, claiming _ and being given _ protection under the law to
menace others. Oops, I forgot. I'm only menaced if the loaded gun
is pointed _ maybe fired _ directly at me.
</P>
<P>
   College students don't know American history? Of course, they
don't. How can they learn something so many have forgotten how to
live?
</P>
<P>
   What has brought us to this point?
</P>
<P>
   There may be as many answers to that as there are Americans
still responsible enough to know there is such a question.
</P>
<P>
   I fear it started to fall down around us the day we first were
told it was our responsibility to remove the keys from ours cars so
none would be tempted _ hey, even lured _ into stealing them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
