<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN BEAT BRAZIL, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ Having relied on a coin toss to prevail over
Brazil earlier in the Gold Cup, the United States achieved a more
satisfying result Monday night with a 1-0 victory in an important
tuneup for the Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   A half-volley by forward Tiffeny Milbrett in the 44th minute
gave the Americans the championship in this regional tournament
before 20,123 at Foxboro Stadium. It was their fifth tournament
victory of the year and an encouraging send-off for a series of
matches this month in Europe against China, Norway and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday the United States and Brazil played to a scoreless
tie, finishing group play with identical records, and a coin flip
gave the group title to the United States. Monday night, the
Americans labored to put away a flurry of chances provided by the
assertiveness of Milbrett and the passing of Mia Hamm and escaped
with a shutout victory after a smothering save in the 60th minute
from goalkeeper Siri Mullinix.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday night, China, the 1999 Women's World Cup
runner-up, struggled against Canada in the consolation match before
prevailing, 2-1. The Chinese played this tournament without their
star forward, Sun Wen, who has a knee injury, and the team appeared
tired and overtrained. China's Olympic prospects remain uncertain
with the Summer Games beginning in two months.
</P>
<P>
   Coach April Heinrichs of the United States continued to
experiment with a three-forward lineup, putting Cindy Parlow
alongside Milbrett and Hamm instead of Shannon MacMillan, who has
the hardest shot on the team and who scored two goals in a 4-1
semifinal victory against Canada on Saturday. The Americans had
repeated chances to score in the first half but could not put the
ball into the net until the 44th minute, while Brazil threatened
twice as midfielder Sissi hit the crossbar on a 22-yard shot and
forward Katia volleyed another shot just high in the 29th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett, the Americans' leading scorer on the victorious 1999
World Cup team, spent much of the half in front of the Brazilian
goal, blasting a left-footer just over the crossbar in the 40th
minute. She has great vision and a searing burst of speed in tight
spaces, and it seemed inevitable that she would get a goal. Four
minutes later, Hamm angled a low bouncing pass into the penalty
box, and this time Milbrett expertly one-timed it past the
Brazilian goalkeeper, Andreia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we catch ourselves watching her, she's so
explosive,'' Hamm said of Milbrett. ``I think she's even faster
with the ball at her feet than without.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she led the team in scoring last year, Milbrett has
said that she felt somewhat constricted by the style of Tony
DiCicco, who coached the Americans to the 1996 Olympic title and
the 1999 World Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   With Heinrichs, Milbrett and Hamm say, there is more opportunity
to be creative and to take risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the freedom to go out and express ourselves and not to
worry about making mistakes,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   Until Milbrett scored, the Americans had a paucity of goals
against the world's top teams in recent months, scoring once
against Norway in March and failing to score against China and
Brazil in previous matches. Hamm is the career leading scorer in
the women's game, but she ranks fifth on the American team this
year, with seven goals. When she is not scoring, the United States
often finds it difficult to manufacture goals, but one
characteristic of Hamm's career has been her continued willingness
to pass the ball and play defense when her offense eludes her. Her
assist to Milbrett Monday night gave her 10 this year, tops among
the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Mullinix, the American goalkeeper, whose play has been notable
for her aggressive roving in the penalty box, prevented the tying
goal in the 60th minute after Sissi played a pass to Cidinha behind
the American defense. Left alone in front of the U.S. goal, Cidinha
hesitated slightly, and Mullinix charged six yards off her line to
smother the ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
