<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v R-PM-BUDGET-NYT     07-04 2340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 R-PM-BUDGET-NYT 
(Repeats to delete FASHION-BRIEFS, which will move later
Tuesday.)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, July 4.
</P>
<P>
   The PM news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time. To
get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns on
AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SALVADOR-U.S. (San Salvador, El Salvador) _ The United States
has touched a nerve in El Salvador by seeking to set up a military
logistics point for its war on drugs in a country where American
advisers, intelligence and money not long ago helped fuel a
devastating civil war. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-MINORITIES (Los Angeles) _ At some unknown moment between
now and next July 1, if state demographers are right, California
will become the first big state in the nation in which non-Hispanic
whites are officially no longer a majority. Or to put it another
way, California will become by far the largest proving ground for
what it may eventually be like to live in a United States in which
no one racial or ethnic group predominates. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT16, and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BROWNSTONE-REVIVAL (Portland, Conn.) _ Brownstone is back. That
somber yet elegant cloak for more than 50,000 row houses, from
Baltimore to Boston, was revered during the so-called Brown Decades
of the mid-19th century, then reviled by the century's turn, when
gleaming white limestone and marble captivated the public. But
preservationists and planners are beginning to see a new future for
the formidable stone. Architects have started using it to give a
touch of historical sobriety to gaudy mansionettes, and
conservators have begun renewing the elegant facades of grand
monuments. But the revival has sparked a debate on whether
brownstone should be used at all. Because the terrible secret is
that brownstone isn't really much good as a building material. By
Tracie Rohzan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT8.
</P>
<P>
   SYPHILIS-ERADICATE (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Even here, where the
syphilis rate is the second-highest in the country among major
cities, topped only by Indianapolis, the numbers are less than
staggering: Only 250 cases of new _ and thus still infectious _
syphilis turned up last year. Nationwide, they dropped below 7,000,
down from the most recent peak of 50,000 in 1990. But that is the
very point, health officials say. Now, when new cases are at an
all-time low, is the time to try to wipe it out altogether. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   DIMAGGIO-PARK (San Francisco) _ The playground is still your
basic city model: Two and a third acres of asphalt, with swings and
monkey bars, a baseball field. The playground probably looks a lot
as it did when Joe DiMaggio, the fisherman's son, was learning how
to turn a bat into a lightning bolt and a hard ball into a whirling
dervish. He played baseball here and made the North Beach
playground famous as the humble beginning of one of the great
baseball players of all time. So when DiMaggio died last year, it
seemed natural to rename the playground in his honor. What DiMaggio
would make of the fight over the renaming of the playground is
anyone's guess. But Morris Engelberg, the Florida lawyer in charge
of guarding the Joe DiMaggio name, apparently believes his old
friend deserves more and is fighting a legal battle to stop the
renaming. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BUSH-COMPARE (Washington) _ With their competing array of
policy speeches, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush
seem to be turning this election into a referendum on which
candidate can best reshape government to meet the challenges of the
New Economy. From health care, to education, to tax cuts to Social
Security, Bush and Gore are placing before the voters significant
questions about how some of the most fundamental public
institutions should be shaped for a global, Digital Age that offers
the prospect of unprecedented prosperity _ and enormous
uncertainty. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT15.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-BUSINESS (Undated) _ In the world of Internet startups,
where a typical chief executive is 30 and a labor shortage
continues even as some Web companies fail, dot-commers are
recruiting their own parents. This curious form of nepotism is
upending traditional notions about family businesses. By Katie
Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-SIGNATURES (Undated) _ The law that President Clinton
signed last week allowing businesses and consumers to seal a wide
variety of legally binding arrangements with electronic rather than
handwritten signatures raised the speed limit on e-business
development, analysts say. They project that many enterprises awash
in documents, especially financial services, real estate and
government itself, will accelerate efforts to use computer
transactions to limit paperwork once the law takes effect in
October. Such a transition is expected to save billions of dollars
annually in administrative costs and cut some online transactions _
like setting up a trading account or applying for a home loan _
from days to minutes. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE _ (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GREEK-FOSSILS (Undated) _ A classical folklorist and
independent scholar has dug deep into the past and found literary
and artistic clues _ and not a few huge fossils _ that seem to
explain the inspiration for many of the giants, monsters and other
strange creatures in the mythology of antiquity. Greeks'
perceptions about fossils, she discovered, were quite amazing for
prescientific people. Her years of research thus challenge the
widely held view that natural historians in classical Greece and
Rome lacked the knowledge to interpret large vertebrate fossils as
organic remains of the past. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROTEIN-SHAPES (San Diego) _ With the human genome sequence
nearly complete, scientists are gearing up for a follow-on project
that some say could be every bit as ambitious. The endeavor is
known as structural genomics and involves trying to determine the
three-dimensional shapes of thousands upon thousands of proteins,
much as genomics determined the sequences of genes en masse.
Knowing the shape of the protein lock could make it easier to
design drugs that act as keys, binding to some particular protein
and turning it on or off. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROTEIN-XRAY (Undated) _ Protein shapes are usually
discerned by X-ray crystallography, a process that in some ways
resembles a CAT scan. An X-ray is taken from multiple angles and a
computer uses that data to calculate a three-dimensional image.
With SCI-PROTEIN-SHAPES. By Andrw Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SAGE-GROUSE (Undated) _ A new species of bird has emerged
from research in the sagebrush ecosystem of western Colorado and
eastern Utah, according to scientists working there. The bird, the
Gunnison sage grouse, named for the area of Colorado where it was
discovered, has been in plain view all along _ seen, hunted as a
game bird and, most spectacularly, heard at sunrise every spring as
part of one of the avian world's oddest courtship rituals. But it
had long been assumed to be the same species as the related
northern sage grouse, even though the two differ starkly in size,
appearance, behavior. By Jon Luoma.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ENVIRON-RIVETS (Undated) _ In trying to illuminate what
humans are doing to the natural environment, scientists and
conservationists over the years have come up with a number of
descriptive images. One of the best known is the metaphor of the
rivets. In this formulation, an ecosystem is likened to an
airplane: Each act of environmental destruction _ the extinction of
a species of plant or animal, for instance _ is akin to removing a
rivet from the plane. At first, the losses make little difference,
because there are lots of rivets. But if enough are removed or a
few are taken away at crucial spots, the plane will crash. An essay
by William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YOUNG-FISH (Undated) _ The typical saltwater fish's
childhood is something of a lost time, at least for scientists
trying to study it. Not much is known about what happens during
most fishes' larval stages, when they are tiny and floating in the
plankton in the swirling waters. And that has led to a great
question in marine ecology: Are fish populations open, with young
fish shuttling in and out across great distances, or closed, with
juveniles largely settling back where they were born? By Henry
Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VIRTUAL-MEDICINE (Seattle) _ Virtual reality now is being
used in medicine: It's helping distract burn patients so they feel
less pain, it's being used to alleviate phobias and it's even
helping people to relax and unclog blood vessels. By Jim Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LOCAL-ANESTHESIA (Undated) _ Doctors recently performed a
heart bypass on a patient using only a local anesthesia. It was
believed to be the first such operation in the United States, but
some doctors are optimistic that many more now can be done, at
least in certain circumstances, like a single bypass. By Denise
Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PSYCHIATRY (Undated) _ A complex but pervasive problem in
psychiatry: It can be frustrating and, at times, nigh impossible,
to sort out where ``reality'' lies in the no man's land between the
patient's preconceptions and distortions of reality and those of
the therapist. In the strange, delicate, dyadic relationship
between patient and therapist, the events of the outside world can
become surprisingly elusive. The case of a patient claiming to be a
famous European artist illustrates the point. By Anna Fels, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-BOOK (Undated) _ Books on Health: With thousands of
cancer patients seeking alternative and complementary medicine,
``The Journey Through Cancer'' by Dr. Jeremy Geffen seems a timely
addition to the medical bookshelf. By Laurie Tarkan.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEDICINE-SUPERSTITION (Undated) _ Don't take the scientist's
objective observation for granted, cautions Dr. Sherwin B. Nuland
in ``The Mysteries Within.'' Until the 19th century, the greatest
thinkers in medicine (Hippocrates, Galen, Paracelsus) turned to
supernatural powers, superstition, fanciful spirits and energies to
fill the holes in their medical theories. By Laurie Tarkan.
</P>
<P>
   VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study shows that the blood vessels of vigorous older
people functioned as well as those of athletes less than half their
age.
</P>
<P>
   _ A hormone produced in pregnancy has been found to reduce
symptoms of scleroderma, a debilitating skin disease that has
previously been considered untreatable, a study says.
</P>
<P>
   _ The chickenpox vaccine is working on both children who take it
and on those who don't. Rates are way down for the contagious
disease in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Migraine headaches strike teenagers most commonly on Mondays
and most rarely on Saturdays, according to a study presented in
June. But researchers do not think that malingering is the reason:
Instead, it probably is stress, anxiety or changing sleep patterns.
</P>
<P>
   _ The most detailed study to date of the acute respiratory
attacks suffered by sickle-cell anemia patients has led researchers
to call for more aggressive tactics in diagnosis and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
