<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-UPDATING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIND TAKES ITS TOLL ON ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 GLAUS' STATS IN FOURTH GRAF-LBPT (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Big Five the Angels have counted on for
most of their offense --- Darin Erstad, Mo Vaughn, Tim Salmon,
Garret Anderson and Troy Glaus --- have also been counted upon to
be in the lineup everyday.
</P>
<P>
   They've missed a total of eight games this season, which reached
the halfway point Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy load, however, may be taking a toll.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, who played in the first 71 games, sat out back-to-back
games last week with back spasms and is 2 for 26 with 16 strikeouts
since.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's Erstad, the Angels best player in the first half, who
is sidelined with a bad back. He was in the DH spot on Sunday and
was slated to play there again Monday, but was scratched just
before game time.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad leads the American League in hits (130), is second in
batting average (.371) and has driven home 59 runs --- tied for
second on the team --- from his leadoff position.
</P>
<P>
   Giants manager Dusty Baker has likened the last week before the
All-Star break to the final minute of a basketball team --- it's a
chance to carry some momentum into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia couldn't disagree more with his former
Dodger teammate. Even as the Angels embarked upon a four-game
series with the first-place Mariners leading up to next week's
break, Scioscia isn't putting any extra importance on this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put a lot of stock in the leading up to the All-Star
break,'' Scioscia said. ``I put a lot of stock in the grind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to (former Notre Dame basketball coach) Digger Phelps
the last time we were in Seattle and he'd look at the schedule and
say we had to be 4-1 in this group. There's a lot of successful
coaches who look at it like that, but I never have as a player,
coach or in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it does two things. First, it set in complacency if
you approach your goal. Second, it ignites a little panic if you're
behind. I think you play the game hard, try to carry some momentum
if you can and turn the page.''
</P>
<P>
   All-Star Game starters will be announced today, and pitchers and
reserves will be announced Wednesday for next week's game in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, the expected starter with leading vote-getter Cal Ripken
out, and Erstad, as a reserve, are locks. If the Angels get a third
player, it could be rookie Bengie Molina, who is having a terrific
season at bat and behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Molina entered Monday night's game batting .309 with 8 homers
and 35 RBI, and had thrown out 36 percent of runners trying to
steal.
</P>
<P>
   Today: Gil Meche (4-4, 3.49 ERA) vs. Kent Bottenfield (4-7,
5.60), 7:05 p.m.; TV: Fox Sports Net. Radio: KLAC/570 AM and
XPRS/1090 AM.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 0237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2640 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-04 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS HOLD ON TO CLIP ANGELS; SASAKI EARNS 17TH SAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ A day at the beach was just what Seattle
manager Lou Piniella thought he needed, so the Florida beach bum
that lurks just under Piniella's skin set out for a two-mile walk
Monday afternoon on Newport Beach, just 20 miles from the Mariners'
team hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But if Piniella thought Monday night was going to be another
kind of day at the beach, he quickly lost that illusion.
</P>
<P>
   Three different five-run leads proved to be castles made of sand
as the Mariners had to fight relentlessly to keep Anaheim at bay
for an 8-6 victory that pushed Seattle's lead over Oakland in the
AL West to 2{ games.
</P>
<P>
   Kazuhiro Sasaki preserved what his teammates had built, getting
the final three outs of the game with the tying runs on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about Sasaki from Pat Mahomes when I was in New
York,'' Mariners left fielder Rickey Henderson said. ``He said the
guy was great, but I didn't believe him. But I know what he was
talking about now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps his poise out there. He doesn't give in.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his 17th save went into the books, Sasaki opened the
ninth by being nicked for a single that Mo Vaughn somehow sneaked
through the right side of the infield, with three infielders
stacked to prevent just that. Then after getting ahead of Tim
Salmon with two quick strikes, Sasaki walked Salmon by missing with
the next four, although he was clearly far from enamored with the
calls of home-plate umpire Mike Winters.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Garret Anderson, who had homered twice and doubled,
Sasaki missed with his first pitch. Piniella told pitching coach
Bryan Price to go out and settle Sasaki down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him not to overthrow,'' Price said. ``If he throws
his good stuff, that was going to be enough to get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Price, who had obviously consulted Tarot cards before the
conversation, was dead on. Anderson flew out. Troy Glaus, who had
snapped an 0-for-20 streak earlier, struck out on three pitches.
And Benjie Molina, who had homered, brought the game to a close
just six minutes short of four hours when he flew out to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He impressed me with his poise and the way he rebounded in
that situation,'' Price said of Sasaki. ``They've got a formidable
lineup, a lot of thunder.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Sasaki, the night belonged to John Olerud. The Mariners
first baseman drove in four runs with a sacrifice fly and a
three-run double as the Mariners built up a lead of 5-0 after 1{
innings.
</P>
<P>
   But after those leads, and margins of 6-1 and 7-2, had all but
been washed away by the relentless Angels, Olerud came up with a
defensive play to save the day. With two on and one out in the
eighth and Seattle clinging to an 8-6 lead, Olerud dived headlong
to his left to steal a game-tying, two-run double from Angels
pinch-hitter Adam Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, batting with runners at first and second with one out,
seemed to have gotten the ball past Olerud. But Olerud used all of
his 6 feet, 5 inches to spear the ball, popped up and threw to
reliever Jose Mesa covering first base for the out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could have been a triple if it gets by him,'' Piniella
said. ``That was a terrific play, because the game was going to be
tied.''
</P>
<P>
   Once past that obstacle, the Mariners soldiered on for their
third straight win and 11th victory in their past 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to close out the first half strong,''
Henderson said. ``It's important for us to go from here to the
All-Star break (Sunday) good and hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners starter Jamie Moyer (7-3) was gifted thrice by leads of
five runs _ 5-0, 6-1 and 7-2 _ but the Angels are a team that
generally hits the left-hander hard, and with center fielder Garret
Anderson leading the way, they did it again.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hit solo homers off Moyer in the second and fourth
innings, then added an RBI double in the sixth as the Angels scored
four times, cutting the deficit to 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Up to that point, Moyer had been doing what he does best _
grazing the boundaries of the strike zone with all manner of
pitches fast and slow, keeping the Angels off balance and, with the
exception of Anderson, off the scoreboard as well.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels' offense, one of the most potent in the game,
refused to be denied. Again, Anderson was in the middle of it.
Salmon and Anderson doubled with one out in the sixth for a run,
Troy Glaus singled a run home and Molina hit a first-pitch homer
off Moyer to get Anaheim close.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Moyer, who entered the game with a 6-7 record and
career 5.91 earned-run average against the Angels, turned the ball
over to Brett Tomko. The right-hander, making just his third
appearance since coming off the disabled list June 25, struggled a
bit but managed to keep the game ever so slightly in the Mariners'
favor at 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson got the Mariners a bit of a cushion with a two-out RBI
double in the seventh for an 8-6 lead. It could have been more than
that, but Anderson made a terrific running catch against Mike
Cameron to take a double and a run away from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   That was just part of Anderson Night at Edison Field _ in
addition to two homers and a double, he made a nice running catch
against Joe Oliver with the bases loaded in the first.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
