<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS FALL SEVEN GAMES BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The state of the Angels' pitching rotation
these days is making Manager Mike Scioscia's stomach churn, as Ken
Hill joined the growing legion of veteran starters who look lately
as if they're over the hill.
</P>
<P>
   One day after Tim Belcher was knocked out in the first inning by
Oakland, Hill was tattooed by Seattle for five runs in 1 fr 2/3
innings, which sent the Mariners on their way to an 8-6 victory
Monday night before 20,919 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The loss drops the Angels a season-high seven games back in the
AL West and a few more this week could drop them out of sight by
the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who attacked the plate in his first start off the disabled
list --- a 3-2 victory last week at Seattle --- never had command
of any of his pitches, routinely bouncing breaking balls and
missing high and wide with his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Hill walked five and allowed five hits, the last of which was
John Olerud's two-out, bases loaded double on a 3-2 pitch that gave
Seattle a 5-0 lead. He was so lost he went into the tunnel between
innings and threw balls into a screen, searching for a better feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a difference a week can make,'' said Hill, who insisted
the strained rib cage muscle that sidelined him for 42 games was
fine. ``I just didn't feel good. My body was tight. It was one of
those days.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Angel veterans in the rotation, Belcher and tonight's
starter Kent Bottenfield, have been having too many of those days
lately. Each has struggled in his last two starts and over the past
month, Manager Mike Scioscia's most reliable starters have been a
pair of 25-year-olds, Brian Cooper and Jarrod Washburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``His velocity was good,'' Scioscia said of Hill. ``But he was
behind too many hitters and he couldn't make a pitch to put some of
their guys away.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he was thinking of when he walked to the dugout after
being pulled, Hill smiled and said, ``The bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   After Belcher's short start, ``the last thing I want to do is go
and inning and two-thirds,'' Hill said. ``At least if I struggle, I
can go five or six innings. Those guys are doing the best they can,
but they get tired too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels rode a spectacular effort by center fielder Garret
Anderson to get back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson made an over-the-shoulder catch of Joe Oliver's
two-out, bases-loaded drive to center field that limited Seattle to
two runs in the first. In the seventh, he made a similar catch to
rob Mike Cameron of a double and an RBI.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate, Anderson hit solo homers in the second and fourth,
both times pulling fastballs from left-hander Jaime Moyer into the
right-field seats. In the sixth, he went with a changeup into the
left-center gap for an RBI double that closed the Angels' gap to
7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus snapped an 0 for 20 skid, going the opposite way on a
3-2 changeup and Bengie Molina followed by hitting Moyer's next
pitch over the left-field fence and suddenly the Angels were within
7-6.
</P>
<P>
   But Mariner relievers Brett Tomko, Arthur Rhodes, Jose Mesa and
Kazuhiro Sasaki shut out the Angels the rest of the way, though
they did get a huge assist from John Olerud. The Seattle first
baseman made a diving stop to rob pinch hitter Adam Kennedy of a
game-tying double in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club is mentally tough,'' Scioscia said. ``Even when we
were down four or five runs, we were working to get back into it.
But their bullpen has been doing the job all year. They tough when
you get down there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
