<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZONA-REPUBLIC </SLUG>
  
The Scottsdale City Council moves one step closer to naming its
first female city manager.1st female city manager likely
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scottsdale ready
</P>
<P>
   to begin talksScottsdale could name its first female city
manager as early as July 11.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour behind closed doors Saturday, the City Council
unanimously voted to start negotiations with Jan Dolan, 47, the
longtime city manager in Menlo Park, Calif. Dolan retired from that
post Friday after leading the Silicon Valley suburb for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   A formal appointment could come at the council meeting on July
11. If selected, Dolan would be the first woman to run a major
Valley city, operating a budget of $894 million and overseeing
2,200 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very impressed with her as a human being and as a
manager,'' Mayor Mary Manross said. ``At this point, I don't
anticipate any sticking points in hiring her. She is a top-notch
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Menlo Park officials and neighborhood activists praise the
Montana native for her fiscal skills and her work in low-income
neighborhoods. Dolan spearheaded a library and health clinic
project in Belle Haven, once called the ``other'' Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan, one of 70 people who applied for the job, worked for six
city councils and 11 mayors during her 10 years in Menlo Park. She
was paid $120,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at
</P>
<P>
   Chip.Scutari(a)Arizona Republic.com or (602) 444-7482.
</P>
