A2695 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-CELLPHONES-TAYLO     07-04 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-CELLPHONES-TAYLOR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRELESS AND WITLESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, July 5, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a separate-buy' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By SHARON WHITE TAYLOR    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WETHERSFIELD, Conn. _ I am about to commit a new millennium
offense for which there is no punishment. In fact, I am sure many
will hail me as a hero.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I'm going to do: The next time I'm in the grocery
store and see someone yakking away on a cell phone, oblivious to
the fact that her grocery cart is blocking the aisle, I will reach
out and press the off button.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about road rage. I am afflicted with a new syndrome, let's
call it ``cell phone rage.'' Try driving behind one of these
wireless scofflaws on the highway as he drives 20 mph, too busy
talking to obey the speed limit. I would feel justified pulling out
a bullhorn and directing, ``Hang up the phone. Hang up the phone
now!''
</P>
<P>
   I am not alone. Signs are beginning to pop up prohibiting cell
phones in certain areas. One New Jersey town has even introduced
one of the country's first local ordinances banning the use of cell
phones while driving.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant owners are creating special sections for cell phone
users. School districts are cracking down on students talking on
phones in the hallways and classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many phone users continue to talk loudly _ and
anywhere. People seem to think every place is a good place to talk
on the phone: the doctor's office, the theater, even funerals. My
cousin told me about one encounter with a man who was sitting under
a sign prohibiting cell phone use and took a call anyway. When my
cousin pointed to the sign, the man apologized and hung up. But a
few minutes later the man's telephone rang again and he took the
call, without even moving from the prohibited area.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who use cell phones are also guilty of broadcasting
too much private information. I don't care about the hives on your
elbow or your Saturday night plans to dine with Joe and Ethel. Save
the gossip about your brother-in-law cheating on your sister with
her best friend. I don't need to know. Lower your voice; you are
not at home or in a telephone booth.
</P>
<P>
   It seems we need more than laws to change this kind of
discourteous _ and even dangerous _ behavior. I say it is time for
the cell phone police to step forward and devise some cell phone
etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   (Sharon White Taylor is a former writer for the Hartford
Courant.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
