<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, July 5:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS-FOX (Mexico City) _ President-elect Vincente Fox
is scheduled to hold a press conference. By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ The Institutional Revolutionary
Party, which lost the presidency in Sunday's elections after more
than 70 years in power, will meet Tuesday to choose a new leader.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-POLITICS (Havana) _ A top Cuban official, Ricardo Alarcon,
says in an interview that the government wants to capitalize on the
momentum created by Elian Gonzalez's return to Cuba to create
anti-U.S. embargo fervor. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-SPY (Paris) _ A French state prosecutor has launched a
preliminary judicial investigation into the workings of the United
States global surveillance system, Echelon, which is said to be
capable of sifting through millions of telephone calls, faxes and
e-mails a day. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Developments following the suicide
bombings of Russian military barracks by Chechen rebels. By Michael
R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-SCHOOL (Undated) _ More students than ever before are
enrolled in summer school this season, as districts throughout the
country _ led by those in major cities _ require or strongly
encourage younger and younger students to attend classes to shore
up basic reading and mathematical skills. Educational experts
believe summer school helps address the yawning academic gaps
between poor, minority students and white middle-class ones, by
slowing the ``summer slide,'' in which children forget study
skills, discipline habits and vocabulary words between Memorial Day
and Labor Day. But many are worried that the mushrooming programs,
many of which are mandatory for students who fail to meet promotion
standards, will simply repeat ineffective instructional approaches
and frustrate struggling students with endless drills for
high-stakes exams. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-GUNS (Denver) _ A ballot initiative to close the gun show
loophole is approved in Colorado and the NRA vows to fight it. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-PAY (Philadelphia) _ According to a new study released
at Tuesday's meeting of the American Federation of Teachers,
teacher salaries have risen an average of only 3 percent in recent
years and remain far below other professions. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   LOW-BIRTH-WEIGHT (Undated) _ Babies born weighing less than five
and a half pounds are almost four times less likely to graduate
from high school by age 19 than their normal-birth weight siblings,
according to a study published in the latest issue of the American
Sociological Review. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-MEMORIAL (Washington) _ Thousands of Vietnam veterans
whose names never made it onto the wall at the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial in Washington because they did not die from battle-related
injuries or accidents will now be honored there, though not by
name. By Renwick McClean.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALZHEIMER (Undated) _ A new study reports that people with
advanced Alzheimer's Disease who break a hip or develop pneumonia
are likely to die within 6 months and should be kept comfortable
and spared painful medical procedures. Currently, the authors say,
such patients are subjected to many needless procedures, and are
not given enough pain medicine. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY-PRICES (Undated) _ After a summer of high gasoline
prices, consumers may be in for another shock this winter, as the
rising cost of heating oil and natural gas threaten to make it
significantly more expensive to heat American homes. By Neela
Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Faced with fresh evidence that the economy
is accelerating, Japan's central bank could soon raise interest
rates, which have been at an effective rate of zero for more than a
year. Such a move would be the first rate increase in Japan in
nearly a decade. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TELEPHONE (Undated) _ A look at Internet telephony, the
growing use of the Internet to make telephone calls, basically for
free. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-TELEKOM-SPRINT (Frankfurt) _ Deutsche Telekom has taken
some preliminary steps to make a bid for Sprint if its merger
agreement with WorldCom is scrapped. By Edmund L. Andrews and
Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-U.S.-MERGERS (London) _ The number and value of mergers
and acquisitions in Europe soared in the second quarter of the
year, and many of the target companies were in the United States.
By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column: A look
at air travel delays. By Nancy Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-AIR-KLM (London) _ British Airways and KLM could lay off
as many as 6000 employees if their planned merger proceeds.
European regulators are also likely to require them to sell their
low-cost subsidiaries. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKHSTAN-U.S.-OIL (Moscow) _ The head of Kazakhstan's
state-run oil company has denied allegations that he and other
Kazak officials accepted bribes from U.S. oil companies. By Sabrina
Tavernise.
</P>
<P>
   Editors, U.S. markets are closed for the Independence Day
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ With a swiftness that has surprised
and puzzled educators, law schools have gained the advantage in
their long tug of war with business schools for the attention of
corporate America's future elite. At virtually every top business
school, the number of applicants fell last spring, and some of the
numbers are startling. At the University of Chicago, they dropped
24 percent. At Cornell, the dip was 23 percent, and at Stanford, it
was 18 percent. As a result, it is considerably less difficult to
gain admission to some business schools than it was a few years
ago, and school officials have relaxed their requirements for work
experience and stepped up overseas recruiting efforts. By David
Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   SIEBEL-BOSS (Undated) _ Thomas M. Siebel, chairman and chief
executive officer, Siebel Systems Inc., a maker of e-business
application software
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krugman's ``Reckonings.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd is on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports, and
