<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, July 5:
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAE (Undated) _ Reinventing the classic: high-end New York
chefs try their hand with the ice cream scoop. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERTS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Wayne Harley Brachman's ``Retro
Desserts'' and Tish Boyle's ``Diner Desserts,'' reviewed by
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   GRILL-EATING-WELL (Undated) _ The height of the barbecue season
is not when anyone wants to hear about the health hazards of eating
meat with nicely blackened crust hot off the grill. But scientists
have known for a long time that the substances created when meat
and poultry are cooked at high heat can cause cancer in animals and
that there is some evidence that they may have the same effect on
humans. And while health professionals still recommend cutting back
on overall meat consumption to reduce the risk, recent research
suggests that there are more appealing ways to make grilled meat
less hazardous. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   With marinade recipes.
</P>
<P>
   BRESAOLA (Undated) _ Bresaola, the genuine air-dried beef from
northern Italy, has quietly begun being imported to the United
States. By Rozanne Gold.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Whole meal salads,
starting with sesame scallops on lettuce. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   LEMONADE (Undated) _ Making better lemonade. By Melissa Clark.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Tuna burgers. By Michel
Richard.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   GOAT-BUTTER (Undated) _ Tasting goat butter is like tasting
pinot noir for the first time when all you've ever had is merlot.
It's creamy, gentle, lighter than cow butter and, well, goat-y. By
Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The column: Summer wines for elegant meals
and rustic picnics. By Frank Prial.
</P>
<P>
   TASTINGS (Undated) _ The column: Merlots from Long Island. By
Eric Asimov.
</P>
