 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 Wine Potpourri: Grapes of Ancient Rome Thrive Again in Southern 
 Italy   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Scratch a lover of Italian wine and the first
words of admiration are not likely to be about the wines of
Campania. Tuscany and Piedmont are the standard choices for the big
reds that seem to characterize modern Italian wine.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the distinctive wines of Campania, a southern region known
as ``the ankle of the boot,'' predate any Tuscan Chianti and
Piemontese Barolo. About 3,000 years ago, the Greeks first planted
vines near what is now Naples, the major city in Campania. When the
Romans arrived 1,000 years later, they planted more vines. The
culture spread throughout the country, but thrived in the  &LR; campania
felix &LR; , or happy countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Modern winemaking in Campania is closely identified with
Mastroberardino, a specialist in the wines of antiquity. The
Mastroberardino family's involvement in winemaking can be traced
back to 1580. In the late 1700s, the family built a winery in
Atripaldacq &LR; , although it was not until 1878 that the winery was
formally established.
</P>
<P>
   Today, brothers Antonio and Walter, and sons Piero and Carlo run
the winery 40 miles northeast of Naples. Using the family's
extensive library of ancient books on viticulture and winemaking
during Greek and Roman times, the Mastroberardinos have
successfully cultivated grapes that were popular centuries ago. In
recognition of the dedication to the wines of antiquity, the
Italian government has awarded them the project of replanting
ancient vineyards amid the ruins of Pompeii.
</P>
<P>
   Employing modern winemaking techniques, such as refrigerated
stainless-steel tanks and rotary fermenters, Mastroberardino
produces intense and distinctive wines from grapes like Aglianico,
Fiano di Avellino, Coda di Volpe and Greco di Tufo.
</P>
<P>
   Aglianico is the grape of Mastroberardino's flagship red,
Taurasi, a rich wine with pronounced tannins that often is compared
to the Nebbiolo-based wines of Piedmont. In fact, Taurasi sometimes
is called the ``Barolo of the South.'' Aglianico also is the
primary grape in Mastro Rosso, the winery's entry-level unwooded
red.
</P>
<P>
   Fiano di Avellino grapes were introduced to the region 2,000
years ago by the Romans. Roman writer Pliny The Elder noted the
grapes were irresistible to bees, and thus dubbed the vine Vitis
Apiana, or ``beloved by bees.'' Fiano di Avellino has a honeyed
aroma and the subtle flavor of hazelnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Greco di Tufo was brought to the region by the Greeks and takes
part of its name from the tufo soil of the region. Greco di Tufo is
dry and rich with the intriguing taste of toasted almonds.
</P>
<P>
   Coda di Volpe, a white grape from Roman times that thrives in
the volcanic soils on the lower slopes of Mt. Vesuvius, is the
grape of Lacryma Christi del Vesuvio Bianco. Noting the clusters of
grapes resembled a fox tail, Pliny the Elder dubbed the vine Coda
di Volpe. The grape also is used to make Mastro Bianco, the white
companion to Mastro Rosso.
</P>
<P>
   Mastroberardino wines are available in restaurants and fine wine
shops. Prices range from a high of $40 for Taurasi to $20 for Greco
di Tufo and $12 for Mastro Rosso and Mastro Bianco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Tears of Christ &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Many stories are told about the origin of the name for Lacryma
Christi del Vesuvio, one of the popular wines from Campania. My
favorite is the one that has God casting Lucifer out of heaven,
with the devil falling from grace and landing in the water off
Southern Italy, forming the Bay of Naples. God was so sad that when
he wept, vines sprang up where his tears struck the soil on the
slopes of Mt. Vesuvius.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Viva Vya &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Andy Quady, the determined and venturesome winemaker who
convinced the wine world that California was capable of making
top-quality fortified wines, scored a coup recently with his Vya
Vermouth.
</P>
<P>
   Quady took on Martini, the traditional Italian producer of
vermouth, at ``The Heavyweight Vermouth Championship of the World''
at Boisdale Scottish restaurant in London, and came out on top.
</P>
<P>
   The judges, mainly barmen from some of London's leading
restaurants, declared Vya (Sweet and Extra Dry) superior to Martini
(Sweet and Dry). Both styles of Vya, priced at $15, are available
in wine retail shops throughout the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Spirits Contest &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The first San Francisco World Spirits Competition will be
September 15-17 at the Park Hyatt Hotel. An off-shoot of the San
Francisco International Wine Competition, the spirits competition
will employ 30 judges to taste and rate hundreds of spirits,
brandies and liqueurs. For more information, call (415) 345-9000 or
log on to  &LR; www.sfspiritscomp.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Under Italian law, wines are approved in four categories. The
least definitive are  &LR; vino da tavola &LR; , wines that may not specify a
grape variety, vintage or place of origin, and IG ( &LR; indicazione &LR; 
 &LR; geografica &LR; ) wines, those that express the ``typical'' character
of a region or commune. Next come the  &LR; denominazione di &LR;   &LR; origine
controllata &LR;  (D.O.C) wines; and finally  &LR; denominazione &LR;   &LR; di origine
controllata e garantita &LR;  (D.O.C.G), the highest ranking,
guaranteeing the authenticity of wines of ``particular esteem.''
There are others, but these are the basic four.
</P>
<P>
   DOCG status has been granted to only 15 wines, including Taurasi
from Campania. The others are Barolo, Barbaresco, Brunello di
Montalcino and Vino Nobile di Montepulciano _ the original four _
and Albana di Romagna in Emilia Romagna; Chianti, Carmignano and
Vernaccio di San Gimignano in Tuscany, Asti Spumante, Moscato
d'Asti and Gattinara in Piedmont; Torgiano Rosso Riserva and
Sagrantino di Montefalco in Umbria. And on June 15, the legislature
added Frascati in the Latium region to the prestigious list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
