 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 Best Way: Summertime Margaritas   By Andy Lax 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Love or hate Jimmy Buffet, you have to admit he's
on to something _ a good margarita. With its quenching pucker of
lime, a cool pitcher of margaritas is the perfect drink for a
summer celebration.
<P>
   Though the summer may encourage laziness, that doesn't mean you
should slack off when it comes to making your margaritas. In order
to bring you the perfect margarita, willing Food staffers sampled a
number of variations.
</P>
<P>
   For our tests, we based our margarita on the following recipe: 2
ounces tequila, 11/2 ounces lime juice, and 3/4 ounce orange
liqueur.
</P>
<P>
   Our first step was to determine the best orange liqueur to use _
Triple Sec, Cointreau or Grand Marnier. Although it's traditional,
we found the Triple Sec margarita too sweet. On the other end of
the spectrum, the Grand Marnier was too tart. Our favorite was the
margarita made with Cointreau, which struck a good balance and
provided the brightest flavor.
</P>
<P>
   While the classic recipe doesn't call for sweet-and-sour mix,
many bartenders add it to their margaritas, and department tasters
found that adding about 1 tablespoon of the commercial mix made for
a better drink. In comparison, the one without it tasted a bit
harsh.
</P>
<P>
   As California food-lovers, we always proclaim the virtues of
fresh ingredients, so we were surprised that most of us preferred
the margarita made with Rose's sweetened lime juice rather than the
one made with freshly squeezed juice.
</P>
<P>
   While the bottled juice gave the margarita a neon color, the
drink was smoother and more balanced. On the other hand, the
fresh-juice margarita did have a markedly fresher taste. The extra
sweetness of the Rose's version, however, gave it the advantage. If
you want the sweetness but want to use fresh juice, mix the juice
with a simple syrup made with equal parts of sugar and water.
</P>
<P>
   All tequilas are not created equal. Fine sipping tequilas are
made with 100 percent blue agave, while less refined tequilas need
only contain 51 percent. We tested a margarita made with Herradura
Silver, a 100 percent blue agave tequila, against Cuervo Gold,
which includes added fermented cane juice. Though the Herradura is
a superior spirit, it does not necessarily make a superior
margarita. It tasted clean and crisp, but those staffers with a
penchant for sweets liked the added sugar in the Cuervo Gold
margarita. However, many bars use Cuervo Gold so it may be what
most people are used to.
</P>
<P>
   As a last test, we took our winning recipe and tried it two
ways: strained over crushed ice and blended. Here, personal
preference rules. Some like the refreshing iciness of the blended
margarita, likening it to an ``adult Sno-Kone.'' Others feel the
blended drink is too diluted and prefer the version on-the-rocks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There was no clear-cut favorite, but the following recipe was
the overall winner. Your own taste may call for alterations.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BEST WAY MARGARITA
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces 100 percent blue agave tequila (such as Herradura
Silver)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 ounces Rose's sweetened lime juice (or fresh squeezed)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 ounce Cointreau
</P>
<P>
   Splash sweet-and-sour mix
</P>
<P>
   Fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Fill a glass or cocktail shaker with ice. Add all ingredients
except lime juice and salt. Shake vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   Dip the rim of a margarita glass into lime juice and then into
salt. Fill the glass with crushed ice.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the margarita into the ice-filled glass and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Alternately, combine ingredients in a blender filled with ice.
Blend until thoroughly mixed. Pour into a margarita glass and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 1
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
