 CHRON  
 Cook's Books: McNair Salutes the Wine Country   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  In the interest of full disclosure, I have to
preface this review with a confession: I am a devoted James McNair
fan.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether this Renaissance man of the kitchen trains his sights on
newfangled pizzas or old-fashioned cakes, the resulting volumes are
everything a cookbook should be: precise and concise, easy to
follow, interesting without getting precious, and accessible for
the home cook.
</P>
<P>
   His latest _ number 35 _ is no exception, though it is somewhat
of a departure. As the title implies, ``The Sutter Home Napa Valley
Cookbook'' is a cooperative effort between the author and the
Trinchero family, the people who own Sutter Home Winery. While
McNair remains true to his usual style, many of the recipes hark to
the Trinchero clan's Italian heritage and some come from the
winery's in-house chef, Jeffrey Starr.
</P>
<P>
   As befits a Napa Valley book, it is oriented toward wine (but no
overt pitch for Sutter Home or the costlier M. Trinchero wines).
Brief sidebars address wine topics (and some Trinchero/Sutter Home
history), and wine is an ingredient in many recipes. Other recipes
are for dishes with an affinity toward wine.
</P>
<P>
   A leg of lamb, for example, destined for the outdoor grill is
marinated in Zinfandel with rosemary, shallots, olive oil, Dijon
mustard, soy sauce, brown sugar and salt and pepper. It is served
with a fusion mint pesto that incorporates soy sauce, sesame oil,
garlic and roasted peanuts. Logically, the suggested accompanying
wine is Zinfandel.
</P>
<P>
   Another lamb recipe, this one for braised shanks, has a
Mediterranean pedigree, including the finishing touch of
parsley-lemon zest-garlic  &LR; gremolata &LR; . Inspired by the same region,
Gina Trinchero Mee's sauteed shrimp with red and green peppers and
feta cheese doesn't take longer to fix than the time it takes to
cook the rice or couscous suggested to go with it.
</P>
<P>
   Tuscany is the country of origin for the grape harvest flat
bread that is featured on the cover of the well-illustrated book.
Moderately sweet, this specialty from the Chianti region goes with
a late-afternoon glass of Pinot Noir as well as with morning
coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Don't want to wait around for yeast dough to rise? You couldn't
do better than the peach and fig galettes, made with a rich
butter-and-egg-yolk pastry partially folded over the fresh fruit
filling.
</P>
<P>
   And for hot nights in the Napa Valley (or anywhere else), try
McNair's rich and luscious lavender gelato _ with or without the
suggested sparkling wine.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The Sutter Home Napa Valley Cookbook,'' by James McNair,
with &LR;   &LR; photographs by Zeva Oelbaum (Chronicle Books; 152 pages; &LR; 
 &LR; soft-cover; $22.95). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FRESH FIG &AMP; PEACH GALETTES
</P>
<P>
   While the combination of peaches and figs is especially nice,
James McNair says you can use just one of these fruits or
substitute other soft fruit such as raspberries or nectarines.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Tart Pastry
</P>
<P>
   31/2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups chilled unsalted butter, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 egg yolks, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons iced water
</P>
<P>
   Filling
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ripe peaches, peeled, pitted, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ripe figs, stemmed, cut lengthwise into halves or
quarters
</P>
<P>
   About 6 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch, potato starch or quick-cooking tapioca
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Sugar for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Position racks in center of oven and preheat oven to 400
degrees. Line 2 baking sheets with parchment paper and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the flour, sugar, salt, lemon zest and butter in food
processor. Pulse just until the mixture is well blended and
resembles cornmeal. With the machine running, add the yolks through
the feed tube, then add the water, 1 tablespoon at a time, until
the dough begins to gather into a shaggy mass.
</P>
<P>
   Alternately, mix the dry ingredients with a pastry blender or
your fingertips; add the yolks and water with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Working quickly, form the dough into a ball and divide into 6 or
8 pieces. Shape each piece into a disk and cover with a kitchen
towel or plastic wrap to keep the dough from drying out.
</P>
<P>
   One piece at a time, roll the dough out on a lightly floured
board into rounds about 1/8 inch thick (7 inch diameter if making 6
tarts). It is not necessary to trim any rough edges. Transfer to
the prepared sheets. Cover the baking sheets to keep the dough from
drying out.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the peaches, figs, sugar to taste, starch or tapioca and
the vanilla, if using, and mix gently. Spoon the mixture onto the
center of the dough rounds, dividing equally and leaving a 2-inch
border. Bring the edges of the pastry up and over the fruit as far
as possible, leaving the fruit exposed in the center. Pinch the
dough to form pleats that make the pastry fit snugly around the
fruit. Sprinkle the exposed pastry generously with sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the pastry is golden brown and the fruit is tender
and bubbling, about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 675 calories, &LR;   &LR; 8 g protein, 80 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 37 g fat (22 g saturated), 172 mg cholesterol, 211 mg sodium, 5 &LR; 
 &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
