<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2750 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SOURCE-BEANS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-04 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-BEANS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. 
 
 At The Source: Getting the Short Skinny On Long Beans  By Janet Fletcher  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Whoever named them yard-long beans was
exaggerating, but not by much. Although growers say these slender
beans can indeed reach three feet, a true yard-long specimen is a
rare sight.
<P>
   Still, the 18- to 24-inch beans are long enough to make them a
curiosity to consumers who grew up on Blue Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, yard-long beans _ also known as Chinese long beans _
aren't even related to the familiar garden green bean. They're a
sister to black-eyed peas, and like those Southern specialties,
they prefer hot weather. In California, they're grown primarily in
Fresno County by Hmong farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The Hmong refugees from Laos who settled in the Central Valley
20 years ago brought a knowledge of long beans with them. Farmers
in their home country, they began farming here, too, growing the
crops they knew and needed for their own cooking. County extension
agents like Richard Molinar in Fresno County helped them establish
farms and master American-style marketing and distribution. At one
point, there were 80,000 Hmong in Fresno County alone.
</P>
<P>
   The county still has more Hmong, more Hmong farmers (about
1,000) and more acreage in long beans than any other county in the
state, says Molinar. But the numbers are declining. Lured by
higher-paying technical jobs in Minnesota and elsewhere, many Hmong
are leaving agriculture and California behind, and Fresno's Hmong
population has fallen to between 30,000 and 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   The county's long-bean acreage has plummeted, too, from 450
acres in 1990 to 119 acres last year. Molinar believes that's a
function of low demand and poor return. An acre planted to long
beans might yield $2,000 to $3,000, with plenty of hand labor
required; an acre of cherry tomatoes or lemongrass might gross
$10,000.
</P>
<P>
   For shoppers who love long beans' crisp-chewy texture and meaty
taste, these numbers are sobering. Still, some supermarkets and
specialty produce markets carry them; Asian markets always do, and
in summer you'll also find them at many farmers' markets.
</P>
<P>
   Most growers plant the familiar dark-green variety, but you may
also spot pale-green, purple and reddish long beans. Michael Yang,
who is Hmong and an assistant to Molinar, says the dark-green beans
are somewhat sweeter and longer-lasting; the other varieties are
more delicate and more prone to swift decline. Produce cookbook
author Elizabeth Schneider suggests using the pale beans for quick
cooking, the darker green ones for braising.
</P>
<P>
   Yang says Hmong often eat the beans raw, in green papaya salad
or as a snack. But they also are commonly stir-fried with bits of
pork or chicken and seasonings, or deep-fried, as in the Sichuan
recipe for ``dry-fried'' beans.
</P>
<P>
   Food writer Grace Young says long beans are one of the only
vegetables that Chinese women are supposed to eat after childbirth
because the beans are neutral _ neither yin, nor yang. Peruse an
Italian seed catalog and you may find long beans there, too; in
Puglia, cooks braise them in tomato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   California farmers plant long beans from April to June and
harvest them from July to November. They are a pole variety, grown
on trellises and hand harvested.
</P>
<P>
   At the market, don't expect long beans to be firm, like Blue
Lake beans. They are always somewhat floppy and flexible, but they
shouldn't be limp. Avoid any that are excessively blemished,
rusty-looking or withered. At home, store them in a loose plastic
bag in the refrigerator crisper and use them as soon as possible;
they are not long keepers. Trim the ends, then cut the beans into
desired lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Long beans usually are not blanched before cooking, but rather
are stir-fried from the dry state. Low in calories, high in vitamin
A and richly flavored, they are a vegetable worth getting to know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT &LR;      07-04 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAX MILITARY SECURITY PERMITTED BOMBINGS IN CHECHNYA, RUSSIAN
OFFICIAL SAYS  
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Negligence by Russian commanders enabled Chechen
suicide bombers to carry out the devastating attacks on Sunday that
killed more than 30 soldiers, the chief of Russia's intelligence
service said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Patrushev, the director of the Federal Security Service,
said that his agency had alerted the Russian military that
terrorist attacks were being planned but that the military had
failed to take proper precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a mistake on the part of commanders in the field,''
he said. ``We have to act in a coordinated fashion to prevent such
things from happening in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Five trucks loaded with munitions exploded in Chechnya Sunday
night, catching the Russian military by surprise and shocking the
nation. Russian officials on Tuesday put the final toll at 33 dead,
84 wounded and three missing.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to restore control over Chechnya's towns and settlements,
Russian officials on Tuesday issued a ``shoot on sight'' order for
any vehicle that breached a 9 p.m. to 7 a.m. curfew. New
checkpoints have been set up, and many Chechen residents were
reportedly staying at home.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 people have been detained, but it is not clear if the
Russian authorities have found any of those who organized the
bombings. In Moscow, the authorities ordered the police to take
special precautions against terrorist bombings.
</P>
<P>
   A series of devastating explosions in Russian apartment
buildings in September helped build public support for the war.
Russian officials said then that the rebels were to blame, but
there is no conclusive proof of their role.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sunday bombings, most of the casualties were in Argun, a
town east of Grozny, where a truck bomb slammed into a dormitory
occupied by a militia unit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite terrorist alerts, there was no concrete barrier or other
obstacle to stop the truck from approaching the building.
</P>
<P>
   Providing new details of that attack, Russian television
reported Tuesday night that 22 militia members had been killed in
that attack and 48 wounded. Many of the dead and wounded were
buried under the debris.
</P>
<P>
   After the bomb exploded, Chechen snipers began shooting at the
building, and a gunfight continued for one-and-a-half hours.
</P>
<P>
   While Russian officials agreed that negligence was a factor,
they said that it was the fault of local commanders, not Gen. Ivan
Babichev, the military commandant of Chechnya.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The destruction in Argun ``resulted from the failure to comply
with an order by General Babichev that additional security measures
were to be taken,'' said Sergei Yastrzhembsky, the senior Russian
government spokesman on the war.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to put the best face on a worsening situation, Akhmad
Kadyrov, the Russian-appointed administrator of Chechnya, described
the bombings as a desperate act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebel leaders are seriously concerned that the people have
lately begun to nurture hope for Chechnya's peaceful development,''
Kadyrov told the news agency Interfax.
</P>
<P>
   Others took a more pessimistic view. Boris Berezovsky, the media
tycoon and a parliamentary deputy who represents a region in the
North Caucasus, said that Russia would not be able to win a
military victory in Chechnya. During the Yeltsin administration,
Berezovsky served as a negotiator in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of the jingoists' loud statements, most of Russian
society believes the war in Chechnya is leading our country to
defeat,'' he said. ``There can be no military victory in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Chechnya, it is necessary to reach an agreement with the
most extremist element of the Chechen population, as well. If the
political process is dragged out, it will be hard on Russia,
including our president's image.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin has kept a low profile in
recent days and has little to say about the bombing attacks, which
have challenged the Kremlin's claims to control the breakaway
republic.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, for their part, were more vocal. They promised more
attacks, warning civilians to move away from Russian bases and
command posts.
</P>
<P>
   Shamil Basayev, the Chechen warlord, demanded that Russian
authorities hand over a Russian officer accused of the rape and
murder of a Chechen woman, according to a Chechen spokesman,
Movladi Udogov. Otherwise, he vowed, there would be more bombing
attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
