<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2772 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WORKING-SFCHRON &LR;      07-04 1657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 The Working Cook: Wanderlust Leads to Pasta, Couscous and 
 Scaloppine  By Tara Duggan  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; A friend just returned from a culinary tour of
Sicily, and her trip got me thinking about the olive oil- and
cannoli-filled trip I took there a few years ago with my father.
<P>
   My dad is also a ``food fiend,'' so we let our taste buds guide
our travels. In Agrigento, we couldn't resist having a second
cappuccino in a charming outdoor cafe and wound up missing a bus
that ran only once every few hours. And we stayed an extra day in
the not-so-interesting town of Trapani to revisit the  &LR; cuscusu &LR; 
(couscous) with fish we tasted at an amazing restaurant there.
</P>
<P>
   Our very first meal was in Palermo, behind a crumbling villa in
a courtyard lined with scraggly palm trees. We ordered Pasta alla
Norma, a local specialty supposedly created at the debut of the
eponymous opera by native son Puccini.
</P>
<P>
   This quintessential dish makes the most of the profusion of
produce that grows on the lush, hot island: robust globe eggplants,
plummy tomatoes, fresh basil. These usually are combined with penne
and ricotta salata, a dry version of ricotta cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I won't be going back to Sicily any time soon. So
I created this week's Lasagna alla Norma, a baked version of my
favorite Sicilian dish. If I can't be in Sicily, at least I can eat
as if I were there.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of ricotta salata, my version has fresh ricotta inside
and grated pecorino on top. I also use roasted eggplant rather than
the traditional fried, which not only is healthier (much less oil)
but far easier to prepare in large quantities.
</P>
<P>
   More in the Northern European tradition, Food Department intern
Andy Lax's Pork Scaloppine with Fennel, Apple &AMP; Cabbage is the kind
of recipe that takes little time and produces a lot of intricate
flavors. A hit of bourbon, cream and caraway adds depth to the
sauce, while the fennel and apple cider vinegar help cut through
any richness.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind Chicken Sausages &AMP; Green Couscous came from my
colleague Karola Saekel. She uses seafood sausages instead of
chicken, but I found that their quality can vary from market to
market. If your store offers high-quality seafood sausages, the
fresh dill and lemon flavors in the couscous are a great match.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN SAUSAGES &AMP; GREEN COUSCOUS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup frozen peas
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon + 11/2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Handful dill sprigs (2 tablespoons chopped)
</P>
<P>
   Handful parsley (2 tablespoons chopped)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Pinch sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound baby greens
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds mild-flavored chicken sausages
</P>
<P>
   1 cup instant couscous
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the peas in a strainer and rinse under cold running water
for a few minutes to defrost. Drain well.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the water, 1/2 teaspoon salt and 1/2 teaspoon oil in a
medium-size saucepan. Cover and bring to a boil. Reduce heat to
low. Keep at a low simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Chop the dill and parsley. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Stir together the remaining 11/2 tablespoons olive oil, the
lemon juice, sugar, salt and pepper to taste. Place the greens in a
bowl and toss with this dressing. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Start cooking the sausages on a grill or grill pan over
medium-high heat. They should take 8 to 10 minutes to cook through.
</P>
<P>
   While the sausages cook, return the pot of water to a boil, then
add the peas and couscous. Stir, reduce heat, cover and cook for 1
minute. Remove from heat. Stir in the chopped dill and parsley,
cover and let stand for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Fluff the couscous with a fork. Portion the greens onto serving
plates and pile the couscous on top. Serve the sausages alongside.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 640 calories, &LR;   &LR; 45 g protein, 42 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 32 g fat (8 g saturated), 172 mg cholesterol, 1,444
mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   PORK SCALOPPINE WITH FENNEL, APPLE &AMP; CABBAGE
</P>
<P>
   This recipe was developed by Food Section intern Andy Lax. Some
grocers sell pork scaloppine (pounded thin like veal scaloppine).
If they don't, ask your butcher to prepare some for you, or buy
boneless pork chops and cut them lengthwise into thin pieces, about
1/4 inch thick. Sandwich each piece between two lengths of wax
paper. Pound gently until each slice is about 1/8 inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 small apple
</P>
<P>
   1 small fennel bulb, fronds intact
</P>
<P>
   About 1/4 head red cabbage (1 cup sliced)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   8 pork scaloppine
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon caraway seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apple juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup bourbon
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons apple cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds fresh potato gnocchi (or vacuum-packed)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Fill a large pot with salted water and set over high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Peel and core the apple, then cut into 1/2-inch dice.
</P>
<P>
   Core the fennel, reserving the lacy fronds. Cut the bulb into
thin crosswise slices.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the cabbage into long, thin strips.
</P>
<P>
   Mince the onion.
</P>
<P>
   Set a skillet over high heat. Add 1 tablespoon of the butter.
</P>
<P>
   Season the pork generously on both sides with salt and pepper.
Add to the skillet, working in batches if necessary, and cook until
almost done, about 30 seconds per side. Remove the pork from the
skillet and tent with foil to keep it warm.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the remaining 1 tablespoon butter in the skillet. Add the
apple, fennel slices, the cabbage, onion and caraway seeds. Stir in
the sugar. Saute until the vegetables are softened, 3 to 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the vegetables are cooking, chop about 11/2 tablespoons
fennel fronds and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add the apple juice, bourbon and vinegar to the vegetables and
bring to a boil. Cook until the liquid has reduced and the mixture
has thickened slightly, about 1 to 2 minutes. Season with salt and
pepper. Reduce heat to medium and stir in the cream.
</P>
<P>
   Drop the gnocchi into the pot of now-boiling water.
</P>
<P>
   Return the pork to the skillet to finish cooking, which should
take 1 to 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When the gnocchi float, after about 30 seconds to 1 minute,
drain them.
</P>
<P>
   Portion the pork onto serving plates.
</P>
<P>
   Add the gnocchi to the skillet and toss with the vegetables.
Spoon onto the plates. Garnish with the chopped fennel fronds.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 780 calories, &LR;   &LR; 49 g protein, 60 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 34 g fat (16 g saturated), 237 mg cholesterol, 184
mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   LASAGNA alla NORMA
</P>
<P>
   The sausage in this recipe may be omitted, as the sauce,
vegetables and cheeses offer plenty of flavor on their own. To
freeze, assemble the lasagna and tightly wrap the portion you wish
to save for later, label it and place in the freezer. Bake the
other portion and serve for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 large globe eggplants
</P>
<P>
   Salt, as needed
</P>
<P>
   5 Italian sausages, casings removed (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil + olive oil to grease pans
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano leaves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   3 yellow onions, cut into medium dice
</P>
<P>
   4 red bell peppers, deveined and cut into medium dice
</P>
<P>
   3 boxes (26 ounces each) Pomi chopped tomatoes, or equivalent
amount of canned tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch basil
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   About 16 sheets lasagna noodles
</P>
<P>
   30 ounces whole-milk ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups grated pecorino cheese
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Trim the eggplants and cut into 1/4-inch slices. Place the
slices in a colander, salting each layer. Weight with a heavy
object to extract the eggplants' bitter juices.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the sauce:  &LR; Brown the sausages in a Dutch oven,
crumbling them into bite-size pieces. Remove from pan with a
slotted spoon and set aside to cool. Add 2 tablespoons olive oil to
the pan. Adjust heat to medium-low. Add the pepper flakes and
oregano; saute for 1 minute. Add the onions and saute for 5
minutes. Add the bell peppers and saute until tender, 10 to 15
minutes. Add the tomatoes and bring to a simmer. Simmer for 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly grease 2 large sheet pans (or more, as needed) with
olive oil. Transfer the eggplant slices to the sheet pans,
arranging them in a single layer. Season with salt. Roast for 15
minutes. Turn the slices over, return to the oven and roast until
tender, 10 to 15 minutes longer. Set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly chop 6 basil leaves. Add them and the sausage to the
sauce and simmer a few minutes to combine flavors. Season with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the lasagna noodles according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble: &LR;  Reduce oven temperature to 350. Spoon a little of
the sauce in two 9 x 13-inch casserole dishes, spreading it with
the back of the spoon to coat the bottom of the dishes. Layer one
quarter of the noodles in each casserole, top with eggplant slices,
more sauce, some ricotta and a few basil leaves. Repeat layering
with the remaining noodles, eggplant, sauce, ricotta and basil. Top
each casserole with grated pecorino.
</P>
<P>
   Bake uncovered until bubbly and golden, about 30 minutes. If the
cheese does not brown in the oven, place under the broiler for a
few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 410 calories, &LR;   &LR; 21 g protein, 49 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 16 g fat (8 g saturated), 44 mg cholesterol, 555 mg
sodium, 6 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
