<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SHAW-THEATER-NYT &LR;      07-04 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAW-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIRECTOR   EXPANDS   SHAW FEST   IN CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Canada, England)   By SUSAN CATTO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIAGARA-ON-THE-LAKE, Ontario _ Sipping a glass of pinot meunier
in a local winery, Christopher Newton reminisced about his first
few seasons as artistic director of the Shaw Festival. Audiences
walked out of his 1980 production of ``The Philanderer,'' and his
1981 plan to stage ``St. Joan'' without its epilogue failed when
the Society of Authors threatened to withhold the rights to the
play. One critic suggested that Newton be fired or that the Shaw
Festival change its name.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one years after he was hired, Newton, 64, still holds the
job, and the Shaw Festival is one of the largest theater events in
North America, attracting nearly 350,000 people a year to this
old-fashioned village 8 miles downstream from Niagara Falls and 35
miles north of Buffalo. The 11-play festival opened in April and
ends on Dec. 10. More than a third of the audience comes from the
United States. Festival memberships, which include advance purchase
privileges, have nearly doubled to 9,000 in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Newton, a native of Kent, England, who has been awarded the
Order of Canada, the country's highest honor, is credited with
``keeping together a strong ensemble of actors and fostering a very
striking, very intelligent visual and aural style of production,''
in the words of Robert Cushman, theater critic for The National
Post.
</P>
<P>
   With just three seasons left until his retirement in 2002,
Newton is leading the festival through a major expansion of its
mandate. Since its inception in 1962, the festival has focused on
plays written during Shaw's lifetime, 1856 to 1950, which meant
Wilde, Coward, Ibsen and Chekhov and musical greats like the
Gershwin brothers and Cole Porter.
</P>
<P>
   This season, however, he opened the festival to more modern
plays. Nigel Williams' adaption of William Goldings 1955 novel
``Lord of the Flies'' opens July 5, and Joe Masteroff's musical
``She Loves Me'' is running through the festival's last day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to rethink yourself and reinvent yourself all the
time,'' Newton said, adding, ``This seemed a good opportunity with
Shaw coming out of copyright.'' The festival has paid $168,000 to
$335,000 a year in copyright fees to Shaw's estate. Since the
copyright expires 50 years after Shaw's death, the festival can use
that money to commission new works and to buy rights to more recent
plays.
</P>
<P>
   Newton directed three plays this season, though only one is a
product of the new mandate. Shaw's exploration of medical ethics,
``The Doctors Dilemma,'' has had three previous stagings at the
festival, and Noel Coward's ``Easy Virtue'' was repeated from last
year. ``The Matchmaker'' by Thornton Wilder, set in 1880s Yonkers,
was written in 1954, four years after Shaw's death.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the playbill is vintage festival material:
Shaw's political satire ``The Apple Cart,'' Wilde's melodrama ``A
Woman of No Importance,'' Coward's ``Still Life,'' J.B. Priestley's
family drama ``Time and the Conways'' and Luigi Pirandello's ``Six
Characters in Search of an Author.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not terribly experimental,'' Newton said. ``We never
will be, because our audience isn't. Most of the plays they've
never heard of, they've never seen. They've got to trust that there
will be good acting and that it will be done sensibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a sommelier bringing obscure vintages from the cellar,
however, Newton ventures beyond classics and crowd-pleasers.
``Where are you going to see `Ivona, Princess of Burgundia' except
here, and where are you going to see any plays by Henry Arthur
Jones?'' he asked. ``You're blowing the dust off things, and in any
major cultural center, that's what you spend a lot of time doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, I must admit, I couldn't quite see what the
relevance was of the Shaw Festival. Then when I got here, the point
suddenly became a lot clearer to me. Shaw's lifetime has given us
all insights and clues into how we live today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
