<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIANS-STATEHOOD-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUTIOUS RESPONSE TO IDEA OF DECLARING PALESTINIAN STATE IN
SEPTEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israelis and Palestinians alike reacted cautiously
Tuesday to a declaration on Monday by the Palestinian leadership
that a Palestinian state would be declared by mid-September,
uncertain whether it was a promise, a threat or another deadline
that could be massaged.
</P>
<P>
   In the streets of Ramallah, many Palestinians tried to keep in
check their enthusiasm, which was egged on by headlines across the
tops of newspapers proclaiming, ``Palestinian State on 9/13!''
Several Palestinians said they were ready to shed blood, if
necessary, but they warned each other not to put too much stake in
a deadline, given that other supposedly sacred dates have come and
gone.
</P>
<P>
   And then were those like Ziyyad, a 26-year-old shopper who would
not give his last name. He said that Palestinian leaders would be
irresponsible to make a unilateral declaration of statehood because
they would trigger a harsh Israeli response that would ultimately
cause the Palestinian people to suffer. ``More border closures,
separation again between the West Bank and Gaza, economic hardship,
more settlements and no prisoners released,'' he said. ``Our
leaders should be more rational.''
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, even dovish leaders like Justice Minister Yossi
Beilin recoiled from the idea that the Palestinians might abandon
the peace effort and proclaim an independent state. He warned that
a Palestinian state would be meaningless if Israel did not
recognize it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will exist only on paper even if the entire world
recognizes a unilateral Palestinian state,'' Beilin said, in
unusually confrontational words.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the Palestinian Central Council unexpectedly
affirmed its commitment to declare a Palestinian state by Sept. 13,
whether a final peace deal had been reached with the Israelis. That
is the target date for a completed deal, although it is highly
unlikely that it will be met.
</P>
<P>
   The council, leaders of the Palestine Liberation Organization,
had not been expected to attach such significance to the Sept. 13
date. Rather, it was believed that it would vaguely endorse the
idea of a state by year's end so as to defuse the mounting
anxieties that September will bring violence if it does not bring
peace. Instead, its members took a risky decision that locks Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, into a tight timeframe and raises
the hopes of his people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Israel Radio Tuesday, Bassam Sayeh, a member of Arafat's
Fatah party, said that while the Palestinians preferred to achieve
statehood through negotiations, they were prepared to do so through
military conflict if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   And several men interviewed in Ramallah Tuesday said that they
were ready to fight. One old man said: ``We have been waiting for
more than 50 years. Nobody will accept postponing this anymore. We
started the intifada,'' the uprising that lasted from 1988 to 1993,
``with stones, and now we are ready to use stones and rifles.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Tuesday and taken late last month, before
Monday's declaration, showed a very sober-minded Palestinian
people. Slightly more than half said that they expected nothing to
happen in September _ not the declaration of a state and not a
peace agreement. The poll also found that trust in Arafat remains
relatively low _ at 31.8 percent _ but that he is still considered
the most trusted Palestinian figure.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was done by Jerusalem Media and Communication, whose
researchers interviewed 1,200 randomly selected Palestinians in the
West Bank and Gaza face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has been pushing for an immediate three-way,
retreat-style summit meeting in the United States to move the
stalemated peace talks into a higher gear.
</P>
<P>
   But the Palestinians have resisted, saying that the two sides
are too far apart and that a summit meeting now would be doomed to
failure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
