<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LYON-BIENNIAL-NYT &LR;      07-04 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYON-BIENNIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EXOTIC'? PERHAPS, YET NEITHER PRIMITIVE NOR PURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ Wielding the persuasive weapon of money, Western
art dealers and collectors appear to have vanquished ethnologists
in the battle over so-called primitive art.
</P>
<P>
   Objects created for religious, ritualistic or tribal reasons,
like African fertility statues, pre-Columbian stone figures and
Oceanic masks, are now routinely traded _ and admired _ as works of
art. Even the Louvre has begun displaying primitive art exclusively
on aesthetic merit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when it comes to contemporary art from outside the Western
world, the lines are far more blurred. This new art is created as
art, it often relies on Western techniques _ its creators may even
live in New York and Paris _ yet its strength still lies in its
identity with a non-Western reality. At the same time, as
multiculturalism has become fashionable in the West, artists
trained in a Western tradition have found inspiration in the
``magic realism'' of much third world art.
</P>
<P>
   This at least is the thesis of ``Sharing Exoticisms,'' the name
given to the Fifth Lyon Biennial of Contemporary Art, which is
being held in the cavernous Halle Tony Garnier through Sept. 24. In
a world ``globalized'' by information, consumerism and migration,
cultures no longer stay put. ``Exoticism'' has ceased to be a
euphemism for folkloric backwardness: it now works both ways.
Anthropology, proclaim the biennial's artistic directors, Thierry
Prat and Thierry Raspail, has defeated aestheticism.
</P>
<P>
   The show's poster image illustrates this with a photograph of a
blond German dressed as a Native American, part of a series called
``German Indians,'' taken by Andrea Robbins and Max Becher in the
German town of Radebeul during its annual Wild West festival. The
colorful geometric mural at the entrance to the show, on the other
hand, is signed jointly by Esther Mahlangu, a South African wall
painter, and the American Sol LeWitt, with no indication as to
which parts were done by which artist.
</P>
<P>
   The biennial's guest curator, Jean-Hubert Martin, who now heads
the Kunst Palast Museum in Duesseldorf, Germany, has long
encouraged this eclectic approach. In 1989, while director of the
Pompidou Center's Modern Art Museum, he organized a show called
``The Magicians of the Earth'' that took the unusual approach of
treating first and third world artists as equals. Then, in the
mid-1990s, while running the Museum of African and Oceanic Art in
Paris, he began adding contemporary art to the colonial collection.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Sharing Exoticisms,'' he formed a committee of five
anthropologists who helped him define 22 ethnological categories,
all linked to human behavior, into which he eventually slotted
works by 120 artists from 30 or so countries. With generic titles
like ``To Dress,'' ``To Love,'' ``To Cure,'' ``To Pray'' and ``To
Die,'' each section opens with an iconic work, in most cases taken
from ``primitive art,'' as a way of demonstrating the continuity of
symbols and concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The work that greets the public in the opening section,
``Exotiser,'' or ``To Make Exotic,'' sets a mischievous tone. An
installation placed in what appears to be an open-sided tribal hut
includes copies of Western paintings, statues and art objects and
is called ``Somewhere in Africa there is a great black man
collecting art from Europe and America.'' Its author, though, is
not African: it is Nedko Solakov, a Bulgarian artist living in
Sofia.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from LeWitt, the biennial includes works by other well
known artists, among them Gilbert and George, Annette Messager,
Antoni Tapies and Anish Kapoor. Yet this is a show in which
individual artists are less important than the voyage through the
theme park of exoticisms. Blue curtains dividing the space more or
less force visitors to follow a prescribed route.
</P>
<P>
   The categories allow works from different continents and
cultures to be confronted, but they also serve as a guide for
interpreting individual pieces. In ``Exotiser,'' for instance, the
colonial view of the exotic is spoofed by the Swiss artists Marcel
Biefer and Beat Zgraggen, who photograph themselves as white
``native'' warriors, naked except for their armor of old cans and
assorted industrial detritus.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Ocampo, a Filipino artist working in Berkeley, Cal.,
paints large primitive-style tableaux that, on closer inspection,
are anticolonialist protest works.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Tattoo'' reminds how the West has embraced a form of body
decoration that was discovered by Westerners in the Pacific Islands
only in the 19th century. Gerald Minkhoff and Mureil Olesen, a
Swiss couple, photograph themselves in mises-en-scene using
Minkoff's tattooed body. Greg Semu, a New Zealand artist of Samoan
extraction, photographs the complex tattoos of the pe'a male
initiation ritual that cover his own body. Farid Belkahia, a
Moroccan artist, works more symbolically, tattooing large hands
made of lamb's skin placed on canvas.
</P>
<P>
   The variety of materials used is impressive. The French artist
Serge Goudin-Thebia has created human forms with old leaves held
together by long wooden pins. Wenda Gu, a Chinese artist living in
New York, has brought ``United Nations'' (renamed ``Temple of
Exoticism'' here), a large room in which chairs have television
screens as seats and the walls are covered in words of many
languages written with human hair and held together by glue.
</P>
<P>
   Another Chinese artist, Liang Shaoij, uses real silkworms in an
installation in which human forms appear to have been smothered in
silk.
</P>
<P>
   One striking work in ``To House'' is ``Exotica 2000,'' an
installation by the French artists Anne and Patrick Poirier, who
have built a vast industrial complex in miniature and entirely in
black (binoculars are available to look into what resembles an
archaeological find). Even larger is a ``United Nations'' by the
Swiss artist Thomas Hirschhorn, an installation showing destroyed
towns and villages in numerous countries where the United Nations
is struggling to keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Two artists have found unusual ways of bridging the gap between
first and third world cultures. Ghada Amer, an Egyptian artist
working in New York, creates large delicate embroideries that seem
abstract from afar but in fact show naked women in sensual poses.
Pascale Marthine Tayou from Cameroon has traced the final days of
an imported car in a short film called ``Old New.'' The car, he
pointed out, was considered scrap in Europe, but it began a new
life when it arrived in Africa. Now a rusting carcass, the car is
on display.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition does not have sections called ``To Travel'' or
``To Migrate,'' but in a sense they would have best sustained the
premise of ``Sharing Exoticisms.'' So many of the third world
artists in the show live or have lived in first world capitals,
while many Western artists now have made a point of discovering
different cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Still more striking, while early 20th-century artists like
Gauguin, Derain, Vlaminck and Picasso borrowed from ``primitive
art'' and made it Western, today third world artists have assumed
control over their own cultures. Indeed, not only do they define
their own ``exoticism,'' but they have also discovered a good deal
of the exotic in the ``advanced'' societies of the United States
and Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
