r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-04 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HILLARY CLINTON GETS MIXED GRADES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Several retired veterans of the Clinton administration get their
say about first lady  &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR;  in the latest issue of More
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mike McCurry &LR; , who was White House press secretary, describes
going along to Martha's Vineyard for the Clintons' August 1998
vacation, just after Bill's  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  testimony in court.
Sometime after the Clinton party arrived, McCurry and  &UR; Gen. Don &LR; 
 &UR; Kerrick  &LR; ``went to see them. Mrs. Clinton was in sweats, not made
up. I could tell that she and the president had been doing a lot of
heart-to-heart talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton knew, writes McCurry, that her husband was
struggling at the same time over whether to bomb  &UR; Osama bin &LR; 
 &UR; Laden &LR; 's headquarters in Afghanistan. After McCurry and Kerrick
apologized for intruding, ``she looked at us as if to say, `Don't
you have a war to run?' Watching her at that moment made me a
lifelong fan. Him, I debate about.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dick Morris &LR; , who was an adviser to the president before he
became enmeshed in marital scandal, said that in 1993, he suggested
that Hillary could improve her image by showing fallibility. ``I
said that the public would have more affection for her if she
talked about things she doesn't do well. ... Hillary wasn't sure
she could come up with anything. `Try,' I said. About a week later,
she still hadn't.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AGE OF PROGRESS &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hit the deck, slugabeds. ``Soda machines hold an almost symbolic
importance in the Internet world,'' writes  &UR; Veronique &LR; 
 &UR; Vienne &LR;  in Metropolis magazine. The lobby of one Manhattan
high-tech media agency features ``three huge supermarket
refrigerator cases containing rows and rows of soft drinks,'' all
free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the world of empty calories, quick energy jolts,
all-nighters,'' writes Vienne, who theorizes that the sugar and
caffeine consumed by employees may enhance competitive tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Vienne quotes company founder &UR; Kevin O'Connor &LR; : ``Our HR (Human
Resources) team is focused on finding athletes. We want employees
with a competitive nature.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Madonna &LR; 's stepmother, who was on hand when World
Entertainment News was interviewing Madonna's father about his
Michigan wine business, blurted out that the singer's forthcoming
baby will be a boy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Alice Waters &LR;  of Chez Panisse told New York magazine that
construction is on hold at Paris' Decorative Arts Museum, wherein
she still hopes to have a restaurant, but she hopes to renegotiate
next year, when work starts again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Lara Starr &LR;  forwards word of a new biographical genre:
`` &UR; Christina Aguilera &LR; : The Unauthorized Audio Biography,''
produced by Scholarly Audio, uses the pop star's own words and
music to tell her story, including ``little-known facts her fans
want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   - The Postal Service's first round stamp, worth $11.75, will be
released next week at World Stamp Expo 2000 in Anaheim. The round
shape is filled with a photograph of Earth taken in space.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many great lamas who recognize me as something
strange and from another time, who refer to me as one of them. I
feel a kinship beyond words with them, something really deep.
People all over the world come up to me and recognize me as a great
spiritual leader.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Steven Seagal &LR;  as quoted by  &UR; Orville Schell  &LR; in ``Virtual
Tibet: Searching for Shangri-La From the Himalayas to Hollywood''
(Metropolitan Books; $26), cited in the New York Review of Books.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
