A2815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-BRESAOLA-NYT &LR;      07-04 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRESAOLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RETURN OF AIR-DRIED BEEF FROM ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROZANNE GOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bresaola isn't exactly a household word in America.
So when the real thing began being imported three weeks ago, there
wasn't much fuss about it. But Bresaola, air-dried beef from
Valtellina, in northern Italy, is moist and delicate, and
completely unlike the salty and slightly leathery domestic
versions, or the dryish Swiss bundnerfleisch that Americans have
had to make do with for so long.
</P>
<P>
   True bresaola, pronounced brez-OW-luh, lays gently on the
tongue, almost like carpaccio, and then melts away. It has an
intriguing, musty bouquet. Unlike prosciutto, bresaola is utterly
lean, with no discernible striations of fat. When sliced
paper-thin, it is almost translucent.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it extraordinary, Lou DiPalo of DiPalo's Fine Foods
in Little Italy section of Manhattan says, is the microclimate of
the Valtellina area in northern Lombardy, where it has been made
for more than 600 years. Lean cuts of beef from the hindquarter are
cured in salt and flavorings _ which ones is a carefully guarded
secret that its producers refused to reveal _ and hung out to dry,
in big houses, in Valtellina's Alpine breezes. It is then aged
three to four months, taking on a deep garnet color and a texture
similar to a good prosciutto. It is this brief aging process that
provides the allure. The domestic and Swiss air-dried beef are aged
considerably longer, making them drier.
</P>
<P>
   Italian bresaola hasn't been available in the United States
since 1930, when a provision of the Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act
stipulated that only cooked beef from Italy be allowed into the
United States, a restriction that expired in October 1996. At that
time, another embargo against Italian beef, because of
foot-and-mouth disease, also was lifted.
</P>
<P>
   But the doors slammed shut again in December 1997, when all beef
products from Italy were banned, and still are, because of bovine
spongiform encephalopathy, also known as mad cow disease. Although
there has never been a case of mad cow disease reported in Italy,
the Agriculture Department instituted the ban after identifying
substantial risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, two Italian bresaola makers have come up with a way
to satisfy all those concerns: they use beef imported from South
America. The Agriculture Department approved their products for
import on April 25.
</P>
<P>
   Italian bresaola made by Rigamonti and Negroni are both
identified as Bresaola della Valtellina and each one bears a
blue-and-yellow government seal of authenticity. In New York, their
product is available at DiPalo's Fine Foods, Todaro Brothers, Agata
&AMP; Valentina, Fairway and Balducci's markets. Prices range from
about $16 to $19 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   A little goes a long way. One ounce of thinly sliced bresaola
will cover a 10-inch plate nicely _ which is the way bresaola
purists like it best, al naturale, eaten with the fingers, just as
it is.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also delicious draped over soft-scrambled eggs, or
dressed with extra virgin olive oil and lemon juice, sliced in a
julienne atop an arugula salad, showered with shards of Grana
Padano cheese or, in autumn, gilded with shaved white truffles.
</P>
<P>
   BRESAOLA AL CARPACCIO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Four Seasons of Italian Cooking'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by A.J. Battifarano and Alan Richardson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces Italian bresaola, sliced paper-thin
</P>
<P>
   24 small prepared marinated mushrooms or wild mushrooms,
coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces Grana Padano cheese, in one piece
</P>
<P>
   4 or more tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, cut into 6 wedges.
</P>
<P>
   1. Arrange bresaola slices, slightly overlapping on a large
platter. Scatter mushrooms over bresaola, then sprinkle with
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   2. Using a vegetable peeler, shave thin slivers of the cheese
over bresaola. Drizzle with olive oil and sprinkle with black
pepper. Serve with lemon wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
