   SUMMER-SCHOOL (Undated) _ More students than ever before are
enrolled in summer school this season, as districts throughout the
country _ led by those in major cities _ require or strongly
encourage younger and younger students to attend classes to shore
up basic reading and mathematical skills. Educational experts
believe summer school helps address the yawning academic gaps
between poor, minority students and white middle-class ones, by
slowing the ``summer slide,'' in which children forget study
skills, discipline habits and vocabulary words between Memorial Day
and Labor Day. But many are worried that the mushrooming programs,
many of which are mandatory for students who fail to meet promotion
standards, will simply repeat ineffective instructional approaches
and frustrate struggling students with endless drills for
high-stakes exams. By Jodi Wilgoren.
