<HEADER>
A2817 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-GETAWAY-OXFORD-COX     07-04 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-OXFORD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The cosmopolitan Oxford: Mississippi town boasts more than
literary life
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Miss. _ The stone Confederate soldier still stands on
the square as a silent memorial to Lafayette County's Civil War
dead, but that's about all that hasn't changed in William
Faulkner's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Once a sleepy community famous only for its literary heritage
and Ole Miss football games, Oxford is rapidly becoming a trendy
urban center for music, art, restaurants and shops.
</P>
<P>
   You can still get collards and chicken-fried steak at the Ajax
Diner or Smitty's, but you also can get cappuccino, shrimp and
grits and gourmet meals at the elegant, white-tablecloth City
Grocery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one of the best meals in my life at the City Grocery,''
says Oxford author Larry Brown (``Fay,'' ``Father and Son'') during
a recent outing to hear a local bluegrass band perform at Off
Square Books. ``They cooked pheasant and some other wild game. It
was wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   The town's main literary celebrity (besides Faulkner, of course)
now that John Grisham has moved to Virginia, Brown is a frequent
visitor at Richard Howorth's Square Books or the nearby Off Square
Books, where customers can find used books as well as signed first
editions by Grisham and dozens of other authors.
</P>
<P>
   Named one of the ``100 Best Small Towns'' by USA Today, Oxford
is a walker's _ and shopper's _ paradise. A shady town square built
around the 150-year-old courthouse offers a variety of shops and
restaurants as well as wrought-iron-enclosed second-floor balconies
where restaurant patrons can take their drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oxford is seen as a quaint Southern town, but it's more than
that,'' says Howorth, who is credited with attracting crowds to the
square with special events and author signings at his bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole nightlife scene has changed,'' Howorth says. ``For a
long time, there were no bars, then there was a Holiday Inn bar.
Now there are more bars on the square than a drinking person could
go to in one night.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the town's population is around 10,000, the University
of Mississippi adds 11,000. The result is an eclectic mix of
locals, students and tourists who come to shop, soak up the
literary atmosphere at Faulkner's Rowan Oak plantation or attend
the numerous music events.
</P>
<P>
   The home of Fat Possum Records, Oxford has become a center for
musicians playing blues, rock, folk and jazz at a number of other
clubs in town. The music scene changed dramatically, Howorth says,
after Proud Larry's opened on the square seven years ago and began
booking big-name acts on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   All the extra traffic and influx of residents have been great
for business, but there's a downside, says Na-Ann Watts, owner of
Na-Ann's New Look, a frame and accessory shop just off the square.
</P>
<P>
   ``Property values have shot up astronomically,'' says Watts, a
former insurance agent who turned her interior decorating hobby
into a profession. ``You have the parents of students coming to
Oxford and liking the town so much they move here. A lot of folks
are retiring here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the square, shoppers can find the South's best assortment
of blues CDs at Uncle Bucks Records; folk art, antiques and weather
vanes at, of course, the Weather Vane; and hand-thrown pottery,
gourmet cookware and kudzu jelly at Mississippi Madness.
</P>
<P>
   Depite the changes and the gentrification of the town, Oxford
hasn't forgotten the man that put it on the map. The annual
Faulkner &AMP; Yoknapatawpha Conference July 23-28 is expected to
attract several hundred scholars, students and lovers of
literature.
</P>
<P>
   Controversial in life, Faulkner has managed to create a fuss
even in death. When some of his supporters announced plans to erect
a bronze statue of the author in front of City Hall,
environmentalists were upset because it meant the removal of a
magnolia tree.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the statue is in place, Faulkner devotees complain that
the likeness is all wrong; and the writer's relatives say he would
have hated everything about it.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Getting there
</P>
<P>
   Oxford is 332 miles west of Atlanta. By car, take I-20 west for
148 miles to Birmingham, then take U.S. 78 west for 134 miles to
the Natchez Trace Parkway. Go south for four miles to Miss. 6. Turn
west on Miss. 6 for 46 miles to Oxford. By air, fly nonstop to
Memphis, $68 each way on AirTran, Delta and Northwest with a 14-day
advance purchase. From Memphis, take U.S. 78 southeast to Miss. 7
to Oxford. It's about a 75-mile drive.
</P>
<P>
   Information
</P>
<P>
   Oxford Tourism Council, 1-800-758-9177.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   The Oliver-Britt House is a restored manor house a short walk
from the University of Mississippi campus and minutes from Oxford
Square. The house features four guest rooms, all on the second
floor, with private baths, cable television and central heat and
air. Rates: $44-$65. 512 Van Buren Ave., 601-234-8043.
</P>
<P>
   The Barksdale-Isom Place was built as a log cabin in 1835.
Remodeled in the Greek Revival style, it has been expanded to
include five guest rooms with private baths. Rates: $150-$190. No
smoking and no pets. It is near the square. 1003 Jefferson Ave.,
1-800-236-5696.
</P>
<P>
   Chain hotels: Like any college town, Oxford is well-represented
by chain hotels. Call the tourism council for specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   The City Grocery is the unlikely name for one of Oxford's most
elegant restaurants. Located in an old storefront building on the
square, the white-tablecloth restaurant serves New South cuisine at
reasonable prices. Lunch specials include penne pasta with shrimp
for $9, an enormous helping of shrimp and grits for $12 and smoked
beef skirt steak sandwiches for $8. An extensive wine list is also
offered. Evening meals are a little pricier. 152 Courthouse Square,
601-232-8080.
</P>
<P>
   The Downtown Grill is another good choice for a quiet, candlelit
meal. Dinner specials include rainbow trout with lump crabmeat for
$20.95 or Mississippi Catfish Lafitte topped with ham and shrimp
for $16.95. Lunch specials include chicken Caesar salad for $5.95
or old-fashioned chicken salad for $6.95. 110 Courthouse Square,
601-234-2659.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best pizza places in town is the Old Venice Pizza
Co., which offers an unusual variety of toppings, from portobello
mushrooms to crawfish and okra pizza for $8.95 and up.
</P>
<P>
   For down-home Southern meals, locals still go to the Ajax Diner
for meatloaf, chicken-fried steak and daily specials for around $6.
118 Courthouse Square, 601-232-8880.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   A must-see attraction in Oxford is Rowan Oak, the house that
William Faulkner bought in 1930. He christened the house after the
Celtic legend of the rowan tree, which was thought to have magic
powers of protection. While living at Rowan Oak, Faulkner wrote
``Absalom, Absalom!'' and ``The Sound and the Fury.'' The stately
old house is now owned by the University of Mississippi and is open
to the public 10 a.m.-noon and 2-4 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays and 2-4
p.m. Sundays. Admission is free. Old Taylor Road, 601-234-3284.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Mississippi Blues Archives, on the University
of Mississippi campus, houses the world's most extensive collection
of blues recordings and other material. The B.B. King collection
alone contains more than 7,000 recordings of blues, big band and
jazz. The Kenneth S. Goldstein Folklore Collection includes books
and records that focus on African-American folklore and music. The
Living Blues Archive Collection features books, photographs and
tapes covering all aspects of the blues. Open 8 a.m.-5 p.m.
weekdays. Admission is free. 601-915-7753.
</P>
<P>
   UPCOMING EVENT
</P>
<P>
   The Faulkner &AMP; Yoknapatawpha Conference, July 23-28, will
examine the topic ``Faulkner in the 21st Century.'' Included will
be discussions by scholars and critics, a reading by author Larry
Brown and a showing of Ross Spears' film, ``Tell About the South.''
The documentary examines Southern literature from 1915 to 1940 and
includes commentary by noted authors Shelby Foote, Cleanth Brooks,
Willie Morris and Reynolds Price.
</P>
<P>
   Other events include tours of the Mississippi towns of Ripley,
New Albany and Holly Springs, which were models for Faulkner's
fictional town of Jefferson, a visit to the Delta Blues Museum in
Clarksdale and a picnic at Faulkner's home, Rowan Oak.
</P>
<P>
   Registration: $175 students, $225 others. Fee includes admission
to all program sessions, a buffet supper on opening day, the picnic
at Rowan Oak, refreshments and a closing reception.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 662-915-7282 or e-mail cstudies(at)olemiss.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
