<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DREAM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     07-04 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DREAM STUFF': WARY AND UNSETTLED IN A GHOST-RIDDEN LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No contemporary literature is more insistently permeated by the
spirit of the land than Australia's.
</P>
<P>
   It is a spirit, though, that instead of forming and fortifying,
deforms and weakens. In the works of such novelists as Rodney Hall,
Janette Turner Hospital and David Malouf, the setting is a canvas
whose chemical makeup reacts upon the figures painted on it,
causing the pigment to wrinkle and curl away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The land was not ours before we were not the land's.'' So an
unlikely Australian Robert Frost might have written. A harsh, even
weird geography _ the vast barren outback, Martian rock formations,
rivers that narrowed instead of widening seaward and sometimes
disappeared altogether _ resisted settlers who pushed beyond the
narrow coastal belt.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty was more than material. What the writers and some
filmmakers register is a flaw of morale, a vulnerability of the
imagination. They evoke the sense of inhabiting a geographical and
historical fault line, haunted by aboriginal ghosts that the
settlers' culture, availing itself of massacre and repression, was
never sufficiently confident of its own identity to dislodge. (What
a contrast with the confidently indifferent majority tradition of
Americans.) Most of the Australian settlers had arrived from
Britain not as pilgrims but as penal deportees; not having sought
freedom, but having lost it.
</P>
<P>
   Malouf, the finest and most expansive of these writers, shares
some of their darkly violent images of estrangement. In his best
and most recent work, though (the novels ``Remembering Babylon''
and ``The Conversations at Curlow Creek''), he goes beyond the
stranger-in-a-strange-land theme to suggest with a few of his
characters a beginning of wisdom, a rumor of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   It is a note he shares to an extent with Michael Ondaatje. In
different ways, each launches upon the tidal wave of nightmare a
tiny raft-borne human figure, paddling if not prevailing.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the short stories in ``Dream Stuff'' evoke the curse
of landscape and history with no reconciliation at all. In ``Lone
Pine,'' an elderly couple on vacation are brutally murdered by a
young tough who, with his wife and child, forces his way into their
camper to steal it, walks them out into the woods and shoots them.
What in another context would be a breath-stopping account of a
sadistic crime _ Malouf remarkably manages to make the pity even
more stunning than the terror _ here seems more than that. It seems
foreordained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacksoil Country,'' set more than a century ago, is the
finest story in the collection, a precursor, perhaps, of
``Remembering Babylon.'' It tells of MacIvor, a rough, bitter
farmer who moves from homestead to homestead without making a go of
any of them. His failures build into rage against the itinerant
bands of aborigines who wander across his property following their
ancestral routes. The practice has become a kind of right,
respected if not welcomed by the other farmers.
</P>
<P>
   MacIvor, though, threatens them with a shotgun until one day,
seeing a band approach with a dead sheep and assuming they've
poached it, he shoots one of them dead. It is blind and tragically
senseless; another settler, hoping to calm his neighbor, had given
the aborigines the sheep to bring as a peace offering.
</P>
<P>
   The truce is broken. Jordan, MacIvor's 12-year-old son, who
until then had wandered the countryside free and unharmed, is
killed by the aborigines. The white farmers, reluctantly perhaps,
start a season of pursuit and massacre.
</P>
<P>
   The story is told _ and it is Malouf's triumph _ in Jordan's
wondering, dead voice. Double victimhood makes him one of the
writer's wraithlike reconcilers:
</P>
<P>
   ``The blacks in every direction are hunted and go to ground.
They too have lost their protection _ what little they had of it.
Me all that while lying quiet in the heart of the country, slowly
sinking into the ancientness of it, making it mine, grain by grain
blending my white grains with its many black ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Malouf's engine may be overpowered for a short track. There are
clever turns in many of the stories but a certain tire shriek on
corners. The ones furthest from his theme of haunted unsettlement
seem most contrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sally's Story,'' set during World War II, portrays the
alienated feelings of an Australian woman employed to provide
weeklong ``marriages'' to American soldiers on combat leave. The
situation is journalistically provocative, at least to an American
reader (Who employed these women? Was it an official program?), but
the story is sketchy and flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Night Training'' is a slight piece about a studious draftee
sadistically abused by his training officer. ``Jacko's Reach'' is a
nostalgic sketch of the conversion into a shopping mall of a bit of
city wasteland used for teen-age adventures with drink, drugs and
sex. More interesting is the title story, but its attempt to
compress in 30 pages the memories and emotions of an expatriate
writer returning for a visit and getting mugged suffers from
forcing. Too much is signaled, too little received.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Day,'' by contrast, gives expansive range to its story
of the passing of a class and a generation. It takes the form of
the annual reunion of a privileged and gifted clan to celebrate the
birthday of Audley Tyler, its patriarch. He is a man of
discriminating temper and shrewd judgment, formerly the highest of
civil servants and adviser to six prime ministers, and still much
consulted.
</P>
<P>
   Individual vignettes weave through the reunion; a familiar
device that Malouf employs effectively, though with more power than
subtlety. It develops a lovely grave complexity, nonetheless, as
Audley presides over not only the reunion but also his own
stock-taking.
</P>
<P>
   His brief, restless visit to the nearby family museum adumbrates
the frailty of privilege and its mementos. (Museums are levelers:
whether an old court dress or an old shepherd's tunic, the
governing word is ``old.'') It evokes Audley's own aging weariness
with who he is. Malouf touches, though indirectly, on his abiding
theme: how frailly the conquerors, about to become ghosts
themselves, have inhabited this ghost-ridden land.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `DREAM STUFF'
</P>
<P>
   By David Malouf
</P>
<P>
   185 pages. Pantheon. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SUNDAE-3TAKES-NYT     07-04 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAE-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO POLISH YOUR SPOONS
</HEADLINE>
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few weeks ago, I sat at the bar at Village and
ordered an ice cream sundae. Minutes later, the bartender came
barreling toward me with what looked to be the classic, from the
whipped cream on top down to the tall, thick glass and long thin
spoon. I could have been on a stool at a soda fountain.
</P>
<P>
   But the similarities stopped there. My first taste, a languorous
spoonful of whipped cream, was not too sweet. The ice cream beneath
was a true, eggy vanilla and was draped with a bitter chocolate
sauce. These were mingling with coarse bits of nut brownie and a
cherry sauce sharpened with kirsch and balsamic vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   The ice cream sundae had shed its youthful, frivolous shell.
This was a balanced, thoughtfully constructed dessert, something
that nourished the intellect and the palate, not just the pangs of
the stomach. It was, in essence, as plain and dutiful in its
purpose as a sundae should be, and yet it intimated just how many
possibilities there are with such a dessert.
</P>
<P>
   It made me wonder what it could be in the hands of a great
pastry chef. Would he reform its parts and turn it inside out?
Would he add new components? Or would he snicker, and act as if I
had asked him to take a stab at toast?
</P>
<P>
   I got on the phone, called seven of New York's top chefs and
pastry chefs and asked them to create their own interpretations of
the dessert, to ruminate on every detail, from the density of the
ice cream to the design of the serving dish.
</P>
<P>
   After what seemed like many long pauses, all but one _ who
dismissed it as ``a study in sugar'' _ agreed, turning out sundaes
that were astonishing both in their ability to stretch the
definition of the dessert and their devotion to the classic design.
</P>
<P>
   For some chefs, like Luis Bollo at Meigas, who recently moved to
New York from Spain, this meant working from what he had read, and
impressions he had formed about sundaes, rather than from
experience eating them. With Roni Ross, the pastry chef at Nobu, it
was a matter of using ingredients familiar from her Asian fusion
repertory and sculpturing them into a sundae. And then there was
Florian Bellanger, the pastry chef at Le Bernardin, a recent
immigrant from France, who had to climb from an abyss: His single
sundae experience was at McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Sundaes, as it turns out, are not strictly American, and so some
chefs drew on desserts from other countries to help improve the
design.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Klinger, the chef at Al Di La in Brooklyn, had already been
working hard on a sundae recipe for her menu when I called. She and
her husband, Emiliano Coppa, had been trying to recreate a dessert,
called gianduiotto, served at a couple of the old cafes in Venice.
Gianduiotto has all the necessary components of a sundae: the ice
cream, the crunch, the whipped cream, the wonderfully sloppy
ending.
</P>
<P>
   She makes a pleasantly gooey ice cream with gianduja and bitter
chocolates, layers it in a baking pan with chopped toasted
hazelnuts, freezes it and cuts it into thick bars. Then, she pipes
whipped cream into a juice glass and presses the bar into the
glass. As she does this, the cream squeezes around it, filling up
all the spaces in the glass and billowing out the top like a cloud.
</P>
<P>
   The ice cream bar starts out hard and softens, but it's creamy
like a toffee and never really falls apart. The nuts appear at
random but not in every bite. And the whipped cream, barely
sweetened, inserts tactile relief, making each taste feel like a
foamy milk shake in the top of your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The textures and temperatures in the dessert are as crucial as
the actual flavors. ``The crunch is very important with the one
that we do,'' Klinger said. ``The ice cream feels very cold, and
somehow the cream doesn't feel very cold and there's something nice
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Zarela Martinez, the owner of Zarela's, a Mexican restaurant,
aimed to fix the sundae with heavy Mexican influences and an
emphasis on peanuts, a crop brought to Mexico by African sugar cane
workers. Rather than a peanut ice cream, she made a peanut ice
milk. ``There are so many fabulous fruits and ices in Mexico,'' she
said, ``and I don't like cream.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sundae, however, does not suffer from a lack of richness.
For a sauce, she turned to a drink called torito, from Veracruz.
It's a loose, boozy liquid of condensed milk, evaporated milk,
peanut butter and sugar-cane liquor. The scoops of the peanut ice
swam in it, and tiny ice crystals formed around it as in an ice
cream soda. On top she sprinkled pieces of peanut brittle. The
repetition of flavor gave it structure; the variation of texture
gave it life.
</P>
<P>
   Where many sundaes go wrong is in the blending of flavors. Most
sundaes are served in a tall glass or deep bowl. The sauces are
warm and the ice cream is slippery, so it is only a few bites
before everything starts melding into a thick soup. Each component
must be able to mix with the population of other flavors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The sundae that Bollo at Meigas assembled was a surprising
juxtaposition of typical Spanish flavors. He served it in a martini
glass with a shot of flame orange kumquat sauce at the bottom,
covered by a mound of coffee-colored crema catalana ice cream, two
thin slivers of almond cake and a jagged shard of caramelized sugar
that glistened like a pane of stained glass. It was beautiful to
look at, but the chances of the components mixing together
successfully seemed slim.
</P>
<P>
   The ice cream was a rich, lazy cream, scented with nutmeg. The
kumquat sauce was aggressively sharp and bitter. The sugar shard
had a burned flavor and crackled like dry leaves. When they mixed
together, though, the jarring contrasts came together like a
Creamsicle. A serious, grown-up Creamsicle.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, Bollo said, he would have used Seville oranges, but
kumquats are a fine substitute. The ice cream, he said, needs that
kind of acidity to balance its richness.
</P>
<P>
   Even more startling was what Ross at Nobu came up with. Her
sundae, served in a tall parfait glass, looked like a child's dream
Bomb Pop with layers of colors _ pale green, pink, white, caramel.
It was leveled cleanly at the top and crowned with a yamamomo
berry, a Japanese mountain berry, flecked with gold leaf. She makes
clean layers by freezing it after each layer.
</P>
<P>
   Ross chose flavors that she uses regularly and ordered them so
that the colors would contrast nicely. That order was also the most
palatable.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was a layer of whipped cream and tiny bits of
pistachio. It tasted uncannily like Lucky Charms. Then things got
serious. A minerally green tea ice cream followed, then a ginger
caramel sauce. A pink layer in the middle turned out to be a red
bean ice cream, sort of the starch of the dish. More caramel sauce
lingered beneath.
</P>
<P>
   Just when things began to seem heavy, the next layer, a lemony
yuzu ice cream, shook it all up. And then there was the kicker: a
base of what looked like pesto. It was shiso leaf, chopped and
marinated in a simple syrup. After it all, you eat the yamamomo
berry, which looks and tastes like a cross between a cherry and
raspberry.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was it a treasure trove of surprises, but each spoonful
was like a geological sample. Only when you got way down into it
did it get mixed up and mushy.
</P>
<P>
   A good sundae should transfix you, as you dig and work and
uncover all of its parts. Eating Nobu's sundae was just that way.
It was impossible to carry on a conversation, impossible to take in
surroundings, impossible to think about anything else but the glass
and getting to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Only Dan Barber and Alex Urena, the chefs at Blue Hill, chose to
serve their sundae unconstructed and in the unpredictable hands of
the diner. They turned it into an interactive playground of
toppings, each with a twist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeals to me to have the overabundance and then feel sort
of sick and full,'' Barber said. ``I wonder if that's not part of
the pleasure, getting to mix and match what you like and then
feeling kind of full.''
</P>
<P>
   With theirs, it's inevitable. You are served a large deep bowl,
with quenelles of chocolate sorbet, vanilla ice cream and
apricot-pit ice cream that lie like rocks in a well. A little
banana foam is sprayed on top in lieu of whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Then it is up to you to fill that well, choosing from a long
rectangular tray of condiments. There were tiny homemade
marshmallows, coated in coconut and as soft as feather pillows; a
hot, bitter chocolate sauce; a warm milk jam; a minty, winey cherry
sauce; crackly coin-shaped pralines; and Scharffen Berger chocolate
nibs for bitterness and crunch.
</P>
<P>
   Self control is pushed to its most fragile limits, but it's a
frantic, delicious circus.
</P>
<P>
   Bellanger, whose sundae journey began with a dud, ended up
sticking very close to the classic, sanding down the rough edges
and refining it with detail work.
</P>
<P>
   He began with a single flavor in mind. Then, he said, ``I decide
other flavors, but they are there to support and enhance the main
flavor.'' And he limited those supporting flavors to five. ``After
that,'' he said, ``it gets confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   His focus was the very un-French flavor of peanuts. He made a
chunky salted-peanut ice cream that was heavier on the milk than
cream, so that it wouldn't be too heavy and wouldn't get too hard.
Over small golf-ball size scoops in a martini glass, he drizzled
thin ribbons of a caramel sauce seasoned with fleur de sel from
Brittany.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped in whole salted peanuts and pieces of
chocolate-covered wafers, bought in the grocery store (better,
Bellanger said, than anything he could make because they are crisp
and as light as air). The chocolate coating adds a dimension of
flavor but also protects the wafers from becoming soggy. ``By the
time you finish your ice cream,'' Bellanger said, ``you should get
different sensations of temperature, of consistency, of crunch.''
With his sundae, you do. Every bite was crunch, crunch, crunch.
</P>
<P>
   On top, there was a sprawling dollop of whipped cream, left
unsweetened to counter the sweet in the ice cream and the salt in
the caramel sauce. ``To add sugar in the whipped cream,'' he said,
``makes the sensation that it is more heavy.'' Such deceptions are
permissible in a sundae.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bellanger conceded that the McDonald's sundae has a
``perfect texture,'' its influences were not evident.
</P>
<P>
   As he assembled his creation, working intensely but excitedly,
Bellanger suffered teasing from others in Le Bernardin's kitchen.
If he was making ice cream sundaes, one cook taunted, were banana
splits next?
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope so.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPES FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   CARAMEL PEANUT SUNDAE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Florian Belanger
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 1 hour, plus chilling and freezing time
</P>
<P>
   For the salted butter caramel sauce: &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   \ cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   \ cup milk
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon fleur de sel or coarse sea salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   For the vanilla-peanut ice cream: &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 Tahitian vanilla bean, split and pulp scraped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   4 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   { cup chopped salted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   For assembly: &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   3 square chocolate-coated wafers, cut into quarters
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coarsely chopped salted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups heavy cream, whipped to soft peaks.
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare caramel sauce: In a small saucepan over medium
heat, stir { cup sugar until melted. Reduce heat to low and slowly
add butter, \ cup heavy cream and \ cup milk; be careful to avoid
spattering. Remove from heat and add salt and 2 tablespoons corn
syrup. Mix until smooth. Cool, cover and refrigerate until chilled,
2 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. To prepare ice cream: In a medium saucepan, combine 1{ cups
milk, vanilla bean and pulp, and 1 tablespoon corn syrup. Place
over medium heat until steaming; meanwhile, in a medium bowl whisk
egg yolks and 1/3 cup sugar until light in color and fluffy. Whisk
about 1/3 of the hot milk mixture into eggs, then whisk egg mixture
back into pan. Continue to heat mixture until it is thick enough to
coat the back of a spoon. Strain into a bowl set over ice water,
and allow to cool.
</P>
<P>
   3. Transfer mixture to an ice cream maker, and freeze according
to manufacturer's instructions. When ice cream has finished
churning, stir in { cup peanuts. Transfer to a plastic container
and freeze.
</P>
<P>
   4. For assembly: Pour a little caramel sauce into each of 4 tall
glasses. Lay a wafer in each glass, top with a scoop of ice cream,
another wafer, another scoop of ice cream, and another wafer. Add
more caramel sauce, and sprinkle on some chopped peanuts. Add
whipped cream, top with more caramel sauce and peanuts, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT SUNDAE WITH PEANUT SAUCE AND PEANUT BRITTLE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Zarela Martinez
</P>
<P>
   Time: 3 hours, plus freezing time
</P>
<P>
   For the peanut ice: &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups skim milk
</P>
<P>
   } cup creamy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   For the peanut and sesame seed candies: &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raw peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   4 piloncillo cones (Mexican brown sugar), about 2 pounds total
(see note)
</P>
<P>
   For the peanut sauce: &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2 12-ounce cans evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1 14-ounce can condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar-cane liquor (see note)
</P>
<P>
   { cup creamy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon vanilla extract.
</P>
<P>
   1. To make peanut ice, in a small saucepan over medium heat,
combine sugar with 1/3 cup water and bring to a boil, stirring
occasionally. Simmer until sugar dissolves.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a blender or food processor, combine syrup, skim milk and
peanut butter, and process until smooth. Transfer mixture to an ice
cream maker and freeze according to manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   3. To make candies, in a heavy skillet over medium heat, toast
peanuts, turning them so they do not burn, for about 5 minutes.
Immediately transfer to food processor or spread them out on a
large baking sheet. If using a food processor, pulse gently until
nuts are just broken up, about 1 minute. Otherwise, use a rolling
pin to crush nuts on baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   4. In same skillet over medium heat, toast sesame seeds,
stirring, for about 3 minutes. Add to peanuts in food processor or
baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   5. In a large heavy saucepan over medium heat, combine the
piloncillo sugar with 1 quart water. Bring mixture to a boil,
stirring frequently until the piloncillo melts. Continue to cook
until syrup reaches hard crack stage (285 degrees on a candy
thermometer), about 1{ hours. Stir in peanuts and sesame seeds.
Pour mixture onto a baking sheet lined with parchment or waxed
paper. Cool. Place candy in a heavy duty plastic bag and use a
rolling pin to crush it into pea-size pieces.
</P>
<P>
   6. To make peanut sauce, in a blender or food processor, combine
all ingredients and process until smooth. Transfer to a tightly
covered bottle and store in refrigerator for up to one month.
</P>
<P>
   7. To assemble sundaes, pour a little bit of peanut sauce into a
tall glass. Place two scoops of peanut ice on top. Sprinkle with a
little crushed candy and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Sugar-cane liquor from Brazil, called cachaca, is
available at liquor stores. Piloncillo sugar is available in
Mexican specialty shops like Kitchen Market, 218 Eighth Avenue
(21st Street); (212) 243-4433.
</P>
<P>
   BROWNIE ICE CREAM SUNDAES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Village
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Brownies (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Cherry sauce (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Fudge sauce (see recipe).
</P>
<P>
   1. In an electric mixer fitted with whisk attachment, whip cream
at medium-high speed until it begins to thicken. Add sugar and
vanilla, and continue to whip until cream forms soft peaks.
</P>
<P>
   2. In an ice cream dish, surround three scoops of ice cream with
4 to 6 brownie cubes. Top with a little cherry sauce, a generous
spoon of fudge sauce and a big dollop of whipped cream. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   BROWNIES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Village
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, plus cooling time
</P>
<P>
   5 eggs
</P>
<P>
   3\ cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon finely ground espresso coffee beans
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   { pound (2 sticks) unsalted butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces unsweetened chocolate, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   12/3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups walnut pieces, toasted.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Line an 11{-by-17{-inch jelly
roll pan with parchment paper, and coat with nonstick cooking
spray. In an electric mixer, whip eggs, sugar, vanilla, coffee and
salt on high speed until thick, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add butter and chocolate, and mix until combined. Add flour,
and mix lightly to incorporate. Add walnuts, and mix lightly until
combined.
</P>
<P>
   3. Scrape batter into pan, and spread evenly with a rubber
spatula. Bake until brownies have set and a knife inserted in
center comes out clean, about 18 minutes. Do not over-bake. Let
cool in pan, then cut into 1-inch cubes.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 6 dozen brownie cubes.
</P>
<P>
   FUDGE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Village
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cream
</P>
<P>
   } cup milk
</P>
<P>
   } cup corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ({ stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   { pound unsweetened chocolate, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a heavy saucepan over medium heat, combine sugar, cream,
milk, corn syrup and butter. Cook, stirring frequently, for about
20 minutes, until mixture reaches about 220 degrees and becomes a
pale caramel.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove pan from heat, and stir in chocolate until it melts.
Stir in 1/3 cup water and vanilla. Use warm or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3{ cups.
</P>
<P>
   CHERRY SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Village
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   Large pinch freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds Bing cherries, pitted (about 5 cups)
</P>
<P>
   } cups kirsch
</P>
<P>
   \ cup creme de cassis
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a saucepan, combine sugar and pepper with 1 cup of water
and bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   2. Put cherries in a large bowl and pour hot syrup over them.
Let cool for 1 minute before adding kirsch, creme de cassis and
vinegar. Stir to combine and refrigerate over night or up to one
week.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 7 cups.
</P>
