<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION _ MEXICO CITY _ Sweeping historic reforms
designed to crack down on corruption and drug trafficking, improve
police and bring in large quanties of investments to help lift the
economy are in store for Mexico, president-elect Vicente Fox told
foreign reporters Tuesday. Fox is using head hunters in a broad
search to find and name cabinet members in the next two months,
well before he takes office Dec. 1. In an effort to alter 71 years
of government under one party, Fox will seek modern checks and
balances. He'll strip the federal government of the power to audit
itself and give it to Congress. He's creating a new ministry for
police and security, taking that power away from the Internal
Affairs Ministry, a political department he said engaged in
espionage and other abuses. Judicial powers will be taken away from
the Attorney General's office. Fox will push for the end of U.S.
certification of drug-fighting partners and the adoption of a
multi-lateral system of mutual approval among countries. With a
vision for a European Union-style relationship with the U.S. and
Canada, Fox will also urge negotiations to establish a development
fund for Mexico and more free transit of Mexican migrant workers.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
