<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-SPY-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE BEGINS INVESTIGATION OF U.S. SURVEILLANCE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A French prosecutor has begun a preliminary
investigation into whether the U.S. global surveillance system,
which listens in on millions of telephone calls, faxes and e-mails
each day, is a threat to French well-being.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Jean-Pierre Dintilhac, has ordered France's
counter-intelligence agency, DST, to appraise the actions of the
system, Echelon. The system links computers in at least seven sites
around the world to receive, analyze and sort information captured
from satellite communications.
</P>
<P>
   If the French agency finds the system ``harmful to the vital
interests of the nation,'' legal proceedings could begin, though it
is difficult to see how a U.S. government agency could be sued in a
French court.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the issue is taken very seriously in Europe. Many fear
that America's vast surveillance system, developed during the Cold
War, is now being used to further U.S. economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have repeatedly denied that. But the issue
continues to arouse passions here. This is particularly true in
France, where even the Justice Minister, Elisabeth Guigou,
contended in February that Cold War-era spy systems had been
converted to ``economic espionage.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the European Parliament held hearings on the
subject, which led to an emotional debate. A report commissioned by
the parliament and written by a British journalist said there was
evidence that the Echelon system had twice helped U.S. companies
gain an advantage over Europeans, though few details were provided.
Some of the members of the parliament expressed skepticism over the
18 page report. But others did not.
</P>
<P>
   The parliament is deciding whether to create a commission to
continue its investigation of Echelon.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Dintilhac, Marie-Annick Darmaillac, said the
prosecutor had decided to begin his own investigation after
receiving a letter from a member of the European Parliament who is
a former French judge, Thierry Jean-Pierre. Darmaillac said the
letter had contained enough information for the prosecutor to feel
an investigation was warranted. But she said she could not discuss
what steps might be taken next as it was up to the prosecutor to
decide.
</P>
<P>
   In Strasbourg, Jean-Pierre told Agence France-Press that he
believes that either the Echelon system should be dismantled or
Europe should have a hand in governing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Echelon is used by the National Security Agency for strategic
and economic gains,'' Jean-Pierre said. ``You cannot make me
believe that the information is not passed on to American
companies.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This is not the first time that France has reacted to
allegations of U.S. spying. In 1995, France expelled five U.S.
diplomats and officials, one of them the alleged Paris station
chief for the Central Intelligence Agency, in connection with the
case.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that many Europeans are particularly galled that the
British are partners with the United States in the Echelon system.
</P>
<P>
   Recently declassified information shows that Echelon is a
network of surveillance stations stitched together in the 1970s by
the United States with Australia, Britain, Canada and New Zealand.
The system listens and watches for key words on a topic requested
by a country. Some experts have said that the most extravagant
claims against the Echelon system make little sense, because the
National Security Agency is overwhelmed by the proliferation of
information over the internet.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely believed that France operates its own surveillance
system, which some have dubbed ``Frenchelon,'' though it is
believed to be much smaller than the U.S. system. However, it is
thought to do much the same thing, eavesdropping on private and
public communications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY-     07-04 1587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-SERIES-ADVISORY-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Eds, adds RACE-HIP-HOP, the 12th article in the series.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors, managing editors, wire editors:
</P>
<P>
   Since Sunday, June 4, and continuing for six weeks, The New York
Times has been publishing a series of articles, ``How Race Is Lived
in America.'' The series is the outcome of a yearlong effort by a
team of Times reporters to capture some of the voices of ordinary
people and some of the troubling issues that Americans continue to
face. These stories, two or three each week, will be approximately
6,000-7,000 words. The News Service will move each story in
advance, and an abridged version will also move, at approximately
3,000 words. They will move in the ``a'' news category and will
carry a slug of the form BC-RACE-SLUG-NYT. Because the articles are
organized into chapters, papers with severe space restraints may
choose to spread a single article over several days.
</P>
<P>
   This story, for papers on Thursday, July 6, will be filed on
Wednesday, in full and abridged versions:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-HIP-HOP (Undated) _ Billy Wimsatt, 27, was born as rap
music was being invented by blacks and Latinos in the South Bronx.
What began as party music became their cry of ghetto pain and their
great hope for a way out. And as hip-hop _ not just rap music but
fashion, break-dancing, graffiti and the magazines that chronicle
it all _ blossomed into the radiant center of youth culture, Billy
Wimsatt and lots of other white kids found in it a way to flee
their own orderly world by discovering a sexier, more provocative
one. Like many young hip-hop heads, he regarded hip-hop, with its
appeal to whites and blacks, as a bold modern hope to ease some of
the abrasiveness between the races. Elliott Wilson, a young black
man, had never met Billy Wimsatt, but their lives had traced
similar trajectories across the hip-hop landscape. As a writer and
editor, he too had spent much of his adult life thinking about
hip-hop. And not just hip-hop, but race and hip-hop. Race was
unavoidable in hip-hop. Hip-hop had inspired him to believe that,
precisely because he was black, he could achieve what whites simply
assumed was theirs by birthright _ a gainful life over which he
asserted control. By N.R. Kleinfield. (6775 words, plus an abridged
version of about half that length)
</P>
<P>
   Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   These stories are available for repeats:
</P>
<P>
   RACE-SPORTS (Baton Rouge, La.) _ In July 1996, Southern
University, a powerhouse among black colleges, desperately needed a
quarterback, and a white player, Marcus Jacoby, badly needed a
place to play quarterback. Southern's head coach, Pete Richardson,
recruited Jacoby. The decision made headlines. So began an odyssey
of triumph and defeat on and off the football field. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT120-125 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-PAPER (Akron, Ohio) _ Carl Chancellor and Bob Dyer were
part of a team of reporters for The Akron Beacon Journal that had
explored the racial attitudes of this city. Their series earned the
paper the Pulitzer Prize. The Beacon Journal also tried to lead by
example, and shortly after the series ended, it introduced a lineup
of columnists reflecting ``the perfect demographic,'' as Dyer put
it. They included a black woman and a white woman as well as
Chancellor, who is black, and Dyer, who is white. The paper, it
seemed, had become a proud model of racial enlightenment. Which
made it all the more startling when just a year later, the
jubilation began to fade. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT110-116 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-POLITICS (Bainbridge Island, Wash.) _ Many voters here say
that by putting a Chinese immigrant's son and two descendants of
slaves atop the governing pyramid of the state, Washington state
has transcended race. But if the old racial order has eroded, a
more complex one has replaced it, and now the system rewards
nonwhites who know how to make the largely white electorate see in
them what the voters see in themselves. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT701-706 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-CHURCH (Decatur, Ga.) _ Nearly 50 years after the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. scolded Christians for making 11 a.m Sunday
the most segregated hour of the week, the Assembly of God
Tabernacle here is the rarest of religious institutions: a truly
integrated church in the heart of the South. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT101-106 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-IMMIGRANTS (Miami) _ Before they left Cuba for America in
1994 Joel Ruiz, who is black, and Achmed Valdes, who is white, were
the best of friends. Today, in Miami, the two men live only 4 miles
apart, not even 15 minutes by car. Yet they are separated by a far
greater distance, one they say they never envisioned back in Cuba.
By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT201-207 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MILITARY (Fort Knox, Ky.) _ On a chill December morning,
two soldiers _ one black, one white, both part of an institution
portrayed as a model of race relations _ stood only yards apart in
the middle of this sprawling base, each believing himself the
victim of racism; one because of an award, the other because of a
transfer. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT301-307 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-TV-DRAMA (Baltimore) _ Who Gets to Tell a Black Story: When
David Simon proposed to HBO a television series based on his book,
``The Corner,'' about black inner-city drug addicts, he was not
thinking much about the fact that he was white, but as the project
began to take shape, the issues of race loomed ever larger. By
Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT401-407 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-WEB-ENTREPRENEUR (Atlanta) _ Timothy Fitzgerald Stevenson
Cobb Jr. and his partner, Jeff Levy, had built an Internet research
company in Atlanta and by May 1999 each man's net worth had swelled
by about $25 million. It conferred an uncommon distinction on Cobb:
He became one of the country's few black Internet millionaires. The
racial backdrop to Cobb's accomplishments went largely unmentioned
by the people he did business with, but he seemed never to forget
it. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT501-506 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MEAT-PLANT (Tar Heel, N.C.) _ The first thing you learn at
the Smithfield hog plant here is the value of a sharp knife. The
second thing you learn is that not everyone has to work with a
knife. Whites, blacks, American Indians and Mexicans, they all have
their separate stations, but it is blacks and Mexicans that are
left to battle over the dirty jobs, one of the only places in this
muddy corner of North Carolina where a person might make more than
$8 an hour. By Charlie LeDuff.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT601-606 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-PLANTATION (Natchitoches, La.) _ At the south edge of the
old plantation, eight simple cabins stood in a field of clover.
Generations of whitewash were peeling in ugly patches from the
mud-brick walls. All but one front porch had rotted away, and there
were gaping holes where doors and windows used to be. Obscured by
rows of live oaks, the cabins had been forgotten by many and
ignored by most. There was almost nothing left _ except the stories
of the slaves who once lived in them. Will re-enactments of slave
life at a former plantation, now a national park, help to heal
racial wounds _ or open them? By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT901-908.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-KIDS (Maplewood, N.J.) _ Friendships ebb and end. It
happens everywhere, but what is striking is that it happens even
here, where the school district is extraordinarily mixed. But as if
pulled by internal magnets, black and white children begin to
separate at sixth grade. These are children who walked to school
together, learned to read together, slept over at each other's
houses. But race becomes as much a fault line in their world as in
the world their parents hoped to move beyond. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   Photos NYT801-NYT806 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
</P>
