A2829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-RUN-PEACHTREE-COX     07-04 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-PEACHTREE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peachtree Road Race 2000: New winners, old traditions
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson and Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the Peachtree Road Race of 2000 _ call it our Y2K
10K _ is any indication, the next 30 years of the world's largest
road race might be more remarkable than the first 30.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's 31st edition of the Peachtree had some big winners:
</P>
<P>
   Alene Emere. The 20-year-old Ethiopian never had set foot on
U.S. soil or run a 10K race on the road before winning Peachtree
2000 by one second over course record-holder Joseph Kimani of
Kenya. Emere beat one of the deepest, most competitive men's fields
in Peachtree history and won in 28 minutes, 4 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Lornah Kiplagat of Kenya. She won her first Peachtree in her
fourth attempt and ran away from the women's field so much that she
briefly considered slowing down to make the race more competitive.
Kiplagat thought better of it and tied the women's course record of
30:52.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Driscoll. She felt ``euphoric'' after winning the women's
wheelchair division for the sixth time in record time. ``My goal
was to reclaim this hilly course,'' said Driscoll, 33, who broke
her own course record with a time of 24:16.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland's Franz Nietelispach. He held off defending champion
Saul Mendoza of Mexico by a second in 19:27 to capture his third
wheelchair Peachtree in four years.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of swift 40-year-olds, Kenya's Andrew Masai and 1989
Peachtree winner Judi St. Hilaire. They won the masters divisions
in 29:37 and 34:16, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   They were the swiftest of the 55,000 who sallied forth down
Peachtree on a warm, but not oppressive, Fourth of July morning,
relatively benign by past Peachtree standards.
</P>
<P>
   The race featured its customary cast of patriotic characters.
Abigail Snead, 17, of Cumming, Ga., dribbled a red-and-blue
basketball the entire way. A group of veterans, chanting and
showing some fancy footwork, occasionally went backwards. Various
runners were Uncle Sams and Statues of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Frank and Patti Lott, who drove from Clarkesville, Tenn., to
stay with relatives in Decatur, Ga., for their 16th Peachtree, said
they wanted to do something special to mark the 2000 Peachtree.
They went to the pre-race expo and stocked up for the holiday: red,
white and blue bandannas, shorts adorned with American flags and
Patti's tank top with a swirling Old Glory across her chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a happening,'' Frank Lott said. ``We are way back in the
pack, but we're just runners who love to have a good time. It's a
great tradition, and we just have a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   They're not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
