<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Potent but widely separated thunderstorms, a few with large hail
and damaging winds, will erupt over eastern Montana and western
North Dakota Wednesday as moist winds from the southeast glide up
the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of heavy thunderstorms will develop across parts of
Iowa and Illinois as very warm and humid air interacts with a
stationary front. A separate system of thunderstorms will produce
heavy rains early Wednesday over the lower Ohio River Valley. The
system will gradually weaken as it slips southeast toward western
Virginia and the western Carolinas late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Humidity will ease Wednesday across the Northeast in the wake of
a front moving off the coast. In the West, isolated but potent
thunderstorms will develop over the Sierra Nevada and Klamath
Mountains of Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: RECORD GUSTS
</P>
<P>
   Winds from a severe thunderstorm gusted to 82 mph on Monday at
Glasgow, Mont., setting a record at that town nestled in the
state's northeast corner. The previous record gust was 76 mph in
1997. Towns like Glasgow, which are immune from the supercharged
winds of hurricanes, powerful coastal storms in winter and
destructive downslope windstorms in the foothills of the Rockies,
typically set records for gusts in severe thunderstorms. Localized
winds in tornadoes seldom qualify since they are usually estimated
by assessing the extent of damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
