<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-NY-STREET-FOOD-NYT &LR;      07-04 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STREET-FOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$25 AND UNDER: OUTSIDE THE WINDOW, THE STREETS OF EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The name `Knoedel' should be set minus the first 'e' and with
an umlaut over the `o'.) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a dedicated follower of fast food fashions, I was
at the head of the line when overstuffed burritos first landed in
New York and when sandwiches changed their names to wraps. Last
year, when Belgian frites shacks started appearing on every corner,
I was dipping fries into mayonnaise all over Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The smorgasbord is always expanding, and no matter how novel it
seems, it is always rooted in traditional street food. The newest
arrivals are admirable versions of great old European standards,
like waffles, sausages and crepes _ all served with American speed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new kiosks, cafes and restaurants are F&AMP;B in Chelsea,
which calls itself a ``European-style eatery'' devoted to ``gourmet
hot dogs.'' In the East Village, Bulgin' Waffles is making the case
that the waffle is every bit as Continental as its more glamorous
cousin, the crepe, which, by the way, has also seen a surge in
restaurants promoting it recently, the latest being Rue des Crepes
in Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   And in Grand Central Terminal, Christer Larsson, the owner of
Christer's on West 55th Street, has opened Knoedel, a kiosk that
treats American-style sausages with European veneration. These
restaurant owners clearly recognize the value of European patina,
even when applied to fast food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that American appetites have become more refined, and
they associate that with European culture,'' said Jeffrey Starin,
the owner of Bulgin' Waffles, who decided to forsake computer
programming for the waffle business after reading a Goldman, Sachs
report a few years ago noting that frozen waffle sales were
increasing by 12 percent a year. ``The crepe has been exploited,
and so has the pancake, but not the waffle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the waffle is now ready for prime time, how about blini? They
are the specialty at Blini Hut in lower Manhattan, along with other
Russian dishes like borscht and pirogi. And where once the sandwich
stood proud as the epitome of the quick American meal, little
Italian panini are encroaching at places like Via Quadronno on the
Upper East Side, Il Posto Accanto in the East Village and numerous
other cafes.
</P>
<P>
   As anyone knows who remembers Zum Zum, a 1960s-era fast-food
chain serving German sausages, the current wave of restaurants is
not an entirely new phenomenon. And of course, hamburgers and
frankfurters reflect their onetime immigrant status in their names.
But as Americans have shifted their critical gaze to include not
only fine wines but also items that were once taken for granted,
like beer, bagels and cigars, these entrepreneurs are setting their
sights on a higher order of fast foods.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Starin's spare corner restaurant, which most resembles
an American college-town coffeehouse, serves wonderful waffles. The
namesake Bulgin' Waffle ($4), the kind you might find in Belgium,
is indeed big and thick, yet it's airy and fluffy. Even better are
the smaller buckwheat wafflettes ($1.75), exquisitely light and
crisp, with more flavor than the big, white-flour waffles. You
won't find those in Belgium, which is Belgium's loss. The biggest
drawbacks at Bulgin' are that the waffles are served on paper
plates with flimsy plastic cutlery and that you have to pay 85
cents for pure maple syrup or any of the excellent fruit syrups.
</P>
<P>
   F&AMP;B, a sleek storefront decorated in soothing pastels with
pleasant lighting, offers a more self-consciously European visage.
The name stands for frites and beignets, but hot dogs are the
centerpiece, including the excellent Great Dane ($2.85), a slender,
red Danish sausage with bright snap to it. It is eaten just as it
is in Denmark, on a roll with frizzled onions, marinated cucumbers,
mustard, ketchup and remoulade.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a lot, but it's an easy mouthful, especially
compared with the Top Dog ($2.85), a plumper German-style sausage
topped with tame sauerkraut and crumbled bacon. Frites ($1.75 to
$5) are crisp and savory, and for an extra 50 cents, they are
served with toppings including aioli, blue cheese and truffle oil.
</P>
<P>
   If truffle oil on frites is your idea of heaven, you may as well
also indulge in a small bottle of champagne ($12). I'd stick with
fresh lemonade ($2.10) or Belgian-style beer ($4).
</P>
<P>
   The sausages are plumper, richer and more expensive at Knoedel,
Larsson's kiosk in the Food Court at Grand Central. Larsson's
restaurant is Scandinavian, but his sausages are American, served
on fresh potato rolls with assorted toppings like hot dogs, though
derived from the European tradition of creative sausage making.
</P>
<P>
   The fine Knoedel brat ($6.95), for example, is mostly savory
pork, with pureed fig for a bit of sweetness and softer texture
and, surprise, pine nuts, which fit in perfectly. Knoedel also
serves an excellent smoky, spicy andouille ($6.95) and a sweet and
smoky chicken-and-apple sausage ($6.95), both from Aidells Sausage
Co. Sides include sesame-scented Asian slaw ($2), with red cabbage,
carrots and raisins.
</P>
<P>
   Knoedel, by the way, is the German word for dumpling. It has
nothing to do with sausages, but Larsson said he likes the way it
sounds.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, crepes have been associated more with kitschy
French-American restaurants of the 1950s than with French street
food, and Rue des Crepes does little to remedy that. The little
dining room resembles a cobblestone Left Bank street by way of
Disney World, complete with street signs and other contrived cues.
But it matters little, because the crepes are very good. Savory
combinations, wrapped in soft buckwheat crepes, include merguez
sausage with white beans and garlic ($7.95) and chewy flank steak
with caramelized onions ($7.95). I especially enjoyed sweet
fillings, like Nutella and banana ($5.50), and the simple lemon and
butter ($2.95) wrapped in white-flour crepes.
</P>
<P>
   You won't think you're in Paris, but you won't think you're in
the '50s anymore, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD     07-04 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LAX MILITARY SECURITY PERMITTED BOMBINGS IN CHECHNYA, RUSSIAN
OFFICIAL SAYS (SUBS 6th graf to delete last line; 9th graf to add
details)  
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Negligence by Russian commanders enabled Chechen
suicide bombers to carry out the devastating attacks on Sunday that
killed more than 30 soldiers, the chief of Russia's intelligence
service said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Patrushev, the director of the Federal Security Service,
said that his agency had alerted the Russian military that
terrorist attacks were being planned but that the military had
failed to take proper precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a mistake on the part of commanders in the field,''
he said. ``We have to act in a coordinated fashion to prevent such
things from happening in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Five trucks loaded with munitions exploded in Chechnya Sunday
night, catching the Russian military by surprise and shocking the
nation. Russian officials on Tuesday put the final toll at 33 dead,
84 wounded and three missing.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to restore control over Chechnya's towns and settlements,
Russian officials on Tuesday issued a ``shoot on sight'' order for
any vehicle that breached a 9 p.m. to 7 a.m. curfew. New
checkpoints have been set up, and many Chechen residents were
reportedly staying at home.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 people have been detained, but it is not clear if the
Russian authorities have found any of those who organized the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   A series of devastating explosions in Russian apartment
buildings in September helped build public support for the war.
Russian officials said then that the rebels were to blame, but
there is no conclusive proof of their role.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sunday bombings, most of the casualties were in Argun, a
town east of Grozny, where a truck bomb slammed into a dormitory
occupied by a militia unit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite alerts of possible attacks, there was no concrete
barrier or other obstacle to stop the truck, which may have been
operated by two suicide bombers, from approaching the building.
</P>
<P>
   Providing new details of that attack, Russian television
reported Tuesday night that 22 militia members had been killed in
that attack and 48 wounded. Many of the dead and wounded were
buried under the debris.
</P>
<P>
   After the bomb exploded, Chechen snipers began shooting at the
building, and a gunfight continued for one-and-a-half hours.
</P>
<P>
   While Russian officials agreed that negligence was a factor,
they said that it was the fault of local commanders, not Gen. Ivan
Babichev, the military commandant of Chechnya.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The destruction in Argun ``resulted from the failure to comply
with an order by General Babichev that additional security measures
were to be taken,'' said Sergei Yastrzhembsky, the senior Russian
government spokesman on the war.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to put the best face on a worsening situation, Akhmad
Kadyrov, the Russian-appointed administrator of Chechnya, described
the bombings as a desperate act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebel leaders are seriously concerned that the people have
lately begun to nurture hope for Chechnya's peaceful development,''
Kadyrov told the news agency Interfax.
</P>
<P>
   Others took a more pessimistic view. Boris Berezovsky, the media
tycoon and a parliamentary deputy who represents a region in the
North Caucasus, said that Russia would not be able to win a
military victory in Chechnya. During the Yeltsin administration,
Berezovsky served as a negotiator in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of the jingoists' loud statements, most of Russian
society believes the war in Chechnya is leading our country to
defeat,'' he said. ``There can be no military victory in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Chechnya, it is necessary to reach an agreement with the
most extremist element of the Chechen population, as well. If the
political process is dragged out, it will be hard on Russia,
including our president's image.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin has kept a low profile in
recent days and has little to say about the bombing attacks, which
have challenged the Kremlin's claims to control the breakaway
republic.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, for their part, were more vocal. They promised more
attacks, warning civilians to move away from Russian bases and
command posts.
</P>
<P>
   Shamil Basayev, the Chechen warlord, demanded that Russian
authorities hand over a Russian officer accused of the rape and
murder of a Chechen woman, according to a Chechen spokesman,
Movladi Udogov. Otherwise, he vowed, there would be more bombing
attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
