<HEADER>
A2834 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-LEMONADE-NYT &LR;      07-04 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEMONADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEMONADE, FROM PLAIN TO PERFECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a drink that seems quintessentially American,
lemonade is at its purest in France. Any cafe there will serve what
is called a citron presse, a glass filled partway with pulpy,
freshly squeezed lemon juice along with a carafe of water and a jar
of simple syrup or superfine sugar for diluting and sweetening to
taste. It is the essence of fresh lemons, the antithesis of the
artificial or too-sweet lemonades so common in this country, where
even children are considered capable of making a pitcherful to sell
at a sidewalk stand.
</P>
<P>
   Citron presse, though, is always the same. In New York, now that
imaginative chefs have embraced the concept, lemonade is becoming
more of a many-splendored drink, made in myriad fruit flavors. What
these chefs are concocting are tart, lemony beverages that easily
rival the French ideal. Their innovations could reawaken interest
in homemade lemonade, and not just for children.
</P>
<P>
   City Bakery off Union Square has been ahead of the curve for
years, serving an excellent version of lemonade as a summertime
sales builder to replace the hot chocolate dispensed in cold
months. The owner, Maury Rubin, is so passionate about lemonade
that he offers at least two types every day, one plain and one
flavored with the juice of a seasonal fruit. Last week the seasonal
fruit drink was a pale red cherry lemonade, just slightly sweeter
than the plain.
</P>
<P>
   Esca, in the theater district, is also using cherries in
lemonade, although the chef, David Pasternack, started out in the
spring _ when the restaurant opened _ by flavoring it with rhubarb
pulp. As apricots and peaches become more available, he says, he
plans to continue varying the recipe. Esca also offers lemonade
spiked with Campari, which may be the best adult version ever
created.
</P>
<P>
   At Gotham Bar and Grill, the house lemonade is flavored with
fresh ginger and whatever berries are in season. The ginger lends a
peppery note to the combination, whether strawberries, raspberries
or both are used. Joseph Murphy, the pastry chef and lemon
squeezer, says the summery drink sells well at lunchtime as an
alternative to bottled water when diners are drinking less wine and
cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   Other restaurants are relying on other fruit flavors for
lemonade. Avenue on the Upper West Side makes a sweet strawberry
version to serve in a glass coupe with a ripe red berry perched on
the rim. Bayou in Harlem adds lime and mint, while Rustic in
Brooklyn is using pomegranate juice. Throughout this whole month,
Cucina at Macy's is featuring a different lemonade flavor every
day, from mango to cantaloupe.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Daniel Silverman at Union Square Cafe simply
heightens the pure lemon flavor by adding dried lemons and lemon
grass. ``The lemon grass has a bright, citrusy element to it, while
the dried lemons add a deeper, base note,'' he said. ``But you
can't actually taste them. In the end it just tastes like really
good lemonade.''
</P>
<P>
   So does the old-fashioned plain lemonade at Good in Greenwich
Village, which is tart but not sharp and filled with thinly sliced
lemons. The chef, Steven Picker, first makes a simple syrup by
boiling and stirring a cup and a half of sugar with a cup of water
until the granules dissolve. After it cools, he combines it with 2
cups of juice freshly squeezed from about 16 lemons, adds 6 cups of
water and chills it completely to make enough lemonade for 10
people or one sidewalk stand.
</P>
<P>
   Once it's finished and poured over ice, it's even better than a
citron presse, since you don't have to mix it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   CHERRY LEMONADE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Esca &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes plus chilling &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cherries, pitted and stemmed (about 1 pound), plus extra
for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh lemon juice (about 8 lemons).
</P>
<P>
   1. Using a juicer or food mill, juice cherries. Reserve juice.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a small saucepan, bring sugar and 1 cup water to a simmer.
Cook, stirring, until sugar dissolves. Pour syrup into a pitcher,
and add 1 cup cherry juice, 1 cup lemon juice and 2 cups water.
Chill until thoroughly cold, at least 2 hours. Serve over ice,
garnished with 2 cherries.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GINGER-BERRY LEMONADE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Gotham Bar and Grill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 50 minutes plus chilling &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups coarsely chopped fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced fresh strawberries or raspberries, or a combination
</P>
<P>
   4 cups fresh lemon juice (from about 32 lemons)
</P>
<P>
   Lemon slices for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large saucepan over high heat, combine sugar and ginger
with 8 cups water. Bring to a boil, stirring occasionally until
sugar dissolves. Boil for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Transfer from heat, and let cool for 15 minutes. Strain
through a fine sieve, discarding solids, and refrigerate until well
chilled.
</P>
<P>
   3. Set aside about a third of the berries for garnish. In a
blender or food processor, process remaining berries until smooth.
Strain puree through a mesh sieve, pressing berries with back of a
wooden spoon to extract as much juice as possible. Discard solids.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a pitcher, combine ginger syrup, strained berries and
lemon juice. Serve over ice, garnished with reserved berries and
lemon slices.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   LEMONADE WITH LEMON GRASS AND DRIED LEMON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Union Square Cafe &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes, plus chilling &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk lemon grass, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 dried lemon (see note)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups fresh lemon juice (from about 24 lemons).
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine sugar, lemon grass and dried lemon in a saucepan. Add
2 cups water, and bring mixture to a boil. Simmer 5 to 7 minutes or
until dried lemon is tender. Use a spoon to squash lemon against
side of pan.
</P>
<P>
   2. Turn off heat, and let mixture rest for 10 minutes, then
strain it into a pitcher. Add lemon juice and 6 cups cold water.
Chill until thoroughly cold, at least 2 hours. Serve over ice.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Dried lemons are available at Middle Eastern markets like
Kalustyan's, 123 Lexington Avenue, between 28th and 29th Streets,
(212) 685-3451, and Sahadi's, 187 Atlantic Avenue, between Court
and Clinton Streets, Brooklyn, (718) 624-4550.
</P>
</TEXT>
