<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TREVOR-NUNN-THEATER-2     07-04 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREVOR-NUNN-THEATER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LONDON, A FULL HOUSE FEELS EMPTY TO CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ While some commercial theatrical producers are accusing
nonprofit theaters in the United States of abandoning their mandate
to take risks and of playing it safe to fill seats, at least one
government-subsidized theater is the subject of similar attacks in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Trevor Nunn, whose credits as director include
``Cats,'' ``Les Miserables'' and ``Nicholas Nickleby'' and who
headed the Royal Shakespeare Company for 18 years, has come under
considerable fire in the London papers for his three-year-old
stewardship of the Royal National Theater.
</P>
<P>
   In general, critics have taken Nunn to task for what they call
cautious programming that they say leans too heavily on
crowd-pleasing musicals and not enough on new work and younger
playwrights. Writing in The Guardian in April, Michael Billington
said: ``What one craves from the National is some alternative to a
musical-dominated commercial culture rather than a duplication of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Billington compared the current National with that of Nunn's
formidable predecessors, Sir Peter Hall and Richard Eyre,
suggesting that Nunn had abandoned the institution's mandate to
break new ground and had failed to make a home for up-and-coming
talent. ``The irony is that under Peter Hall and Richard Eyre, new
writing was the National's strongest card,'' Billington argued.
``Under Trevor Nunn it has become its Achilles' heel.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when Nunn does showcase new work, some critics say, he
misfires. ``Nunn's choice of new work _ Stephen Poliakoff's abysmal
`Remember This' and Nick Stafford's `Battle Royal,''' wrote
Nicholas De Jongh in The Evening Standard, ``reminded us what a
feeble judge of new plays he is.''
</P>
<P>
   All this is coming while the National, on London's South Bank,
has had a banner year by any standards. In February it won won a
record nine Olivier Awards, the London equivalent of the Tony
Awards, including one for best director for Nunn. The new musical
``Honk!,'' based on ``The Ugly Duckling,'' beat ``The Lion King''
for best new musical.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the theater's 43 productions this past season received
stellar reviews, including ``The Merchant of Venice'' and
``Summerfolk.'' The National also exported three productions to New
York: ``Copenhagen,'' which won the Tony Award for best play;
``Rose,'' a one-woman play with Olympia Dukakis, which had a less
successful run; and ``Our Lady of Sligo,'' a critically praised new
Irish drama off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Nunn sent over ``Not About Nightingales,'' a
previously unproduced play by Tennessee Williams that was widely
praised by critics. And, next season, Nunn's acclaimed production
of ``Oklahoma!,'' produced by Cameron Mackintosh, is expected on
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   In The Evening Standard, Nunn answered his critics with a
1,500-word explanation of his goals for the National and how he is
trying to achieve them. In the piece, he quoted Laurence Olivier,
who once told him, ``Make no mistake, my boy, running a
state-subsidized theater will always be a war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my darker moments at the South Bank, I feel I know just
what he meant,'' Nunn continued, ``but most of the time I recognize
the flak for what it is: a necessary and ongoing debate about what
a national theater ought to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Peter said that catching flak was part of the job
description and that what Nunn had suffered so far was
comparatively mild. ``It's a political appointment, and you get a
lot of mud thrown at you,'' Sir Peter said. ``I'm sure Trevor would
love to take risks in the National's two main houses, but he'd get
run out of town if he didn't balance the books.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office on a break between rehearsals recently,
Nunn acknowledged that taking the risk to produce untested work
demanded more bravery now than it once did. ``The effort to come to
new plays is greater than it ever used to be,'' he said. ``You have
to these days recognize the consequence that you could be doing
considerable damage to your box office figures if you do that. But
one's got to be able to dare. This is not a time to be timid.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunn is constantly aware of the financial pressure. He succeeded
in getting the government's Arts Council, which distributes
treasury money to the arts, to increase its annual grant to the
National to about $21 million; the grant had been frozen at $19
million for six years. Still, Nunn has said, he has to raise $3.5
million more from private sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nonstop,'' he said. ``It's a sword of Damocles that
dangles above us by a thread and you're constantly imagining that
the thread is going to break, it's going to slice you in two.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunn suggests that the critics have pigeonholed him as populist
because they associate him with ``Cats'' and Andrew Lloyd Webber,
who is known for appealing to middlebrow tastes. He also defends
his decision to do musicals, having long disputed any distinction
between what is artistically worthy and what is commercially
popular. Nunn maintains, for example, that ``Oklahoma!'' is not
only a palatable piece of entertainment but also a pivotal work
that changed musical theater.
</P>
<P>
   As for new work, Nunn said that up-and-coming playwrights were
welcome and that he was committed to producing venturesome
material. ``At least 50 percent of the work should be new
writing,'' he said. ``We should be commissioning more, we should be
developing and encouraging more new writing in all sorts of
different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Nunn said, it is not easy to tap into a new
generation of Gorkys or Marlowes, writers who changed the form with
their plays. ``You can't just bring about such an age because you
want it,'' he said. ``It has to be a confluence of people wanting
it and talent and interest being present and available. But I sense
that is the case.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the latest slings and arrows, Nunn clearly takes
refuge in the work itself. Perhaps his greatest point of pride is
in bringing on an ensemble of 50 actors, each with an unusually
diverse series of roles in the company's repertory, from a small
part in Shakespeare's ``Troilus and Cressida'' to a lead role in
the Leonard Bernstein musical ``Candide.'' The whole group agreed
to stay for 18 months, from January 1999 to June 2000. ``I think
that alone is evidence that something special is happening here,''
Nunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn has received considerable praise for this ensemble. Writing
in the The Times of London, Benedict Nightingale called Nunn's
troupe ``the most exciting innovation of his two-year reign.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Blakemore, who directed ``Copenhagen'' and has known
Nunn for many years, said that getting to know cast members over an
entire season adds a layer of loyalty to the theatergoing
experience. ``You can follow individual actors like you follow
members of the sports team,'' he said. ``It's the first time the
National has been a resident company.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was any advice Blakemore might have for Nunn, he said,
it would be to enlist some help and attempt less himself. ``I'm a
little surprised he hasn't taken on board a small group of
associate directors,'' Blakemore said. ``He may be trying to do too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunn, 60, conceded that the job had taken a personal toll, that
he had had less time than he would have liked to see his five
children _ ages 4, 9, 11, 14 and 19 _ and his wife, the actress
Imogen Stubbs. ``You need to feel there are rewards, that you're
making some progress,'' he said. ``I've become a bit of an Eeyore
these days. There's a looking on the grimmer side.''
</P>
<P>
   He feels there is much left to accomplish. While he has stepped
up the National's touring, he hopes to do still more as well as to
showcase the best of Britain's regional theaters. (The National
imported the Birmingham Rep's version of ``Baby Doll,'' which
subsequently moved to the West End, and West Yorkshire's revival of
``Singin' in the Rain,'' which plays till July 20.)
</P>
<P>
   Nunn also wants to attract younger and more diverse audiences
with special offers. ``There is a perception that the National
Theater is for affluent middle England,'' he said. ``It's a
perception that I'm determined to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Nunn's tenure expires in 2002, there is no obvious
successor in view. Would he be interested in a second term, as has
been rumored? ``Thoughts about leaving are connected to thoughts
about succession,'' Nunn said. ``One has to know the organization
is going to go from strength to strength, rather than by certain
calendar day. I'm a believer in organizations finding their future
from within. That takes nurturing time.''
</P>
<P>
   While he could fill his time at the National simply dealing with
administrative matters like raising money and programming, he
continues to direct (he staged three productions last season) and
believes the two roles are complementary. ``The only place from
which the theater can be led is the rehearsal room,'' he said. ``I
say that in as doctrinaire a way as you care to report it. Doing
work, creating work in the rehearsal room is where all the energy
of a theater organization proceeds from.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Planning a repertoire can only be done by artists,'' he
continued. ``Artists with passions, artists with visions, artists
with obsessions. Then all of those things have to be rationalized
and made possible. They have to be enabled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
