<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-DESSERTS-BOOK-REVIEW-     07-04 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESSERTS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO DESSERT COOKBOOKS PROVIDE PLENTY OF TIMELESS FAVORITES 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer turns the clock back. We recapture childhood, eat hog
dogs at street fairs, have picnics, sip lemonade and hanker for
old-fashioned treats like strawberry shortcake.
</P>
<P>
   So, how do you like your strawberry shortcake? Made with layers
of feathery golden spongecake slathered with whipped cream and
studded with berries? Or with a rich, crumbly biscuit as the
underpinning for the cream and fruit?
</P>
<P>
   Today, both are considered shortcake, though technically a
shortcake is a sweet biscuit-style cake made with a lot of
shortening _ hence the name _ or butter. If the spongecake style is
for you, so is ``Retro Desserts'' by Wayne Harley Brachman (Morrow,
$27). It claims its recipe, called ``diner-style strawberry
shortcake,'' is the one diners always used. But in ``Diner
Desserts'' (Chronicle Books, $18.95), Tish Boyle begs to differ,
saying her biscuit-style strawberry shortcake is the true diner
classic. Can we take a vote?
</P>
<P>
   Both of these new cookbooks are filled, cover to cover, with
mostly timeless favorites, many of which _ like the shortcakes, all
sorts of ice cream specialties, a sumptuous fresh strawberry
chiffon pie and moist crumb-topped blueberry muffins _ are suited
to summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retro Desserts'' has fancier sweets, like crepes suzette,
brandy Alexander pie, eclairs, cherries jubilee and baked alaska,
but no recipes for coffeecake, cobbler, doughnuts or muffins. The
source for those, as well as for German chocolate cake, is ``Diner
Desserts.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's plenty of overlap in the books: Boston cream pie,
coconut layer cake, black-and-white cookies, rum-raisin rice
pudding and butterscotch pudding show up in both.
</P>
<P>
   I was delighted to find finely tuned recipes in each book.
Brachman, who worked as the executive pastry chef at Mesa Grill and
Bolo in Manhattan and now has the same position at Michael
Jordan's: The Steakhouse, Tapika and the Strip House, which will
open soon, is a rare restaurant chef: he has written a book without
the help of a professional cookbook writer. He obviously tested his
recipes with great care on home equipment. It's no surprise that
Boyle, the food editor of the magazines Chocolatier and Pastry Art
&AMP; Design, knew what she was doing when it came to recipe writing.
</P>
<P>
   Though I loved some of Brachman's innovations, like using white
chocolate in brandy Alexander and grasshopper pies, I was not
tempted by some of his more cock-eyed numbers, like cookies made
with chow mein noodles, rocky road ``pizza'' on a chocolate crust,
or cornflake macaroons. And I wish I could have prepared his
Nesselrode pie using commercially prepared fruit instead of having
to concoct a liquor-soaked mixture at home, with canned chestnuts,
no less. On the other hand, I wanted to make his mousse-like
mile-high peach pie from scratch with fresh fruit, but he called
for frozen fruit only.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, though the peach cobbler in ``Diner Desserts'' calls
for fresh peaches, the cherry pie uses canned fruit. That's the
downside to throwback baking. It's too bad the author did not
suggest fresh fruit as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diner Desserts'' updates peach cobbler with crystallized
ginger, which I liked, but I omitted the orange zest in that book's
black-and-white cookies. I preferred Brachman's version, which
calls for a touch of lemon. I also liked his rice pudding, made
simply with half-and-half, better than Boyle's custardy version.
</P>
<P>
   If pushed, I'd have trouble picking one book over the other,
because the recipes are never highfalutin, and are so reliable that
they're truly fun to prepare and serve. That's what summer's all
about.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY CHIFFON PIE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Retro Desserts'''
</P>
<P>
   Time: { hour, plus baking time for pastry and 2 hours' chilling
</P>
<P>
   1 quart strawberries, hulled, plus 8 big berries for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 envelopes plain gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream plus { cup (optional) to whip for serving
</P>
<P>
   4 large egg whites, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   Pastry shell baked in 9 1/2- to 10-inch tart pan with removable
bottom, cooled.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place berries in food processor with 3/4 cup sugar. Puree.
Transfer 1/2 cup puree to a 1-quart metal bowl, and stir in gelatin
to soften. Refrigerate remaining puree.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whip cup of cream until softly peaked. Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mix egg whites with cream of tartar, salt and remaining sugar
in metal bowl of electric mixer. Set bowl atop a saucepan of
simmering water. Whisk mixture until very hot, 150 degrees to 160
degrees. Transfer bowl to mixer, and beat at high speed 2-3
minutes, until mixture holds soft peaks and is the consistency of
shaving cream. Egg whites will become very thick and white, but not
increase in volume as much as if beaten without heating.
Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   4. Set bowl of gelatin-puree over pan of simmering water until
gelatin dissolves and mixture liquefies, about a minute. Gradually
whisk in remaining strawberry puree. Fold into chilled whipped
cream. Fold in a third of egg white mixture, then remaining egg
whites.
</P>
<P>
   5. Pour into cooled pie shell. Chill at least 2 hours, until
set. Garnish with fresh strawberries and, if desired, more whipped
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   JUMBO CRUMBLY BLUEBERRY MUFFINS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Diner Desserts''`
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   11 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh blueberries
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract.
</P>
<P>
   1. Melt 6 tablespoons butter. Cool. Use 1 tablespoon butter to
grease six 8-ounce muffin cups. Toss blueberries with 1 tablespoon
flour. Set aside. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Dice remaining butter with 1/2 cup flour, 1 teaspoon cinnamon
and brown sugar. Mash until crumbly.
</P>
<P>
   3. In large bowl, mix remaining flour with sugar, baking powder,
baking soda, remaining cinnamon and salt. Make a well in center.
</P>
<P>
   4. Whisk egg into melted butter. Whisk in buttermilk and
vanilla. Gradually pour into well, stirring to combine ingredients.
Do not over mix. Fold in blueberries. Divide batter into muffin
cups and top each with crumble mixture.
</P>
<P>
   5. Bake about 35 minutes, until cake tester comes out clean.
Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 large muffins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
