<HEADLINE>
BUILDING A SALAD CLEVERLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whole-meal salads always feel like a bit of trickery. The best
ones are as interesting and varied as a well-conceived meal, and
they invariably leave guests impressed that a mere salad could be
so satisfying. But the fact that the base is a pile of greens makes
me feel as if I'm getting away with something. And I suppose I am.
This one, for example, made with grilled scallops and a mesclun
mix, takes only 10 minutes longer to make than an ordinary green
salad.
</P>
<P>
   Good whole-meal salads have several things in common. There are
a range of textures _ crunchy greens, a toothsome meat or fish, a
creamy dressing _ and ingredients cut into a variety of sizes and
shapes. The flavors are usually simple, but they build on one
another to create a whole that is greater than the sum of its
parts.
</P>
<P>
   This salad accomplishes that with few ingredients. The greens
are basic; you can use any combination, or a single lettuce, but a
mesclun mix is the easiest and best choice. The dressing is
powerful and delicious. You might call it a soy-sesame vinaigrette,
but there's more to it than that. Although it will taste exotic to
most people, it's prepared with fairly common ingredients like soy
sauce, sesame paste, ginger and garlic.
</P>
<P>
   I use a blender to assemble the dressing for two reasons: It
makes quick work of dispersing the sesame paste throughout the
liquid ingredients _ something that can be difficult to do with a
fork or a whisk _ and because the blender purees the garlic and
ginger, it eliminates the need to mince them.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled scallops are almost ludicrously fast and easy, and their
texture and flavor complement the greens and the dressing. But you
could also use shrimp, steak or boneless chicken _ preferably
thighs, which have better flavor than breasts and are less likely
to dry out over the grill's heat. Whichever you choose, you could
also cook it on top of the stove in a grill pan or a regular
skillet.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe's timing is one of its strengths. Start the grill, or
heat a pan on top of the stove, and while it is getting warm, make
the dressing and wash the greens. When everything is ready, sear
the scallops just long enough to brown the exterior _ a couple of
minutes a side is plenty.
</P>
<P>
   TRIPLE SESAME SALAD WITH SCALLOPS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   \ cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   \ cup rice wine or other vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sesame tahini or smooth peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon crushed red pepper flakes, cayenne or ground chilies,
or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon peeled and chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon peeled and chopped ginger
</P>
<P>
   1{ to 2 pounds sea scallops
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 cups mesclun or other salad greens, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   \ cup torn Thai or other basil, washed and dried, optional
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare a gas or charcoal grill. Place soy, vinegar, tahini,
sesame oil, red pepper, honey, garlic and ginger in a blender, and
blend until smooth. When the grill is hot, sprinkle scallops with
salt and grill about 2 minutes a side; they should remain tender
and undercooked in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine greens and basil, and divide among 4 plates. When
scallops are done, place them on top of the greens. Drizzle with
dressing, sprinkle with sesame seeds and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
