<HEADER>
A2843 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SUMMER-SCHOOL-2TAKES(     07-04 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-SCHOOL-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE STUDENTS THAN EVER ARE ENROLLED IN SUMMER SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., La., Fla., Mo., Texas, Mass., Ohio, Minn.,
Ga., Mich.)   By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More students than ever before are enrolled in summer school
this season, as districts throughout the country, led by those in
major cities, require or strongly urge younger and younger students
to attend classes to shore up basic reading and mathematical
skills.
</P>
<P>
   About one in five of the nation's 53 largest urban districts
said their students will be facing homework and tests this month,
with some places, notably Chicago, Miami and St. Louis, keeping
more than 40 percent of pupils in class during what once was
vacation. Other areas have multiplied attendance markedly in recent
years as they add programs in both remediation and enrichment:
Cleveland's enrollment jumped to 18,000 students this year, from
just 1,000 in the summer of 1998; New Orleans has gone to 11,000
today from about 500 in 1995; Boston expects about 12,000, up from
2,800 five years ago. New York is expecting 260,000 students,
nearly a quarter of its enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   Several districts begin classes Wednesday. Most last about five
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The push for summer school is a byproduct of the national
movement to raise academic performance, increase standardized
testing and end automatic promotion based on age rather than
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   But as educators try to bridge the yawning achievement gaps
between poor minority students and white middle-class ones, some
are worried that the mushrooming summer programs _ many of which
are mandatory for failing students _ will simply repeat ineffective
instructional approaches and frustrate children with endless drills
for high-stakes exams. Others fear the safety net of summer school
will let teachers and administrators off the hook for problems
during the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If kids need additional time, they need additional time, but
they also need, during the September to June period, good teachers
and good curriculum,'' said Amy T. Wilkins of the Education Trust,
a Washington organization focused on equity among students of
different races and income levels. ``A little summer school thrown
on top is not going to make up for the deficiencies in either of
those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a sort of dreaded lockup for teen-agers who failed
chemistry or skipped too many gym classes, summer school has become
a mix of test-preparation seminars and day-camp substitutes,
serving students as early as kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Research has documented a ``summer slide'' in which children _
particularly those from low-income backgrounds _ forget study
skills, discipline habits and vocabulary words between Memorial Day
and Labor Day. Educators are eager for the extra class hours, while
many parents who work full-time are often thrilled to have
somewhere to send their children.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of summer school also reflects increasing concerns
that America's school calendar _ which falls short of the more than
200 days required by Japan, Korea, Germany and Israel, never mind
China's 250 _ is insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``This notion of a 180-day school year is really obsolete,''
said Judith Johnson, deputy assistant secretary of the Department
of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stop thinking about summer school as an activity
separate from the regular school year,'' Johnson said. ``All
children do not learn in the same way, nor do all of them learn
along the same developmental timelines.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no current figures estimating the number of students
enrolled in summer school, but most agree it has risen
substantially from the 9 percent of America's schoolchildren who
attended in 1996. An informal telephone survey by The New York
Times found some 1.3 million students, or 19 percent, are scheduled
for classes this summer in the 53 largest districts, which have a
total enrollment of 6.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Though the phenomenon is growing in suburbs as well as cities,
it is most prevalent in low-income areas; in 1998, 27 percent of
all school districts, but 52 percent of those with large numbers of
poor pupils, offered summer school.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many of our kids, they're city kids, and sometimes their
opportunities are not so many,'' said Patrick Bryan, a summer
school principal at Dayton Bluffs Elementary School in St. Paul,
Minn. ``It would be a long, dry summer if they did not have summer
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Chicago in 1996 and New York last summer, more and more
states and school districts require students to attend summer
classes or risk being left back. Fourteen states recently enacted
legislation expanding summer school requirements, and 24 of the 53
districts in the Times survey have mandatory attendance for some
students.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, third-graders who do not meet standards must stay
through the summer in order to move on. Washington, D.C., requires
students in all grades with low standardized test scores to
participate in its 3-year-old ``Summer Stars'' program _ and to
pass the test at season's end to be promoted. Administrators in
Boston, Detroit, Houston, Los Angeles and New Orleans all ordered
struggling students in specific, benchmark grades to report for
summer classes, though they cannot make them show up. (Detroit
expected 36,000 in its ``mandatory'' program and ended up with
25,000.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be motivated to be here,'' said Linda Miller, who
teaches an intensive reading and math class at Douglas High School
in Parkland, Fla., part of the Broward County school district,
which requires summer school for those who fail the state
Comprehensive Assessment Tests. ``Those who stay, stay because they
want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Janicia Jackson, 15, a student at the school, said she benefits
from studying the same subject for four straight hours each day.
``I understand things a lot better the second time around,'' she
said. ``All this information is floating around the back of my
head, but being in summer school brings it out.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Anchorage, 7-year-old Adrian Ramos, who speaks Spanish at
home and is enrolled in a Japanese immersion program, is spending
summer school working on his English.
</P>
<P>
   ``He heard me on the phone trying to enroll him, and he said he
didn't want to go,'' said Adrian's mother, Yadira Ramos. ``But
yesterday, as soon as he got out, he told me he really likes being
in summer school.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey of the nation's 100 largest school districts by
Geoffrey D. Borman, a researcher at Johns Hopkins University, found
that 59 percent offer summer school as an alternative to social
promotion, and 55 percent are using the extra weeks to help
students meet more challenging state and local standards. Only 16
percent said the aim was enrichment, and just 1 percent of programs
were designed to addressed summer learning losses.
</P>
<P>
   But even as they design summer classes focused on math and
language literacy, with an eye toward the tests students failed
before arriving, many districts are searching for innovative
curriculums to keep students engaged and motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis offers a menu of 73 courses, including ``Real and
Alternate Histories of World War II.'' In Fort Worth, Texas,
multi-age classrooms of elementary students tackle topics including
``Bubbleology'' and ``Tool Time for Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   At Houston's Macario Garcia Elementary School, children learn
about the digestive system and body temperature by working at a
mock hospital. ``Science can be dry and boring,'' said Adriana
Castro, the principal. ``All these lessons are designed to be
hands-on.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago in Newark, N.J., summer school was basically a
rehash of the previous year's lessons. ``If they didn't get it the
first time, we were trying to teach them the same way the second
time around, and it didn't work,'' said Jerry Bruno, a district
administrator. Now, reading, math and science are filtered through
thematic units: first- and second-graders will study sunlight and
shadows, while third- through fifth-graders examine rain forests
and weather, and middle school students do robotics. ``It's all new
material that the kids are exposed to during the summer,'' Bruno
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As districts have expanded their summer programs, they have
tripped over a host of problems, from students sweltering in
schools without air conditioning to a lack of money for
transportation or a dearth of teachers. Last year, thousands of New
Yorkers were wrongly forced to enroll because of test scores that
turned out to have been improperly reported.
</P>
<P>
   Effectiveness is also unclear: In Chicago last year, nearly half
of those forced to attend summer school still failed to meet the
district's promotion requirements afterward. Seattle abandoned its
``academic boot camp'' for 500 fifth-graders after the summer of
1998 because only a few improved enough to go on to sixth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Cooper, author of ``Making the Most of Summer
School''(Blackwell Publishing, May 2000), said small classes, good
teachers, parental involvement and rigorous evaluation were crucial
to success. Middle-class students tend to benefit more from summer
school than low-income children, according to Cooper's study, but
overall, 85 percent of the students who attended outperformed their
peers who did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are learning all year long,'' said Cooper, chairman of
the psychology department at the University of Missouri at
Columbia. ``They're learning every day. The question is, really,
what is it that they're learning?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Karl L. Alexander, a Johns Hopkins sociologist who has been
following a group of Baltimore schoolchildren since 1982, said
tests taken each spring and fall showed that low-income children
kept pace with their better-off peers during the year, but
stagnated during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In upper-income families, they more often go to the library
during the summer, they more often go on summer vacations, they
more often attend summer camps _ and there's more reading material
in the household, more of them have computers,'' Alexander said.
``The summer period is a chunk of time, and it's like a black box.
What you drop into it is really important.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Johnson, of the Department of Education, recently
ran a summer program in White Plains, N.Y., that wrapped a basic
skills curriculum around field trips and guest speakers, and even
included free tennis lessons. ``If I could have taken them to the
opera, I would have taken them to the opera,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns over ``summer slide'' and other worries about the
calendar have also nourished separate movements to extend the
school year beyond the United States' 180 days. Dozens of schools
and districts around the country are adding days to the calendar,
while others run classes year round, typically with three- or
four-week vacations sprinkled every few months.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ballinger, director of the National Association for
Year-Round Education, said nearly 3,000 schools in 43 states _
serving more than 2 million students _ use a year-round schedule
now, compared to just 411 schools serving 354,087 students in
1985-86.
</P>
<P>
   ``By reducing the vacation, obviously you reduce the chance of
forgetting to occur,'' he said. ``If students learn anything on a
given day, one has to make the assumption that more days would
allow more learning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
