<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2848 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-OZON-FILM-ART-$ADV09-     07-04 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZON-FILM-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE ENFANT TERRIBLE TRANSLATES ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Germany)   (For release Sunday, July 9)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By LESLIE CAMHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The French director Francois Ozon has made thrillers
about homicidal house guests and high school killers. In satire,
he's explored the lighter sides of cannibalism, sadomasochism and
incest. But his latest film tackles the horrors of la vie a deux.
``Water Drops on Burning Rocks'' is his screen adaptation of a play
written by the German auteur Rainer Werner Fassbinder at the age of
19 _ an utterly disillusioned teen-age vision of a couple's
intimate life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water Drops'' will begin its New York run on July 12.
(``Criminal Lovers,'' Ozon's previous film, opens July 21.) This
chamber piece for four players is set in Germany during the 1970s.
One evening, Leopold (Bernard Giraudeau), an insurance salesman and
aging Lothario, brings the 19-year-old Franz (Malik Zidi) back to
his apartment and seduces him. Six months later their relationship
has calcified: Leopold ceaselessly bickers and complains, while
sensitive, intellectual Franz is meekly loving. When Franz's
ex-fiancee (Ludivine Sagnier) and Leopold's former girlfriend (Anna
Thomson) show up at their apartment, the older man's frightful
egotism and sexual charisma spark a lot of black humor and a few
grim consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 19, Fassbinder had already formed his view of the world and
human relationships _ already, he didn't believe in love,'' Ozon
said over coffee one recent morning in SoHo. ``He never staged or
filmed that play, but the seeds of all his later works are in it.
Perhaps it was just too personal. When I presented `Water Drops' at
the Berlin International Film Festival in February, members of
Fassbinder's circle were in the audience; they told me that in his
youth he resembled Franz, but when he got older, he became
Leopold.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassbinder died in 1982 at the age of 36, leaving behind more
than 40 films that dissect and demystify every aspect of postwar
German society, from transsexual love and the aspirations of
anarchists to the workings of major corporations. At 32, Ozon's
career has made a quick start. Three years ago, his short film,
``See the Sea'' _ a taut psychological drama about a new mother
whose vacation house on a beautiful island is suddenly invaded by a
sullen hitchhiker _ earned its writer and director comparisons to
Chabrol and Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sitcom,'' a comedy and Ozon's first feature, a typical
bourgeois French household dissolves into a den of perversion when
a pet white rat unleashes the family members' pent-up libidos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criminal Lovers'' was loosely inspired by a murder that took
place in the French provinces. ``A few years ago, an adolescent boy
and girl killed a fellow student,'' Ozon said. ``They were great
admirers of Oliver Stone's film `Natural Born Killers.' And they
wanted to commit a senseless crime. I didn't want to present a
realist version of these events, to offer psychological or social
explanations, but rather to tie them to something deeper and more
symbolic, like a fairy tale.''
</P>
<P>
   That film's style gradually shifts from ``Bonnie and Clyde'' to
``Hansel and Gretel,'' as Alice (Natacha Regnier) and Luc (Jeremie
Renier) kill Said (Salim Kechiouche), an Arab classmate, then take
refuge in the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Alice, who incites her boyfriend to murder, takes her cues not
from Hollywood but from the poetry of that troubled French
teen-ager Arthur Rimbaud. ``In real life, the girl wrote very
beautiful poems,'' Ozon said. ``Excerpts from her diary were
published in the press. She wrote of her desire for this Arab boy,
and how she had to kill him because she wanted him so much. It
reminded me of Jean Genet. At the same time, it was frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozon remains fascinated by adolescence. ``It's virgin
territory,'' he said. ``A blank page. Anything can happen.'' He
grew up in Paris (where he still lives), the oldest child in a
family of bourgeois intellectuals, and describes his own youth as
``turbulent.'' ``I was in revolt against my parents,'' he said,
``at once very aggressive and introverted. My Catholic education
had given me a taste for sin.''
</P>
<P>
   His earliest films starred his siblings and were shot with his
father's Super-8 movie camera. By the time he graduated from Femis,
the prestigious, state-run French film school, he had made more
than 40 shorts on film and video.
</P>
<P>
   Ozon's boyish charm seems purely Parisian, but his outre and
somber preoccupations have made him something of an anomaly among
French directors of his generation. ``Intimate dramas inspired by
the Nouvelle Vague and set in Parisian apartments are not his
thing,'' said Olivier Delbosc, whose company, Fidelite Productions,
has produced or co-produced all of Ozon's features. ``And he loves
to work very fast,'' Delbosc added. ``He's like a bulldozer; we
just follow along with him.''
</P>
<P>
   A bulldozer with a light touch, however. ``Francois is very
playful, very joyful to work with,'' said Malik Zidi, who plays
Franz in ``Water Drops.'' ``He's both intellectual and childlike.
Fassbinder's text is very heavy. But on the set, Francois made it
seem fresh and almost buoyant.''
</P>
<P>
   Too young to have seen Fassbinder's films when they first
opened, Ozon discovered the German director's work retrospectively.
``Fassbinder spoke of Germany in a way that no other filmmaker has
spoken of his country, of its wounds and hurt,'' he said. ``And I'm
attracted to his way of working so quickly, his cinematic bulimia,
using a small band of the faithful, and with or without money. Of
course, there was a dark side to his method. Sometimes when he was
broke, he'd ask his actresses to work as prostitutes.''
</P>
<P>
   With its deadpan humor, single setting and claustrophobic focus
on a few characters, ``Water Drops'' recalls the style of such
Fassbinder classics as ``The Bitter Tears of Petra von Kant.'' At
the same time, Ozon's version is distinctively French, far more
tightly controlled and lighter than the original, closer to farce
than tragedy. He also moved the play's setting up to the 1970s.
``Fassbinder wrote it in the early '60s, but he was so far ahead of
his time,'' Ozon said. ``The men's homosexuality is not an issue.
They're a couple like any other.''
</P>
<P>
   That period is also linked to Ozon's childhood memories of
Germany. ``We went there almost every year to visit friends of my
father's,'' he said. ``The daily life fascinated me, the beer and
sandwiches, the cleanliness and the colors, which were so sad. The
country was still in the midst of postwar reconstruction. People
worked a lot. They were still caught in the guilt of what had
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ozon, the ravages of German history lie behind Fassbinder's
ruthless portraits of sexual opportunism and failed intimacy.
``Fassbinder often repeated that there was no such thing as a
marginal existence,'' he said. ``In `Fox and His Friends,' for
example, he showed a homosexual milieu in 1970's Germany as a
culture entirely apart, yet reproducing the same traps as classic
heterosexual society. It's fascinating, and also deeply disturbing.
Because when you're on the margins, you can imagine for yourself a
certain liberty. But he showed that it wasn't so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
