<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2852 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PODESWA-FILM-ART-$ADV     07-04 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PODESWA-FILM-ART-$ADV09-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENSING WHAT BRINGS US TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)   (For release Sunday, July 2)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By LAURA WINTERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the fall of 1994, the Canadian director Jeremy
Podeswa and his producer Camelia Frieberg were heading down the
West Coast to promote Podeswa's first film, ``Eclipse.'' They
stopped to see a woman whom Frieberg had met when she was a
teen-ager on vacation; they had agreed, as a lark, to meet again in
20 years' time.
</P>
<P>
   During the visit, they met the landscaper Larry Burkam, who was
working on the woman's property, and they all ended up having
dinner. ``And you could just see the lightning bolts over the
table,'' Podeswa recalled recently. ``When we got back to the hotel
that night, I looked at Camelia and said, `You know, I have the
funniest feeling that you're going to marry that guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Frieberg did marry Burkam, and this random encounter _ like
something out of an Eric Rohmer film _ became one of the
inspirations for Podeswa's second feature, ``The Five Senses,''
which opens on Friday and which traces the tangled relations among
a group of people in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I witnessed with Camelia got me going on the idea of
destiny and what brings people together,'' Podeswa said when he was
in New York recently. ``We tend to lead our lives in a very
intellectual way _ but, in fact, our lives are irrational and there
are things we can't explain. I wanted to make a film about people
who are coming to understand those kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Podeswa, who is warm and bitingly articulate,
has seen his own share of life's eccentricities. He struggled for
years in Canada to find financing for his feature films while he
worked as a journalist, a film publicist and an assistant film
editor. Though Podeswa is relatively unknown in this country, his
profile in Canada and abroad has changed dramatically with ``The
Five Senses'': the film was a hit at both the Cannes and Toronto
International Film Festivals, was sold in more than 40 countries
and earned Podeswa the Genie Award (Canada's version of the Academy
Award) for best director last January.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Ackerman's 1990 book, ``A Natural History of the Senses,''
was the direct impetus for the film. ``I loved Ackerman's
enthusiasm for how the senses enhance our lives,'' Podeswa said.
``We tend to take our senses for granted, just as we can take other
people for granted. So I began to write about these characters who
are surrounded by a wealth of possibilities, and yet they all feel
that there is something missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of Podeswa's five main characters in ``The Five Senses'' is
linked thematically to a particular sense. For hearing, there's an
eye doctor (Philippe Volter) who is going deaf; for taste, there's
a cake-maker (Mary-Louise Parker) whose gorgeous but bland cakes
only hint at her deeper emotional blockage. Smell is represented by
a bisexual housecleaner (Daniel MacIvor) who is convinced that love
has its own distinct scent. Touch is symbolized by a massage
therapist (Gabrielle Rose), who can soothe strangers but who is
unable to reach her teen-age daughter (Nadia Litz), a budding
voyeur who, in turn, represents sight.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of a little girl draws together these
interlocking stories. Her mother's (Molly Parker) desperate search
for the child galvanizes the other characters and throws into
relief their prickly, fervent attempts to connect with other
people.
</P>
<P>
   But the film also has a light touch in scenes such as the one
where MacIvor's and Mary-Louis Parker's characters avidly gossip in
a car. Their mutual list of romantic no-no's includes ``never fall
in love with someone who's too good looking'' and ``never fall in
love with someone who lives more than a bus ride away.''
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa has always been interested in the quest for intimacy,
whether it be through romance, friendship or family. Though his
films are not directly autobiographical, he calls each one ``a
snapshot of my psyche at a particular time.''
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the generation of Canadian filmmakers that includes
Atom Egoyan, Patricia Rozema and Don McKellar, among others.
``Jeremy was an inspiration to me in the 1980s because of a
supremely assured short film he did called `David Roche Talks to
You about Love,''' said Egoyan, on the telephone from Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``But Jeremy had a long apprenticeship. He went to
the American Film Institute, which I think gave him a different
outlook. As Canadians, we're very aware of making our films in
contrast to a dominant American cinema.'' He laughed. ``Jeremy was
one of the few who spent time in the belly of the beast, so to
speak, and then came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa spent a year in Los Angeles after graduating in 1984
from Ryerson Polytechnical Institute in Toronto. ``It really
demystified the studio system for me,'' he said. ``But I also
discovered that there were films I wanted to make that I didn't
think could be made in that system. Canadian filmmakers tend to use
film as a form of personal expression, to say something that is
personal and idiosyncratic.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Podeswa's strongest signature as a director is his
insistence on pluralism, whether it be the range of languages
spoken by his characters or the variety of sexual relationships he
depicts. ``Eclipse,'' Podeswa's first feature (1995), was inspired
by Arthur Schnitzler's play ``La Ronde'' and featured a gallery of
lonely, questing characters who go from partner to partner. ``The
Five Senses'' also portrays both gay and heterosexual relationships
without judgment or stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for me to deal with sexuality in a
non-hierarchical way,'' Podeswa said. ``I always resented, when I
was younger, seeing films where the only gay character would be the
best friend, or the kooky neighbor. I wanted to move those stories
into the center and give them equal weight with the other
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa's producer, Frieberg, describes him as ``interested in
the diversity of experience, be it sexual or ethnic.'' But his goal
is not polemics, but, rather, universality _ to show how love and
longing cut a swath through everyone's life.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have shaped Podeswa's outlook _ ``being gay,
being Jewish and a first-generation Canadian,'' he said. ``My
parents are both immigrants and my father is a Holocaust survivor.
This background makes you very aware of what it feels like to be an
outsider. But I think it's also made me sensitive to other people's
issues as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa's father, who is from Poland, survived concentration
camps and emigrated to Toronto after the war, where he met
Podeswa's mother, who had come there from England. Both Podeswa's
father and his brother are painters, and he himself grew up, he
says, addicted to movies.
</P>
<P>
   After attending the American Film Institute, he moved back to
Toronto determined to start making films. But a musical feature
that he was planning fell through, and it took him considerable
time to finance ``Eclipse,'' and then, in turn, ``The Five
Senses.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why it took so long, Podeswa said, `` `Eclipse' was a
multi-character tale with an unconventional story. `The Five
Senses' was even more ambitious. But feature film funding has also
really dried up in Canada. The government film funding agencies
have quite limited resources now, so they can't really support that
many movies a year.''
</P>
<P>
   What got Podeswa through was what he calls his ``monomaniacal''
nature: ``I'm like a dog with a bone,'' he said. ``I wouldn't let
go.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
