s e BC-PODESWA-FILM-ART-$ADV     07-04 0256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PODESWA-FILM-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: let go.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He now has a first-look deal with Alliance Atlantis, an
independent distribution and production company and one of the
principal backers of ``The Five Senses,'' and he is set to adapt
and direct Anne Michaels' acclaimed novel, ``Fugitive Pieces,''
about the legacy of the Holocaust, for the Toronto-based
Serendipity Point Films. He is also adapting Catherine Bush's first
novel, ``Minus Time,'' about the relationship between a young girl
and her astronaut mother, for the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is not out of the question, either, though his
approach would no doubt be novel there. ``I remember at one point
during the shoot, we disagreed about something and he stopped and
said, `Let's talk about this,''' Parker recalled. ``There wasn't
that feeling which happens so often of ``just get the shot and move
on.'''
</P>
<P>
   Emotional truth is Podeswa's priority. For him, ``The Five
Senses'' is his most affirmative film. ``I had done a film about
people who were unfulfilled and afraid,'' he said, ``and I wanted
to show people who were at the next stage, trying to engage with
life.'' At the same time, he deplores what he calls ``the tyranny
of happy endings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood-style endings can sometimes make an audience feel
really bitter,'' he said with a laugh, ``because they start to
think, `Why can't my life be more like that?' I'd like, instead,
for people to see themselves in my work. It's about the reality _
rather than the fantasy _ of how we live now.''
</P>
<P>
