<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2871 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-0705-     07-04 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-0705-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN PRESIDENT-ELECT PLANS BIG REFORMS TO END CORRUPTION
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In a dramatic attempt to move Mexico from 71 years
of one-party rule and end corruption, president-elect Vicente Fox
said Tuesday he plans to create an independent department to
command federal police and transfer the power for auditing federal
spending to Mexico's Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Mexican police are under the Department of Internal
Affairs, which handles the executive's relations with state
governors and political parties. Under one-party rule, it has long
been accused of mixing political ambitions with police power _ and
engaging in repressive activities and spying against perceived
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This separation is crucial to eliminating corruption and
pressure on citizens and espionage, which we have denounced
before,'' Fox said in a wide-ranging press conference with foreign
correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of corruption, yes, we are going to end it in six
years,'' he said, referring to his presidential term. ``The
proposals are profound.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said his other top commitment is reducing poverty _ half of
Mexico's population is poor _ by increasing investment and opening
up lines of credit closed off to most Mexicans. He plans to start
traveling soon to the United States and other countries, with a
goal of boosting foreign investment here to $20 billion from about
$12 or $13 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   The president-elect said he also wants to pursue long-term
negotiations to open up the United States to legal Mexican guest
workers so that migrants don't have to work as undocumented aliens.
But he said his country also needs to urgently create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico's goal has been to open the escape valve, avoid its own
responsibility to create jobs here, allow 350,000 young people to
cross the border each year, and wash its hands of responsibility,''
Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was elected on Sunday and on Dec. 1 he will assume the
presidency, ending the seven-decade presidential reign of Mexico's
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive and agricultural businessman,
belongs to Mexico's conservative National Action Party, or PAN. But
he has pledged to build a plural ``transitional'' government to
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   He is using five international and national ``head-hunting''
firms to help him narrow his search for candidates for his cabinet
_ a new phenomenon in a country where cronyism is often the rule.
</P>
<P>
   He has promised political plurality in his cabinet, as well as
gender equality and geographic diversity so that people from all
parts of Mexico are represented.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he experienced ``an explosion of happiness'' in the
wake of his election. To assure a smooth transition where files
won't be destroyed or offices stripped, Fox said, ``I have to trust
in the open doors offered by President (Ernesto) Zedillo,'' who met
with Fox on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Among other reforms, Fox also wants to transfer police to a new
Department of Security and Justice and narrow the powers of the
Attorney General's office so it will focus primarily on
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   These reforms, Fox said, ``will assign specific responsibilities
to each one of these institutions, instead of having this
corruption or linkage between activities that do not correspond (or
make for) a real transparency in accountable government.''
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's office has special police whose job it is
to investigate narcotics trafficking. Drug-related corruption
within that department, as well as all levels of Mexico's federal
and state police, are a major sore point between the United States
and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's office works closely, but not always
smoothly, with the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration and the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   When he travels to the United States soon to meet with President
Clinton, Fox said he also hopes to meet with Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore and Republican candidate George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he recommends the United States scrap its annual
certification of countries it considers partners in the fight
against drugs and instead opt for a system of mutual scrutiny among
nations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his call for a freer flow of guest workers from
Mexico to the United States and Canada, he also raised the
possibility of creating a special development fund, backed by
foreign governments, to spur growth in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least, we could sit down and say our goal is to
close the income gap'' among the North American countries, Fox
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's domestic proposals, including his idea to give Congress
the power to audit federal spending, ``are all reforms that reduce
the power of the presidency,'' said Joel Estudillo of the Mexican
Institute of Political Studies. ``This is a great advance. An
alternation in power will give Mexico the opportunity to really
reform government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The great political capital that Fox has,'' Estudillo added,
``is his charisma and leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox will probably have a Congress and Senate willing to approve
these ideas, Estudillo said, because all parties _ including the
PRI _ now have a greater interest in creating checks and balances.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Fox's PAN party tried to enact legislation to give
Congress the power to audit federal spending but the PRI blocked
the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has invited all lower-level federal employees to remain in
their posts when he takes office. But he plans on promoting
professionalism to root out corruption and make government more
responsive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ambitious program that takes time. But it is the
only way, at the end, you will have changed the culture,'' he said.
``The president has to (provide) the very first example of ethics,
ethical values and morality and behavior. Unfortunately, in this
country we haven't had that. The example has been the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss can be reached by e-mail at:
susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2872 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ROSLER-ART-$ADV09-NYT     07-04 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSLER-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PURE ARTIST IS EMBRACED BY THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 9)  
 By MICHAEL RUSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I knew I was going to be either an artist or a
criminal,'' says Martha Rosler, the multimedia artist, critic,
theorist, teacher and art-world provocateur. In a career spanning
35 years, Rosler, whose disdain for the normal rites of passage
from galleries to collectors to museums struck many as criminal,
has clung tenaciously to a very personal art that refuses to
separate aesthetics from politics.
</P>
<P>
   Declining to be represented by a gallery until 1993, Rosler
relented when Simon Watson, who then owned a gallery in SoHo,
approached her with an offer to preserve her work for history. ``He
made sense,'' she says, holding fast to a glass of cold water at
the Housing Works Used Books Cafe not far from Watson's old
gallery. ``So much of my work involved the Vietnam War that it
would have been obscene to show it in a gallery. But now, it's
different; it's important to remember and to enable the young to
discover what to some of us is still so present.''
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkable affirmation from a museum world that she so
often criticized, Rosler is now receiving a major retrospective
organized by Elizabeth Ann Macgregor of the Ikon Gallery in
Birmingham, England, and Sabine Breitwieser of the Generali
Foundation in Vienna. After stops in England, France, Austria and
Spain, ``Martha Rosler: Positions in the Life World'' makes its
only United States appearance in a joint presentation by the New
Museum of Contemporary Art in SoHo from Saturday through Oct. 8 and
the International Center of Photography on Fifth Avenue from July
29 through Oct. 1. ``Martha Rosler is one of the most important
artists of the last 25 years,'' says Brian Wallis, chief curator at
ICP, which will be focusing on Rosler's photography.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Phillips, director of the New Museum, where a broad survey
of Rosler's large installations, photos, videos and sculptures can
be seen, adds, ``She is a pioneering artist whose influence is
widely recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   While this burst of affection from institutions may seem at odds
with her reputed iconoclasm, Rosler has actually been represented
in about 10 nonprofit group and solo shows in Europe and America
since the early 70's. ``I was never against museum audiences,'' she
says. ``Only the nexus of cash that saw art principally as a
commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming of age in the late '50s and '60s (she graduated from
Brooklyn College in 1965), she was immersed in a culture of
protests from her early teens. ``I was a beatnik in high school,''
she says, ``always going to hear Allen Ginsberg and Thelonius Monk.
I also went to a lot of theater from Broadway to the Living
Theater, where I was exposed to Brecht, Pirandello and Beckett.
They showed me how you could dispense with excessive amusement in
favor of language and gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosler's mother was a New York City school teacher and her
father had ``a one-man law office.'' She credits her yeshiva
education (which she hated at the time) with her strong sensitivity
to the ``public and the political.'' If her broad range of work can
be characterized briefly, it involves bringing a critical eye to
public struggles, in unexpected ways.
</P>
<P>
   In one of her most celebrated works, ``The Bowery in Two
Inadequate Descriptive Systems'' from 1974, Rosler challenges the
sentimentalism of postwar photography as represented by Robert
Capa. Instead of photographing the familiar ``Bowery bums,'' the
alcoholics and drug addicts who could be found lying in doorways
and on streets in lower Manhattan, Rosler took shots of shop
windows and disintegrating storefronts, void of people but
representing the life that is lived there by the neighborhood's
many diverse inhabitants. She placed the photos in a grid along
with texts containing synonyms for inebriation (loopy, groggy,
potted, pickled, etc.). The combination of photos and texts, placed
in a minimalist grid, forced a critique of assumptions about the
Bowery without offering any concrete alternatives. ``I wanted to
strip away any ornament,'' she says, ``and return power to the
viewer,'' something she felt had been contaminated by the overt
humanism of Capa and Walker Evans.
</P>
<P>
   This spareness of approach, often joined with a biting sense of
humor, was inspired partly by the films of Jean-Luc Godard, the
Swiss experimentalist who came to prominence in the early '60s.
Rosler met Godard a few times during her graduate studies at the
University of California in San Diego, where she also met the
filmmaker Roberto Rossellini and influential intellectuals like
Herbert Marcuse, Jean-Francois Lyotard and Fredric Jameson. In
Godard, the young Rosler found a model artist who resisted the
commercialization of ideas even as he dazzled with his command of
striking images, sounds and texts.
</P>
<P>
   Rosler spent a dozen years in southern California from the late
'60s to the early '80s, a time she says was immensely important to
her. ``I lost my New York provinciality,'' she says, ``and was let
loose from the strictures of being a middle-class Brooklyn Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   During this time she married, had a son, Joshua (now a
32-year-old comics artist and writer), and divorced after seven
years. After graduate school she taught art and began her lifelong
avocation of gardening. ``But I started dreaming of sidewalks,''
she says, ``so I knew it was time to go back East.'' She was
offered a job at Rutgers, where she is a professor of art.
</P>
<P>
   It was during her time in California that Rosler created some of
her most enduring work in performance, video and photography.
``Bringing the War Home,'' 1967-1972, is a series of 20
photomontages that places images of Vietnam War victims (girls with
missing limbs, mothers holding their dead children, wounded
soldiers) in the midst of tranquil suburban American interiors cut
from the pages of Life magazine. As the art historian Alexander
Alberro says of this series, ``She was, in effect, making concrete
`the war abroad, the war at home,' produced by the mass media,
which imported images of death from Vietnam into U.S. homes every
evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Domesticity also played a role in ``Semiotics of the Kitchen,''
a 1975 video, in which a deadpan Rosler, dressed in an apron, sends
up culinary shows and the woman's place in the kitchen, performing
mannered gestures with a variety of cooking utensils. Like so much
of her early work, ``Semiotics'' is striking both for its innocence
as well as its sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   Rosler's photographs and videos were fully formed from the
start, it seems, displaying a strong grasp of technique peppered
with youthful exuberance. In her 1977 performance and, later, video
``Vital Statistics of a Citizen, Simply Obtained,'' the artist
submits to having every inch of her nude body measured and recorded
by two white-coated men as a ``chorus'' of women stand to the side
watching silently. ``This is a work about how to think about
yourself,'' Rosler says in a voice-over on the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Rosler has taken her cameras (moving and still)
to airports (producing stunning shots of architectural details in
empty terminals) and housing projects (a video study of Corbusier's
last development in Firminy, France), while maintaining her
commitment to the plight of the homeless (``Housing Is a Human
Right,'' a billboard display in Times Square) and politically
oppressed (``Chile on the Road to Nafta,'' a video made in Chile 25
years after the coup that deposed Salvador Allende).
</P>
<P>
   ``My art is a communicative act,'' Rosler says, ``a form of an
utterance, a way to open a conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Completing a conversation with her, during which topics have
flown from Aristotle to Marx, Nicaragua to Kosovo, is like coming
to the end of a roller coaster ride. You're relieved, but you want
to go at it again. Her enduring vision linking art and public
purpose can be exhausting as well as exhilarating. As the New
Museum's chief curator, Dan Cameron, says of Rosler: ``She's the
purest artist there is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
