<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-2TAK     07-04 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS SAW TWO SIDES OF GORE IN FUND-RAISING INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his April interview with federal investigators,
two very different Al Gores seemed to be present, according to law
enforcement officials. One was a confident master of detail, the
other a defensive witness who could not recall basic facts about
his fund-raising activities in the months before the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset, Gore remembered with precision how long he had
served as vice president and as a senator from Tennessee. ``I've
been vice president for seven years and two months and 28 days,''
Gore said. ``Before that, I was a member of the United States
Senate for eight years and 18 days.''
</P>
<P>
   But later in the April 18 interview, Gore said he did not know
whether the now-infamous luncheon that he attended at a Buddhist
temple in California was a fund-raising event. He disputed the
suggestion that White House coffees were used as fund-raising tools
by the Democratic Party _ although millions of dollars flowed from
the people who attended them. And the vice president said he
thought he had attended only one White House coffee when documents
showed that he had attended 23.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that Gore was so meticulous in
his recall of some matters (at one point describing himself as a
``stickler to a fault'' who sometimes corrected the grammar of his
campaign letters) that they doubted his vague responses to
questions about his campaign finance activities.
</P>
<P>
   That contradiction fueled investigators' skepticism about Gore's
truthfulness. Robert J. Conrad Jr., the head of the Justice
Department's campaign task force, recommended that Attorney General
Janet Reno appoint a special counsel to investigate the vice
president's veracity during the four-hour interview.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad is focusing on three principal areas of inquiry, law
enforcement officials said. None of the issues are new: the vice
president's appearance at a luncheon at the Buddhist temple, his
attendance at White House coffees and his fund-raising telephone
calls from the Executive Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   On June 23, after he ordered his lawyers to release copies of
the 123-page transcript of his interview, Gore told reporters, ``I
think the truth is my friend in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for the vice president's office, said,
``This isn't news. This is archaeology and it has no relevance to
the kind of issues that the vice president is working on and the
American people care about.''
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a status report on the significant matters in
the Gore inquiry:
</P>
<P>
   Hsi Lai Temple Luncheon
</P>
<P>
   Issue: On April 29, 1996, Gore attended a luncheon organized by
John Huang and Maria Hsia, both of whom were Democratic
fund-raisers, at the Hsi Lai Temple, a Buddhist monastery near Los
Angeles in Hacienda Heights, Calif. The luncheon with about 100
community leaders was one of the first campaign finance
controversies to embroil the vice president, who was invited to the
temple by one of the leaders of the Taiwan-based group.
</P>
<P>
   The event raised the issue of whether the temple had held a
political fund-raiser in violation of its tax-exempt status as a
religious institution and whether temple monastics were illegally
reimbursed for contributions. There was also the question of
whether Gore knew it was a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Gore said in an October 1996 interview with National
Public Radio that the luncheon was a ``community outreach'' event.
But in January 1997, a spokesman for the vice president said that
Gore ``knew it was a finance-related event.''
</P>
<P>
   The Investigation: Investigators found that Gore routinely
attended fund-raisers and community outreach events organized by
the Democratic National Committee. Some documents suggested
confusion among Gore's staff because the vice president initially
planned on attending two events in a single day in Los Angeles, one
a fund-raising luncheon and the other a visit to the temple. The
two stops were melded into one because of time constraints.
</P>
<P>
   Reno decided against appointing an independent counsel to review
any of Gore's fund raising, although he was not questioned about
the temple event until last April. Justice Department prosecutors
brought criminal charges against the two fund-raisers involved in
the temple luncheon. Huang pleaded guilty for his role in
soliciting about $159,000 in contributions from people who attended
the event and from temple monastics. In an appearance before a
House committee, Huang testified that he had no evidence
implicating Gore in any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Hsia, the other fund-raiser, was convicted in March of campaign
finance violations, including helping to arrange for donations to
be made in the names of monks and nuns who were later reimbursed by
the temple.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's comments: In one of the most caustic
exchanges of his April interview with federal prosecutors, Gore
angrily denied that he had been told by aides that the Buddhist
temple event was a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure as hell don't recall having _ I sure as hell did not
have any conversations with anyone saying this is a fund-raising
event,'' Gore testified.
</P>
<P>
   Unresolved Questions: Conrad is said to be dissatisfied with
some of Gore's answers. Several documents indicate that Gore's
staff knew that the purpose of the temple luncheon was to raise
campaign contributions. Because of the discrepancy between Gore's
responses and some of the documents, Conrad has recommended that a
special counsel be appointed to investigate the matter further.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The White House Coffees
</P>
<P>
   Issue: Gore's attendance at White House coffees, which were used
by the White House in 1995 and 1996 to help the Democratic Party
raise millions of dollars in campaign contributions. From November
1995 to August 1996, the White House organized 103 coffees. Guests
contributed a total of $26.4 million, and $7.7 million was
contributed by guests within one month of attending a coffee,
usually held in the White House Map Room.
</P>
<P>
   Investigation: Charles G. LaBella, a former head of the Justice
Department task force, investigated the White House coffees, and
concluded that they required no further inquiry. And late in 1997,
Reno also decided that the coffees merited no further action.
</P>
<P>
   However, Conrad, who was appointed by Reno in late December,
decided to ask Gore questions about the coffees. Gore disputed
Conrad's suggestion that White House coffees were used as
``fund-raising tools'' by the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad asked: ``In your opinion, there simply was no quid pro
quo of attendance at a coffee, payment to follow?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said, ``That is absolutely my impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Conrad asked if it was true that Gore had served as host of 23
White House coffees and sat in with President Clinton at eight
others. ``Would that be an accurate statement?'' Conrad asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore said he could not recall attending any coffees.
``This was on the president's side of things,'' he said. ``That's
my memory and impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said it ``was not my practice to go to any of these
coffees.'' He added, ``There may have been one that I attended
briefly, perhaps because some of the invitees were known to me and
wanted to say hello.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the interview, Gore's personal lawyer, James F.
Neal, acknowledged in a letter to Conrad that the vice president
misunderstood the question, and thought it dealt only with ``White
House coffees.'' Neal wrote that according to the vice president's
schedule, Gore had attended four White House coffees and he had
served as host of 21 coffees in the Old Executive Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   Unresolved Questions: The discrepancies between the documents
and Gore's hazy recollection of his role in the coffees have
prompted Conrad to recommend that Reno appoint a special counsel to
investigate the matter.
</P>
<P>
   White House Telephone Calls
</P>
<P>
   The Issue: From December 1995 to April 1996, Gore made 45
fund-raising telephone calls from his West Wing office in the White
House. The calls raised the issue of whether Gore had violated the
Pendleton Act, an 1883 civil service law that bars elected
officials from using federal property to raise campaign
contributions. The law was designed to prevent officeholders from
pressuring their subordinates into making political donations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his fund-raising calls from his White House office.
Clinton made similar calls from his White House quarters, which is
not considered official government property.
</P>
<P>
   Among those Gore telephoned was Robert Johnson, chairman of
Black Entertainment Television. In one document disclosed by a
House committee, a call sheet prepared by the Democratic Party,
Gore was told to ask Johnson ``to write $30K for the media
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   During an interview with FBI agents, Johnson said he took Gore's
call and then wrote a check to the Democratic Party for $30,000.
Later, a Democratic Party finance officer noted on a computerized
record of the vice president's fund raising: ``$30K in.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation: In 1997, Reno absolved Gore of any wrongdoing
in connection with the phone calls. She found that Gore's calls
were intended to raise money only for general party purposes, a
category known as ``soft money.'' She concluded that Gore did not
realize that part of the money was funneled into hard money
accounts that were used for Clinton-Gore re-election activities but
were restricted by federal election laws.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Reno's findings were challenged when investigators
obtained a Nov. 21, 1995, memo written by David M. Strauss, then
the vice president's deputy chief of staff. On the memo were
Strauss' handwritten notes that suggested that Gore might have
known that a portion of the money raised by his calls was allocated
to direct re-election activities.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews with prosecutors, four participants in
the meeting, including Leon Panetta, the former White House chief
of staff, recalled that Gore was present for a discussion of the
how the money was to be allocated. But seven or eight others told
investigators they could not recall a discussion about money raised
by phone calls going to the restricted hard money accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Comments: When interviewed by prosecutors on Nov. 11,
1998, Gore said that he was sometimes inattentive and missed parts
of the fund-raising meetings. According to FBI notes on the
interview, Gore said that he ``drank a lot of iced tea during
meetings, which could have necessitated a restroom break.''
</P>
<P>
   Unresolved Issues: In December 1998, Reno cleared Gore of
wrongdoing. In reaching her decision, she rebuffed recommendations
from six senior aides and relied instead on the advice of single
trusted adviser, Lee J. Radek, the chief of the Justice
Department's public corruption unit.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last several weeks, Conrad, urged on by the FBI,
concluded that Gore's truthfulness about the phone calls should
also be examined by an outside prosecutor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
