<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANTAGE WILLIAMS:IT'S VENUS VS. SERENA
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ It was the sixth game of the third set when
a nervous murmur slipped out of the spellbound witnesses. A
desperate Martina Hingis had lunged to send back a shot that
fluttered like a harmless butterfly above the net, and they could
see what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Rushing forward with a furious churn of arms and legs, the
intimidating Venus Williams materialized like a praying mantis to
devour Hingis' effort with a swinging forehand volley. On instinct,
Hingis guessed right at the angle, stabbed at the blur of yellow
only to flick a lob long. With a deep sigh, Hingis expressed her
hopeless state.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, beneath the ominous clouds suspended above Center
Court Tuesday, the powerful Williams made Hingis look as vulnerable
as a victim in a dunk tank. Hingis kept popping to the surface,
steeling herself for more, but she could only endure so much. In
the sixth game of the third set, Williams became the first of the
two to hold serve over an eight-game span. Once she grabbed the 4-2
lead, Williams never wavered on serve again.
</P>
<P>
   On match point, Williams reached back and uncoiled a 118 mph ace
to end a 6-3, 4-6, 6-4 classic quarterfinal at Wimbledon. As her
serve rocketed past Hingis, Williams squealed for joy. Suddenly,
the ominous 20-year-old morphed into a child as she skipped to the
net with her ponytail bouncing and her smiling eyes fixed on the
friends' box.
</P>
<P>
   There was her giddy father, Richard, and her next opponent, too.
Not even an hour into her sister's match, Serena Williams sneaked
into the stadium and sat down next to their father after having
razed Lisa Raymond, 6-2, 6-0, in 41 minutes. On Thursday, Venus and
Serena Williams will meet in the semifinals at Wimbledon, marking
the third time sisters have met in the tournament's history. ``I
see it as an opportunity, not an opportunity against Serena,'' said
Venus, who was an emotionally detached spectator when Serena became
the first of the two to win a Grand Slam at the U.S. Open last
summer. ``She's been blazing past opponents _ no mercy. I want to
go in with that same attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of edge was there for Lindsay Davenport Tuesday.
Persevering through a troublesome start, she outlasted a
surprisingly focused Monica Seles, 6-7 (4), 6-4, 6-0, and will play
Jelena Dokic in the other semifinal. Typical Davenport, she has
made her way through the draw in wallflower fashion. In all
likelihood, she'll continue to be part of the background when the
Williams sisters meet for the fifth time since they arrived on the
pro tour..
</P>
<P>
   First there was Venus, then Serena. At least one of the parents
who guided them to this amazing point won't be in attendance on
Thursday. The eccentric Richard Williams plans to attend a funeral
on Thursday. He doesn't know the deceased _ it's a friend of an
acquaintance he met at Wimbledon this week _ but he said it'll be
his escape from a match he sees as a toss-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was betting, I'd put 50 pounds on Venus and 50 pounds on
Serena; then I can't lose because one of them will be in the
final,'' Richard Williams said. ``I think they're excited to get
his far, but you have to understand human feelings. I don't think
they're excited about playing each other, but their family bond is
stronger than tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was anxiety between Venus and Serena Williams _ both of
whom dismiss the notion of a sibling rivalry _ they camouflaged it
Wednesday afternoon with giggles and jokes. Serena, 18, flashed her
half-moon grin when told of her father's match-day plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I would be heartbroken if my little Jackie had to play
my Star ... those are my two dogs,'' Serena said like a comic
delivering a punch line. ``Maybe it's too much pressure on him.
It's probably the same reason I wouldn't watch my dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   There was laughter as Serena finished her monologue. She is the
more extroverted of the sisters, but even the more serious Venus
couldn't resist adding to the light-hearted atmosphere by
describing the strategy her little sister used when they were
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena was a cheater,'' Venus Williams said. ``I just rolled
with it. It's tough to argue against Serena because she was so good
at arguing, so good at cheating. It was no use. I don't think this
time we'll be calling the lines. Hopefully, I won't get any hooks,
and she won't be paying any line judges.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The level of play in the Hingis-Williams match even surpassed
the tension-filled, three-set semifinal the two played at the U.S.
Open last summer. Hingis won that day, but that victory only set
her up to lose to Serena in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   During the sixth game of the second set, Hingis was at her
clairvoyant best. As Venus Williams lined up an overhead, Hingis
paged through her mental scouting report, crept to her right and
was in position. As Williams smashed the overhead, Hingis lunged
and blocked it back down the line for a winner. The shot helped
produced the break of serve she needed to go on and take the second
set.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Hingis can shake an opponent's confidence by breaking
their spirit. But Williams just kept coming, kept taking the ball
in the air on swinging volleys and kept pounding her backhand for
14 winners. To keep pace, Hingis went for every line, as well. Both
players took risks with drop shots, and continued to aggressively
plant ground strokes into the grass like drill bits.
</P>
<P>
   The two were in an attack-and-response mode that produced
endless deuce games and few holds of serve. Hingis won 6 of 16
break chances, while Williams converted 7 of 20. At one overlapping
point of the second set and third, the players went eight games
without holding serve. With Williams going for every first serve,
she gave Hingis chances by making 61 percent. Although Hingis was
cautiously spinning in her first serve at 81 percent, it sat up in
the cross hairs for Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to put a first serve in,'' Hingis said.
``It's going to be good enough usually, but not enough against
Venus today.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the sixth game of the third set, Venus Williams
stopped the trend and never looked back. In the end, Hingis
probably did the best she could do, and she still lost. A player
whose self-esteem was once impenetrable was left doused in
self-doubt. Over her last four Grand Slams, Hingis has lost to four
hard hitters: Serena Williams (U.S. Open), Lindsay Davenport
(Australian Open), Mary Pierce (French Open) and Venus Williams
Tuesday at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be enough just with my abilities I had at the
time,'' said Hingis. ``It has changed so much since the Williamses
started playing better. I guess as the No. 1, you're supposed to
win a Grand Slam. But now someone else probably deserves to be No.
1.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one Williams sister can win a Wimbledon title this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this things boils down to is Venus and Serena,'' Richard
Williams said. ``Everyone else has to step aside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
