<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-ALZHEIMER-550&AMP;ADD     07-04 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ALZHEIMER-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREATMENT OF SOME ALZHEIMER PATIENTS INVOLVES NEEDLESS PAIN, STUDY
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   People with advanced Alzheimer's disease who are hospitalized
for a broken hip or pneumonia are often subjected to needless,
painful medical procedures and not given enough pain medication,
doctors are reporting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even with aggressive treatment, these patients have a high
probability of dying within six months, making it more important to
keep them comfortable rather than trying to cure their infections
or injuries, according to Dr. R. Sean Morrison and Dr. Albert L.
Siu, of the Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York. Their
report is being published Wednesday in the Journal of the American
Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Their study involved 216 patients who were treated for broken
hips or pneumonia at Mount Sinai Hospital from September 1996 to
March 1998. Of the 216 patients, 98 suffered advanced dementia; the
rest did not have any form of dementia.
</P>
<P>
   On average, people live 10 years after a diagnosis of dementia.
The condition is considered advanced when patients have trouble
communicating and identifying relatives, and can no longer eat,
dress, bathe or get out of bed by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison and Siu found that compared with the patients who were
mentally intact, those who had severe dementia were far more likely
to die within six months of pneumonia or a hip fracture, even with
equal medical care. Only 12 to 13 percent of the patients without
dementia died within six months, compared with 53 to 55 percent of
those with advanced dementia. But the patients with dementia
underwent as many painful and invasive procedures as the other
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people with a terminal diagnosis,'' said Morrison,
an assistant professor of geriatrics and a specialist in palliative
care, which is treatment meant to control pain and other forms of
discomfort. ``But physicians and families focus on the acute
illness and ignore that this is occurring in the setting of a
terminal illness with an average survival of six months.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, he said, the best treatment may be to maximize
pain control and minimize repeated blood tests and the insertion of
intravenous lines and urinary catheters, which are painful and
frightening to demented patients. Some patients with severe
dementia may even be better off without surgery to repair a broken
hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the patient didn't walk and is not going to walk again, it
may be appropriate just to have analgesics and keep comfortable,''
Morrison said. ``We can provide them with good pain medication and
get them out of the hospital and back to the living environment at
home or in a nursing home where they feel safe and comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Morrison and Siu found that the patients with dementia did
not receive good pain control. They were given less than half as
much pain medication as the patients without dementia, even though
they probably needed at least as much. Morrison said the difference
may have occurred because patients with dementia cannot ask for
pain medicine, and doctors and nurses may not realize that they are
suffering. Such patients should be given ``standing orders'' for
pain medicine, he said, meaning that the drugs are given
automatically whether or not the patient requests them. Only 24
percent of the patients with dementia, however, had standing orders
in their charts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dr. Ladislav Volicer, an expert on dementia and the director of
geriatric research at the E.N. Rogers Memorial Veterans Hospital in
Bedford, Mass., said the best solution to the problems described by
Morrison may be to keep patients with dementia out of acute-care
hospitals and let them stay in their homes or nursing homes, even
with a broken hip or pneumonia. Hospitals are geared toward
providing aggressive treatment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Volicer said that at the Veterans Hospital dementia unit, which
provides long-term care, some patients had broken hips but did not
have surgery, and were kept comfortable with morphine. He also said
that most patients with pneumonia were not sent to the hospital,
and many did not receive antibiotics, which studies have shown do
not prolong life in people with advanced dementia.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen McConnell, a spokesman for the Alzheimer's
Association, said Morrison's recommendations for better palliative
care were consistent with those of the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that people get good care, but the definition
of that care may be different in the late stages of the disease,''
McConnell said. ``People with advanced dementia are near death.
Good palliative care is probably going to be much more important
than the standard medical treatments designed to fix people.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said he began the study after noticing that after a few
days in the hospital, patients with dementia would flinch and
shrink away from anyone who touched them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' he asked. ``Every human touch is associated with pain
or discomfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said that because patients with dementia cannot
understand what is being done to them, they may perceive even a
blood test as an assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't communicate and no one can communicate with you,''
he said. ``Somebody comes in and grabs your arm, this painful
needle goes into you and you know no reason for it. It's just to
make sure the numbers are right. For a terminal illness, that may
not be an appropriate goal of care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
