<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LESSON IN TIME TRIALS SPANISH TEAM
</HEADLINE>
  By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. NAZAIRE, France _ The ONCE team from Spain gave a classic
illustration Tuesday of how to ride a team time trial, winning by
45 seconds, finishing with all nine of its men together at the same
time and placing two of them atop the new standings in the Tour de
France.
</P>
<P>
   But ONCE also offered too obvious a picture of how to shield a
rider illegally from the wind. Because the team car blatantly rode
beside a rider, Marcos Serrano, offering him protection and a
forward draft when the Spaniard began to fall behind on a windy
uphill on a long bridge, all its riders were penalized 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise smoothly rotating riders at the head of its single
file, ONCE powered to victory over the 70-kilometer (43-mile) flat
course from Nantes to the shipbuilding center of St. Nazaire in
western France in 1 hour 25 minutes 35 seconds. Second was the U.S.
Postal Service team, 46 seconds behind before the penalty, with
Telekom from Germany third, 40 more seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   That meant that the new man in the overall leader's yellow
jersey is Laurent Jalabert, a Frenchman who long reigned as No. 1
among the world's top 800 professional racers, but who has never
finished higher than fourth in previous Tours because of his
weakness in the highest mountains. Jalabert will most likely
continue to wear the jersey at least until the first of those
mountains, the Hautacam climb in the Pyrenees, is reached on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Second overall is his teammate David Canada, a Spaniard, 12
seconds behind, with Lance Armstrong, an American and the defending
Tour champion, third, 24 seconds behind. Abraham Olano, a Spaniard
with ONCE, is fourth, 35 seconds behind, and Slava Yekimov, a
Russian with Postal Service, is fifth, 43 seconds behind. Five
other ONCE riders rank in the first 11 since the entire team
received the time of its fifth man across the line.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first team time trial in the Tour since 1995. The
race against the clock, in which teams set out five minutes apart,
was dropped because it penalizes strong riders with weak teams and
those teams that have lost riders because of crashes in the early,
nervous days. There were no such casualties this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cofidis team from France finished seventh among the 20
entries, costing David Millar, a Scot, the yellow jersey he won
when the Tour began its three-week journey last Saturday. Tuesday
morning, Millar was guarded about his chances to remain the leader,
especially since his team had worked hard the past two days to
chase breakaways and protect his jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rode the course a couple of months ago to check it out,''
Millar said. There's a lot of headwind because of the prevailing
wind off the nearby Atlantic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we've got winds like that all the way, it's going to be
fairly harsh.''
</P>
<P>
   It was. Millar is now in 24th place, 2:27 behind Jalabert, whom
he led by 6 seconds when the teams set out.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also cited the wind as a big factor when he said a few
days ago: ``It's point to point, so if there's headwind, it'll be
there all the way. If it was start to finish in the same place, at
least part of the way you'd have tailwind.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's Postal Service team finished with only six of its
nine starters together, a perilous situation since the time of the
fifth man across counts for himself and anybody ahead of him. Johan
Bruyneel, the team's directeur sportif, or coach, said Armstrong
had gone too hard as the team approached the 4-kilometer-long
(2.5-mile-long) St. Nazaire bridge over the Loire River estuary
with the gray Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Three riders were unable to keep pace and dropped far behind
with a dozen kilometers (7.5 miles) to go. A fourth, Tyler
Hamilton, an American, managed to hang on through great courage and
willpower.
</P>
<P>
   A bull throughout the stage, Armstrong remained bullish about at
least part of the outcome. ``All is not lost,'' he said. ``The Tour
de France won't be decided by the team time trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's important that I picked up some more time on the
climbers and on Ullrich,'' he added, referring to Jan Ullrich, the
Telekom leader and the winner of the 1997 Tour. He appears to be
the rival the American most fears. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
