<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2899 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-GOLD-NYT &LR;      07-04 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-GOLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE'S ECONOMIC WOES EXPECTED TO GET WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Just days after Zimbabwe's fledgling
opposition party splashed into Parliament, its jobless supporters
were still digging for dreams.
</P>
<P>
   There is talk of gold hidden beneath the red soil on a deserted
farm here. And one recent morning, desperate men and women were
clawing into the earth, hunting for the glimmers that might buy a
bag of rice or a pair of secondhand shoes.
</P>
<P>
   It is hopeless, backbreaking work, and the diggers pray that
their new representatives in Parliament will help ease
unemployment, which stands at nearly 50 percent, so they can find
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are thinking our lives will change now,'' said Francisca
Makumbe, 32, as she hauled a sack of the red earth to the river for
panning. ``There is no future in this.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the strong showing of the opposition in the
parliamentary election last week has heightened expectations among
the urban poor, economists predict that the coming months will only
bring more hardship to a country already staggering through its
worst economic crisis since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In a new study, the U.N. Development Program reported that the
number of people living in poverty in Zimbabwe surged from 40
percent to 75 percent in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Government spending on health and education has dipped so
sharply that schools routinely run short of textbooks, hospitals go
without medicines and the sick are increasingly turning to
traditional medicine and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Economists fear that the worst is yet to come. While neighboring
countries in southern Africa this year are expected to enjoy their
highest growth rates since 1996, Zimbabwe's economy is expected to
shrink, perhaps as much as 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, which won 57 seats in the 150-member Parliament,
lacks a majority and control over the government's fiscal policy,
which has been characterized by chronic budget overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers and business executives say economic recovery will
depend largely on foreign investment and financing from the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund. But in a ranking of the
economic prospects of African countries issued last month by the
World Economic Forum, Zimbabwe placed next to last, dimming most
hopes for private investment.
</P>
<P>
   With President Robert Mugabe vowing to reinstate price controls
and to seize white-owned farms without compensation, there is
little chance that Western donors will rush to fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   And so in an abandoned field of tall grass and white
butterflies, the prospectors here will likely cling to their dreams
and dig for gold while their children go to sleep hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of parliamentary debate, the coming of the opposition
is positive, but the power they have is limited,'' said James Jowa,
the research economist at the Zimbabwe National Chamber of
Commerce. ``Things are getting worse and worse. We need urgent
rescue.''
</P>
<P>
   But investors have already suspended most expansion plans. And
officials say the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund,
which cut off financing last year after the government
underreported the cost of its role in the war in Congo, want to see
signs of fiscal discipline before offering aid.
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks donors will be watching to see how Mugabe
realigns his Cabinet, manages his budget and handles land
redistribution. They will be looking for significant changes,
particularly in fiscal management, in which the government's track
record has been dismal.
</P>
<P>
   The government, which budgeted a one-third salary increase for
civil servants this year, has actually increased salaries by nearly
65 percent, according to an economic analysis conducted by Standard
Chartered Bank here. And the budget deficit, expected to total 3.8
percent of the gross domestic product, is now expected to soar to
12 percent by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credibility of the regime is dead,'' said one Western
official familiar with the negotiations between Western aid donors
and the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not going to be any money flowing unless Mugabe
changes his ways,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``The donors cannot go to their boards with a program
based on promises.''
</P>
<P>
   The unraveling economy has also been hurt by external factors
like the falling prices of tobacco and gold in recent years, two
droughts and a so-called structural adjustment program that was
applauded by the West but plunged many more people into poverty
than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Under such programs, international lending organizations demand
that countries living beyond their means reduce spending on public
projects and cut subsidies that often keep the cost of living down.
``We all underestimated the social impact of the program,'' said a
Western economist, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``And when
we recognized it, we didn't get our act together quickly enough to
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Mugabe's party, who still control the Cabinet and
Parliament, say they are keenly aware that they must address the
economic crisis. But the Cabinet is split between those who want to
move toward a socialist, managed economy and those who embrace the
market.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt of the sense of urgency. Inflation stands
at about 50 percent and is expected to soar. For many of the
diggers here, meat and shoes without holes have become unimaginable
luxuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
