<SLUG> BC-APBNEWS-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE SPECIALIZING IN CRIME NEWS PLANS CHAPTER 11 BANKRUPTCY
FILING 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   APB Online, Inc., which operates a criminal justice news Web
site that foundered last month prompting executives to lay off all
the staff and scramble to find additional investors for the
debt-laden enterprise, plans to file for bankruptcy under Chapter
11 of the federal bankruptcy code.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which the executives of APBnews.com said they would
announce as early as Wednesday, is designed to provide breathing
space for the cash-strapped Web venture, according to its chairman
and chief executive, Marshall Davidson. At the moment, APBnews.com
has recalled about two dozen staff members and is updating the site
_ this week, it featured a report from Sacramento about illegal
fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   But the enterprise still has $7 million in debts. Davidson and
Mark Sauter, the site's chief operating officer, said in a
telephone interview that the terms of Chapter 11 bankruptcy could
help them attract reticent investors by providing assurances that
new capital would not simply be funneled into debt repayment, but
would ensure the site's viability. A business filing for Chapter 11
protection staves off lawsuits from creditors seeking repayment and
provides the business time to reorganize finances, though the
reorganization must be accepted by a majority of creditors for the
business to recover.
</P>
<P>
   APBnews executives' current plea to potential investors,
including large media companies, is that they can provide the most
popular services of the site, like local crime statistics, while
spending far less for staff and news-gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cash-burn rate and projected revenues are under $10
million for the next 12 months,'' Davidson said in a telephone
interview. ``Under $10 million keeps us operating. A total of $15
million breaks us even.''
</P>
<P>
   The site's original, more expensive ambitions, he said, matched
the demands of private equity investors in the summer of 1998, when
APBnews.com mustered its first financing, selling a 40 percent
stake of the business for $3 million. A year later, he said, it was
turning away investors willing to buy in at a much higher premium.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Giving his version of his company's brief,
roller-coaster history in the private equity markets, Davidson said
``if the capital markets would support a more rapid'' _ and
expensive _ ``build-out and thus the value of your company is
greater earlier, then that's what you would do.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``If the cap markets want to support a lower-cost
build-out and accept a lower valuation, then you'll do that. The
capital markets really made that change in March and April.''
</P>
<P>
   Sal Muoio, the president of S. Muoio &AMP; Co. and an early investor
in APBnews.com _ to the tune of $100,000 _ said that the Chapter 11
strategy ``makes sense, for now. I think it's better than selling
the desks. They've got good people and they've built a terrific
news organization _ they obviously lost sight of what happens in
financial markets.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
