u f BC-WORKING-DOGS-NYT &LR;      07-04 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-DOGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SOME DOGS ARE PROFESSIONALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRED BROCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My two Rhodesian Ridgebacks were only vaguely attentive as I
tried to explain to them that some dogs actually work for a living.
Canines that can hold their heads high as they approach their
supper dishes. Animals whose vet bills could be a tax-deductible
expense for their owners.
</P>
<P>
   My dogs yawned as their attention drifted to a chattering
squirrel. They gave me their how-long-until-we-are-fed look and
wandered deeper into the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   I sighed and returned to my growing list of what working-class
dogs do for a living. I was helped by a new book, ``Dogs With Jobs:
Working Dogs Around the World,'' by Merrily Weisbord and Kim
Kachanoff (Pocket Books, $24.95). The possibilities are impressive.
There are dogs that work as actors and guards; there are dogs that
aid the blind, the deaf and the ill. There are dogs that work for
the police sniffing out drugs, bombs and missing bodies. Then there
are racing dogs, rescue dogs and show dogs. There are dogs that
herd cattle and sheep, and dogs that serve as companions for
patients in nursing homes and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most dogs do duty as family pets, and that role
should not be made light of. These stalwarts provide love and
security to tens of millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But I wanted to check out some working dogs _ dogs with real
jobs, that work each day in a particular place with a particular
goal. I was interested in canines that, if they had two legs
instead of four, would be entitled to the minimum wage. Dogs like
Smokey, who works as a fire department mascot and guard dog in
Paterson, N.J.; Pearl, who herds cattle in New Mexico; Royce, who
sniffs out illegal drugs for the sheriff's department in Essex
County, N.J.; and Moki, who works as a companion to residents of a
nursing home in California.
</P>
<P>
   BEATING THE FLAMES
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters at the Northside Firehouse on Temple Street in
Paterson, N.J., call Smokey, a friendly 9-year-old mixed breed who
looks mostly like a German shepherd, a ``Paterson street dog.'' But
it's a compliment to his street smarts, not a slur on his lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Smokey has lived and worked at the firehouse since he was a
puppy and two firefighters brought him there from an animal shelter
in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Coughlan, a Paterson firefighter who usually watches after
Smokey, says the dog doesn't go on as many fire calls as he did
when he was younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watch him a little more carefully now,'' he said. ``We
don't want him to get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't stopped Smokey from working: When he's not on a
fire call, he stays behind and guards the firehouse until the
firefighters return.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had his share of battle wounds _ stitches for cuts from
broken glass and stuff like that,'' Coughlan said.
</P>
<P>
   When Smokey goes to a fire, he often beats the firefighters
inside a burning building.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking for people and pets,'' Coughlan said. ``Many
times he's beaten me into a building and then come out choking
while I'm still getting my gear on. Later, he'll check to make sure
we're all safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlan sometimes takes Smokey to his house for a visit. ``But
after a few hours, he wants to get back to the firehouse,''
Coughlan said. ``It's his home.''
</P>
<P>
   ROUNDING UP CATTLE
</P>
<P>
   Wherever John Gard goes, Pearl is usually right by his side. Or,
more precisely, by the side of his cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl, a 10-year-old bluish-black-and-white Scottish border
collie, helps Gard, who is 80, run cattle on 9,000 acres near
Gladstone, in northeastern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Gard is working from the back of a horse or behind the
wheel of a truck, Pearl stays busy helping him round up stray
cattle and move herds into corrals or from pasture to pasture.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a big help,'' Gard said. ``She really works.''
</P>
<P>
   Gard got Pearl when she was a puppy and trained her himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pearl and border collies like her are only happy when they're
working,'' he said. ``They want to work, and they learn easily.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that like many border collies, Pearl is a master of
getting cattle to do her bidding without hurting them. ``These dogs
are best for working cattle, I think,'' he said. ``They mainly snap
at the heels, just enough to scare the cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Gard has used border collies on his ranch and
can't imagine being without one. ``Pearl takes care of me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   DETECTING THE DRUGS
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Rispoli, a detective with the canine unit of the Essex
County sheriff's department, had carefully hidden two plastic bags
of cocaine and marijuana in an abandoned building next to his
unit's offices in Belleville, N.J. Then, when detective Chris
Di-Rocco gave the command, Royce _ a 3-year-old black mixed
Labrador and retriever _ bounded into action. Within seconds he had
found the first stash in a discarded file cabinet; with equal
dispatch he found the second in the drawer of a old desk. In both
cases he signaled his discovery by frantically pawing at the hiding
places.
</P>
<P>
   Royce is a specialist in sniffing out narcotics. He is one of
three dogs used for that purpose by the canine unit. Ten other dogs
of various breeds, including bloodhounds and German shepherds, are
used to find bombs, detect arson, track suspects or missing people,
or help in search-and-rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
   Royce came to the sheriff's department from Morristown, N.J.,
after the Seeing Eye Inc., which trains guide dogs, rejected him
because of a short attention span. But this characteristic made him
perfect for rapid police searches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Royce is an amazing dog,'' said DiRocco, who is the dog's
human partner and takes him home when the two aren't on duty. ``He
loves to work and he loves to play. And he knows the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   SPURRING THE SMILES
</P>
<P>
   Moki is on duty 24 hours a day at the Vista Del Sol Care Center,
a nursing home in Culver City, Calif. During rounds each morning,
he visits patients; later, he meets them in an exercise room.
</P>
<P>
   Moki, who is 1 year old, is a black and white peekapoo, a cross
between a Pekingese and a miniature poodle.
</P>
<P>
   Stella Henry, a nurse who is a co-founder and director of the
nursing home, says Moki has had an extremely positive effect on the
patients. She cites examples of usually unresponsive patients who
have reacted to Moki by petting him and talking to him.
</P>
<P>
   She says attendance and laughter at activities programs increase
as Moki ``works the room'' and ``earns his keep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Moki sees no age, no wrinkles, no tremors and no tubes,'' she
added. ``His expertise lies in giving unconditional love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
