<SLUG> BC-NY-JULY4-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALL SHIPS LEAD 11-MILE REGATTA ON JULY 4 IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2-9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Under a steamy cloud-bound sky, one of the largest
gatherings of seagoing vessels assembled since man discovered that
iron and pine would float cruised majestically through the salty
flats of New York Harbor on Tuesday in a nautical tribute to
America's 224th year of independence.
</P>
<P>
   A stately march of 26 Class A tall ships, hulls humming and
sails belled, led an 11-mile regatta of 300 military vessels from
nearly 20 nations across the harbor's watery parade ground and up
the Hudson River in a five-hour wind-blown ballet witnessed by
thousands aboard bobbing pleasure craft and more than 1 million on
shore.
</P>
<P>
   It was a splendid maritime collage: teak-decked schooners daubed
with sailors in spanking whites, grey swells heaving brown-masted
barks into yellow skies, bowsprits slicing through ocher haze,
jibtops whipping, and hundreds of canvas mainsails flickering like
birthday candles on the foamy, white-capped cake of the bay.
</P>
<P>
   As he reviewed the display from the flight deck of the USS John
F. Kennedy, President Clinton said: ``On this Fourth of July,
standing in the shadow of Lady Liberty, we must resolve never to
close the golden door behind us and always not only to welcome
people to our borders but to welcome people into our hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who accepts the rights and responsibilities of
citizenship is our fellow citizen, equal in the eyes of God,
entitled to be treated equally and with dignity by all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, the crowd, which stretched from the Battery to the
George Washington Bridge on the west and from the South Street
Seaport to above Roosevelt Island on the east, turned its attention
from sea to sky as 60,000 pyrotechnic shells, rising from 13 barges
spread across the harbor, sizzled, whined and burst, conjuring a
hothouse of exotic flowers in mid-air.
</P>
<P>
   The rich blossoms of red, blue, yellow and green exploded once
in the black of the night, then again in reflective flashes on the
glassy facades of buildings and the dark surface of the surrounding
water.
</P>
<P>
   Independence Day began with a sultry, humid morning in the New
York area as temperatures hovered in the low 70s and pewter clouds
massed above the harbor, giving the ships a somber elegance.
Gathering in the early-hour heat, the vessels slipped like brigands
past the shores of Gravesend, gliding slowly through the mist
toward eager crowds.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, the haze had retreated but the overcast sky had
been soldered into an unbroken scrim of clouds that glared above a
wonderful sight _ an armada of full sails stretching into the
distance, fireboats spraying red, white and blue parabolas of water
into the air and military jets booming over the clogged harbor,
which was covered in a bright white Jackson Pollack splatter of
pleasure boats.
</P>
<P>
   From piers and decks, rooftops and shoreside restaurants, from
apartment living rooms and from lampposts and the hoods of
strategically parked cars, the crowds watched the antique vessels
drift by with a speed and courtliness seemingly drawn from a
distant, gentler age. This was how the world traveled ages ago, at
the pace of nature and at the discretion of capricious winds.
</P>
<P>
   With so many gathered to watch the parade _ 10,000 packed onto
the USS Intrepid and its berth at 46th Street alone _ there was
bound to be confusion. A brief spell of disappointment hit the
masses gathered on the Upper West Side, for example, when many of
the tall ships turned around at 54th Street, following what
organizers said was the flotilla's prearranged route.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're calling it Slop Sail,'' said Kate Foster, who watched
with a sinking heart from her apartment on Riverside Drive and
113th Street as the full-rigged brigs and barkentines came about
and sailed south before reaching her and a dozen guests. ``We have
friends over and everyone's gathered around, but there's better
coverage on television. It's a real disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   The august tall ships massed in the harbor seemed to catch the
uneasy optimism of the country at the turn of the millennium. They
were made of simple and practical stuff _ oak, canvas, steel _ and
proved to the crowd that ingenuity, craftsmanship and rugged
self-reliance were once common values. At the same time, however,
the ships were relics, reminders that these values had flourished
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The procession Tuesday was billed as the largest naval operation
in history, and its organizers said it would contain more floating
vessels than D-Day or the Spanish Armada. While 70,000 sailing
craft of all types were expected, far less _ perhaps as few as half
_ showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the 295-foot, American three-masted bark Eagle, the
Parade of Sail eased under the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge shortly
after 9 a.m. in a northwesterly wind of less than 10 mph. A regal
line of 180 tall ships led the fleet, followed by scores of modern
and antiquated military craft and surrounded by as many as 30,000
recreational boats.
</P>
</TEXT>
