<HEADER>
A2924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR05-COX     07-04 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Team time trial concept costs Armstrong
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Sedrvic e
<TEXT>
<P>
   St. NAZAIRE, France _ As Lance Armstrong chugged up the Pont de
St. Nazaire, a huge, winding bridge that looms almost 100 yards
above the mouth of the Loire River, his coach screamed for him to
put on the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   The defending Tour de France champion was riding too fast and
was breaking away from the rest of his U.S. Postal Service Team.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's stage four from Nantes to St. Nazaire was a unique one
for this year's Tour. Rather than have a traditional time trial,
the Tour planners opted for a team version for the first time since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   At least five riders from the same team had to cross the finish
line together. If one broke away, the team risked a penalty. All
the riders who finished together received the same time as the
fifth rider.
</P>
<P>
   So Armstrong, rather than simply putting his head down and
pumping out the miles, had to wait for everyone to catch up. His
squad managed a second-place finish, but because of the team time
trial concept, Armstrong lost ground in the overall standings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of celebrating American Independence Day seven time
zones from home by wearing the Tour's traditional yellow jersey,
Armstrong was forced to find a quick ride to his team hotel while a
new leader was presented on the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Jalabert, already one of the most popular athletes in
his country, gave the French something to cheer on this blustery
afternoon along the Atlantic Ocean. Jalabert was the leader of the
winning ONCE team, and his squad's performance allowed him to zoom
from third to first place in the overall standings, or ``general
classification'' as it's called in cycling.
</P>
<P>
   Jalabert's overall time of 10 hours, 9.1 seconds was 12 seconds
better than second-place David Canada, also of ONCE. Armstrong, who
started the afternoon in second place and four seconds behind the
leader, fell to third place, 24 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   ONCE's dominant performance Tuesday allowed them to pack the top
10. Seven members of the Spanish team were in the top 10. U.S.
Postal members made up the other three spots, with Vjatceslav
Ekimov in fifth (43 seconds behind) and Tyler Hamilton in 10th, 55
seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   USPS member Kevin Livingston, an Austin, Texas, resident, was
13th, 1:18 behind Jalabert. USPS rider George Hincapie was 14th
overall and 1:33 out of first. Austin resident Chann McRae, who
rides for Mapei, was 51st overall, 3:57 back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed not to have won it, because we spent a lot
of time preparing for it,'' said Mark Gorski, USPS general manager.
``But ultimately, this was a real key for our team and Lance
because we picked up 40 seconds on Telekom.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorski was specifically referring to the advantage Armstrong
picked up on Telekom's team leader Jan Ullrich, who won the 1997
Tour while finishing second in 1996 and 1998. He did not compete in
1999 because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Telekom's third place finish knocked Ullrich from fourth to
12th, 1:07 behind Jalabert and 43 seconds behind Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Gorski had been riding in one of the team cars tailing the USPS
riders, so he got an upclose look at what happens during a team
time trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance got on that bridge, and Johan (Bruyneel, the USPS coach)
was shouting at Lance, 'slow it down, slow it down,''' Gorski said.
``He was riding so strong, the other guys were just hanging on the
best they could.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, three USPS riders lost track of the leading six. But
that wasn't unusual, given that every team but ONCE suffered
casualties on the 43.4 trek from Nante to St. Nazaire. The winds
turned nasty, consistently gusting 35 mph. Brief showers and
temperatures in the low 60s also made for a miserable day.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was too tired to talk to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's happy with the results,'' said Bill Stapleton,
Armstrong's Austin-based agent. ``He gets to keep the pressure of
the yellow jersey off his back. There's not going to be another
lead change until Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong left the course thinking he was in fourth place
overall. About an hour after the finish, the Tour officials
penalized ONCE 20 seconds for breaking driving rules. A judge
spotted a ONCE team car trailing too close to the riders. The judge
ruled that the car served as a shield to keep the wind off the ONCE
team, thus giving them an unfair advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The yellow jersey is tiring for a team to defend, especially
this early in the three-week long Tour. Jalabert's eight other
riders must chase down breakaways and control the tempo of the
peloton while he is wearing yellow. He hinted that ONCE may have a
different strategy for the rest of the flat stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have the yellow jersey,'' Jalabert said. ``And we
knew it would be possible thanks to the strength of our team. Now
that we have the race lead, we'll discuss how to handle it at a
team meeting (Tuesday night). Our priority is to ensure that we
maintain the strength of our team for the climbing stages of the
Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
