<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POWER STRUGGLE BEGINS FOR MEXICO'S DEFEATED LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MEXICO-POLITICS-FOX) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A battle has broken out within Mexico's governing
party, following its election defeat, with several rival leaders
maneuvering for control during a painful transition that will test
its powers of survival, party leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   Near chaos gripped the party after its leader, installed during
the presidential campaign by the party's candidate, Francisco
Labastida, presented her resignation, with the expectation that her
entire Cabinet would leave with her. The party called a meeting of
its leaders for Tuesday night to choose replacements, but the elder
statesmen were so divided over whom to pick and how to pick them
that the meeting was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's resignation by Dulce Maria Sauri, the party president,
was not formally accepted, said Marcos Bucio, a congressman who was
the party's spokesman during the Labastida campaign. But Sauri
appeared to have lost her authority.
</P>
<P>
   Who was in charge of the party, if anyone, was not clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time of catharsis,'' Bucio said.
</P>
<P>
   The power of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the
PRI, has always been based on the influence and resources of the
Mexican presidency, and by tradition, the president or
president-elect has hired and fired the party's top leaders,
virtually by whim.
</P>
<P>
   But after the party's first defeat in a presidential race since
its founding seven decades ago, several of its elder statesmen on
Monday refused to back a former governor, Jesus Murillo Karam, to
replace Sauri in the top party post because he was seen as
President Ernesto Zedillo's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many very different positions now,'' said Javier
Trevino, who resigned his post as deputy treasury secretary to work
as a senior campaign aide to Labastida. ``Some groups think they
don't want a leader who seems to reflect the president. They don't
want the president involved. They want this to be more of a PRI
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   A few party leaders said they hoped Labastida might take the
party reins personally, but it was not clear if he would accept the
post. On Monday, the defeated presidential candidate went to the
party's hulking concrete headquarters in downtown Mexico City to
collect his personal belongings from his office.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, Roberto Campa, who sought the nomination last
fall as the party's Mexico City mayoral candidate and later worked
for Labastida's campaign, also packed up his personal photos and
files and stalked out of party headquarters. He vowed to abandon
politics altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters' message was very clear,'' Campa said. ``But it
doesn't look to me like people around here understood that.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Labastida's defeat, the party should also be disturbed
by the fact that most of the party's votes in Sunday's election
came from sectors of the Mexican population that are disappearing,
said Carlos Elizondo Mayer-Serra, a political scientist at the
Center for Teaching and Learning in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the demographics,'' Elizondo said. ``They received
votes from rural people, who are moving to the cities. They
received votes from old people, who are dying. And they received
votes from illiterate people, who are becoming more educated. This
is a terrible problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some leaders were looking on the bright side.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a trial by fire for us,'' said Cristina Alcayaga, a
former party human rights official who worked for Labastida. ``But
don't forget, our party received 12 million votes. We have to build
bridges to new constituencies and that's not easy. But we're not
dead yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in December, though, when President-elect Vicente Fox
takes office, the party's base of governmental support will shrink
drastically _ to its 20 state governors and the party's
much-reduced congressional delegation. How firmly the party's
several large unions and peasant organizations will remain tied to
it remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``With respect to the PRI's future, an optimist would have to be
a badly informed pessimist,'' said Agustin Basave, a former party
official who is now a political science professor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The elections have not only devastated the governing party. The
largest leftist group, the Party of the Democratic Revolution, is
also in turmoil after its presidential candidate, Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, came in a distant last among the major candidates in his
third presidential race. The party's congressional delegation also
has been reduced, although it retained control of Mexico City's
municipal government.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Fox repeatedly invited Cardenas to join
forces with him to defeat the governing party, but his flirtations
went unrequited. Tuesday Fox again invited the left to join with
him in forming the new ``government of unity.'' But Cardenas
spurned that offer, too, and Amalia Garcia, the party president,
said Fox had a ``conservative and backward position.''
</P>
<P>
   One leftist senator urged Garcia to call a party congress, to
``put the party on a new footing.'' Then an ugly public dispute
flared with the Workers' Party, a small party with which Cardenas
had forged an electoral alliance, after one of its leaders
criticized Cardenas' handling of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should just keep their mouth shut,'' said Carlos
Navarrete, the Party of the Democratic Revolution's spokesman.
``Out of prudence we haven't wanted to make public their behavior
in the political and economic areas of our alliance, but if they
want to have a public fight, things are going to turn out badly for
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
