<HEADER>
A2933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-2     07-04 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 9,
2000. Many of the stories focus on the Lincoln Center Festival. If
you have questions about stories, call 888-346-9867 or
212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (moving in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VERMEER-OPERA (Amsterdam, the Netherlands) _ Peter Greenaway,
the British movie director, and Louis Andriessen, the Dutch
composer, are opening the Lincoln Center Festival 2000 with a new
opera, ``Writing to Vermeer.'' Focusing on two weeks in 1672 when
the painter Johannes Vermeer made a trip to The Hague, the creators
imagine that he received 18 fictional letters from women in his
life and sensed the crisis gripping the country as it prepared to
breach the country's dikes to hold off invasion by France. Alan
Riding concludes that the creators are saying that Vermeer painted
idyllic domestic scenes as a response to agitated times. Vermeer
never replies to the letters, but Riding says he is ever-present in
the 100-minute opera.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-MUSIC (New York)_ The development of 12-tone composition
was one of the most invigorating occurrences of the 20th-century
music. Now two theories persist and conflict: Was there a tyranny
of the atonal composers who seized the intellectual high ground and
intimidated tonal composers or was it these modern composers who
were the beleagured minority? Joseph N. Straus, a professor of
music theory at Queen College, has an answer. The dominance is a
myth. More than two-thirds of the active composers were tonal,
whereas serial composers constituted less than 15percent of the
total. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CIRCUS-LES-COLPORTEURS (Marseille, France) _ ``Filao'' from Les
Colporteurs, the French nouveau cirque, is the story of a French
aristocrat who becomes so disgusted with the world he climbs a tree
and stays there. The trapeze artists mix art forms and execute
their feats to music and with theatricality. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-DIAMOND (New York) _ Learn by doing: that is the premise
of the Diamond project, named after its principal donor, Irene
Diamond. Peter Martins, City Ballet's artistic director, initiated
this showcase for new choreography in 1992, repeated it in 1994 and
1997 and hit pay dirt with this spring's series. By Anna
Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-ULTIMA-VEZ _ (New York) _ When Wim Vandekeybus, the
Belgian choreographer, presented in New York from 1987 to 1991,
dancers ducked as others threw bricks at them, and the norm
consisted of flying bodies, confrontational games and erotic
aggressiveness. The 37-year-old choreographer warns the Lincoln
Center Festival says he no longer has to throw bricks to show
intense instinct. The title of his newest dance, ``In Spite of
Wishing and Wanting,'' refers to the impossibility of explaining
wishes and fears except in dreams. That is why the dancers often
assume sleeping positions, even when they are standing up. ``They
sleep in the air and wake up as they hit the floor,'' he said in an
interview with Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-NOCHE-FLAMENCA (Madrid, Spain) _ In the gypsy quarter of
Madrid, Martin Santangelo rehearses five musicians and six flamenco
dancers for an American tour. This New Yorker has found a calling
in a 15th-century dance form. By Valerie Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SINGER-XMEN-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Bryan Singer's ``X-Men,'' based
on characters from the comic book series created by Stan Lee, is
one of the bigger extravaganzas of the summer. Twentieth Century
Fox chose Singer, a low-budget and indie filmmaker, because they
wanted someone who would care about the characters, not just the
action and the making the big budget ($75 million, plus $30 million
for marketing) even bigger. Others may see a science fiction
extravaganza, but not Singer. ``It's actually about prejudice,''
said the 34-year-old filmmaker. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   PODESWA-FIVESENSES-FILM (New York) _ Laura Winters interviews
Jeremy Podeswa, the Canadian filmmaker whose ``Five Senses'' will
open at the Lincoln Center Festival. He explains how a chance
encounter led to the story of five characters, each linked to a
sense. For hearing, there's an eye doctor (Philippe Volter) who is
going deaf; for taste, a cake-maker (Mary-Louise Parker). Smell is
represented by a bisexual housecleaner (Daniel MacIvor). Touch is
symbolized by a massage therapist (Gabrielle Rose), who is unable
to reach her teen-age daughter (Nadia Litz), a voyeur who
represents sight.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OZON-FILM (New York) _ The French director Francois Ozon has
made thrillers about homicidal house guests and high school
killers. In satire, he has explored the lighter sides of
cannibalism and incest. But his latest film tackles the horrors of
one couple's life. ``Water Drops on Burning Rocks'' is his screen
adaptation of a play written by Rainer Werner Fassbinder at the age
of 19. This utterly disillusioned teen-age vision opens in New
York. By Leslie Camhi.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION/RADIO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HAMBURG-RADIO (New York) _ Joan Hamburg speaks to listeners in
the warm, confidential manner women use when chatting with friends.
She dispenses tips on city living, interviews an entertainer or the
author of a book and then takes calls for an hour, keeping a
million and a half people _ mostly women over 30 _ listening. Her
audience, nearly twice the size of those for competing talk shows,
earns WOR in New York nearly $1 million a year in revenue, a
remarkable figure for a daytime show.
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITE-SISTERS-RADIO (New York) _ The Satellite Sisters _
Liz, Julie, Monica, Sheila and Lian Dolan _ are WNYC Radio's rising
stars. What the Satellite Sisters do is get together for a
conference call. Liz is usually in New York, Lian is in Pasadena,
Calif., and Julie comes in via satellite from Bangkok. The other
two sisters _ Monica in Portland and Sheila in New York _ are also
sometimes on the line, depending on their schedules.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-MUSIC (New York) _ The ``Electronic Evolution''
series presented by Lincoln Center this coming Wednesday through
Sunday is dominated by the role of electronic instruments in
performance. This dominance seems calculated to assuage the fear
most widely associated with electronic music: that live performers
will be replaced by machines. Electronic music in this festival
revolves around the live musician, not the stationary, unemotive
tape recorder or computer. By Kyle Gann.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-MUSIC-POP (New York) _ The composers, visionaries,
theorists, tinkerers and crackpots who invented electronic music
probably never imagined that by the end of the 20th century,
thousands of people would regularly turn out to hear electronic
music in clubs and that the futuristic sounds are now taken for
granted by anyone who tunes in a Top 40 radio station. By Jon
Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARCHITECTURE/ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-COLUMBUS-CIRCLE (New York) _ Herbert Muschamp,
architecture critic for The Times, evaluates David Child's design
for the Columbus Circle site and finds it ``vastly superior'' to
earlier versions. Where the old version mimiced the Central Park
West apartment buildings, in the new version period details have
given way to crisp geometric solids; the towers have been tweaked
into trapezoids and the setbacks form a crystalline silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOGRAPHY-SACCO (New York) _ Argentine artist Graciela Sacco
uses a heliography technique to place images on suitcases, Venetian
blinds, refrigerators and even postage stamps. In the current
exhibit at the Argentine Consulate here, visitors are confronted
by, among other things, small spoons hanging from a line. On each
spoon an open mouth has been heliographed. She has also hung a
series of clear plastic frames imprinted with the image of eyes as
if the art were looking at the visitor, not vice versa. By Lyle
Rexer.
</P>
<P>
   ROSLER-ART (New York) _ Martha Rosler, the multimedia artist,
critic, theorist, teacher and art-world provocateur, has shown
disdain for the normal rites of passage from galleries to
collectors to museums. She even declined to represented by a
gallery until 1993. That makes it all the more remarkable that
Rosler is now receiving a major retrospective. After stops in
England, France, Austria and Spain, ``Martha Rosler: Positions in
the Life World'' makes its only United States appearance in a joint
presentation here by the New Museum of Contemporary Art and the
International Center of Photography. By Michael Rush.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The following stories were sent on July 3 in the ``t'' category
for release on July 9.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-GORT (Undated) _ Gort has no shop selling Celtic
knickknacks, no pub with performances of ditties on the half-hour.
Even its name lacks the lyricism of more famous Irish destinations.
But within a 10-mile radius you can find Coole Park, once Lady
Gregory's sanctuary for the leaders of the Irish literary revival;
Thoor Ballylee, the tower of inspiration for William Butler Yeats;
Kilmacduagh, some of the finest monastic remnants in Ireland;
Kinvara, an inviting fishing village; and the Burren, the dramatic
limestone landscape sloping into the Atlantic. Then there are the
people and places of Gort proper. Those who pay attention will see
life in the Irish west as it is, not as it might be imagined. Dan
Barry returns to the town where his mother spent her childhood.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-IRELAND-BURREN (Undated) _ Bleak and harsh are the
adjectives often used to describe the Burren, a roughly
100-square-mile limestone landscape of cliffs, stony hills and
broad stretches of rock. But Lisa Fugard discovered the profusity
and mystique of wildflowers growing there.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GASOLINE-PRICES (Undated) _ A random sampling of
destinations, including the nation's two most popular tourist
sites, Las Vegas and Orlando, Fla., found no appreciable falloff in
visitors because of the increase in gasoline prices. Yet Edwin
McDowell also found many indications that travelers are downsizing
vacations _ cutting short the number of days and number of miles
traveled _ to economize on gas.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ There are a lot of new ways to
dial home from Europe. Travelers can buy or rent a cell phone
compatible with European; they can sign up for an international
program with a local phone company, or sign up for another overseas
service. Betsy Wade reviews a few of the newer possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Ray Cormier answers questions about the
new United States Lines, tours of World War I sites in France and
where to hear church music in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Kiosks open at seven airports to rent
DVD players and movies; Hotel Savoy reopens in Florence, Italy;
Francis Gary Powers Jr. leads a Cold War tour; a hotel in St.
Thomas offers Nannies in Paradise so parents can have a night out
and rail service is completed for Sydney Airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
