u f BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT &LR;      07-04 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN FINALLY CONSIDERING INTEREST RATE BOOST UP FROM NEAR ZERO 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Faced with growing evidence that the Japanese economy is
gaining momentum, the country's central bank could decide later
this month to raise interest rates from their near-zero level.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would be the first increase in Japanese rates in a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   The latest sign of economic strength came Tuesday with the
bank's closely watched quarterly survey of business sentiment,
known as the tankan, which showed that big Japanese manufacturers
were more confident of their future business prospects in the
quarter ending on June 30 than they have been in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of the tankan means the probability is now quite
high for a rate hike,'' said Masaaki Kanno, a senior economist at
J.P. Morgan in Tokyo and a former official at the central bank.
``But it's hard to say whether that's a good or bad thing at the
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the tankan survey was in many ways a tale of two
economies, the global and the domestic, making it hard to draw
overarching conclusions from the data.
</P>
<P>
   While executives at Japan's large corporations were feeling more
confident, their colleagues at smaller businesses remained gloomy.
That difference in sentiment will complicate the central bank's
decision on interest rates, which is likely to be the hottest topic
of discussion among the nine policy board members at their next
meeting on July 17. The central bank governor, Masaru Hayami, has
made it clear that he favors raising rates as quickly as possible,
and at least two other members of the policy board have supported
him.
</P>
<P>
   The bank lowered short-term interest rates virtually to zero a
year and a half ago, when significant parts of Japan's financial
system seemed at risk of collapse and the threat of severe
deflation loomed large. But in the process, the bank deprived
itself of its most valuable tool, the ability to use interest rates
to influence the economy.
</P>
<P>
   While many economists and policy makers agree that bank
officials did the right thing, opinions about when and how the bank
should go about re-creating a more normal interest rate environment
diverge widely.
</P>
<P>
   There is as yet no clear consensus that the budding economic
recovery can flourish on its own, and the tankan survey results did
little to resolve the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Big companies reported that they intended to increase their
capital investment by 4.6 percent on average in the current fiscal
year, ending in March 2001, but smaller companies said they would
be cutting their spending _ and even more sharply than they
projected in the previous quarter, from January through March.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say that difference speaks volumes about the strength
of the nascent recovery in Japan's economy, the world's second
largest.
</P>
<P>
   Larger corporations have been able to rely on demand in Europe
and the United States to increase business. Were they solely
reliant on the domestic economy, like smaller companies and service
businesses, they too might be less optimistic about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Big multinationals also have less need than small companies do
for the short-term financing that would become more expensive if
the central bank raised interest rates. Indeed, a surge in profits
has enabled many large companies to go on a spending spree using
their own cash, as reflected in the continuing decline of bank
lending here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big guys that rely on export markets are doing great,''
said Jesper Koll, chief economist at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. in Tokyo,
``but the domestic service sector and small and midsized companies
that do most, if not all, of their business domestically are only a
little better than stagnant. The question for the bank thus becomes
whom do you run the bank for?''
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates and borrowing costs for companies might curtail
their investment activities or even accelerate the pace of
bankruptcies. ``My view is that raising rates would kick off a
recession,'' said Robert Alan Feldman, chief economist at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter here.
</P>
<P>
   But others consider such concerns overblown because the bank is
not likely to raise rates above 0.25 percent. ``The increase in
borrowing costs should have only a small impact on economic
activity,'' Kanno of J.P. Morgan said. ``Bank lending is declining
anyway, and capital expenditures are increasingly financed
internally.''
</P>
<P>
   The central bank has not laid out guidelines, such as inflation
targets, that would help steer its decision making and increase
understanding of its intentions. It has said that the low rates are
meant to help stimulate the economy by keeping the cost of
borrowing down. But low rates may also be contributing to a
deflationary chain of lower prices, wages and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer prices in Japan are currently falling at the fastest
rate in the last decade. Moreover, the prices that manufacturers
can charge for their goods is falling much faster than the prices
of their raw material and other costs, eroding profit.
</P>
<P>
   Central bank policy board members argue that much of this is
``good deflation,'' but they have yet to produce convincing
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The finance ministry is also making things difficult for the
central bank in setting a clear policy. The ministry, another
center of financial power in this country and often a rival, is
using its authority on intervention in the currency markets to send
a clear message that it does not favor raising interest rates. It
has ordered the central bank to intervene to keep the yen from
rising more than 10 times this year. Such intervention tells the
market that rates are unlikely to rise, since a rate increase would
itself put upward pressure on the yen.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the bank seems confused about its role. Like most
central banks, its legal mandate is to maintain price stability.
But lately, some policy board members have expressed concern that a
``moral hazard'' is emerging from the exceptionally loose monetary
policy. They fear that by holding rates effectively at zero, they
have enabled corporate Japan to avoid the painful overhaul it
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand, and in some ways agree with the concern about
moral hazard,'' Feldman said. ``But the bank is not in charge of
structural policy, and anyway, using interest rates to influence
structural reform is sort of like using a hammer to hit a screw.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
