<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS' UNIONS ENDORSE GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ill.)   By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ After months of supportive speeches, fat donation
checks and thousands of hours of volunteer campaign work, the two
national teachers' unions formally endorsed Vice President Al Gore
for president Tuesday in separate votes.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsements came as no surprise, but could prove
significant in a campaign in which both candidates are making
education a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore the union backing is an important symbol of support
from the Democratic Party's traditional base and a significant
organizing tool for the coming months. But while the vice president
will try to use the endorsements to show that his education agenda
reflects the opinions of classroom experts, his opponent, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, will undoubtedly accuse Gore of being in
the unions' pockets and uninterested in true school reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs more than unions,'' said Mindy Tucker, a campaign
spokeswoman for Bush, a Republican. ``He needs the support of
parents and school board members and people in local communities
that make the decisions that affect our schools. It takes more than
an endorsement to improve education in America.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, both candidates have been trying to one-up each
other with education proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants to provide preschool for every 4-year-old, give
teachers who agree to work in difficult schools signing bonuses and
pump federal money into school construction projects, plus a host
of other ideas whose costs total $115 billion over a decade. Bush
would spend far less, some $13 billion, and focus his attention on
holding low-performing schools accountable by imposing financial
penalties and heightening scrutiny of test data, particularly among
minority students.
</P>
<P>
   Among the chasms between the candidates are their positions on
providing vouchers, financed by taxpayers, for tuition in private
schools, an issue that alone might have been enough to decide the
union endorsements. Bush refrains from using the word ``vouchers,''
but would let students at failing schools take $1,500 of government
money to pay for tuition at a private school, while Gore opposes
vouchers, as do the unions.
</P>
<P>
   At the biennial convention of the American Federation of
Teachers here Tuesday afternoon, Nat LaCour, the union's executive
vice president, ticked off issue after issue, such as increasing
teacher salaries and providing better health care for children. On
each one, La Cour said, Gore was a friend of the union's 1 million
members, ``Not Mr. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaker after speaker lavished praise on the vice president, who
is scheduled to speak here on Wednesday and at the convention of
the 2.5 million-member National Education Association, in Chicago,
on Thursday. Several Texas teachers told their colleagues that
Bush's accomplishments in schools have been exaggerated. Finally,
one man recommended no endorsement, saying that the Clinton
administration's trade policies have expanded child labor overseas,
but the endorsement was overwhelming on a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   At the NEA convention in Chicago, the vice president received 89
percent of the votes cast by secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the search for ideas to improve public education, Al Gore
knows where to look first,'' said Robert Chase, the president of
the NEA. ``He looks to teachers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
