<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumers May See Higher Heating Bills This Winter
</P>
<P>
   After a summer of high gasoline prices, consumers may be in for
another shock this winter, as the rising cost of heating oil and
natural gas threaten to make it significantly more expensive to
heat American homes. With demand for fuel and electricity soaring,
natural gas prices have nearly doubled in the last year, to their
highest levels in more than a decade. Heating oil prices have risen
10 percent just in the last month. This winter, many homeowners
could discover that it costs at least 30 percent more to heat their
homes than it did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Of Parachutes and Software
</P>
<P>
   Did you hear the one about the optimistic sky diver? No, this is
no joke. Thomas Siebel, chief executive of Siebel Systems, a maker
of e-business application software, compares sky diving to taking
business risks. He also likens house painting to the software
business. And he says that as a result of his Midwestern
sensibilities and lessons about hard work and debt, he prefers real
business attire for business dealings and hopes his employees never
boast about all the Ferraris parked in their lot.
</P>
<P>
   European Companies Eye U.S.
</P>
<P>
   First The conventional wisdom has been that European companies,
newly emboldened by a common currency and economic growth at home,
would use Wall-Street-style tactics in cross-border deals unifying
the Continent. But not following the script, European companies
have increasingly set their sights on acquisition targets in the
United States first.
</P>
<P>
   Crime News Site to File Chapter 11
</P>
<P>
   APB Online, operator of a criminal justice news Web site that
recently foundered, plans to file for protection for creditors
under Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Code. Last month, ABP
Online laid off the staff and scrambled to find private investors
to inject new capital into the debt-ridden company. The bankruptcy
filing, which the executives of APBnews.com said they would
announce as early as Wednesday, is designed to provide a little
more breathing space for the site.
</P>
<P>
   Record Delays in June for Airlines
</P>
<P>
   June appears to have been the worst month in domestic airline
history for delayed flights, preliminary statistics from the
Federal Aviation Administration indicate. In general, bad weather
accounts for about 70 percent of flight delays, which are the bane
of business travel. The big question now is whether the trend will
continue as record numbers of passengers crowd onto planes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Markets Reopen
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States reopen today after being closed yesterday in observance of
the Fourth of July.
</P>
</TEXT>
