A2952 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MEXICO-FOX-560(2TAKES     07-04 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTOR IN MEXICO PLANS TO OVERHAUL LAW ENFORCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MEXICO-POLITICS) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The president-elect of Mexico, Vicente Fox,
announced plans Tuesday to rebuild the country's federal law
enforcement system, moving it toward a U.S. model of justice as a
way to wipe out corruption that has crippled his nation for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also said that he would travel to the United States soon to
meet with President Clinton, and both major presidential candidates
to press his proposal to open the U.S.-Mexico border to a
less-restricted flow of immigrants. The president-elect also
explained some of the measures his new government would take to
deal with a range of Mexico's most persistent and complex troubles,
including the fight against poverty, efforts to stem the flow of
drugs through Mexico and the unresolved conflict in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   A two-hour news conference by Fox, whose election on Sunday
ended a 71-year rule of the Institutional Revolutionary Party,
turned into a wide-ranging foreign policy address. But his most
detailed proposals centered on his fight against corruption, a
problem he considers a top priority. To accomplish the overhaul, he
is likely to use executive powers that allow him to create a
federal police agency and to shift law enforcement responsibilities
from one agency to another.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, he said that he would create a Ministry of
Security and Justice _ similar to the U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation _ that would be responsible for all the federal
police.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's plans would also significantly reduce the powers of the
Interior Ministry, which currently manages a recently created
federal police force. And the attorney general's office would be
similarly weakened, not only by the removal of its control over
federal law enforcement, but also by Fox's plans to create a new
agency of federal prosecutors to manage investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Because his ideas have widespread support, Fox's transformation
of the system is also expected to be well-received in the Mexican
Congress, even though the Congress is no longer dominated by any
single political party following Sunday's elections.
</P>
<P>
   During his wide-ranging comments, Fox brought up his goal of
greater cooperation among the United States, Mexico and Canada. He
suggested the creation of a North American common market that would
allow a freer flow of merchandise and workers, with strict
adherence to standards for the protection of the environment, law
enforcement and workers' rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to me that both of us have lost sight of the
goal,'' said Fox, referring to the United States and Mexico. ``The
United States' goal has been to put up walls, police and soldiers
to fight immigration. That can't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico's goal has been to open an escape valve, allowing
350,000 young people to cross the border each year and washing its
hands of any responsibility,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are serious,'' Fox concluded, ``The least we can do is
sit down and say, `this is the problem' and the goal is to close
the development gap.''
</P>
<P>
   In his answers to reporters' questions, Fox also offered
specific proposals for improving U.S.-Mexican relations, including
extending the benefits of NAFTA more evenly to small businesses on
both sides of the border and turning the drug certification program
from a unilateral to a multilateral process involving all countries
affected by trafficking.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fox said that in the next two months, he will use five
international head-hunting firms to help him select the members of
his Cabinet so that leading up to his Dec. 1 inauguration, they can
work side-by-side with the ministers they will replace. A team of
aides to Fox have also been assigned to work with the current
leaders of the Finance Ministry on setting next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to transform the law enforcement system, Fox's plans
could be upset by a backlash from below, where bureaucrats and
officers enjoy strong civil service protections.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo reorganized and renamed the nation's
drug police at least twice, and each time traffickers quickly
infiltrated the forces and bought off leading officials. And
Zedillo created a new federal police force to fight a mounting wave
of federal crimes, including kidnapping. But so far the new police
have done little to make Mexicans, especially those in larger
cities, feel any safer.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Chabat, an analyst of Mexican law enforcement praised
Fox's plan to take the federal police out of the hands of
politicians, who used the agents for their own agendas. He said he
felt some pessimism over whether the new system would be resistant
to the corrupting forces of drug traffickers. But, he said,
``Someone has to try to fight them. The truth is whatever the
government tries, it will face a problem with the corruption of
traffickers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a signal of assurance to the Mexican military, Fox also said
he would not consider appointing a civilian as chief of the
Ministry of Defense. ``I see no reason to break a tradition that
has brought stability to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   On other domestic issues, Fox said he wanted to visit Chiapas as
soon as possible and reopen peace talks with the Zapatista rebels,
and he said that he was willing to consider one of the rebels'
principal demands to withdraw the military from rural areas of
conflict in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting poverty was another area that Fox called a priority and
he said that as president he would not approve budgets or program
proposals from members of his Cabinet unless they could demonstrate
in concrete terms how their programs would help the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be our way to pay attention to the groups that have
been totally excluded from the development of our country,'' he
said. ``It is one of the strong principles that we are going to
introduce in the decision-making process of the new government.''
</P>
<P>
   In emphasizing his commitment to fighting corruption, Fox turned
the spotlight not only on the past, but also on his administration
and its future. He announced that he would create a ``Commission of
Transparency,'' made up of Mexican citizens whose job would be to
investigate high-profile scandals of past administrations as well
as to serve as a watchdog over his own government.
</P>
<P>
   But he was careful to make clear that he would not conduct
wholesale investigations of government conduct before taking
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to waste our government looking only at the
past and conducting witch hunts that could be misinterpreted,'' Fox
said in the press conference at the presidential residence, Los
Pinos. The transparency commission, he added, would be his
government's way to ``set its sights forward, to construct a
harmonious government and also to make an accounting of the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
