A2957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BB0-ALLSTARS-COX     07-04 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-ALLSTARS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giants' Kent comes from way back; others wait
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The fans' All-Star votes have been counted, with Jeff
Kent of San Francisco coming from far behind to win the start at
second base for the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part. Managers Bobby Cox and Joe Torre must
pick the pitching staffs and reserves for Tuesday's All-Star Game
at Turner Field In Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The complete NL and AL squads will be announced today. As
always, there will be plenty of disappointed players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost an impossible job,'' said Cox, managing the
National League team for the fifth time. ``I'm sure that there will
be 10 or 12 people upset. You can't blame them. It's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones was the only Braves' player voted in, winning by a
landslide at third base. As many as four teammates might make the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I hope we get five in the game,'' said pitcher Tom
Glavine, who is on the bubble. ``With the game here, it makes it
extra special. You see the ovations players get in their home parks
and you can't help wanting that, too. Especially if you have spent
your whole career with one team, like I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine said he ``feels good'' about his chances after beating
the Mets 10-2 Sunday to improve his record to 8-5 and lower his ERA
to 3.62. The left-hander pitches Friday in Boston and will be
well-rested for the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Although he pitches again Sunday, Greg Maddux is a cinch to make
the team. Other deserving Braves are first baseman Andres
Galarraga, coming back from treatment for cancer, and outfielder
Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Kent, who leads the NL in RBIs, overcame a 138,000-vote deficit
in the final week to overtake Houston's Craig Biggio and Edgardo
Alfonzo of the Mets at second base.
</P>
<P>
   Ballpark voting closed last Tuesday, but fans could vote through
Saturday on their computers.
</P>
<P>
   At first base in the American League, Jason Giambi of Oakland
held off Cleveland's Jim Thome. Giambi and Kansas City outfielder
Jermaine Dye, a former Brave, are the only starters who will be
playing in their first All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the leading vote getter in each league was a
catcher. Pudge Rodriguez of Texas led the AL with 2,808,456 votes.
Mike Piazza of the Mets led the NL with 2,780,452 votes.
</P>
<P>
   THE FACTS
</P>
<P>
   What: Major League All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 8 p.m. EDT Tuesday; Turner Field, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   TV: NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: Sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Other All-Star events: Futures Game and Celebrity Hitting
Challenge, Sunday; Home Run Derby and All-Star workout, Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
