<SLUG> BC-BIKER-COPS-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE OFF-DUTY OFFICERS RIDING IN MOTORCYCLE GANGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are police officers by trade, but their
appearance, as a group, does not exactly shout law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is the tattoos and beards. Or the bandanas and bare,
barrel chests. Or the black leather vests crowned with the likeness
of a tusked boar in mid-snarl. Or the V-Twin Harley-Davidson
cruisers equipped with shotgun dual exhausts and tuned to scorch
the road.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it is their name: The Wild Pigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been stopped by police officers out of state,'' said
one Wild Pig who asked to remain anonymous. ``We tell them, `Hey,
we're cops,' and they say, `Really? You guys are cops?' And two
hours later they are at our barbecue.''
</P>
<P>
   With 1,400 members in 80 chapters, the Wild Pigs are one of two
increasingly popular, national motorcycle clubs that draw their
members from the law enforcement ranks. The second club, known as
the Blue Knights, is even larger, with 11,630 members in 373
chapters, including dozens of chapters in New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In a world infatuated with stereotypes, police biker clubs
illustrate that the universe of officers includes more than a few
free spirits for whom rebellion has become a weekend pastime.
During riding season, from April to October, Wild Pigs and Blue
Knights, and smaller clubs like the Lawmen and Celtic Law, organize
trips as ambitious as a weeklong pilgrimage to Daytona Beach and as
modest as an evening spin to Little Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Two thousand bikers, primarily police officers, poured into that
New York neighborhood on the night of June 28, roaring through the
Holland Tunnel from New Jersey, as part of Gooch's Garlic Run, a
ride sponsored by the Blue Knights to benefit sick children. The
bike procession stretched 14 miles along Route 80, organizers said.
Then the leather-clad riders filled Mulberry Street trattorias to
overflowing. Manhattan may not be a place that routinely welcomes
bellowing choppers, but this night there were few complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a family on the corner who wanted to know what was going
on,'' said Anthony Fontana, manager of Caffe Napoli. ``I told them,
these are cops and they come here once a year. They smiled. If this
had been some other group they would have turned around and left.''
</P>
<P>
   As motorcyclists, the Wild Pigs and the Blue Knights share a
taste for a face full of wind, the freedom of the open road, the
embrace of the wide, blue sky and the brotherhood of bikes and
babes in black leather. As public safety officers, both active and
retired, they share an interest in supporting the families of
fallen colleagues and raising money for charity. The Blue Knights,
for example, say they have raised nearly $3 million in cash for
charity since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But there are distinctions between the clubs as well. The Blue
Knights, who were founded 26 years ago in Bangor, Maine, are a
G-rated bunch, as motorcycle clubs go. Club members, a range of law
enforcement professionals, including correction officers, wear
leather vests, or ``colors,'' that are an unthreatening shade of
powder blue. Their logo is a knight atop a rearing white horse. One
of their slogans is: ``There are no strangers, only friends you
haven't met.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You ride safe and you are courteous,'' said Joseph Edelmann, a
Blue Knight who retired from the New York City Police Department 13
years ago and rides with Chapter 7, which covers Queens, Staten
Island and Brooklyn. The 70 members (about half of them New York
Police Department officers, both active and retired) meet monthly
at a diner on Emmons Avenue in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to change the whole outlook on bikers,''
Edelmann said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wild Pigs have adopted a more intimidating look, a la the
Oakland Raiders, and their manner is more full-throttle. Posted on
one Wild Pig Web site, for example, alongside the club bylaws and
photos of noteworthy bikes, are occasional snapshots of women in
abbreviated attire bending over to grab a beer.
</P>
<P>
   The club was born in San Jose, Calif., 13 years after the Blue
Knights, and it accepts a variety of public safety personnel as
members, including firefighters, as long as they ride American-made
bikes, usually Harleys.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like to portray us as a bunch of knuckle draggers
wearing leather jackets,'' said one Wild Pig. ``The reality is that
it's a fraternal organization of people who share a common
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Buck, 37, editor of Thunder Press East, a monthly
motorcycle newspaper, said the Wild Pigs drew members from those
who thought the Blue Knights were too strait-laced. ``They wanted
black vests instead of blue,'' she said. ``They wanted a little bit
of the bad boy image.''
</P>
<P>
   Buck recalled riding to the annual nationwide motorcycle rally
in Sturgis, S.D., in 1996 when a traffic jam in western
Pennsylvania forced her and some Wild Pigs to take a break along
the road, not far from a state trooper. ``I reach in and pull out a
bottle of water,'' she said. ``They are popping beers on the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Blazer, a Wild Pig from Chicago who is the club's spokesman
and lawyer, said the incident, if true, was an aberration. ``Our
members are sensitive that they live under a microscope,'' he said,
``so they are incredibly careful and scrupulous about the creation
of any false impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, like the Blue Knights, the Wild Pigs organize benefits
for charity each year, with each chapter involved in staging at
least one. The Westchester chapter, one of eight in New York State,
will be holding a pig roast in August for Nick Springer, a
15-year-old boy from Croton-on-Hudson who lost his hands and the
lower part of his legs last year to a bacterial disease. The boy's
father, Gary Springer, said the club just sent him a letter one
day, out of the blue, offering its help.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great group of guys,'' he said, ``and it's obvious
that they care.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Membership in either club is not an issue with the New York City
Police Department. ``Officers are allowed to join fraternal clubs
or organizations at their own discretion as long as they do not
engage in any criminality,'' said Deputy Chief Thomas Fahey.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of Wild Pigs were willing to be interviewed for
this article. Only one, Blazer, would agree to be quoted by name.
He said the club had been victimized in the past by bad press and
overzealousness by a small circle of motorcycle gang investigators
who had chased some unfounded rumors about unsavory activities.
Some of the suspicion, he said, stemmed from a member's brief lapse
in judgment seven years ago when he posed for a picture with a
Hell's Angel, who was his cousin. The Wild Pig was later kicked out
of the club because contact with outlaw bikers is banned, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a zero tolerance policy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Wild Pigs do not chase trouble, it has found them on
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   In May, two Wild Pigs from Washington, D.C., who were in New
York for a charity event were wounded, although not seriously, in a
drive-by shooting at 4 a.m. as they walked outside the Red Rock
West, a biker bar in Chelsea. Investigators said it remained
unclear what led the gunman, in a sports utility vehicle, to open
fire.
</P>
<P>
   But the investigators are looking into a report that it might
have stemmed from an altercation several weeks earlier on Long
Island between several Wild Pigs and Hell's Angels after a bike
blessing, an event in which clergy members bless motorcycles to
keep their riders safe. Hours after the blessing, outside a nearby
bar, an argument erupted over whether a Wild Pig had slapped a club
sticker on an Angel's bike, investigators said. There were words,
and by some accounts, punches thrown, but no one ever pressed any
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Blazer said the Wild Pigs who were there that day did not touch
anyone else's bike, which is a mortal sin in the motorcycle world.
A lawyer for the Hell's Angels, Ronald Kuby, said his clients had
no role in the Manhattan shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Pigs and Blue Knights said that in general, they keep their
distance from outlaw bikers and the parties they sponsor, although
they do attend large motorcycle rallies that often draw outlaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do their thing,'' said one former Wild Pig. ``We do ours.
We don't talk to them or shake hands.''
</P>
<P>
   This policy has had breakdowns, however. Three years ago, in
Laconia, N.H., at the town's annual motorcycle rally, a group of
Hell's Angels confronted two Wild Pigs to object that a Wild Pig
had called them ``drug dealers and punks'' in a newspaper article.
The discussion ended peacefully, but police officials have said it
helped set a tone that led to a later brawl in which several Hell's
Angels assaulted uniformed officers patrolling the event.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago at the Laconia rally, there were rumors of
brewing trouble between the Wild Pigs and the Angels, stemming from
the recent incidents in New York, said the town's police chief,
William Baker. A number of Wild Pigs even offered to doff their
colors to avoid an incident, but Baker said he did not think it was
necessary and there were no problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our detractors,'' one Wild Pig acknowledged, ``those
that have decided that anyone on a Harley must be some kind of
lowlife.'' In reality, he said, ``we're just a bunch of cops who
like to ride motorcycles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
