<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: 20 QUESTIONS ON SLOGANS, COMMERCIALS AND CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is time again to ask 20 questions about
advertising, marketing and the media.
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that the Kellogg Co. is sponsoring a promotion with Etrade
Group, centered on a $100 bonus account deposit for consumers who
buy Smart Start cereal, will their next joint venture be a Special
401(K)?
</P>
<P>
   _ How come a newspaper advertisement from FleetBoston Financial
Corp. to promote its status as a sponsor of Major League Baseball,
which reprinted the lyrics of ``Take Me Out to the Ball Game,'' was
careful enough to note that the baseball ``trademarks and
copyrights are used with permission'' but misrendered the brand
name Cracker Jack as ``crackerjacks''?
</P>
<P>
   _ How pleased were the staff members of Talk magazine and its
parents, Hearst and Miramax, to see that a recent subscription
offer in a Sunday newspaper insert appeared under a coupon for Tidy
Cats Disposable Cat Box and Litter in One?
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that Qwest Communications International has merged with U
S West, wouldn't it make for a memorable brand if the combined
company were named West Qwest or Qwest West?
</P>
<P>
   _ How could CBS have promoted the sitcom ``Grapevine'' with
commercials in which the actors said, ``It's like nothing you've
ever seen before'' when it was a remake of a series on the same
network in 1992?
</P>
<P>
   _ Did the Kraft Foods unit of Philip Morris really believe
parents would rush to buy Capri Sun Fruit Punch Drink Mix because a
line at the bottom of print ads reassured them that the product
``won't stain most fabrics and surfaces''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that Chad and Alisha Blondeel of Newaygo, Mich., have
named their son Espen after ESPN, the sports cable television
network, will maternity wards someday soon be filled with babies
named Emteevee, Cy Fi, Pax and Dubbya Bea?
</P>
<P>
   _ And will executives at another cable network try to entice
Espen's parents to nickname him E?
</P>
<P>
   _ Was it some kind of inside joke that in a magazine ad for a
promotion sponsored by Miller Lite beer, depicting a living room
furnished with seats from Milwaukee County Stadium, there was a
book on an end table titled ``The Italian Renaissance''?
</P>
<P>
   _ What could have put copywriters in the morbid mood to create
print ads for the Stouffer's Home Style Entrees line of frozen
foods sold by Nestle and the Campbell's Cheddar Cheese Soup sold by
Campbell Soup Co. that carried the headlines ``Potatoes so good,
you'll think you died and went to heaven'' and ``Quick and easy
quesadillas so delicious, you'll swear you've died and gone to
Acapulco''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that the Army has hired Leo Burnett as its agency, will a
Madison Avenue version of ``Fail-Safe'' include a scene in which
one general frantically shouts to another: ``Call the president!
We've gone to B Com3'' ?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will critics of boy bands cite as proof of their blandness a
decision by Famous Fixins, a company that produces celebrity
licensed products like Britney Spears Bubble Gum, to introduce a
flavored lip balm named after Justin Timberlake of the group 'N
Sync that comes in vanilla?
</P>
<P>
   _ Would The Economist magazine have run an ad poking fun at the
presidential candidacy of Steve Forbes, carrying the headline
``Concise reporting of the naked truth, love handles and all,'' if
Forbes were not president and editor in chief of Forbes magazine,
which competes with The Economist?
</P>
<P>
   _ Now that Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. has introduced a brand called
Kenmore Elite, will the next innovation in appliances be a brand
called Sub-Zero Plebeian?
</P>
<P>
   _ When the Nabisco Biscuit unit of Nabisco Holdings introduced a
character named the Honey Maid Bee in ads for Honey Maid Graham
Crackers, did anyone recall the 1950s character Buffalo Bee that
appeared in ads for two Nabisco cereal brands, Wheat Honeys and
Rice Honeys?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will the introduction by the Franklin Mint of a model of
Bonnie and Clyde's getaway car _ a 1932 Ford V-8 ``fully authorized
by the Ford Motor Co.'' _ mean that collectors will one day be
offered a Ford Bronco model to commemorate the O.J. Simpson
low-speed chase of 1994?
</P>
<P>
   _ Has there been a better example of an ad slogan boomeranging
on the company that made it famous than in a recent ad for
TheStreet.com, citing a recommendation to sell Dial Corp. stock
before the shares fell sharply, that ended: ``Aren't you glad you
read TheStreet.com? Don't you wish everybody did?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Was a recent print ad for the Broadway musical ``Saturday
Night Fever'' rendered in the orange and yellow colors of Tide
detergent because producers hoped the show would clean up at the
box office?
</P>
<P>
   _ Are there any consumers who like the Tic Tac breath mints sold
by Ferrero enough to buy the 1,500 packages that will earn the
points necessary to order a Trek mountain bike offered as part of
the Tic Tac Incredible Stuff promotion?
</P>
<P>
   _ If an advertising columnist asked a posse of beer-drinking
buddies ``Whassup?,'' would they reply, ``You ask a lot of
questions for someone from Brooklyn''? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
