<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-380(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: WILL NUMBER OF DELAYED FLIGHTS CONTINUE TO GROW? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: also sent with `f' code) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   June appears to have been the worst month in domestic airline
history for delayed flights, preliminary statistics from the
Federal Aviation Administration indicate. The big question now is,
will the trend continue as record numbers of passengers crowd onto
planes, making this summer even worse than last for the prospect of
getting there on time?
</P>
<P>
   In general, bad weather accounts for about 70 percent of flight
delays, which are the bane of business travel. This June, a
greater-than-normal number of thunderstorms contributed to the
pile-up of delays, which rose sharply against the expectations of
the airline industry and the FAA. Only a month earlier, both had
been pointing hopefully to some signs that things might be
improving after three years of rapidly deteriorating on-time
performance.
</P>
<P>
   In May, for example, delays dropped 7 percent from May 1999.
That was one month after the FAA and the airlines put into place an
ambitious new strategy called the Spring/Summer 2000 Severe Weather
Plan. This allowed the FAA's main traffic center in Virginia to
function as a kind of super control tower to coordinate operations
hour-by-hour with the airlines and help regional radar centers
integrate traffic throughout the nation's air space.
</P>
<P>
   But here are the latest statistics compiled by the FAA just
before the long Fourth of July holiday: From June 1 to June 28,
airlines reported more than 44,000 delays. That compares with about
38,000 delays in the same 28-day period for June of 1999, when a
total of 39,533 flights were delayed for the whole month. The
previous record number of delays _ 45,162 _ came in July of last
year. Given even a routine number of delays during the last two
days of this June, that record will likely be broken when the final
statistics for the month are compiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do is try and provide factual information,'' said
Steven J. Brown, the acting associate administrator for air traffic
services at the FAA ``We have a collaborative effort with the
airlines in making the daily plan and adjusting it hourly. If we
failed, we should say it. But if in fact the collaboration is
making a difference, which I believe there is plenty of evidence
for, then we should provide the objective measures to talk about
that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Brown said that it was difficult to say whether the plan would
succeed in actually reducing delays this summer over last, since
the June statistics were skewed by an atypical number of
thunderstorms that raked major air corridors in the central and
southwestern United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some airlines have cut a small number of flights from their
schedules this summer, partly in anticipation of delays. United
Airlines, which is grappling with a labor dispute in which some
pilots have refused to work overtime, recently canceled more than
4,500 flights throughout the summer. United has about 2,500 flights
a day. Its pilots union has said that the airline unfairly blames
it for flight cancellations and delays.
</P>
<P>
   Some other airlines might also reduce their summer schedules,
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``United was the first to come out and say for a number of
reasons they felt they needed to rationalize their schedule,'' he
said. ``I know from talking with the airlines over the last week
that others are considering'' dropping some scheduled flights.
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, airlines operate on razor-thin profit
margins and are not likely to deliberately cut revenues
significantly, even if it means a summer of mounting flight delays
and unhappy customers.
</P>
<P>
   Flight delays are a constant headache for business travelers,
who are the airlines' most lucrative source of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Among those delayed in June was Kevin Mitchell, the director of
the Business Travel Coalition, a trade group that lobbies for more
airline competition and lower fares on behalf of businesses. Last
Thursday night, Mitchell cooled his heels in Detroit thanks to a
Northwest Airlines 5:30 p.m. flight that was delayed for hours
before he finally got a 9 p.m. flight on US Airways. The delay
caused him to forego a 7:30 a.m. meeting in Washington the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we've had a lot of bad weather in the last 60 days, but
these delays are a real burden,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For businesses, frequent airline delays mean that valuable
employees are ``sitting around for hours unproductive,'' he said,
adding that businesses are also beginning to asses the impact of
delays on employee morale.
</P>
<P>
   A delay is defined by the FAA as a flight that arrives at the
gate more than 15 minutes behind schedule. But average delay times
now exceed an hour, according to industry statistics.
</P>
<P>
   As customers fume, the airline industry has sought to shift much
of the blame to the FAA, which the industry says has been slow in
replacing inadequate technology even as air travel demand has grown
steadily. This year, the FAA estimates, airlines will carry about
640 million passengers in the United States, compared with about
460 million in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But the airlines themselves have been accused of exaggerating
the role of weather in the delay crisis. And frequent fliers know
that on some flights, some airlines have begun adding minutes to
the posted flying times to keep delay statistics in check. As a
result, on days when the airspace is humming efficiently, some
flights arrive well ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Messing around with the schedules, padding them a bit to help
improve on-time arrivals, is pretty common in the industry,''
Mitchell said. ``You'll sometimes hear the captain announcing that
we're going to arrive, say 45 minutes early because there's a
strong breeze behind us _ which flies in the face of reason.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the FAA's Brown said he believed that the new system
was working and that delays could begin to drop this summer ``if by
some miracle the weather turns more favorable during July and
August.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new centralized system, federal air traffic employees
