<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-U.S.-MERGERS-N     07-04 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-U.S.-MERGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS SEE ACQUISITIONS IN U.S. AS FASTEST ROUTE TO
TRANSFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The conventional wisdom has been that European
companies, emboldened by a common currency and economic growth at
home, would use Wall Street style tactics in cross-border deals
unifying the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   But not following the script, European companies have
increasingly set their sights on acquisition targets in the United
States first.
</P>
<P>
   From Vivendi's recent deal to acquire Seagram to Unilever's
agreement to purchase Bestfoods to Terra Network's buyout of Lycos,
Europe is increasingly looking across the pond before it looks
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   And with Deutsche Telekom of Germany considering a bid for
Sprint, trans-Atlantic deal-making seems unlikely to stop anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``European companies are in a pretty mad scramble to be
global,'' said Donald Meltzer, co-head of global mergers and
acquisitions at Credit Suisse First Boston in London. ``You go
where you can do the deals to achieve a critical mass. And
acquiring control is still easier in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, European companies have completed a handful of
cross-border deals, including the largest takeover in corporate
history, Vodafone Airtouch's $183 billion acquisition of
Mannesmann. That was supposed to pave the way for even more such
takeovers, but now investment bankers are less sure about the
potential for big cross-border European deals than they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the past year it became apparent that many of the
political and cultural roadblocks that were supposed to have
disappeared were still up. Spain's largest telephone company,
Telefonica, tried to buy the Dutch telephone operator Royal KPN in
May, but was foiled by the Spanish government, which owns a
controlling share in Telefonica and blocked the deal over political
concerns. A privately proposed merger between Telefonica and
British Telecommunications also was thwarted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In certain sectors _ telecommunications, banking, media _
there is still going to be nationalistic tendencies,'' said Daniel
Dickinson, co-head of global mergers and acquisitions for Merrill
Lynch in London.
</P>
<P>
   Even intra-country deals have been stymied, exemplified in
Germany by Dresdner Bank's recently failed merger with Deutsche
Bank, and in Norway by the foiled marriage of two phone companies,
Telenor and Telia.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some investment bankers are not too concerned about the
problems that have hung up European deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Anglo Saxon tactics can be applied in Europe,'' said
Simon Robey, co-head of global mergers and acquisitions at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter in London. Nonetheless, he added, ``It's pretty
natural to expect we'll see trans-Atlantic activity in all the big
sectors.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have pointed out that the market for trans-Atlantic deals
has expanded because investors in the United States are now more
receptive to foreign acquirers. One reason is that the stocks of
many European acquirers are relatively high, enabling them to pay
big premiums for American takeover targets. And European companies
that want to increase their size quickly are inclined to go after
American companies, which are usually much bigger, before looking
at their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game at the moment is to do something strategically
transforming,'' Robey said.
</P>
<P>
   While trans-Atlantic mergers and acquisitions have increased
recently, overall deal-making activity has actually slowed in the
last three months, according to statistics released Tuesday by
Thomson Financial, which tracks mergers and acquisitions. The
global market for deals in the April-June quarter fell by 32
percent to $760 billion following a record-breaking first quarter
of $1.121 trillion. Most of the decline can be attributed to
activity from deals in the United States, which fell to $324
billion from $568 billion. European activity remained relatively
flat at $298 billion, compared with $303 billion in the earlier
quarter. Nonetheless, global activity for the first half of the
year surpassed previous results with a total of $1.882 trillion in
deals.
</P>
<P>
   As Wall Street banks jockey to rake in the most deals, the race
is tight, with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Goldman Sachs in a
virtual tie at the top. Based on completed deals so far this year,
Goldman is the leader, followed by Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch,
Credit Suisse First Boston, J.P. Morgan and UBS Warburg. But if the
measure is based on deals announced so far this year, Morgan
Stanley leads, followed by Goldman, Salomon Smith Barney, Merrill,
and Credit Suisse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
