<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SIEBEL-BOSS-NYT &LR;      07-04 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIEBEL-BOSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM AND SKYDIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: THOMAS M. SIEBEL is chairman and chief executive officer of
Siebel Systems Inc., a maker of e-business applications software;
this was written with GEOFFREY BREWER.) 
 By THOMAS M. SIEBEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I grew up in a modest home in Wilmette, Ill., a suburb of
Chicago. My first job was painting houses in the Chicago area
during summers in high school and college. I used to paint about
three houses a summer with a team of two or three other guys. Some
summers, I also cut logs for people. In doing those jobs, I learned
that you had to set expectations, in terms of quality and
timeliness, at a high level, then exceed that level.
</P>
<P>
   This works in the software business, too.
</P>
<P>
   I've had other outdoor jobs. After I graduated from the
University of Illinois in 1975, I did ranch work outside of
Bellevue, Idaho. I moved cows, baled hay, irrigated. This was a
great experience, but it was really hard work.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest role model I had growing up was my father, who was
an attorney. He was a smart guy and worked really hard. I'd see him
working at the dining room table at 2 a.m. or 3 a.m. in the
morning, even on a Saturday and Sunday. One thing he taught me was
to stay out of debt. He wouldn't even borrow money for a car.
</P>
<P>
   When I started this company in July 1993, I didn't get any money
from venture capitalists. Our office space was 11 cents a square
foot in East Palo Alto, Calif. Even though our company is in
Silicon Valley, my sensibilities are essentially Midwestern.
</P>
<P>
   When customers come to visit us from Munich, Germany, or Paris,
I think people should wear coats and ties when they meet with them,
not polo shirts and jeans. It's never a casual day when you meet
with someone who is spending millions of dollars with you.
</P>
<P>
   I also never want this company to be one where employees boast
of all the Ferraris we have parked in our lot, or one that values
raising venture-capital money over profits. Serving customers
should be a humbling experience.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not, however, risk-averse. During and after college, I used
to go sky diving, and probably did it about 20 times. It's tough to
put yourself out there by the door of a plane, looking down from
10,000 feet. Every fiber of your being is telling you not to do it.
You climb out on a little metal step, hold on to the wing and let
go. At that point, you start dropping pretty fast. The thing is,
once you let go, it's not as exhilarating as you think. You fall
down a little while and pull the chute. It's not that big of a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   I guess that's the way I feel about taking business risks: Don't
dwell on decisions. Just make them and go.
</P>
<P>
   It was risky joining Oracle Corp., which I did in 1984. The safe
thing would have been to go to IBM. Oracle was a small company then
with untested management, and it wasn't well-financed. Its software
product was speculative. But they have proven to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this company was a risk. All of the experts said we
wouldn't succeed with our sales-automation software, that it was a
crummy market and it would be impossible to build a good product.
But we took the plunge. I just generally have an optimistic
attitude, and I think optimism is self-fulfilling. My parents had a
very positive view of the world, and I guess that rubbed off on me.
</P>
<P>
   One of my philosophies is, in any meeting, however fragmentary
the information we have, we will make a decision before the meeting
is over. We won't wring our hands. I've made a lot of bad decisions
and some good ones. Sixty percent of the time I turn out to be
right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-04 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE HAVE YOU GONE, DAVID CONE?
</HEADLINE>
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Less than a year ago on the Yankee Stadium mound,
David Cone, with his pitching hand and his glove hugging his Yankee
cap in disbelief, watched a pop-up come down, down, down into third
baseman Scott Brosius' glove for the final out of his perfect game.
Then he collapsed in celebration.
</P>
<P>
   His body language is different now. His disbelief is the same.
</P>
<P>
   After snatching Oriole left fielder B.J. Surhoff's one-hopper to
lead off the sixth on Tuesday, Cone floated the ball high and wide
to first baseman Jorge Posada, whose lunge at the bag was too late.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound, the 37-year-old right-hander looked away, shaking
his head in disbelief at his error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember ever doing that,'' he said later. ``It was
just an easy toss to first base.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, after he watched second baseman Mark Lewis'
two-out, three-run homer disappear beyond the right-center-field
fence for a sudden 7-2 lead in an eventual 7-6 loss, Cone stood
like a statue, his back to home plate, his head down, his hands on
his hips in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``First-pitch slider,'' he said, ``for a three-run homer.''
</P>
<P>
   By, of all people, the Orioles' ninth-place batter, who had not
had a home run all season. And now, after Joe Torre arrived at the
mound to change pitchers, Cone jogged to the dugout, trying to
ignore the mixture of realistic boos for his 1-7 record and
sympathetic cheers for old-times' sake when he was the Yankees'
ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deserved it and I don't blame them,'' he said of the most
boos he has ever heard as a Yankee. ``I kept putting us in a hole.
We had a nice comeback, but I put us in too big a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to the second half of the season, it's understandable to
wonder if Cone will be able to help the Yankees dig themselves out
of the hole that jeopardizes another first-place finish in the
American League East, if not a wild-card berth in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He has pitched so poorly that it's understandable to wonder if,
despite a career 181-109 record in his 15th major league season, he
will ever again be the dependable big-game pitcher that the Yankees
relied on so often in the playoffs and the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   He insists his arm is sound, which makes it even more
understandable to wonder if he is through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't keep the ball in the ballpark,'' he said. ``I only
gave up six hits, but four were home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone has allowed 17 homers this season, including four Tuesday
that were a one-game high for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried some things,'' he said, alluding to remedies for
his poor record. ``I've moved from the right side of the rubber to
the left; I've tried different mechanics. I feel good while I'm
doing it, but I've just got to keep the ball in the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   His earned run average is a shabby 6.40. He has not won in his
last 11 starts, the longest streak without a victory of his career.
His only victory this season occurred April 28, when he pitched
seven innings in a 6-0 victory over the now first-place Toronto
Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to work on your confidence when you haven't won
since April,'' Torre said. ``He's got to find a way to win a
game.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Yankees have to find a way to win more games. Over the
last several weeks, their record is 18-28 _ not exactly
cost-efficient for baseball's first $100 million payroll. With a
$12 million one-year contract, Cone has also been anything but
cost-efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm holding the club back,'' Cone said. ``I still
believe I can turn it around, but my numbers are ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers indeed are ugly. Cone is 5-13 over the last 12
months (including his 6-0 perfect game last July 18 against the
Montreal Expos). He has a shaky hits-to-innings ratio: 108 in 90.1.
He has a weak walks-to-strikeouts ratio: 43 to 64.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stuff and his velocity numbers have been consistent with
last year, but his total command isn't there,'' Torre said. ``He's
having trouble locating the slider. I don't know what the answer
is, but I'm not about to give up on him helping this team.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees are to start winning, David Cone needs to start
winning, beginning Sunday night when the Yankees play the Mets at
Shea Stadium. To know how he is doing, you don't need to watch the
scoreboard. Just watch his body language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
