<HEADER>
A2974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN--WIMBLEDON-HNS &LR;      07-04 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN--WIMBLEDON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Venus aligns with Serena at Wimbledon
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ Before Tuesday's matches, Richard Williams
predicted both his daughters would advance to the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he wasn't going out on too big a limb, seeing as how
both sisters had swept through their portions of the draw, neither
dropping a set or really being tested.
</P>
<P>
   But with No. 1 and top seed Martina Hingis, a former Wimbledon
champion, standing in Venus Williams' way, nothing was assured.
</P>
<P>
   It's assured now. There will be one Williams sister in the
Wimbledon final.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams, seeded fifth, needed 2 hours and 5 minutes to
knock off Hingis 6-3, 4-6, 6-4. Her sister Serena, the eighth seed,
was able to watch much of her match after polishing off her
quarterfinal opponent, Lisa Raymond, in a mere 40 minutes, 6-3,
6-0.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters will face one another in a Thursday semifinal.
Defending champion and second seed Lindsay Davenport escaped a
challenge from sixth seed Monica Seles, needing three sets for a
6-7 (4), 6-4, 6-0 victory. Davenport, who drilled 14 aces and had
20 backhand winners in that quarterfinal match, will face unseeded
Jelena Dokic, a 6-3, 6-2 winner over Magui Serna in the other
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know at least one of us will be there in the next round,''
said Serena, insisting there is no sibling rivalry. ``It would have
been more exciting as a final; unfortunately, I was not able to be
in the other half of the draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus and Hingis put on one of the best shows women's tennis has
seen in a long time, using power and finesse to fight for every
point. Few games were settled quickly, most going to several deuces
before a slugger emerged.
</P>
<P>
   After losing her serve more than she won it in the third set,
Venus served out the final game at love, drilling an ace out wide
on match point. She leaped in celebration even before the ball
touched Hingis' side of the court, then searched out her father and
sister in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going in, I felt confident. I felt I was playing well,'' Venus
said. ``Naturally, if I had won the match 6-2, 6-2 it would have
been different. I had been running. I had some tough service games,
some tough return games. So when I hit that ace, it was a great way
to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   From the third game of the second set through the fifth of the
third, every server faced at least one break point. Ten of those 14
games did result in service breaks, including six consecutive from
the final game of the second set through the fifth game of the
third.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis faced 20 break points in all, seven of those being
successfully converted by Venus. Hingis broke Venus six times on 16
break point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always had great matches playing each other,'' Hingis said.
``Sometimes I won, sometimes she did. Especially when it was
important _ at the Grand Slams _ I was able to pull it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Venus played the riskier game, making more errors but drilling
50 winners, those being almost equally divided between her
forehand, backhand and volleys. Hingis played a cleaner game but
hit only 19 winners, most of those coming from advances to the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good win for me because I've never advanced past the
quarterfinals,'' Venus said. ``The two times I was in the quarters,
I had some tough, heartbreaking matches. Today, I was ready to pull
this one out because I had a bad history.''
</P>
<P>
   Both women had to stretch their legs to counter cramping and
looked winded in the final set after running each other all over
the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was probably a little bit more hungry,'' Hingis said. ``We
both wanted to win very much. She was just a tiny bit better
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister, meanwhile, has been much better every day. Serena
has been so dominating, she has dropped only 13 games in five
matches. But Venus will be the first seeded player she has faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling very excited,'' Serena said. ``Very happy. I feel
like I can make anything happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena had 15 unreturned serves and nine aces. She never faced a
break point. She smashed 37 winners. Raymond had only one winner.
</P>
<P>
   The reigning U.S. Open winner said she's playing better than
when she won that Grand Slam last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm playing much better here than I was in the U.S.
Open, or any other tournament I've played in my life,'' said
Serena, calling Tuesday's match one of the best of her career.
</P>
<P>
   Serena beat her sister in their last meeting, that one coming at
last year's Grand Slam Cup. But Venus holds a 3-1 edge and is still
missing that initial Grand Slam trophy to start building a
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both had dreams. She had a dream of winning the U.S.
Open,'' Venus said. ``I had a dream of winning Wimbledon.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena's dream has come true. Thursday, Venus will discover if
she still has a chance of seeing hers realized as well.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
