u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     07-04 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS YANKEES WAIT, THE LOSSES PILE UP 
</HEADLINE>
 (With ANDERSON-COLUMN) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees keep waiting for the streak, the burst of
victories that will remind them how good they were and might be
again. Orlando Hernandez won Saturday, Roger Clemens won Sunday and
many of the Yankees probably started thinking about riding a string
of victories into next week's All-Star Game break.
</P>
<P>
   The streak was relayed to David Cone on Tuesday and he dropped
it, right in the middle of Yankee Stadium, surrendering four homers
in five and two-thirds innings to the aging Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees rallied in the ninth, but never overcame Cone's
deficit, losing by 7-6. And now the Yankees are stationary again,
bogged in mediocrity, their record 40-37, their position a game and
a half out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Losing a game to the Mets last month was annoying to the
Yankees. Dropping a couple to Cleveland might be frustrating.
Tuesday's loss was devastating, ``a killer,'' Cone called it, and
he was right.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had won back-to-back games to finish a long 6-7 road
trip; they were home to play a second-division team _ a club the
Yankees need to dominate _ and Cone never gave them a chance. He is
1-7, more than two months removed from his last victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing anything to help the team,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees keep waiting for that winning streak, and the
starting pitching keeps undermining them. Sometimes the saboteur
has been Cone, sometimes Clemens or Andy Pettitte, sometimes it has
been injuries. But it's always the starting pitching. The Yankees
have not had three consecutive quality starts (six or more innings,
three runs or less) since the middle of May.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee starters have reached the seventh inning in only 15
of the team's last 40 games, which goes a long way toward
explaining why they have not won more than two consecutive games
since the last time Baltimore was in town; on May 6, they collected
the fourth and final victory in a winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   They needed this game, and they had an early lead, scoring twice
in the bottom of the first after the Orioles had scored a run in
the top of the first. But Cone was essentially without ammunition.
He has had days this season when he wielded a decent fastball or an
effective slider, but Cone had neither Tuesday; his fastball was
benign and his slider was flat and lifeless. He was relying on
guile and guts.
</P>
<P>
   If this had been a bad Western, he would have thrown his pistol
at the Orioles. ``His stuff has been consistent,'' Yankees Manager
Joe Torre said. ``He just has trouble with his total command.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone's approach in pitching to the second batter of the game,
Mike Bordick, revealed much about his stuff. He threw fastballs to
get ahead in the count no balls and two strikes, Bordick fouling
off two pitches. Cone has dominated Bordick over the years, holding
him to nine hits in 42 at-bats, with nine strikeouts. When he got
ahead in the count in past seasons, he would sweep sliders near the
outside corner, or lower his arm angle and tease Bordick into
chasing a high fastball.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone did not choose to throw sliders to Bordick in the first
inning Tuesday, perhaps because his slider hasn't been that good.
He rarely lowers his arm angle this season. Cone tried finishing
off Bordick with fastballs, instead, thrown over the top. He tried
jamming Bordick, and Bordick pulled a home run down the left-field
line.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Turner, Cone's catcher, said later that he thought Cone
had pitched better than the results indicated, that it was only a
matter of time before Cone rebounded. The slider, he acknowledged,
``was just kind of rolling; it didn't have that much bite.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner added: ``He's going to have to spot his fastball because
it doesn't have the velocity it used to have. If he doesn't, he's
going to get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Baines opened the second inning by slamming a low
split-fingered fastball into the seats. Charles Johnson, the next
batter, almost never draws walks, but Cone walked him on four
pitches. Two batters later, Cone tried to get ahead on the count
with Brady Anderson, tried sneaking a first-pitch fastball past
him, and Anderson bashed the pitch into the seats. The Orioles had
three more runs and led, 4-2. An absolute killer.
</P>
<P>
   Cone changed speeds better in the third, fourth and fifth
innings, pitching mostly outside, some of his sliders a little
sharper. But there was always the sense that he was just hanging
on, one mistake away from a major crisis.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Surhoff smashed a one-hopper to the mound leading off the
sixth and Cone reacted well, gloving the ball, before stepping
toward first base and throwing _ high. Jorge Posada, normally the
Yankees' catcher, was playing first, and he had to leave the bag
and leap. By the time he stretched a foot to touch first, Surhoff
was across the bag. Cone dropped his chin, disgusted.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff took second on a grounder, and the Yankees intentionally
walked Baines, who has always hit well against Cone. Bernie
Williams made a diving catch on a looper to center by Johnson, and
it looked as if Cone would get through the inning, still holding
Baltimore to four runs.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lewis, a part-time player who had not hit a home run this
season, strolled to the plate. Lewis decided that if Cone threw a
slider, he was going to swing at it. Cone did throw a slider, a
lifeless slider. Lewis hammered it to right-center field, over the
wall. The home run muted the crowd of 44,447 for a few seconds. But
the fans were revived by Cone's departure, booing him purposefully.
</P>
<P>
   Down by 7-2, the Yankees scored one run in the eighth, three in
the ninth. But with Derek Jeter at second base and two out, Paul
O'Neill grounded out and the Yankees fell short by one run, a
discouraging defeat, a killer loss. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
