<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S PRESIDENT PARRIES CRITICISM WITH A RAPIER TONGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The biographer of Abdurrahman Wahid,
Indonesia's unpredictable president, thinks he has him figured out:
He is the drunken swordsman in the martial arts movie who disarms
his enemies with his seeming foolishness, then cuts them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great master who looks like a complete walkover,'' said
the biographer, Greg Barton, an Australian political scientist.
``Suddenly there's a whirl of limbs and then everyone is lying on
the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The swords are out again this week as the president and his many
opponents start slicing the air in advance of a special
parliamentary session next month.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are talking about impeachment, although the national
assembly does not technically have that power. At the least, it
will be a grandstand for the criticism that has dogged Wahid since
his improbable election last October.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody saw it coming when Wahid (who in fact is not a drinker)
announced that the police would investigate up to 10 members of
Parliament on suspicion of fomenting violence and unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Then came his now-familiar pattern of verbal feints and jabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one big fish,'' he said on Saturday, ``but we haven't
found the supporting evidence yet. Once we catch him it will all be
over.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, according to a local newspaper, he said: ``I have
ordered the police to arrest and interrogate those suspected of
creating or being involved in riots. With or without evidence they
have to be captured.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday his Cabinet secretary, Marsilam Simanjuntak, said the
president had signed an order for the investigation of the
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, with newspaper headlines blurting ``Confusion Reigns,''
the president said: ``I've never accused the legislators of being
guilty. My other statement was twisted for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Jakarta is abuzz with rumors and political scurrying as
people name names, point fingers and nudge the points of their
knives into one another's backs.
</P>
<P>
   Two prominent legislators, Ginandjar Kartasasmita and Fuad
Bawazier _ once ministers in the Cabinet of former President
Suharto _ found themselves angrily denying that they were on
Wahid's list.
</P>
<P>
   Bawazier did not seem to help his case much when he denied a
suggestion that he was financing armed groups by saying: ``The
accusations are baseless. It is normal that I give donations to the
needy.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be a diverting spectacle, but the stakes are high.
Indonesia is _ as the pilots of jetliners say _ passing through a
period of turbulence after the ouster of Suharto two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As it does so, it sometimes seems that Wahid is alone at the
controls. And there are disconcerting moments when he seems,
willfully, to be steering into the thunderheads.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who say Wahid is his own worst enemy,
undermining Indonesia's stability and economic recovery by his
impulsiveness and his tendency to cry wolf. Although economic
analysts insist that in real terms the economy is on an upturn, the
confidence of investors has continued to sink.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the political noise, the currency, the rupiah, fell to
below 9,000 to the dollar Tuesday, its lowest point in 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   The catch-phrase in Jakarta now is: ``The best thing the
president could do for the economy is to keep his mouth shut for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's defenders say that shutting his mouth would in effect be
laying down his weapons. With few political cards to play, they
say, the president is lucky that he is an expert bluffer.
</P>
<P>
   The back-room coalition he yanked together last October to win
the presidency has mostly turned against him, ready to devour him
when he presents his state of the nation address to the assembly
next month.
</P>
<P>
   And he is operating without much of a functioning bureaucracy,
which was eviscerated by Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Where Suharto kept his opponents at bay by force of arms, Wahid
must operate by the force of his personality. That is how he
undercut his recalcitrant military chief, Gen. Wiranto, in
February, pummeling him with a barrage of intemperate remarks and
finally dismissing him.
</P>
<P>
   The newly empowered legislature has roared to life as what one
analyst called a ``crocodile pit'' of political agendas. The
legislators fired the first shot last Friday when they voted to
call in the president later this month _ ahead of the assembly _ to
explain his firing of two Cabinet ministers in April. Barton,
Wahid's biographer, said the president had already ``done his
deals'' in advance of the assembly, well aware that few of his
critics are prepared to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gus Dur has done his political homework,'' said Barton, using
the president's nickname. ``In this, he is brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the president is faced with a surge of violent
unrest around the country.
</P>
<P>
   There is a religious war in the far eastern Maluku islands,
where more than 2,500 Christians and Muslims have been killed in
the last 18 months. There has been communal fighting on the islands
of Sulawesi, Bali and Lombok. There have been bomb blasts at
mosques and churches. And there are insurgencies in the provinces
of Aceh and Irian Jaya that appear to be receiving outside aid.
</P>
<P>
   The unseen hands behind them may include military plotters,
local power blocs, ambitious politicians and people from the former
government.
</P>
<P>
   Their message, said Barton, is: ```Back off or we'll make
problems.' It's a sort of hostage situation; it doesn't take a lot
of money to set things off. From others, it's, `Let's see what a
weak leader he is.' There are all sorts of crazies, all sorts of
people trying their thing, trying to get him to take them
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a lot for one man to handle. And, according to Barton, it
is a battle the president relishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feint to the left, hit to the right: Your opponent never knows
where you're coming from,'' Barton said. ``It's strongly his style,
like a kung fu expert. He doesn't always land on his feet, but
don't underestimate him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT     07-04 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LEFT-HANDED JONES FAILS HIS FIRST TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ On Sunday night, facing the Yankees at Shea Stadium on
national television in their final game before the All-Star Game
break, the Mets are scheduled to start the left-hander Bobby M.
Jones. Another option would be to bring back Mike Hampton on three
days' rest.
</P>
<P>
   After Jones failed to hold a five-run lead Tuesday and lost to
the Florida Marlins, 9-8, Mets manager Bobby Valentine was asked if
Jones would still pitch that showcase game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, probably,'' Valentine said. ``He's in line to, let's put
it that way. We'll just see how the whole thing shakes out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a lukewarm endorsement, and it was understandable. Making
his first Mets start in place of the injured Rick Reed, Jones'
command escaped him in the fourth inning. In the fifth, he faced
four batters and retired none, then watched as the Marlins took the
lead on a double steal that really was not.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored three runs after falling behind by 9-5, and with
one on and one out in the ninth, Mike Piazza came off the bench to
pinch hit. Piazza was hit on the left elbow by the backswing of
Preston Wilson on Monday, and he did not start because of soreness.
X-rays on the elbow showed that nothing was broken, and when Piazza
began feeling better Tuesday as the game went on, he volunteered to
pinch hit.
</P>
<P>
   With Jay Payton on first, Piazza hit a grounder to third and
Payton beat the throw to second. Though Piazza reached first base
safely, the fielder's choice ended his hitting streak at 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   Worse for the Mets, Antonio Alfonseca then struck out Todd Pratt
and Melvin Mora to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jones worked four-plus innings, and gave up seven runs on six
hits and three walks. He was starting for the first time since June
10, after pitching only one inning during an eight-game stint with
the Mets in mid-June and an inning and a third in a subsequent
relief appearance for Triple-A Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Jones worked two bullpen sessions in that time, but there is no
substitute for game experience. His fastball was not down as often
as he wanted it to be, he said, and his slider was inconsistent.
Jones knows the Mets demand better from him, no matter how little
he has worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, personally, it's a direct reflection of only pitching
two innings in 20 days,'' Jones said. ``But I don't have room to
make mistake after mistake. This is a team that's very good with a
chance to go a long way. That's not what they're looking for;
they're looking for a pitcher to get people out. I think I'm that
person, but, hey, I have to show it. I can't just tell them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Bill Pulsipher arrived at spring training as the
favorites to land the fifth starter's spot, but Glendon Rusch
passed them both and won the job. Pulsipher, who was traded to
Arizona in June, had two starts in May for the Mets and was roughed
up, faltering in the fourth inning both times.
</P>
<P>
   Jones followed the same pattern. He retired eight of the first
nine Marlins hitters Tuesday, but the more of Jones the Marlins
saw, the better they did. Protecting a 5-0 lead in the fourth,
Jones issued a pair of two-out walks and was visited on the mound
by the pitching coach, Dave Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   The next hitter was Alex Gonzalez, batting .174, and Jones fell
behind, 2-0. His next pitch was a high fastball _ ``He laid one in
there,'' Valentine said _ and Gonzalez belted it deep into the
left-field seats for a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some pitches that I thought were strikes got called balls
today,'' said Pratt, the catcher in place of Piazza, ``and any time
the count turns into 1-0 instead of 0-1, or 2-1 instead of 1-2, it
doesn't matter who's pitching, the hitter's more confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Things got worse for Jones in the fifth. The pinch-hitter Mark
Smith drew a leadoff walk and Luis Castillo singled. Mark Kotsay
ripped an opposite-field double to the warning track in left,
scoring two runs to tie the score, 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Floyd then dribbled a grounder about 50 feet toward third
base, and it went for an infield single, ending Jones' day.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Mahomes entered, and with runners at first and third, Floyd
broke for second on the first pitch. Pratt's throw bounced off the
infield grass and deflected off Floyd's helmet. Mora, the
shortstop, raced over to grab the ball, but he could not get it
from his glove as Kotsay scampered home with the go-ahead steal of
home.
</P>
<P>
   The play was ruled a double steal, even though Kotsay did not go
until the throw bounced and struck Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The triple-clutch _ we had him easy,'' Pratt said. ``The guy
didn't break until Melvin had the ball. But that isn't to blame.
I'm supposed to be the leader on defense, and I didn't execute
well. Our offense gave us enough to win, and the defense didn't
play up to our capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   After Mahomes walked Wilson, a one-out intentional walk to
Derrek Lee loaded the bases. Gonzalez struck out, and Mike Redmond
grounded a ball up the middle, giving the Mets a chance to escape
the inning with minimal damage.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mora ranged to his left, he bobbled the ball, and his
error sent Floyd home to give Florida a 7-5 lead. Smith singled in
two more to increase the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets got closer on a two-run homer in the sixth by Todd
Zeile, who did not start because of a stiff neck, and a bases-empty
shot by Edgardo Alfonzo in the ninth, but the Marlins prevailed,
winning their fifth game in a row. The Mets have lost six of 11
games to Florida this year, and they will be glad to be done with
the upstart Marlins after Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to play havoc with people who have to play them
the rest of the year,'' Valentine said. He did not note that the
first-place Atlanta Braves have five games left with the Marlins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
