<HEADLINE>
PHILIPPOUSSIS READY TO TAKE ON AGASSI 
</HEADLINE>
   (With TEN-WIMBLEDON)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ There is still a Ferrari in the garage, but
it is a lonely set of wheels since Mark Philippoussis began
discarding the artificial fillers in a life once scant on career
substance.
</P>
<P>
   He would spent his days wave running on Miami Beach, his nights
surfing for fun and only his spare moments applying his
considerable talents to tennis. The serve, the strokes, the range.
He had all the skills, but fell short in work ethic. He has put a
``For Sale'' sign on his bachelor pad in south Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Philippoussis is following the lead of his opponent
Wednesday in a quarterfinal at Wimbledon. While Pete Sampras tries
to fend off the hot Jan-Michael Gambill in one highlighted
quarterfinal match, Philippoussis will look across the court and
find Andre Agassi in another one.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Agassi has searched for deep meaning;
Philippoussis is starting the same journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had everything that you could possibly have,''
Philippoussis said. ``Now I'm a little sick of it, which is good.
It's a phase I went through. I got it out of my system. Obviously I
still like the fast cars, but I've sold almost all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miami was exciting for me as a 22-year-old when I first moved
there. Of course, I mean, the night life and the atmosphere is
incredible. But I'm actually moving. I'm going to go back to
Australia. I want to be with my family and friends. Start
concentrating.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been focused throughout a laborious but uplifting run
through Wimbledon, which included a five-hour victory in the third
round and another five-set victory in the fourth. Agassi is much
fresher.
</P>
<P>
   Although Todd Martin pushed Agassi to a fifth set in the second
round, he has not dropped a set since. But he is wary of
Philippoussis, who has served 77 aces in his last two matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to know what it feels like to be Mark
Philippoussis and hit a 128-mile-per-hour serve down a set point,''
Agassi said. ``I'd like to know what that feels like. But I like
the fact that my dynamics of play matches up pretty well against
baseliners and big power hitters. I think it brings a lot of
elements that the game of tennis has to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why his quarterfinal is so intriguing. If Philippoussis
is the biggest server in the game right now, Agassi is the best at
returning the blasts. Although Agassi has won three of the four
previous matches against Philippoussis, there is a notable change
in the Australian's desire.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this metamorphosis can be credited to Boris Becker, who
recently told Philippoussis that he hadn't reached 40 percent of
his potential. Mostly, Philippoussis has been influenced by his
coach, Mike DePalmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been talking, and obviously we talk every day,''
Philippoussis, who will be 24 in November, said of his coach. ``He
sits me down just to tell me what he thinks I need to do. We've
definitely talked about that. Pretty much what he said is: `If you
want to be a champion, you have to be a champion 24 hours a day.
You've got to live like a champion, think like a champion, talk
like a champion in order to become one.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
