<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR LEAGUES ANNOUNCE STARTERS FOR ALL-STAR GAME
</HEADLINE>
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It has become a rite of summer for Mike Piazza. The
results of the All-Star balloting are announced, and Piazza has
more votes than any other National League catcher. The fans have
voted him to the All-Star team seven years in a row, and this year
made him the league's leading vote-getter.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's teammate Edgardo Alfonzo was leading in the balloting
at second base on Friday, poised to be an All-Star for the first
time. Alfonzo might still make it, but he will have to do so as a
reserve. The San Francisco Giants' Jeff Kent, a former Met, surged
ahead of Alfonzo and Houston's Craig Biggio and will be the
starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want Fonzie to be recognized,'' Piazza said of his
teammate, ``but he's such a well-kept secret for us in so many
ways. He's just got a really cool vibe going there. But he deserves
every bit of recognition that he has coming _ and he's got a lot
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent, who is leading the league in runs batted in with 80,
received 1,018,430 votes, about 55,000 more than Biggio and 145,000
more than Alfonzo. He is one of four players who were voted to the
team for the first time this year, joining American League
outfielders Bernie Williams of the Yankees and Jermaine Dye of
Kansas City, and first baseman Jason Giambi of Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who is batting .331 with 18 homers and 77 RBIs, was
selected as an All-Star reserve in each of the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a good choice,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre
said. ``It was great to have Griffey go to the other league and
Bernie lead all outfielders in votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was the leading vote-getter among AL outfielders, a
distinction that had usually been Ken Griffey Jr.'s before his
trade from Seattle to Cincinnati before the season.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey had been the leading vote-getter in the American League
each of the last four seasons, and five times overall. Griffey
started off slowly this season, but he batted over .300 in June and
is among the National League leaders with 26 home runs. He finished
first in the balloting among NL outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez led all major leaguers with
2,808,456 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza led National Leaguer players with 2,780,452 votes, over 2
million more than Pittsburgh catcher Jason Kendall, the runner-up.
It was the third time in his career _ and first time as a Met _
that Piazza has been the leading NL vote-getter. ``It never gets
old,'' Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo, who is batting .333 with 13 homers and 57 RBIs, was
second to Biggio when in-stadium balloting ended early last week,
but received a boost from online voters. That proved to Alfonzo
that more fans were noticing him, and that is a great feeling, he
said. But he knew Kent could pull ahead; he said he sees Kent's
highlights on television all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it was real close and I'm kind of a little
disappointed, but I think I did everything,'' Alfonzo said. ``I
just put everything all together. There's a lot of competition at
second base. We'll see what's going to happen next.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves manager Bobby Cox, who must choose from a cluster
of talented second basemen including Florida's Luis Castillo and
Montreal's Jose Vidro, has said that he would consider selecting
Alfonzo as a backup at another position, like third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could play anywhere,'' Alfonzo said. ``If he wants me to
play third base, second base, shortstop, catcher, whatever. I'll be
prepared for it, no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' Derek Jeter finished second to Seattle's Alex
Rodriguez, his good friend, after being the runner-up to Boston's
Nomar Garciaparra last year. Torre selects the American League
reserves, and Jeter is one of several Yankees likely to be named to
the team. The closer Mariano Rivera and catcher Jorge Posada are
also strong candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Torre also could select Toronto's David Wells as the starting
pitcher for the game, which will be played at Turner Field in
Atlanta next Tuesday. Wells, who sometimes clashed with Torre when
he pitched for the Yankees from 1997-98, is 14-2 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Pedro Martinez is having the best season among AL
starters, but is on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Mets starter Al Leiter is 10-1 with a 3.04 earned run average
and will almost certainly be selected.
</P>
<P>
   The closer Armando Benitez, who is third in the National League
with 18 saves and who has a 1.19 ERA since May 6, also has a chance
to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   The voting for National League second baseman was not the
closest at any position.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's Manny Ramirez won the third and final outfield spot
by fewer than 30,000 votes over Boston's Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Ivan and Alex Rodriguez, Giambi, Williams, Dye and
Ramirez as American League starters are second baseman Roberto
Alomar of Cleveland and third baseman Cal Ripken of Baltimore.
Ripken is an 18-time All-Star who has been elected to the team
every year since 1984, except in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Piazza, Kent and Griffey, National League
starters include first baseman Mark McGwire of St. Louis, third
baseman Chipper Jones of Atlanta, shortstop Barry Larkin of
Cincinnati and outfielders Barry Bonds of San Francisco and Sammy
Sosa of the Chicago Cubs.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
