<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S PRESIDENT-ELECT FOX OUTLINES AMBITIOUS PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Vowing to reduce poverty and to eliminate Mexico's
chronic government corruption within six years, President-elect
Vicente Fox Quesada outlined an ambitious program for his incoming
administration Tuesday, including positions on drug policy and
immigration that showed the first signs of possible friction with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, the conservative candidate elected Sunday in a landmark
vote that halted 71 years of uninterrupted presidential rule by the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, offered a sweeping
blueprint of what Mexico's government might look like after he
takes office Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's most important goal, he said, would be to
cut growing poverty levels, particularly among indigenous and rural
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before every program we create and decision we make, I want
every one of my ministers to ask, `How will this affect the
indigenous and the marginalized in our country?' '' Fox said during
a 2 1/2-hour interview Tuesday morning with foreign news media.
</P>
<P>
   As a short-term measure, he said, he would work to ensure that
incomes rise higher during his government's first year than the
rate of inflation, something Mexico hasn't seen in more than a
decade. The former Coca-Cola executive also said he would seek to
attract more private investment, especially to the southeast
region, the country's poorest.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who defeated PRI candidate Francisco Labastida Ochoa 43
percent to 36 percent, also pledged that by the end of his six-year
term he would end rampant government corruption. To do that, he
said, he would create a Ministry of Justice and Security that would
remove federal police departments and investigative
responsibilities from the Interior Ministry, which oversees most of
the government's domestic programs, incuding immigration and
customs. He also would transfer the attorney general's special
powers to determine guilt in some criminal cases to the judiciary,
thereby limiting the role of the office to prosecuting cases.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also proposed transferring the government's main accounting
office to Mexico's Congress to allow for more independent analyses
of government spending and operations.
</P>
<P>
   But it is his views on drug policy that may present the new
administration's first test with Washington, which has so far
welcomed Fox's triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's president-elect proposes to do away with the annual
process of certification of drug-fighting allies by the US
government and replace it with a multilateral agreement between the
United States and drug-producing countries that would set goals for
each nation _ including the United States _ to reduce the supply
and demand for illegal narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This multilateral effort should have specific obligations for
each country,'' Fox said. ``I don't think that any country
individually can solve this cancer. It has to be a coordinated
international effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The current US certification program, which Mexico and other
countries have criticized as being punitive, evaluates the efforts
by drug-producing countries every year. Nations that fail to be
certified as cooperating partners risk sanctions or the loss of
some US trade benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also proposed a deepening of the 1994 North American Free
Trade Agreement among the United States, Mexico and Canada, saying
that the economic benefits of the pact haven't ``flowed down to the
level of the medium and small businesses or the regions.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the 58-year-old former Guanajuato state governor,
who once spent a year studying at Harvard University, said he
favored a freer flow of immigrants among the NAFTA countries, a
different view from that of Washington, which has tried to limit
the number of immigrants crossing the border.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Fox added, he would support the creation of a
borderless North American area, with a common currency, similar to
the European community.
</P>
<P>
   US officials were not available for immediate comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On other domestic issues, Fox pledged to restart negotiations
with the indigenous Zapatista rebels in Chiapas, whose six-year-old
armed struggle against the government is unresolved, and he
promised not to fire all federal workers who were hired by the
current ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   The president-elect continued his work Tuesday on assembling a
Cabinet and transition team that will inherit control from the
ruling party administration of Ernesto Zedillo in five months. It
will be the first transfer of federal power to a different party
since the birth of the PRI in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Tuesday night at Los Pinos, the presidential
residence in Mexico City, Zedillo and Fox pledged a smooth
transition, despite the absence of a formal protocol for the
handover. Fox said he would name a Cabinet within sixty days to
work with current government ministers.
</P>
<P>
   He also vowed to create a citizen-dominated transparency
commission to monitor the transfer. Mexico's fiscal 2001 federal
budget would be put together by both administrations, Fox added.
</P>
<P>
   Some Mexico analysts Tuesday praised many of Fox's proposals as
bold and innovative, saying they addressed the most pressing issues
facing the country's 96 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   But one worried that some of Fox's plans, including his promise
to slash poverty or erase corruption in just one presidential term,
might be too ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying he can't make major strides,'' said Roderic Ai
Camp, a Mexico specialist and professor of government at Claremont
McKenna College in California. ``But to altogether eliminate
something as widespread as corruption, I'm not optimistic. But he
is facing very high expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucia Arroyo, a 37-year-old bakery assistant in southern Mexico
City, said she'd love to see a Mexico where she didn't always have
to pay off government clerks or traffic cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I get pulled over in this city, I have to beg and
bribe a patrolman not to ticket me just because my car has
out-of-state license plates,'' she said. ``But it happens all the
time, and it's not fair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0190 </DOCNO>
