u a BC-ELEMENTARY-GYM-NYT &LR;      07-04 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELEMENTARY-GYM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELEMENTARY SCHOOL GYM CLASSES STRESS COOPERATION AND ACTIVITY OVER
COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAYVILLE, N.Y. _ With its squeaky wooden floor, cement-block
walls and stalwart basketball hoops, the gymnasium at Sunrise Drive
Elementary School has barely changed since the school was built
four decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   But physical education has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Signs posted around the gym remind students that they have
entered a ``no-fault zone'' where they are allowed to make
mistakes, and that ``if you had fun, you won.''
</P>
<P>
   Students here no longer pick their own teams for ball games
because egos may be too easily wounded. Dodge ball, a gym class
favorite for decades, was banned a few years ago because it was too
confrontational and, for many children, too demoralizing.
</P>
<P>
   And these days, students at Sunrise not only exercise but write
about the experiences in fitness journals. There are two
objectives: expressing their feelings about various sports and
explaining how each makes them more physically fit.
</P>
<P>
   Here, as in many elementary schools around the country, the
emphasis is increasingly on cooperation, not competition. Joanne
Hamilton, the gym teacher at Sunrise since 1982, said the idea was
to nurture children's self-esteem and teach them more about how to
keep healthy than how to play team sports. The fewer discouraging
experiences students have in gym class, she said, the more likely
they are to continue exercising for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever gets their feelings hurt in my class,'' said
Hamilton, thin and no-nonsense in khaki shorts and a tucked-in
T-shirt, as a class of second-graders skittered around the gym.
``Because once you turn a kid off to movement, they are never going
to move again.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Young, executive director of the National Association for
Sport and Physical Education, said physical education classes were
focusing more on cooperative activities because they allow even the
least athletic students to play important roles.
</P>
<P>
   One way that Hamilton keeps her students enthusiastic is to
avoid elimination games, much less let them strike out. In
baseball, instead of switching roles after three outs, each team
gets 10 minutes at bat, then 10 minutes in the field. Players may
choose between having the ball pitched to them or hitting it off a
tee.
</P>
<P>
   And in Hamilton's version of tag, boys and girls alike pretend
they are fairies and skip around the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Players who are ``it'' can tag their classmates, but the
children who are caught are not necessarily out of the game. They
can escape from captivity by shouting to other players, ``Free
me!''
</P>
<P>
   But if gym class is kinder and gentler these days, it is also
more goal-oriented. The standards movement that has swept the
nation in recent years, while focused mostly on academic subjects,
has led many states to adopt physical education standards for each
grade level, too.
</P>
<P>
   New York's standards, for example, require students to
``demonstrate mastery of fundamental motor, nonlocomotor and
manipulative skills'' and ``demonstrate and assess their fitness by
performing exercises and activities related to each health-related
fitness component.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the new standards, students at Sunrise learn the
difference between muscular strength (``being able to lift our
books up'') and muscular endurance (``being able to carry them
home''). They get homework questions about upper body strength, for
example, and volleyball terminology. And in their fitness journals,
they explain how different physical activities keep them in shape
and, in some cases, foster cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The journals also give students an opportunity to vent about
their gym class frustrations. Lauren Gajewski, a fifth-grader,
confided that she was relieved when she failed to hit the ball in a
recent softball game because ``I didn't have to worry about what to
do if I got to first base.'' And Jacklyn Spaeth, also in fifth
grade, complained in her journal that students who are caught
during tag pretend to be still free. ``That's when you know a fight
is going to begin,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In grading the journals, Hamilton has been known to offer
therapeutic advice. ``During tag you can always resolve the
conflict with rock-paper-scissors,'' she wrote to Jacklyn.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of scolding raucous students with a shrill whistle,
Hamilton uses carefully chosen language to make students reflect on
what is now known as inappropriate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg, that wasn't a good choice to make, to throw that ball in
Lissa's face,'' she said calmly to a first-grader. ``You owe her an
apology.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no such denigrations at Sunrise's annual field day in
June _ an event that, not surprisingly, has been renamed Fun Day.
None of the games were competitive, and each student was given a
ribbon. Instead of ``First Place'' or ``Second Place,'' the ribbons
were printed with ``Everybody's a Winner'' and ``It's Great to
Participate.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a partner tire roll, in which students paired up to
push a tire down the field. The point was not to beat other teams,
but to cooperate with your partner and see how many times you could
race back and forth in 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object is to accept everyone and their abilities,''
Hamilton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
