<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ALBERT-THE-GREAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBERT THE GREAT IS ZITO'S TICKET TO THE 3-YEAR-OLD RACES
</HEADLINE>
  By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Can a 3-year-old colt named Albert the Great, who
skipped the Triple Crown wars in the first half of the racing
season, become a star in the second half and help restore Nicholas
the Great to his rank among trainers?
</P>
<P>
   Nick Zito considered the question at Barn 12 at Belmont Park the
other day, and said: ``He made the first start of his career only
in January, but he has the potential to be one of the best we ever
had. He'll run all day, and as he goes longer, he'll get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Zito is plotting an ambitious summer and fall for his prodigy,
who has won his last three races, but who will take a giant step
upward next Sunday in the Dwyer Stakes when he tangles with several
top graduates of the Triple Crown. They are More Than Ready, who
ran fourth in the Kentucky Derby; Red Bullet, who won the
Preakness, and Commendable, who won the Belmont Stakes. They will
run 1 1/16 miles for a purse of $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Albert the Great will test these formidable stars with two
strikes on him: He did not run anywhere last year as a 2-year-old,
and he will be appearing in his first stakes race. He will be a
figure of unusual intrigue, the late bloomer, the ace in the hole
for one of the most accomplished trainers of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Zito won the 1991 Kentucky Derby with Strike the Gold, the 1994
Derby with Go for Gin and the 1996 Preakness with Louis Quatorze,
snapping the winning streak in the classics by D.Wayne Lukas at
six.
</P>
<P>
   Albert the Great was still running in allowance races earlier
this year while Zito was approaching the Kentucky Derby with
Greenwood Lake, winner of the Champagne and the Remsen last year
and one of the early favorites for the Derby this year. But just
like that, in the first week in March, the chance was gone.
Greenwood Lake came back from a workout limping, and his quest for
the Triple Crown was ended with a fractured left foreleg. And for
the first time in 10 years, one of the star trainers of the Triple
Crown did not even see a Triple Crown race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it was emotional for me,'' Zito said. ``This is a game of
dreams, a game of people and so much romance. The Triple Crown has
been part of my life for the last 10 years. It means so much to our
stable. It seemed strange for me to miss the Derby, Preakness and
Belmont this spring after years of being deeply involved. There
were rumors that I might run Albert in the Belmont, but it was too
big a step. And Bare Outline just didn't make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now I have the chance to catch the first-half horses with
a second-half winner. People get caught up with the horses that win
the classics. But for the rest of the year, the fresh-horse theory
can be just as important in deciding championships. Everybody's
looking for the good horse these days. I think I've found mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert the Great is a bay gelding who was bought by Tracy Farmer
of Lexington at the Keeneland auction sale last year for $85,000.
But he did not race at 2 because, Zito said, ``he had the usual
series of baby things, like splints and shins.'' But he finally
went to the races in January at Gulfstream Park, ran third twice,
then second and then seventh at Keeneland.
</P>
<P>
   But finally, he began to dazzle people. On April 22 at
Keeneland, he won by 10 lengths. Then he came to New York and won
in May and again in June. He went to the front in all three races
and stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   His next test will be the Dwyer Stakes. ``It's a major test, but
the way he trains makes me think he will handle it,'' Zito said.
``Then we'll aim him for the Jim Dandy at Saratoga in August and
the Travers later in August. Ambitious, yes. But he strikes me as
the horse who can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   At 52, with or without Triple Crown honors, Zito continues to
rank among the leading trainers in his hometown, New York City. He
trains full barns at Belmont Park and at Saratoga. He has been
forced to cope in the last few years while other trainers, notably
Lukas and Bob Baffert, have monopolized the winner's circle at the
classics. But he has the feeling now that he has found an
alternative path to the top.
</P>
<P>
   He also disclosed that his private life had been stabilized
recently with his marriage on June 4 to Kim Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been planning it,'' he said, ``but we made the decision
one Sunday when we were in Cooperstown upstate. We got a justice of
the peace, and got married. I said to Kim, `I know you like me, but
you're not so crazy about the job.' But she accepts it with good
grace.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``job'' takes a new turn Sunday when Albert the Great
springs from the starting gate to pursue his campaign to overtake
the veterans of the Triple Crown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
