<SLUG> BC-BBA-MOLINA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOLINA IMPRESSES BEHIND THE PLATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Young pitchers, inexperienced catcher. That is
not a combination that often gets, or keeps, a team in contention.
But so far this season, rookie catcher Bengie Molina and the
Angels' cast of young pitchers have perhaps surprised everybody but
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Molina, who started the season with just 77 days of major-league
service, has caught 11 different starters. Manager Mike Scioscia
has been forced to juggle his rotation because of injuries to Tim
Belcher, Ken Hill, Kent Bottenfield and Jason Dickson.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Schoeneweis, Brian Cooper, Jarrod Washburn, Ramon Ortiz
and Seth Etherton had a combined 35 big-league starts entering the
season, but Molina has handled the veterans and youngsters with
equal poise.
</P>
<P>
   He's a big reason why the Angels were 42-40 entering Tuesday's
game and were six games behind first-place Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   As a bonus, Molina is hitting .311 with nine home runs and 37
RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is taking the job and running with it,'' said Scioscia, who
admitted he knew little about Molina except the young catcher was
``a great talent, but durability was a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then (at spring training) I saw how hard he worked and his
dedication. He has tremendous ability . . . the only thing Bengie
can't do is run fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither durability nor speed has been an issue this year.
Scioscia has been careful not to overwork Molina and the strategy
has paid dividends both offensively and defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Molina, who has played in 57 of 85 games (including Tuesday), is
among the league leaders in throwing out runners attempting to
steal (23). He also put together a 14-game hitting streak and set
an Angels record for the highest batting average in a month (.461
in May).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great success story,'' Cooper said. ``He's had to work
his way through the system. Sometimes he wasn't even the No. 1
catcher. Now he gets his shot and and is making the most of it. . .
. catching well, throwing guys out and hitting (above .300).''
</P>
<P>
   While Molina has been impressive at catcher, it didn't start out
that way in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how to catch and I didn't know how I was going
to move up if I didn't know how to catch,'' Molina said.
</P>
<P>
   Molina spent most seven of years in the minors, where his
progress was slowed by a variety of injuries (shoulder, hamstring
and wrist).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after hitting .257 in 31 games with the Angels late
last season, Molina won the starting job in the spring and hasn't
looked back. But the 25-year-old remains firmly grounded, even
though some are touting him as Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing the same things that got me here and I'm not
planning on changing,'' he said. ``I never imagine good or bad, I
try to stay level-headed and not put pressure on myself, just do
what I do best.''
</P>
<P>
   And Molina is getting rave reviews from his pitchers, many of
whom he caught in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all came up together and he knows our strengths and
weaknesses,'' said Washburn. ``I have great confidence in him;
there are very few times that I shake him off. I can't say enough
about the job he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn describes Molina as shy but said a transformation of
sorts takes place when he's behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll come out and take charge; he doesn't hold back,''
Washburn said. ``And that's his job . . . to take charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper found that out first-hand when he shook off Molina
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came out and said, `That's not the pitch we should go
with,' '' Cooper said. ``We went with his pitch and we got the
batter out.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the youngsters who appreciate Molina's style.
Veteran closer Troy Percival gives Molina high marks as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a good idea what to call and you can feel a
confidence back there,'' Percival said.
</P>
</TEXT>
