<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-1S     07-04 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S PRESIDENT PARRIES CRITICISM WITH A RAPIER TONGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to recast graf about Kartasasmita and Bawazier, deleting
reference to their being legislators.)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The biographer of Abdurrahman Wahid,
Indonesia's unpredictable president, thinks he has him figured out:
He is the drunken swordsman in the martial arts movie who disarms
his enemies with his seeming foolishness, then cuts them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great master who looks like a complete walkover,'' said
the biographer, Greg Barton, an Australian political scientist.
``Suddenly there's a whirl of limbs and then everyone is lying on
the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The swords are out again this week as the president and his many
opponents start slicing the air in advance of a special
parliamentary session next month.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are talking about impeachment, although the national
assembly does not technically have that power. At the least, it
will be a grandstand for the national harrangue that has dogged
Wahid since his improbable election last October.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody saw it coming when Wahid (who in fact is not a drinker)
announced that the police would investigate up to 10 members of
Parliament on suspicion of fomenting violence and unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Then came his now-familiar pattern of verbal feints and jabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one big fish,'' he said on Saturday, ``but we haven't
found the supporting evidence yet. Once we catch him it will all be
over.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, according to a local newspaper, he said: ``I have
ordered the police to arrest and interrogate those suspected of
creating or being involved in riots. With or without evidence they
have to be captured.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday his Cabinet secretary, Marsilam Simanjuntak, said the
president had signed an order for the investigation of the
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, with newspaper headlines blurting ``Confusion Reigns,''
the president said: ``I've never accused the legislators of being
guilty. My other statement was twisted for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Jakarta is abuzz with rumors and political scurrying as
people name names, point fingers and nudge the points of their
knives into one another's backs.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the Cabinet of former President Suharto _
Ginandjar Kartasasmita and Fuad Bawazier _ found themselves angrily
denying that they were on Wahid's list.
</P>
<P>
   Bawazier did not seem to help his case much when he denied a
suggestion that he was financing armed groups by saying: ``The
accusations are baseless. It is normal that I give donations to the
needy.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be a diverting spectacle, but the stakes are high.
Indonesia is _ as the pilots of jetliners say _ passing through a
period of turbulence after the ouster of Suharto two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As it does so, it sometimes seems that Wahid is alone at the
controls. And there are disconcerting moments when he seems,
willfully, to be steering into the thunderheads.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who say Wahid is his own worst enemy,
undermining Indonesia's stability and economic recovery by his
impulsiveness and his tendency to cry wolf. Although economic
analysts insist that in real terms the economy is on an upturn, the
confidence of investors has continued to sink.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the political noise, the currency, the rupiah, fell to
below 9,000 to the dollar Tuesday, its lowest point in 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   The catch-phrase in Jakarta now is: ``The best thing the
president could do for the economy is to keep his mouth shut for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's defenders say that shutting his mouth would in effect be
laying down his weapons. With few political cards to play, they
say, the president is lucky that he is an expert bluffer.
</P>
<P>
   The back-room coalition he yanked together last October to win
the presidency has mostly turned against him, ready to devour him
when he presents his state of the nation address to the assembly
next month.
</P>
<P>
   And he is operating without much of a functioning bureaucracy,
which was eviscerated by Suharto during his 32-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   Where Suharto kept his opponents at bay by force of arms, Wahid
must operate by the force of his personality. That is how he
undercut his recalcitrant military chief, Gen. Wiranto, in
February, pummeling him with a barrage of intemperate remarks and
finally dismissing him.
</P>
<P>
   The newly empowered legislature has roared to life as what one
analyst called a ``crocodile pit'' of political agendas. The
legislators fired the first shot last Friday when they voted to
call in the president later this month _ ahead of the assembly _ to
explain his firing of two Cabinet ministers in April. Barton,
Wahid's biographer, said the president had already ``done his
deals'' in advance of the assembly, well aware that few of his
critics are prepared to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gus Dur has done his political homework,'' said Barton, using
the president's nickname. ``In this, he is brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the president is faced with a surge of violent
unrest around the country.
</P>
<P>
   There is a religious war in the far eastern Maluku islands,
where more than 2,500 Christians and Muslims have been killed in
the last 18 months. There has been communal fighting on the islands
of Sulawesi, Bali and Lombok. There have been bomb blasts at
mosques and churches. And there are insurgencies in the provinces
of Aceh and Irian Jaya that appear to be receiving outside aid.
</P>
<P>
   The unseen hands behind them may include military plotters,
local power blocs, ambitious politicians and people from the former
government.
</P>
<P>
   Their message, said Barton, is: ```Back off or we'll make
problems.' It's a sort of hostage situation; it doesn't take a lot
of money to set things off. From others, it's, `Let's see what a
weak leader he is.' There are all sorts of crazies, all sorts of
people trying their thing, trying to get him to take them
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a lot for one man to handle. And, according to Barton, it
is a battle the president relishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feint to the left, hit to the right: Your opponent never knows
where you're coming from,'' Barton said. ``It's strongly his style,
like a kung fu expert. He doesn't always land on his feet, but
don't underestimate him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
