<HEADLINE>
MATHIS WINS MLS HONOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Former Los Angeles Galaxy striker Clint
Mathis, who proudly displays his ``I Love NY'' T-shirt after each
goal he scores for the New York/New Jersey MetroStars, was named
MLS player of the month for June.
</P>
<P>
   New York picked up Mathis from L.A. in the dispersal draft that
followed the allocation of Luis Hernandez to the Galaxy. Hernandez
scored his first goal in eight games on Saturday; Mathis has
recorded four goals and eight assists for the East-leading
MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hartman, Elliott return: Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman
returned to his starting role after missing Saturday's 4-2 loss to
the Dallas Burn so he could attend his sister's wedding in Palos
Verdes.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, Matt Reis, likely doesn't want to remember that
match. It was the most goals allowed by a Galaxy team since four
were allowed against Dallas last October.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Simon Elliott is back to his starting role after
returning from Tahiti where he played for New Zealand in the
Oceania Nations Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott missed two games before returning as a late substitute
Saturday in Dallas. He is having his best MLS season and it's
paying off with his national team. He scored two goals off free
kicks for New Zealand during the tournament as New Zealand reached
the championship before falling to Australia 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Midfielder Danny Pena underwent surgery last
week to repair a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee.
Galaxy fitness trainer Jim Liston believes Pena can recover before
the season ends. Pena, 32, is expected to be out four to eight
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
