<HEADER>
A3119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COL-CELEBRATION-NY     07-04 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CELEBRATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: OF ALL PLACES, LADY LIBERTY OFF LIMITS? 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Oh, it was grand all right, grand as could be, the
crisp procession of tall ships along the waters of New York. You'd
have had to be drained of every drop of romance to be unimpressed
by the spectacle and the grace that it shed on us all.
</P>
<P>
   But it was hard not to feel that several important, if
undistinguished, vessels were missing in the hullabaloo of OpSail
2000. They were ordered off the water so they would not get in the
way of their fairer, more favored cousins that set sail on this
Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   We are talking about the ferryboats that carry thousands of
people a day from Battery Park to the Statue of Liberty and Ellis
Island. Since they were unable to leave their moorings, it meant
that the inspiring statue and the historic immigration center were
closed to the public for the day.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, you say? What's one day?
</P>
<P>
   Not much perhaps. But it did seem strange that on the day
Americans celebrated their emergence as a people, the people could
not reach enduring symbols of the country's claim to be a beacon
for _ how did Emma Lazarus put it? _ those ``huddled masses
yearning to breathe free.''
</P>
<P>
   Close Liberty and Ellis Islands on Independence Day? Fine. While
you are at it, why not shut the doors of St. Patrick's Cathedral on
Easter Sunday because all those worshipers interfere with the
thousands flocking to Fifth Avenue for the fashion show known as
the Easter Parade?
</P>
<P>
   Larry Drees, of Boulder, Colo., was one of many visitors to
Battery Park on the eve of the holiday who could not believe that
the Statue of Liberty, of all places, would be off limits on the
Fourth of July, of all days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely ridiculous,'' he said as he stood Monday
afternoon outside Castle Clinton, the old fort that now serves as a
ticket booth for the ferries.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there might be legitimate security concerns, Drees said.
But he added, ``What's the point of this country if you're going to
let your fears over security shut it down?''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the twin islands of liberty and immigration were
hostage Tuesday to the classically American _ and very New York _
need for chest-thumping over superlatives.
</P>
<P>
   A parade of graceful ships that pleased the eye and exercised
the imagination was of itself insufficient. It had to be beaten
into everyone, mercilessly, that this was the biggest, the best,
the boldest, the most whatever of all time.
</P>
<P>
   The advance billing, repeatedly echoed by television announcers,
was that it would be ``the greatest event in maritime history.''
Didn't anyone off camera ever whisper ``D-Day'' in these people's
ears? Or at least show them a video of ``Saving Private Ryan''?
</P>
<P>
   But then television merely fell in step with the times. New
York, in general, seems to be hooked on always having to top
itself.
</P>
<P>
   It was not enough for people to enjoy themselves last New Year's
Eve. For New Yorkers to have a good time, the celebrations had to
be the largest, the liveliest, the most bubbly and eye-popping
ever. The same principle governed OpSail Tuesday morning and the
holiday fireworks displayed later that night, an appreciated annual
gift from Macy's that is also an obvious promotional device _ call
it OpSale.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks were not merely splendiferous. What counted for
many New Yorkers was that they were the most outsized: 60,000
shells weighing 150 tons and bursting at a rate of 2,000 per
minute, or if you preferred, 34 per second.
</P>
<P>
   On and on, for weeks, the numbers poured out of an ever-churning
hype machine. Four million people would view the ships. There would
be 70,000 craft in the water. About 28,000 police officers would be
on duty. That some of those numbers were gross exaggerations made
no nevermind. What mattered for many people were the superlatives
themselves. They were the ultimate affirmation of our civic worth,
not the waterborne displays of grace and majesty.
</P>
<P>
   Some people did not buy it.
</P>
<P>
   They knew that numbers were fleeting and that the Statue of
Liberty was a lot more than a backdrop for a fireworks display,
especially on this holiday.
</P>
<P>
   They were people like Jo Ann and Sam Mannino, visitors from
Detroit, who went to the statue with their three small children on
the Third of July.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get our kids to understand things like the Statue
of Liberty, and the pain that people went through ... '' Mannino
said. He did not finish the thought, picking up a different one
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first symbol of America,'' he said, as his wife
nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called a reality check,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband agreed, and pointed to the children. ``They've got
to learn about it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-04-00 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
