<DOCNO> NYT20000704.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-04 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3121 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-COL-DEMONSTRATIONS     07-04 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COL-DEMONSTRATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: JULY FOURTH IN MORRISTOWN, N.J., MARKED BY DEMONSTRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORRISTOWN, N.J. _ This town, which served as a headquarters of
the Revolutionary Army, usually celebrates the Fourth of July with
a dramatic reading of the Declaration of Independence, complete
with muskets and tricorn hats. But this year, Morristown also had a
live-action drama showcasing those inalienable rights of life,
liberty and the pursuit of happiness.
</P>
<P>
   The action began when a white supremacist from Mississippi won
the right in court to hold a rally here Tuesday. Richard Barrett,
whose Nationalist Movement oath declares ``the white race is the
superlative civilizer,'' said he chose Morristown because of its
history. Just as George Washington ``said no to the privileges of
the king, today we're saying no to the privileges of minorities,''
Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett got what he wanted Tuesday _ helmeted police protecting
his right to march on Washington Street, a crowd of angry
counter-protesters that drew pepper spray and 10 arrests. A perfect
forum for a man with bullhorn and bombast. Barrett brought to town
an anemic anti-affirmative action protest and a racist version of
the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday night, as Barrett prepared to deliver his divisive
message, Morristown made its elegant statement. About 1,000 people
filled the Calvary Baptist Church for what was billed as a
celebration of diversity. There were clerical collars and
embroidered yarmulkes, prayers read in Spanish and Tamil, and a
community brought to its feet by a guitar-strumming cantor, then
brought to critical mass by a stirring soloist from the church.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's name was hardly mentioned, but Morristown wouldn't
have done it without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here tonight to reject any notion that one race is
superior to another,'' Calvary's pastor, the Rev. Jerry Carter,
said to cheers.
</P>
<P>
   The service and candlelight march to the Morristown Green was
arranged at the urging of the mayor, John DeLaney Jr., who was
looking for a way to counter Barrett without giving him the
satisfaction of a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The town has about 17,000 residents _ about 15 percent black and
20 percent Hispanic _ and just around the corner from Calvary
Baptist Church is evidence that all is not harmonious. Outside a
house, a sign commemorates the death of a black resident who was
killed last year by police in a neighboring town. Prosecutors
cleared the officers, but, for some, his death remains an example
of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, though, was a display of racial accord. Rabbi
David Nesson of Morristown's Jewish Community Center reminded the
crowd that Washington once wrote to a synagogue in Newport, R.I.,
that one of the country's guiding ideals was ``to give to bigotry
no sanction, to persecution no assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakki Dumas-Footman, 33, a financial analyst who is black, said
she felt compelled to come to the service with her daughter even
though she grew up in a largely white Morristown neighborhood and
rarely felt racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a KKK march,'' she said. ``I brought my
daughter. She knows about the KKK. I want her to see it. This is
our history, in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nate Moore, a 58-year-old computer consultant, came Monday night
remembering that history from having grown up black in Alabama.
Barrett's message ``really astounded me,'' he said. ``I really
thought these days were passed.''
</P>
<P>
   The songs of equality at the church recalled the old days, Moore
said, but there were more white faces in the pews, and the ranks of
racists were thinner. ``I think you have to accept the differences
and move on,'' he said. ``I think that's what we're doing more of _
accepting the differences and moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   But moving on is not a straight course.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's harmony gave way to Tuesday's ugliness.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's sad parade of eight followers was separated from an
angry crowd of about 250 by barricades and helmeted police on
horses. At the height of the event, protesters from groups,
including the Progressive Labor Party, were hurling vile taunts at
the police as some protesters knocked down barricades and threw
golf balls and batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Asa Watkins, an 83-year-old artist from Morristown, had come to
oppose Barrett, but was taken aback by the anger on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins was reminded that Washington had spent two treacherous
winters in Morristown on the way to victory. This Fourth of July
freedom had another tough, but victorious, round in Morristown.
``It's a messy process, democracy is,'' said Mr. Watkins, leaving
the rally. ``It always is.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
