<HEADER>
A3125 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CRIME-SENATERACE-2TAK     07-04 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIME-SENATERACE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHCROFT, CARNAHAN TRY TO OUTDO EACH OTHER ON CRIME ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Never mind that crime and mayhem are down
nationwide. John Ashcroft is pursuing that tried-and-true
Republican tactic of thumping his rival, Democrat Mel Carnahan, as
soft on crime.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, seeking a second term in the U.S. Senate, slams the
two-term governor for taking a murderer off death row at the
request of Pope John Paul II. Carnahan, Ashcroft says, never even
told the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   But Carnahan now asserts that Ashcroft did the same thing when
he was governor. And he says that Ashcroft's crime-fighting
credentials are suspect because of his opposition to gun-control
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashcroft's been against every reasonable gun-safety measure
that's come before Congress during his almost six years in
office,'' said Carnahan campaign manager Marc Farinella.
</P>
<P>
   That crime has moved to the forefront of the state's Senate race
should be no surprise, experts say. Although the issue may have
been surpassed by education, health care and sometimes Social
Security as higher priorities in national opinion polls, crime
remains a perennial voter concern.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates, no matter where they are from, don't want to appear
weak-kneed on law-breakers the way Democrat Michael Dukakis did
when he lost the 1988 presidential race to George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis opposed capital punishment, and Bush made him pay for
that stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates cannot afford to be out `anti-crimed,' so to
speak,'' said Ken Warren, a St. Louis University political
scientist. ``They want to make sure they look the toughest on
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft and Carnahan both favor capital punishment. When
Ashcroft was governor, the state began carrying out executions
again in the wake of the U.S. Supreme Court's 1976 decision. Seven
inmates were put to death under Ashcroft; Carnahan has so far
overseen 36 executions.
</P>
<P>
   Although several recent studies have raised questions about the
fairness of capital punishment, neither candidate favors a
moratorium on executions.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, said spokesman Steve Hilton, ``believes in capital
punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan is convinced that ``the system works well here,'' said
spokesman Jerry Nachtigal.
</P>
<P>
   Crime surfaced as a point of contention only weeks after
Carnahan announced his plans to challenge Ashcroft in late 1998.
The door opened the next year after Carnahan agreed to Pope John
Paul II's request to commute the sentence of convicted killer
Darrell Mease.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan called the decision a one-time act in response to a
personal plea from the pope. Mease will now spend his life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have done it,'' said Ashcroft, who complained that
an act of a jury was nullified by a governor's personal whim. It
also showed that Carnahan would use the death penalty to score
political points _ in this case with Roman Catholic voters, Hilton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Farinella is convinced that Ashcroft's focus on crime is a
result of the Mease commutation.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft wants to make himself into the anti-crime candidate,
Farinella said, ``and the one and only thing he has to point to is
Mease.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Senate hearing in March 1999, the senator complained that
the relatives of the couple and their paraplegic grandson whom
Mease shot to death ``did not get a phone call, even a letter''
about Carnahan's commutation.
</P>
<P>
   Now Carnahan accuses Ashcroft of doing the same thing. In 1992,
Ashcroft commuted the sentences of Helen Martin and Becca Hughes,
who were convicted in Jefferson County of murdering or arranging
the murder of their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Both faced life imprisonment without parole. Ashcroft's decision
meant that the women were eligible to seek parole.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft had never commuted a prisoner's sentence. He said he
did so in these two cases because the women were convicted before a
1987 law went into effect allowing women to use the battered-spouse
syndrome as a defense. Juries never heard about the severe abuse
each woman endured, the governor said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, though, pointed out that Ashcroft did not notify the
victims' families when he took his action.
</P>
<P>
   But Ashcroft contends MORE
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ...when he took his action.
</P>
<P>
   But Ashcroft contends his action only allowed the women to
eventually seek parole. Notifying relatives, he said, was a parole
board task.
</P>
<P>
   Martin eventually was released from prison, although Hughes was
not, Carnahan aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Farinella said blaming someone else for the lack of notification
isn't valid.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is...a flat-out contradiction,'' Farinella said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan opposed last year's failed Proposition B, which would
have allowed Missourians to carry concealed weapons. He often
points out that Ashcroft was a prime proponent who made radio ads
last year in support of concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-gun stands sell well in rural areas, but not in the state's
two major cities, where crime is more prevalent and where
Proposition B was defeated with more than 70 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the balance are the state's suburban voters, who also
were strong in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suburban areas are very important in terms of electoral
outcomes,'' says Farinella. ``Crime is likely to be one of the key
issues that suburbanites vote on.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan has gone out of his way to label Ashcroft's gun record
a carbon copy of the National Rifle Association's agenda. The NRA
has given Ashcroft more than $50,000 in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft opposed the federal assault-weapons ban in 1994 when he
was running for the Senate. In 1998, he voted against a bill that
would have required dealers to sell child-safety locks with each
handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan has highlighted Ashcroft's firearms votes in news
releases to reporters titled ``Ashcroft's Gun Safety Charade.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ashcroft maintains he has ``zero tolerance'' for gun
violence. He favors a program known as Project Exile that
guarantees prison sentences for anyone caught using a gun in
connection with illegal drugs, children or domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates claim that the program has resulted in dramatically
fewer murders in Atlanta and Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Missouri,'' said Hilton, the Ashcroft aide,
``are interested in programs that work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft also points to his work last year on a juvenile-crime
bill that remains bottled up in a House-Senate conference
committee. In particular, the Senate passed an Ashcroft amendment
that bars juveniles from possessing semiautomatic assault weapons,
such as an Uzi or ``street sweeper'' shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture of violence that has polluted our society and
desensitized our children to violence over the past decade must be
confronted,'' the senator said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But Carnahan criticized Ashcroft's amendment, which passed with
96 votes, saying the so-called ban provides too many exceptions.
``The point is, the law is so broad that any juvenile can carry a
semiautomatic weapon,'' Farinella said of the Ashcroft amendment.
An NRA spokeswoman said the group ``didn't oppose'' the senator's
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft's provision would make possession of a semiautomatic
weapon subject to the same rules as possession of a handgun. In
most cases, those rules require a parent to authorize use of the
weapon for hunting or farming, or at the juvenile's job.
</P>
<P>
   The two remain somewhat divided on the issue of mandatory
background checks at gun shows. Ashcroft voted for a 1999 bill that
Republicans say would have taken care of the issue. Many Democrats
disagreed. They preferred what they called a tougher version
sponsored by Sen. Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey; it ultimately
passed when Vice President Al Gore cast a tie-breaking vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft opposed the Lautenberg proposal.
</P>
<P>
   In a race filled with contrasts, the two campaigns differ on why
crime has become a focal point. Democrats point out that
violent-crime rates have dropped dramatically during Carnahan's
eight years as governor and under President Clinton's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are concerned that they are now vulnerable on the
crime issue, which the Republicans have always viewed as a core
issue for them,'' Farinella said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft points to recent federal crime statistics showing that
Kansas City and St. Louis now rank fourth and first respectively
nationwide in per-capita serious-crime rankings. The ranking came
despite figures showing that the number of reported serious crimes
in both cities had declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City has very problematic numbers,'' Hilton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
