u a BC-CT-HILL-LAWSUIT-NYT &LR;      07-04 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-HILL-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT CITY SUES ITS PLANNING COMMISSION FOR APPROVING
DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDEN, Conn. _ In this struggling blue-collar city, tucked
into the leafy Quinnipiac River Valley halfway between Hartford and
New Haven, the fight over a 100-foot-high mound of jagged shale
boulders and scrub brush has turned ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the city filed a lawsuit in Superior Court against
its planning commission for approving a plan by the property owner
to blast the hill to build 36 town houses. The city contended in
the lawsuit that the commission approved the project illegally,
contravening its own rules protecting local ridge lines.
</P>
<P>
   City council members voted unanimously last week to spend
$15,000 on lawyers to for the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting the July 25 court date: on one side, environmentalists
and North End residents who live near the hill; and, on the other
side, the politically connected businessman permitted to raze the
hill.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists and residents say the hill is a natural
extension of Cathole Mountain, a towering face of rock cliffs
looming over Meriden from the northwest, and should only be
developed with care. But to the businessman, William Corvo, and his
partners, the hill is privately owned and worth millions of dollars
after development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you feel this is _ not to exaggerate _ the Rocky Mountains
or something of that nature, then you should acquire it,'' said
Corvo, 49.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Corvo bought the the hill and its 660,000 cubic
yards of shale from two of his friends, Joseph and Salvatore
Carabetta, brothers who have made a fortune in area real estate
deals over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Since the commission's vote, on June 1, everyone says things
have gone drastically wrong. The hill, and Meriden's planning
commission, were not supposed to end up in court _ again.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the planning commission denied a company controlled by
the Carabetta brothers a permit to level the same hill and build
houses. The brothers sued the commission, arguing it had no right
to deny them a permit, but a Superior Court judge in New Haven
sided with the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is in a fervor over this thing,'' said Dominick
Caruso, Meridan's director of planning, who had warned the
commission minutes before its vote last month to reject the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The tug of war over the hill, which is too small to hike and too
gentle to climb, may been seen as a case study of Meriden city
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, Joseph Marinan Jr., is a Democrat who appointed the
planning commission, including its chairman, Roger DeZinno. At a
meeting last month, DeZinno, also a Democrat, voted with the
commission's two Republicans to approve Corvo's housing project,
which passed, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   That is when the city council directed the city manager and
Caruso to file a lawsuit. Corvo hired Meriden's former Democratic
mayor, William Shea, as his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, including some city officials, say they believe
that the Carabetta brothers are behind Corvo's bid and that they
improperly influenced the planning commission vote to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   The planning commission's chairman, DeZinno, and the Carabetta
brothers ``enjoy boating together'' on a powerboat owned by the
brothers, said Stephen Anderson, a lawyer representing two
homeowners suing the city and the commission to stop the project.
Anderson also points out that Lois DeMayo, a Republican planning
commissioner who voted to approve razing the hill, owns a
telephone-answering service that contracts its services to
companies owned by the Carabettas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Corvo accuses Caruso, the city planner, of being
unprofessional and having a ``personal problem'' with developing
the hill.
</P>
<P>
   DeMayo blames the local media and a pack of ``tree huggers'' for
keeping the issue in local newspaper headlines for the past month.
She also accused the city council of playing favorites with local
developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the proper excavation company applied, the one that the
city wants to get the contract, that hill would be down tomorrow,''
she said. ``This is all politics. This thing is a hill. It's not
cliffs, it's not climbing, it's not hiking, and besides, it's
private property.''
</P>
<P>
   If the city council wants to protect the property, she asked,
why doesn't it vote to buy it?
</P>
<P>
   The city may get its chance on Wednesday, when Corvo is
scheduled to meet with Marinan to try resolving their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they feel that it's absolutely critical,'' Corvo said of
the hill, ``then they are going to be given the option of buying
it.'' The price: somewhere in the single-digit millions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If that does not work out, he said, he is also considering
filing individual lawsuits against all 12 Council members for
voting to sue the planning commission and his development company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody,'' he said, ``has got to be personally responsible
for their actions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
